[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

{ Hello dear friends! Welcome to my lifetime repertoire against 1.d4 based on the Benko and Vienna openings.    For those who don't know me, I am a Grandmaster from India. I have been coaching chess for the last 5 years where one of my students, Raunak Sadhwani, became a Grandmaster at the young age of 13 years and 9 months. I have seconded the Indian Women's team in the Chess Olympiad 2018. I was also the coach of the Indian Women's team in the World team chess championship held in Georgia in 2019 and the Asian Nations Cup held in Iran in 2018.    As a player, the Vienna Opening and the Benko Gambit were my main weapons against 1. d4. I have played it for many years in numerous games, against opponents of varied strengths and tried almost all the variations that these two openings have to offer.   When you try to master a certain thing in life, you get your share of bitter and sweet memories. I experienced the same with these openings throughout my career. I learnt some really important lessons the hard way and scored some delicious sweet victories in the crucial rounds. At one point, I was so confident in the Benko Gambit that I played it in one of my crucial games when I needed a win to score my final GM norm. My opponent was the experienced Belarusian GM Aleksej Aleksandrov @@StartBracket@@who at one point of his career was 2700!@@EndBracket@@. In a topsy- turvy game @@StartBracket@@to be honest I was almost lost at one point@@EndBracket@@ I managed to win by playing a combination that involved sacrificing a queen! When you win such an important game in your career with the Benko Gambit, you are bound to fall in love with this opening!   Both the Vienna and the Benko Gambit have stayed close to my heart and I wish to share my knowledge in these openings in this lifetime repertoire. There has always been a notion in the Chess world that the Benko Gambit is objectively worse but practically a good opening weapon. With this repertoire, it is my humble attempt to change this belief and present the Benko Gambit as an objectively sound opening as well.     Apart from the main openings of this repertoire @@StartBracket@@Vienna and Benko@@EndBracket@@, I have also analyzed the deviations including popular openings like the Catalan, London, etc with the strongest engines! Against these openings, I have recommended some relatively rare lines that will carry an element of surprise! I hope that whenever you wish to get a fighting position out of the opening you will look forward to playing the lines suggested in this repertoire. All the best! }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4
{ 2.Bf4  The London system is covered in Chapter 1. Our main line is based on bringing our light-squared bishop out of the pawn chain to g4 or f5 and then playing ...e6.   2.Bg5  The Trompowsky is covered in Chapter 2. We answer with 2...d5 and get ready to play an unbalanced position in case White exchanges on f6.   2.Nc3  this is the entrance to the Veresov or the Jobava Attack.  2...d5  and now we cover both:    3.Bf4  The Jobava Attack and    3.Bg5  The Veresov in Chapter 3   2.Nf3  d5  3.c4   3.Bg5  The Torre Attack is covered in Chapter 4 where I again recommend developing our light-squared bishop out of the pawn chain before playing ...e6.   3.e3  The Colle Zukertort variation is covered in Chapter 5. I have analyzed both the setups:    1. If White plays c2-c3 and    2. If White plays b2-b3.   3.g3  Has witnessed some top-level games occasionally so I made sure to analyze it in a separate chapter. White fianchetto's his bishop on g2 without playing c2-c4 which gives it an independent value. This line is analyzed in Chapter 6.  e6  4.Nc3   4.g3  The super solid Catalan Opening is analyzed in Chapter 7. I have recommended a relatively rare line played frequently by GM Anton Guijarro in recent times.   4.e3  is a safe but dull way of playing with the White pieces and is analyzed under 'Deviations to Vienna' in Chapter 8.  dxc4  This is the doorway to the Vienna!  5.e4  This aggressive way of playing against the Vienna has become the main weapon for White lately.   5.Qa4+  White decides to recapture the c4-pawn with his queen and is analyzed in Chapter 9.   5.g3  is analyzed in Chapter 10 where I recommend a novelty as early as the 7th move in the mainline.   5.Bg5  Has been played rarely but is analyzed in detail in Chapter 11.   5.e3  This has been the main response for White since the early days of the Vienna opening.  5...a6  6.Bxc4   6.a4  White prevents b7-b5 and is covered in Chapter 12.  b5  7.Bb3  seems to be the best of the bishop retreats and is analyzed in Chapter 14.   7.Be2  and   7.Bd3  is covered in Chapter 13.  5...Bb4  6.Bg5   6.Bxc4!?  an interesting line where White sacrifices a pawn early in the opening in an attempt to seize the initiative. This is covered in Chapter 15.  c5  7.Bxc4  The most popular line for White which is analyzed in Chapters 18, 19 and 20.   7.dxc5  is not so challenging and leads to an endgame. You can check Chapter 16 for this line.   7.e5  This leads to complicated play and is covered in Chapter 17. }
2... c5 3. d5
{ 3.Nf3  cxd4  4.Nxd4  e6  5.Nc3  is covered in Chapter 22.   5.g3  Bb4+  6.Nc3  leads to the Romanishin Variation in the Nimzo-Indian Defence and is analyzed in Chapter 21.   3.e3  along with  3.dxc5  is covered in Chapter 23. }
3... b5
{ Welcome to the world of the Benko Gambit! Now White has two options. Either he can decline the Gambit or accept it and I have covered variations arising from both ways of handling the Benko. }
4. cxb5
{ 4.Nd2  is a sideline covered in Chapter 24.   4.a4  is analyzed on Chapter 25.   4.f3  is covered in Chapter 26.   4.Nf3  is one of the mainlines in Benko Gambit Declined and is analyzed in Chapter 27.   4.Qc2  is a popular way of declining the sacrifice and is covered in Chapter 28. }
4... a6 5. bxa6
{ 5.f3  White sacrifices the pawn back to quickly put his pawns in the centre with f3-e4. This is analyzed in detail in Chapter 28.   5.Nc3  This is known as the Zaitsev line and is covered in Chapter 29.   5.e3  is a popular line frequently seen in Grandmaster games. This is covered in Chapter 30.   5.b6  White gives the pawn back keeping the lines closed on the queenside. This line is analyzed in Chapter 31. }
5... g6 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. e4
{ 7.Nf3  O-O  8.g3  Fianchettoing the Bishop on g2 has always been an attractive way of playing from the White side in the Benko Gambit Accepted lines. I have analyzed this line in Chapter 33. }
7... O-O 8. e5
{ this is one of the most critical continuations along with  8.Bc4!?  and  8.a7  .    All these options are covered in detail in Chapter 32. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "The London System"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
{ The London System has become a main weapon these days thanks to the efforts of the World Champion Magnus Carlsen for reviving this opening. }
2... d5
{ We face the London System in traditional style by playing in the centre. } 3.
e3 { This is the most flexible move order for White. } 3... c5 4. Nf3 Nc6
{ We develop both our knights before deciding on the future of our bishops. }
5. Nbd2 cxd4 { This makes sure that White does not have the option of dxc5. }
6. exd4 Qb6 { Attacking both the d4- and b2-pawns. } 7. Nb3
{ The only way to defend against Black's dual threats. } 7... Bf5
{ It is important to develop our light-squared bishop out of the pawn chain before we play ...e6. Otherwise, the bishop gets locked in on c8. }
8. Be2 e6 9. O-O Be7 { Preparing O-O. } 10. a4
{ White plans to gain space on the queenside with a5-a6. } 10... a6
{ Preventing White's a-pawn from reaching a6. } 11. a5 Qd8 12. Ne5 Rc8
{ Black is ready to capture on c6 with the rook. Next Black would simply O-O with a completely fine position. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "The Trompowsky Attack"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 { The Trompowsky Attack! } 2... d5
{ With  2...d5  we are ready to play an unbalanced position in case White exchanges on f6. }
3. Bxf6
{ This is in the spirit of the Trompowsky Attack. White creates an unbalanced position by giving up his bishop pair and ruining Black's kingside pawn formation. }
3... gxf6 { Capturing towards the centre! } 4. e3 c5
{ It's time to challenge the centre. } 5. dxc5
{ This move has been typical in recent times. White captures on c5 and aims to break in the centre with c4 at an appropriate moment. }
5... e6 { We aim to recapture the pawn quickly. } 6. c4 dxc4 7. Nd2
{ White avoids the exchange of queens in the hope that he can exploit Black's weakened kingside pawn structure. }
7... c3 { We give the c4-pawn back but not without ruining White's queenside. }
8. bxc3 Nd7
{ This is a rare move! We prefer to keep our bishop on the kingside and capture the c5-pawn with our knight. }
9. Bb5 { White forces us to recapture on c5 with the bishop. } 9... a6
{ It is better to insert ...a6 before playing ...Bxc5. } 10. Ba4 Bxc5
{ Black is all set to O-O. } 11. Ngf3 O-O 12. O-O Qc7
{ Intending to develop our light-squared bishop with ...b6 and ...Bb7. Black is slightly better because of the bishop pair. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "The Veresov"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3
{ With this development of the knight, White hints at entering the Jobava Attack or the Veresov opening. White's immediate idea is to play e4 and seize the centre. }
2... d5 { This is the most logical move, preventing e4. } 3. Bg5
{ The Veresov opening. With  3.Bg5  White continues to fight for the e4-square. }
3... c5 { We attack White's centre immediately. } 4. Bxf6
{ White exchanges on f6 in order to break with e4 quickly. } 4... gxf6 5. e4
{ White plays in the spirit of the Veresov. } 5... dxe4 6. dxc5 f5
{ it is important for us to protect the e4-pawn as it limits White's pieces. }
7. Qxd8+ Kxd8 8. O-O-O+
{ White seems to have some initiative as Black's king is unstable in the centre. But he does not have sufficient pieces in the game yet to create something worthwhile against our king. }
8... Bd7 9. g4 { Trying to open up the position as swiftly as possible. } 9...
Bh6+
{ A nice move pushing the White king away from the centre before playing ...Bg7. }
10. Kb1 Bg7 11. gxf5 Bxc3 12. bxc3 Kc7
{ We are all set to win either the f5-pawn with ...Bf5 or the c5-pawn with ...Na6 @@StartBracket@@in case White defends the f5 pawn with Bh3@@EndBracket@@. Black stands slightly better because of White's weak pawn structure. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "The Jobava Attack"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3
{ With this development of the knight, White hints at entering the Jobava Attack or the Veresov opening. White's immediate idea is to play e4 and seize the centre. }
2... d5 { This is the most logical move, preventing e4. } 3. Bf4
{ This is known as the Jobava Attack named after the creative Georgian GM Baadur Jobava, who achieved some great wins with White in this system. }
3... a6
{ With this little move we cover the b5-square and prevent any Nb5 ideas. } 4.
e3 Bf5 { Developing our light square Bishop before playing ...e6. } 5. f3
{ This is in the spirit of the Jobava Attack. White covers the e4 square and intends to gain space on the kingside with pawn advances - g4-h4-h5. }
5... e6 6. g4 Bg6 7. h4 { White threatens to trap our Bishop with h5. } 7... h5
{ This stops White's aggressive plans on the kingside and forces him to play g5 which weakens the f5 square. }
8. g5 Nfd7 9. Bd3
{ White needs to exchange the light-squared bishops otherwise he won't be able to create anything on the kingside. }
9... Bxd3 10. Qxd3 c5
{ It is high time we start creating counterplay on the queenside. } 11. g6
{ White starts his attempts to weaken Black's kingside. } 11... f6
{ We can't allow White to open up the kingside. } 12. Nge2 Nc6 13. O-O-O Nb6
{ Now we threaten to play Nc6-b4, Nb6-c4 and then Qd8-b6 creating a strong attack against the White king. }
14. a3 cxd4 { Opening the c-file for counterplay. } 15. Nxd4
{ Exchanging the e2-knight opens the e-file for White to create pressure on the e6-pawn. }
15... Nxd4 16. exd4 Bd6
{ The more the pieces are exchanged, the better it is for Black. Endings favour Black as White's g6 pawn will become a target for Black's pieces. }
17. Qe3 Bxf4 18. Qxf4 Rc8
{ The rook is useful on the c-file and Black is ready to support the e6-pawn with ...Rc6. The position is fine Black. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "The Torre Attack"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. Bg5
{ The Torre Attack! We should again focus on developing our light-squared bishop out of the pawn chain before playing ...e6. }
3... Ne4
{ Centralizing the knight and attacking the bishop on g5 at the same time. } 4.
Bf4 { This is White's main retreat against ...Ne4. } 4... Bf5
{ Now we are all set to play ...e6 next and follow it up with ...Bd6, offering the exchange of dark-squared bishops. }
5. e3 e6 6. Nbd2 { A typical way of developing the b1-knight. } 6... Bd6 7. Bd3
{ White continues to develop his pieces without worrying about the doubling of the pawns on the f-file. }
7... Bxf4 8. exf4 Nd6
{ Retreating the knight before White could capture on e4 changing the pawn structure. }
9. Qe2 { Supporting the bishop on d3. } 9... O-O 10. O-O Nd7
{ Preparing to break in the centre with ...c5. } 11. c3 c5
{ Black has no problems whatsoever in this position. All our pieces are developed and we have a better pawn structure. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Colle Zukertort #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3
{ This defines the beginning of the Colle Zukertort variation. } 3... c5 4. b3
{ This is the most popular move order for White to enter the Zukertort setup. White intends to play Bc1-b2, Bf1-d3 and Nb1-d2. }
4... cxd4
{ We exchange on d4 immediately before White plays Bb2. The point is that now after the exchanges on d4, White is forced to recapture with the pawn while after Bb2 he will have the option of recapturing with the bishop. }
5. exd4
{ With the pawn on b2, White would develop his bishop on f4 without thinking. But with b3 played he is forced to fianchetto his bishop on b2. }
5... g6
{ Our dark-squared bishop is well placed on g7 to face the upcoming hanging pawns. }
6. Bb2 Bg7 7. Bd3 O-O 8. O-O Nc6
{ We intend to play ...Nb4 followed by ...Bf5. } 9. a3
{ White prevents ...Nb4. } 9... Ne4
{ We plan to play ... Bf5 next, supporting our e4-knight. } 10. Nbd2 Bf5 11.
Re1 Nd6
{ This is the best way to exchange the light-squared bishops. With Black's pieces actively placed we can claim to be slightly better here. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Colle Zukertort #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3
{ This defines the beginning of the Colle Zukertort variation. } 3... c5 4. c3
{ This is the traditional Colle pawn structure  @@StartBracket@@b2-c3-d4-e3-f2@@EndBracket@@. White also threatens to capture on c5 after which he can easily support his c5-pawn with b4. }
4... e6
{ We immediately support the c5-pawn and prepare to develop our dark-squared bishop at the same time. }
5. Nbd2 Nc6 6. Bd3
{ This is the usual way for White to place his pieces. knights on f3 and d2, while the bishop goes to d3. }
6... Bd6 7. O-O O-O
{ Both sides have castled safely and now it is up to White to initiate a plan. }
8. dxc5 { White exchanges on c5 so that he can break in the centre with e4. }
8... Bxc5 9. e4
{ Now White's ideal plan would be to advance the e-pawn further with e5 and create some attacking chances on the kingside. }
9... Qc7 { Our queen is well placed on c7 covering the e5-square. } 10. Qe2
{ White's queen supports the e5 advance from e2. } 10... b6
{ We prepare to develop our light-squared bishop. } 11. e5 Ng4
{ Black attacks the e5-pawn aggressively. } 12. Bxh7+
{ This is the tactical idea that White was counting on. } 12... Kxh7 13. Ng5+
Kg8 14. Qxg4 Qxe5
{ We have managed to get rid of the central e5-pawn in return for the wing pawn on h7, which is a good trade for us. In case White creates threats on the kingside, our queen is sufficient to handle them on her own.  Black is slightly better in this position because of the bishop pair and good central control. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "3.g3 without c2-c4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. g3
{ By fianchettoing his bishop on g2, without playing c2-c4, White plays in the style of the Grunfeld Defence. }
3... c5
{ Black intends to exchange on d4 and in case White recaptures with his knight then seize the centre with ...e5. }
4. Bg2 cxd4 5. O-O
{ White waits for Black to play ...Nc6 before capturing on d4 so that ...e5 can be met by exchanging on c6. }
5... h6 { A useful waiting move covering the g5-square. } 6. Nxd4 e5 7. Nb3 Nc6
{ Black has managed to seize the control in the centre. Now, it is up to White to find a way to challenge our central pawns. }
8. c4 { A typical pawn break in this structure. } 8... d4
{ We gain space in the centre with this advance. } 9. f4
{ White continues to undermine Black's centre. } 9... Be7
{ This is an interesting pawn sacrifice for the initiative. } 10. fxe5 Ng4 11.
Bxc6+
{ White should accept our offer. Otherwise, after the simple ...Nxe5 we regain our pawn with a better position. }
11... bxc6 12. Qxd4 Qxd4+ 13. Nxd4 Bc5 14. e3 Nxe5
{ Attacks the c4-pawn. If White defends it we can go ...Bh3 followed by ...Rd8 or O-O-O. White's queenside is still undeveloped and his pawns are targets for our pieces. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
