[Black "The Catalan #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. c4 e6 4. g3 { The super solid Catalan Opening. } 4...
dxc4 5. Bg2 c6
{ This is a slightly rare and fresh line against the Catalan which gives us fighting positions in most of the variations. GM Anton Guijarro is a strong advocate of this variation as this is his main weapon against the Catalan recently. With 5...c6 we aim to defend our dear pawn on c4 with b7-b5. }
6. Ne5 { White plans to recapture the c4-pawn quickly. } 6... Bb4+
{ An important intermediate check before we do something to defend our c4 pawn. }
7. Bd2 Be7
{ This was the point of ...Bb4+. We have provoked White's bishop to d2 and now the d4 pawn is hanging so White has to delay his plans of recovering the c4 pawn. }
8. e3 { White defends the d4-pawn and again gets ready to capture on c4. } 8...
b5 { This leads to an interesting exchange sacrifice! } 9. Nxc6
{ Accepting the sacrifice is the critical test of Black's idea. } 9... Nxc6 10.
Bxc6+ Bd7 11. Bxa8 Qxa8
{ White has won an exchange but after the departure of his light-squared bishop, the h1-a8 diagonal is seriously weakened which Black hopes to exploit. }
12. f3 { White delays O-O and covers some light squares in his camp. } 12... e5
{ A strong move opening up our light-squared bishop. } 13. O-O exd4 14. exd4
O-O
{ Both sides have castled but White's king is still not so comfortable on the kingside because of the weak light squares and absence of the light-squared bishop around the king.  One of Black's main ideas is to play ...Nd5 followed by ...Bf6 adding pressure on the d4-pawn. We can also think of expanding on the queenside with ...a5-b4 or on the kingside with ...h5-h4. Black has nice compensation for the exchange. }
