[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Deviations to Vienna 4.e3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. c4 e6 4. e3
{ is a safe but dull way of playing. White aims for strategic positions rather than trying to push for an advantage in the opening. }
4... a6
{ A generally useful move. One of the ideas is to capture on c4 and when White recaptures with the bishop we can play b7-b5. }
5. b3
{ White supports the c4-pawn so that he can recapture back with the b-pawn on c4. }
5... c5 6. Bb2 cxd4
{ With this exchange we get ready to face the hanging pawns. } 7. exd4 Nc6 8.
Bd3 { White prepares O-O. } 8... g6
{ Fianchettoing the bishop on g7 is the best way to play against the hanging pawns. }
9. O-O Bg7 10. Nbd2 { White develops his pieces normally. } 10... O-O
{ Now we intend to play ...dc4 followed by ...b6 and then ...Bb7. } 11. Ne5
{ White creates a disturbance in Black's plans. } 11... Nxd4
{ This is an interesting sacrifice that has not been played before. By eliminating the d4-pawn we aim to enhance the power of our dark-squared bishop on g7. }
12. Bxd4 dxc4 13. Bc5
{ This ensures that White wins an exchange, but we are going to get strong compensation for it. }
13... cxd3 14. Bxf8 Qxf8 15. Nxd3 Nd5
{ The power of our dark-squared bishop can be seen in its full flare. } 16. Rc1
Nc3 { The knight is actively placed on c3. } 17. Qf3 Bd7
{ With the idea to play ...Bc6 after which Black's minor pieces will exert strong pressure on White's position and he will have good compensation for the exchange. It is important to note that White cannot capture the b7-pawn due to ...Ne2+ winning the c1-Rook. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Vienna 5.Qa4+"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 dxc4 { This is the doorway to the Vienna! }
5. Qa4+
{ White decides to recapture the c4-pawn with his queen, which is handled in Chapter 9. }
5... Nbd7
{ We block the check with our knight and not with the c-pawn because we would like to break with ...c5 in one move. One of Black's main ideas is also to play ...a6 followed by ...b5. }
6. e4
{ The only challenging continuation. White controls the centre with e4-d4 and prepares to recapture the c4-pawn with his bishop. }
6... a6 { Preparing ...b5. } 7. Bxc4 Rb8 { Threatening ...b5. } 8. Qc2 b5 9.
Bd3 Bb7 { Now Black is ready to break with ...c5. } 10. e5
{ White gains more space in the centre and makes sure that Black does not get a chance to play ...c5. But, this surrenders the d5-square to Black forever. }
10... Nd5 11. Be4 { Preparing to exchange the light-squared bishops. } 11...
Nxc3 12. Bxb7 Rxb7 13. Qxc3 Be7 { Black prepares to O-O. } 14. Be3
{ Increasing control on the c5-square. } 14... O-O
{ Now Black's main idea is to transfer the knight to d5 via b6. } 15. Qc6
{ Forces the rook to the b6-square. } 15... Rb6 16. Qc2 Rb8
{ Black frees the b6-square for the knight. White should also watch for the ...c5-break which may be possible due to some concrete tactics. }
17. O-O Nb6
{ Black has a firm outpost on the d5 square, his bishop is slightly better than White's and he can think of expanding on the queenside with a6-a5-a4.  White on the other hand has pressure on the c-file and his knight also has a good post on the e4-square.  In short, the position is playable for both sides but I would prefer to play with the black pieces. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Vienna 5.g3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 dxc4 { This is the doorway to the Vienna! }
5. g3
{ Handled in Chapter 10, this is an inferior version of the Catalan Opening or the g3 variation in the Slav defence. }
5... c5
{ We start action in the centre immediately, creating pressure on the d4-pawn. }
6. Qa4+ { White goes for the c4-pawn. } 6... Bd7 7. Qxc4 b5
{ This move has never been played before. We sacrifice the b-pawn to open up lines on the queenside and bring our pieces out with a tempo. This time gained can be utilized to create pressure on the queenside. }
8. Nxb5
{ White has to accept the challenge otherwise he will simply be worse. } 8...
Qb6 { Attacking the b5-knight. } 9. Nc3 cxd4
{ Opening up lines before White gets a chance to settle down. } 10. Nxd4 Nc6
{ Attacking the d4-knight. We cannot afford to slow down yet. } 11. Nxc6 Bxc6
12. Be3
{ White attacks our queen using the fact that Black cannot capture the b2-pawn as the queen is tied down to the defence of the c6 bishop. }
12... Qb7 13. f3 Rc8 { Threats continue non-stop! } 14. Qb3 Bb4
{ Of course, we are not interested in exchanging queens as White's king is still in the centre. }
15. Bg2 O-O 16. Kf2 a5
{ All of Black's pieces are well placed and threats like Nf6-g4+ are in the air. We also exert sufficient pressure on the queenside and can think of adding more by playing Nf6-d5. All in all, Black has nice compensation for the pawn. }
