1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 dxc4 { This is the doorway to the Vienna! }
5. Bg5
{ White pins the f6-knight and can later decide whether to play e3 or e4 next. }
5... a6
{ White has delayed the capture of the c4-pawn, so we prepare to support it with ...b5. }
6. e4 { Threatening to recapture the c4-pawn. } 6... b5
{ Black is not worried about e5. } 7. e5 h6
{ A typical way of defending against the pin on the f6-knight. } 8. Bh4 g5
{ In the style of the Botvinnik variation of the Slav Defence. } 9. Nxg5 hxg5
10. Bxg5 { White threatens Bxf6. } 10... Nbd7 11. exf6 Bb7
{ Now Black threatens to take the f6 pawn with ...Nxf6. Also, ideas like ...Bh6 are possible. Black is doing fine here. }
