1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 dxc4 { This is the doorway to the Vienna! }
5. Bg5
{ White pins the f6-knight and can later decide whether to play e3 or e4 next. }
5... a6
{ White has delayed the capture of the c4-pawn, so we prepare to support it with ...b5. }
6. a4 { White prevents ...b5. } 6... Nc6
{ Black intends to defend his c4-pawn by placing the knight on a5. } 7. e3 Na5
8. Ne5 Bb4
{ Exploiting the drawback on a2-a4. Now our bishop is stable on the b4-square and cannot be kicked with a2-a3. }
9. Nxc4 Qd5
{ This is the advantage of pinning the c3-knight on the previous move.  9...Qd5  forces White to part with his bishop pair. }
10. Bxf6 Nxc4
{ This capture is more challenging for White as he needs to be aware of tactical ideas in this position. }
11. Bxg7 Rg8 12. Bf6 Rg6 { Kicking the bishop around. } 13. Bh8
{ Is the best move here sticking to the a1-h8 diagonal, but you will probably hardly ever face this move over the board! }
13... Bd7 { Black prepares O-O-O with a very strong initiative. } *

