[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 dxc4 { This is the doorway to the Vienna! }
5. e3
{ This has been the main response for White since the early days of the Vienna opening. }
5... a6 6. a4
{ White prepares to capture on c4 without allowing Black to gain space on the queenside with ...b5. But this seriously weakens the b4-square. }
6... c5 7. Bxc4 Nc6 8. O-O Be7 { Black prepares to O-O. } 9. Qe2
{ White intends to bring his rook to d1 creating threats against the black queen. }
9... cxd4
{ This leads to a simplification in the centre after an almost forced sequence of moves. }
10. Rd1 { White prepares to recapture on d4. } 10... e5
{ making sure White does not get his pawn back easily. } 11. exd4 exd4 12. Nxd4
{ White resorts to tactics to recover his lost pawn. } 12... Nxd4 13. Qe3
{ White is about to win the d4-knight. } 13... O-O 14. Rxd4 Qc7
{ White's pieces look a bit active right now but Black can easily neutralize it. }
15. Qd3 Rd8 { Exchanging White's active d4-rook. } 16. Bf4 Rxd4 17. Qxd4 Qc5
{ Exchanging White's active centralized queen as well. } 18. Qxc5 Bxc5
{ Black is ready to develop his bishop and then bring his rook into the game with a completely equal endgame. }
