1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 dxc4 { This is the doorway to the Vienna! }
5. e3
{ This has been the main response for White since the early days of the Vienna opening. }
5... a6 6. Bxc4 b5 7. Bd3 c5
{ Black challenges the centre quickly before developing his minor pieces. } 8.
O-O Bb7 9. Qe2 { White prepares Rd1. } 9... Nbd7
{ Black has placed his pieces ideally on d7 and b7. } 10. Rd1 Qb8
{ A typical reaction to Rd1. We remove our queen from the d-file to avoid any future tricks with the white rook in front of our queen. From b8 our queen also exerts pressure on the h2-b8 diagonal as we will soon see. }
11. e4
{ White marches forward in the centre and is ready to advance further with e5 or d5. }
11... cxd4 12. Nxd4 Bd6 { Developing with tempo! } 13. h3 O-O
{ Black has developed all his minor pieces and also successfully castled. We have more space on the queenside and good control in the centre, especially the e5-square. Black is doing fine. This line is covered in Chapter 13 }
