1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 dxc4 { This is the doorway to the Vienna! }
5. e4
{ This aggressive way of playing against the Vienna has become the main weapon for White lately. }
5... Bb4 6. Bxc4
{ This is a dynamic line where White sacrifices the e4-pawn in an attempt to seize the initiative as speedily as possible. }
6... Nxe4 { We accept the challenge. } 7. O-O Nf6
{ We retreat the knight to f6 as it can play a huge role in defending White's kingside aggression. }
8. Qa4+ { White forces ...Nc6. } 8... Nc6 9. Ne5
{ This is the point behind forcing ...Nc6. White threatens to win the b4-bishop by playing Nxc6. }
9... Bd6 { We sacrifice the pawn back to get rid of threats. } 10. Nxc6 bxc6
11. Qxc6+ Bd7 12. Qf3 O-O
{ Black has safely O-O and avoided an early assault by White. } 13. Bg5
{ White creates pressure against the f6-knight and intends to increase it by playing Ne4. }
13... h6 14. Bh4 Rb8
{ Attacking the b2-pawn while also preparing to go to the b6 square. } 15. b3
Rb6
{ Black intends to improve the position of the light-square bishop with ... Bc6 next. }
16. Ne4 { This leads to simplifications after } 16... Be7 17. Nxf6+ Bxf6 18.
Bxf6 Qxf6 19. Qxf6 gxf6
{ And we have reached an endgame which is completely fine for Black. Black's main source of counterplay is the a5-a4 pawn advance on the queenside. }
