[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Vienna 5.e4 Bb4 6.Bg5 with 7.e5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 dxc4 { This is the doorway to the Vienna! }
5. e4
{ This aggressive way of playing against the Vienna has become the main weapon for White lately. }
5... Bb4 6. Bg5 c5 7. e5
{ This attempt to win the f6-knight leads to complicated play where tactics dominate. }
7... cxd4 { Black counter-attacks by hitting the c3-knight. } 8. Qa4+
{ White finds a forcing way to O-O-O and take his king to safety on the queenside while also bringing his rook into the game. }
8... Nc6 { The only move, supporting the b4-bishop. } 9. O-O-O
{ White has achieved his idea. Now the f6-knight is under attack and so is the d4-pawn. }
9... Bd7
{ A strong move! Breaking the pin on the c6-knight and reigniting the threat of dxc3. }
10. Ne4
{ White protects his own knight and continues to put pressure on the f6-knight. }
10... Be7
{ Black gives up the f6-knight. But it is important to remember that we have already won two pawns on c4-d4 and once White captures our f6-knight, we are going to get a third white pawn. }
11. exf6 gxf6 12. Bh4
{ A critical position. White has won a piece but at the cost of three pawns which maintains the material balance in the position. The pawns on d4 and c4 limit White's pieces effectively and can be useful in creating an attack against White's king. }
12... a6
{ This silent little move is an important one to remember. We threaten to play b7-b5 after which White's position will be extremely passive. So, White is more or less forced to capture the c4-pawn and open the c-file for our rook. }
13. Qxc4 e5
{ Another simple move, supporting the very important pawn on d4 and also opening up the black light-squared bishop to come to active squares like e6 or f5. Black's a8 rook is ready to come to c8 where, combined with ideas like ...Nb4, it can create serious threats on the queenside. Another important fact is that the white queen is badly misplaced on the c-file. }
14. Nxe5
{ With this return sacrifice White destroys the black central pawn shield and curbs our initiative. }
14... Nxe5 15. Qxd4
{ White has eliminated all three black pawns. Black's kingside is slightly weak but Black has good counterplay on the queenside which ensures that White does not have sufficient time to exploit it. }
15... O-O
{ With O-O Black completes his development and now we are ready to start action on the queenside. Black has sufficient counterplay on the queenside to maintain the balance. I have analyzed this position in further detail in Chapter 17. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Vienna 5.e4 Bb4 6.Bg5 with 7.Bxc4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 dxc4 { This is the doorway to the Vienna! }
5. e4
{ This aggressive way of playing against the Vienna has become the main weapon for White lately. }
5... Bb4 6. Bg5 c5 7. Bxc4
{ The most popular line for White and is analyzed in Chapters 18, 19 and 20. Here I will just mention the most important lines that you need to know after 7.Bxc4. }
7... cxd4 8. Nxd4 Bxc3+
{ it is better to exchange on c3 immediately before playing ...Qa5.     The immediate  8...Qa5  gives white an additional option of  9.Bd2 }
9. bxc3 Qa5 { Threatening both the g5-bishop and the c3-pawn. } 10. Nb5
{ This is the third most popular move in this position. White supports the c3-pawn and at the same time has ideas to exploit the control on the d6 and c7 squares, thanks to his active knight on b5. White is ready to sacrifice his e4 pawn for the initiative. }
10... Nxe4
{ Black should accept the challenge. The position now becomes very concrete and it is important to study the upcoming moves carefully and remember them clearly. }
11. Bf4
{ This continuation is much stronger and requires more precision from Black. As compensation for the pawn, White has a strong pair of bishops. At the same time, Black is behind in development and his knight is quite vulnerable in the centre. Nevertheless, Black has enough resources to keep the balance. }
11... O-O 12. O-O Nc6
{ Black is ready to advance ...e5 and cut off White's f4 bishop from the queenside. }
13. Bc7 b6 14. Qf3
{ This forces us to weaken our kingside. White is trying his best to create some targets to attack in Black's position. }
14... f5 15. Rfe1 a6
{ Kicking the White knight from its annoying active post. } 16. Nd4 Ne5
{ Compeling White to part with his bishop pair. } 17. Bxe5 Qxe5
{ And Black is doing just fine. White still has good compensation for the pawn here due to the weak e6-pawn and pressure down the e-file, but Black can manage it pretty well. I have analyzed the continuation further in Chapter 18. }
*

