[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 dxc4 { This is the doorway to the Vienna! }
5. e4
{ This aggressive way of playing against the Vienna has become the main weapon for White lately. }
5... Bb4 6. Bg5 c5 7. Bxc4
{ The most popular line for White and is analyzed in Chapters 18, 19 and 20. Here I will just mention the most important lines that you need to know after 7.Bxc4. }
7... cxd4 8. Nxd4 Bxc3+
{ it is better to exchange on c3 immediately before playing ...Qa5.     The immediate  8...Qa5  gives white an additional option of  9.Bd2 }
9. bxc3 Qa5 { Threatening both the g5-bishop and the c3-pawn. } 10. Bxf6
{ This is the second most popular move for white. He exchanges on f6 first and intends to O-O next. }
10... Qxc3+
{ Of course we don't give him the chance to O-O and grab the c3-pawn immediately. }
11. Kf1 gxf6 { This is the correct White bishop to capture. } 12. Rc1
{ A logical move. Attacking the Black queen and hoping to create pressure on the c-file. }
12... Qa5
{ It is important to control the c7 square preventing the white knight from arriving there in the future. }
13. h4
{ An interesting way to activate the sleeping rook on h1. White intends to bring his rook to the action with Rh3. }
13... Ke7
{ Black plans to bring his kingside rook to d8 at the correct moment. } 14. Rh3
Nc6
{ it's essential to challenge the d4-knight quickly before it starts to create problems for us.   14...Rd8??  is a huge mistake due to  15.Re3!!+-  when the threat of Nf5+ is extremely lethal for Black. }
15. Nxc6+ bxc6 16. Rd3 Rd8 { simplifications are always welcome for Black. }
17. Rxd8 Qxd8 18. Qh5 Qd4
{ We have centralized our queen and Black is doing completely fine in this position. Our next plan would be to activate our rook with ...Rb8. I have analyzed this position further which can be found in Chapter 19. }
