[Black "Vienna 5.e4 Bb4 6.Bg5 with 7.Bxc4 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 dxc4 { This is the doorway to the Vienna! }
5. e4
{ This aggressive way of playing against the Vienna has become the main weapon for White lately. }
5... Bb4 6. Bg5 c5 7. Bxc4
{ The most popular line for White and is analyzed in Chapters 18, 19 and 20. Here I will just mention the most important lines that you need to know after 7.Bxc4. }
7... cxd4 8. Nxd4 Bxc3+
{ it is better to exchange on c3 immediately before playing ...Qa5.     The immediate  8...Qa5  gives white an additional option of  9.Bd2 }
9. bxc3 Qa5 { Threatening both the g5-bishop and the c3-pawn. } 10. Bb5+
{ The most popular move by White. } 10... Bd7 11. Bxf6
{ White needs to exchange on f6 as the bishop on g5 is always under the radar of the black queen on a5 and Black has ideas like ...Ne4 in air. }
11... gxf6 12. Bxd7+ Nxd7 13. O-O
{ There are more than 100 games played from this position and now I would like to propose a rare line for Black! }
13... Qxc3
{ Black simply grabs the c3 pawn and challenges white to prove compensation for it. As we will see, Black has sufficient resources to defend against White's threats. }
14. Qa4
{ This is the critical test for black's idea with 13...Qc3. White prevents the black king from running to the kingside and connects his rooks at the same time. }
14... O-O
{ We take our king to safety nonetheless, using tactics.   If White captures our knight with  15.Qxd7  we have  15...Rad8  winning the d4-knight. }
15. Nxe6 { White uses tactics in return, destroying Black's pawn structure. }
15... Nb6 { A counter-attack on the white queen. } 16. Qd4
{ This was White's point behind 15.Nxe6! } 16... Rfc8
{ It is better to exchange queens while activating our rook at the same time. }
17. Qxc3 Rxc3 18. Nf4
{ This is the best square for the white knight. He intends to play Nf4-h5 next to attack the f6-pawn. }
18... f5
{ A strong novelty! Black immediately gets rid of his weak pawn on f6. } 19.
exf5 Rc5 20. Rfd1 Rxf5
{ Despite White having a slightly better pawn structure on the kingside, Black maintains balance in this endgame. Further analysis can be found in Chapter 20. }
