[Black "Deviations to Avoid Benko #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nf3 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e6
{ Preparing to develop our dark-squared bishop to b4. } 5. g3 Bb4+ 6. Nc3
{ With this move we enter the Romanishin variation of the Nimzo-Indian. } 6...
O-O 7. Bg2 d5
{ Black immediately breaks in the centre and also hopes to put pressure on the pinned knight on c3 with subsequent moves. White now needs to address our question that we posed to the c4-pawn. }
8. cxd5 Nxd5 { Threatening to take on c3. } 9. Qb3 Qb6
{ We not only attack the knight on d4 but also threaten to win a pawn with ....Bxc3+. With both queens standing in front of each other, the exchange of queens is highly probable transposing into an endgame. }
10. Bxd5
{ It is necessary for White to eliminate our d5-knight so that he can play Bc1-e3 on the next move. }
10... exd5 11. Be3 Nc6
{ This is the simplest way to transposes into a roughly equal opposite coloured bishops endgame. }
12. Nxc6 Bxc3+ 13. Qxc3 Qxc6 14. Qxc6 bxc6
{ White may claim to have a slight edge on paper due to Black's weaker pawn structure, but, because of the presence of opposite coloured bishops, this endgame is highly drawish in practical play.   A general plan for Black is to play Bc8-d7 and Rf8-b8. Then we should arrange our pawns with f7-f6 @@StartBracket@@limiting the White bishop which will most probably stand on d4@@EndBracket@@ and a7-a5-a4 @@StartBracket@@gaining space on the queenside@@EndBracket@@. }
*

