[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Deviations to Avoid Benko #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. e3
{ White avoids playing d4-d5 immediately and thus prevents us from playing the Benko. At the same time with 3.e3 White does not aim to fight a direct advantage. }
3... g6
{ There are many satisfactory ways for Black to deal with 3.e3, but I want to recommend a setup with our bishop on g7 as this is how we are going to play in the Benko as well. At the same time, I wanted to avoid entering the Benoni structure which is a completely different territory altogether. }
4. Nc3
{ This is the most challenging move order for Black. White ensures that we are not able to achieve our plan easily of capturing on d4 with ...cxd4 followed by playing ...d5. }
4... cxd4 5. exd4 Bg7
{ Now we are all set to play ...d5.   We don't want to play  5...d5  immediately because  6.Qb3  is very annoying for Black. }
6. d5 { White puts his own pawn on d5 and prevents us from playing ...d5. }
6... O-O 7. Nf3 e6
{ We start our action in the centre and open lines for our pieces. } 8. Be2
{ White prepares to O-O. } 8... exd5 9. cxd5 d6
{ Opening up the light-squared bishop. } 10. O-O Nbd7
{ Our knight would like to go to c5 from where it will always have the option of playing ...Nfe4 and challenge White's c3 knight. }
11. Be3 Nc5 12. Rc1 Re8 { Our rook is useful on the e-file. } 13. Re1 Bd7
{ We prepare to bring our a8-rook to c8. } 14. Nd4 Rc8 15. h3 Nfe4
{ Exchanging the c3-knight is favourable for us as it makes the d5-pawn a little shaky and opens up our dark-squared bishop on g7. }
16. Nxe4 Nxe4
{ And we reach a fine position for Black. Major pieces are likely to be exchanged on the open c-file. }
*

