[Black "Benko Gambit Sideline 4.Nd2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5
{ Welcome to the world of Benko Gambit! Now White has two options. Either he can decline the Gambit or accept it and I have covered variations arising from both the ways of handling the Benko. }
4. Nd2
{ This is an odd way of developing the knight and preparing e4. No prize in guessing that 4.Nd2 is played less frequently. }
4... bxc4 5. e4
{ White supports the d5-pawn and prepared to recapture the c4-pawn with his bishop. }
5... e6 { We continue to challenge the d5-pawn. } 6. Bxc4 exd5 7. exd5 d6
{ Now Black's plan is clear. We want to play ...Be7 and ...O-O. } 8. Ne2
{ White develops his knight to e2 and not to f3 in order to keep both his knights flexible. }
8... Be7 9. O-O O-O
{ Both sides have castled safely and now it's time to develop queenside pieces. }
10. b3 { White prepares to fianchetto his bishop. } 10... Nbd7
{ We want to put our knight on b6 so that it can exert pressure on both d5 and c4. }
11. Bb2 Nb6 { Threatening to take the d5-pawn. } 12. Nc3 Nxc4
{ Exchanging the bishop before White gets a chance to move it away. } 13. Nxc4
Ba6 { Our bishop exerts pressure along the f1-a6 diagonal. } 14. Re1 Re8 15.
Ne4
{ Eliminating the f6-knight with the hope to create some pressure on the a1-h8 diagonal. }
15... Bxc4 16. bxc4 Nxe4 17. Rxe4 Bf8
{ More simplifications are about to occur in the position with a completely fine position for Black. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Benko Gambit Sideline 4.a4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5
{ Welcome to the world of Benko Gambit! Now White has two options. Either he can decline the Gambit or accept it and I have covered variations arising from both the ways of handling the Benko. }
4. a4
{ With 4.a4 White forces Black to make a decision on the queenside. Again this move is not played regularly and can be considered a sideline. }
4... Qa5+
{ Once we close the queenside with ...b4 White would like to fianchetto his bishop with b2-b3 and Bc1-b2. But by interposing ...Qa5+ we provoke him to play Bd2 which misplaces his bishop and he cannot fianchetto anymore. }
5. Bd2 b4
{ Now we close the queenside. Our plan is very simple. We want to go ...g6, ... d6, ...Bg7 and then O-O. Once this is done we can think about whether to close the centre with ...e5 and start playing on the kingside @@StartBracket@@this is usually done when White has already castled on the kingside@@EndBracket@@ or we can play ...e6 and open up the centre. }
6. Qc2 { White prepares e4. } 6... g6 7. e4 d6 { Preventing e5. } 8. Bd3 Bg7 9.
h3
{ White covers the g4 square which prevents any future ideas like ... Bg4 or ...Ng4-Ne5. }
9... O-O 10. Nf3 Qc7
{ The queen was not doing anything on a5, so Black brings it back. } 11. O-O e5
{ The correct strategy! It might seem like a counter-intuitive move closing the diagonal of our strong dark-squared bishop, but our main point is that we want to close the centre and start creating an attack on the kingside. This structure is quite similar to the King's Indian Defence, though, with one big difference. White does not have his traditional counter-play on the queenside as it closed here. So, it is just a one-way attack for Black on the kingside. }
12. Qc1 Nh5 13. b3 f5 { Black gets a strong attack on the kingside. } *

