[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Benko Gambit Sideline 4.f3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5
{ Welcome to the world of Benko Gambit! Now White has two options. Either he can decline the Gambit or accept it and I have covered variations arising from both the ways of handling the Benko. }
4. f3
{ With 4.f3, White does not care about Black's pawn sacrifice with ...b5 and decides to prepare e4 next. }
4... bxc4 5. e4 d6
{ We prevent e4-e5 and now our plan is very straightforward. We want to go ... g6-Bg7 and then O-O. }
6. Bxc4 g6 7. Ne2 { White prepares to O-O. } 7... Bg7 8. O-O O-O 9. Nec3
{ White wants to put one knight on c3, hoping to manoeuvre the other knight to c4 via d2 or a3 in future. }
9... Nbd7
{ This is the best way of developing the b8-knight. Our knight can go to e5 or b6. }
10. Be2 { Freeing the c4-square for the knight. } 10... Ne8
{ A strong novelty! After ...Ne8 we have two plans. The chief plan is to break with ...f5 with the idea to exchange on e4 with ...fxe4. Another plan is to play ...Nc7 followed by ...Ba6, exchanging the light-squared bishops. }
11. Na3 { White intends to plant his knight on c4. } 11... f5
{ A strong pawn break which allows Black to create counterplay. } 12. exf5
{ This prevents the opening of the f-file but it also weakens the d5-pawn a bit. }
12... Rxf5 13. Nc4 Nc7 { We start creating pressure against the d5-pawn. } 14.
Kh1 Nb6 15. Ne3 { Protecting the d5-pawn and kicking the rook from f5. } 15...
Rf4
{ The white pawn on d5 needs constant care from White's minor pieces. We have ideas like ...Bb7 by which we can increase pressure on the d5 pawn or ...e6 which eliminates the d5 pawn so that we can start rolling our d-pawn forward. Black has good play in this position. }
*

