[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Benko Gambit Sideline 4.Nf3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5
{ Welcome to the world of Benko Gambit! Now White has two options. Either he can decline the Gambit or accept it and I have covered variations arising from both the ways of handling the Benko. }
4. Nf3
{ This is one of the main ways to decline the pawn sacrifice. White waits for Black to capture with ...dxc4 so that he can play Nc3 followed by e4. }
4... Bb7
{ We develop our bishop and create pressure on the d5-pawn which will be useful when we break in the centre with ...e6. Also, we delay the decision of capturing on c4 keep White in the dark on the best way to develop his queenside knight. }
5. a4
{ White forces black to make a decision on the queenside so that it would be clear for him to develop the knight on c3 or on d2. }
5... Qa5+
{ A nice intermediate move. We provoke Bd2 so that we can then close the queenside with ...b4. }
6. Bd2 b4
{ Now the White bishop is misplaced on d2 as it should have been on the a1-h8 diagonal. }
7. Qc2 { White prepares e4. } 7... d6 8. e4 Nbd7
{ Covering the e5 square and preventing e4-e5. } 9. Bd3 g6 10. O-O Bg7 11. h3
O-O
{ Both sides have castled. Now it is time to break in the centre with ...e6. }
12. Be3 Rae8
{ All our pieces are well placed and now we can think of playing either e7-e5 or e7-e6. }
13. Nbd2 e6
{ It is better to advance our e-pawn one square for now so that we always have the option of either capturing on d5 or advancing further with ...e5. }
14. Rae1 Qc7
{ Black is doing completely fine in this position. It is in our hands when to close the position in the centre with e7-e5 and start playing on the kingside. }
*

