[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Benko Gambit Mainline 4.Qc2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5
{ Welcome to the world of Benko Gambit! Now White has two options. Either he can decline the Gambit or accept it and I have covered variations arising from both the ways of handling the Benko. }
4. Qc2 { This is another way of preparing the desirable pawn advance e4. } 4...
bxc4 5. e4 e6
{ We hit the centre immediately as we do in some other variations of the Benko. }
6. Bxc4 exd5 7. exd5 d6
{ Black simply wants to play ...Be7 and follow it up with ...O-O next. } 8. Nf3
Be7 9. O-O O-O
{ Both sides have castled and now it is time to focus on developing the queenside. }
10. Nc3 Nbd7
{ The knight aims to go to b6 from where it can put pressure on the d5-pawn and the c4-square. }
11. h3 { A generally useful move for White covering the g4-square. } 11... Nb6
12. b3 Rb8
{ The b-file is about to open soon once we exchange on c4, so it is useful to place our rook on the b-file. }
13. Bf4
{ This bishop is well placed on f4 and always keeps an eye on the d6-pawn. So we start playing against this bishop immediately before it puts pressure on our position. }
13... Nxc4 14. bxc4 Nh5
{ Immediately playing against White's dark-squared bishop before he gets a chance to bring his rooks into play and settle down. }
15. Bd2 f5 { With  15...f5  we gain space on the kingside. } 16. Nb5
{ Threatening to capture the a7-pawn. } 16... Qd7 17. Ng5
{ Heading towards the e6-square. } 17... Bxg5 18. Bxg5
{ Black has lost the bishop pair but now we can start pushing White's pieces back with, }
18... h6 19. Bd2 a6 { Time to kick the knight back from b5. } 20. Nc3 Rb4
{ Attacking the c4-pawn. } 21. Ne2 Qa4
{ Exchanging the queens favours Black as it helps us to create pressure on the queenside. }
22. Rfc1 Qxc2 23. Rxc2 Ra4
{ Our idea now is to play ...f4 which of course White should stop. Black has pressure on the queenside because of our active rook on a4, but it will be difficult to break through as White is quite solid. The presence of the opposite coloured bishops makes this endgame pretty equal. }
*

