[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Benko Gambit Accepted Sideline 5.f3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5
{ Welcome to the world of Benko Gambit! Now White has two options. Either he can decline the Gambit or accept it and I have covered variations arising from both the ways of handling the Benko. }
4. cxb5 a6 5. f3
{ White sacrifices the pawn back to speedily put his pawns in the centre with f3-e4. }
5... e6
{ We hit the centre immediately and does not allow White to consolidate in the centre. }
6. e4 exd5 7. e5
{ This is White's only challenging try. White pushes our active f6-knight back before developing his own pieces. }
7... Qe7 { Pinning the e5-pawn. } 8. Qe2 Ng8
{ We have finished 8 moves and all the pieces except queens are on their initial squares! }
9. Nc3 { Developing the knight as well as hitting the d5-pawn. } 9... Bb7 10.
Nh3
{ The White knight can further go to f4 increasing pressure on the d5-pawn. }
10... c4
{ An important pawn advance for Black. This cuts the support of the b5 pawn and gains space for Black on the queenside. It always frees the c5 and b4 square for the Black queen. }
11. Nf4 { The d5-pawn is under attack again. } 11... Qc5 12. Nfxd5
{ This tactical trick leads to wild complications! } 12... Bxd5 13. Be3 Qb4
{ Black is holding on to his extra piece for now. } 14. a3 Qa5 15. Bd2
{ White unpins the c3-knight and threatens to capture on d5. } 15... Be6
{ With  15...Be6  ,  we keep the c4-pawn supported for a while. } 16. Nd5 c3
{ It is better to give up the c-pawn on c3 so that when White captures it will close the c-file and White will not be able to create pressure on it. }
17. Bxc3 Qd8 18. Qc4 Ra7 { Preventing Nc7+. } 19. Qd4 Ra8 20. Nb6 axb5
{ Giving up the rook on a8. } 21. Nxa8 Nc6 22. Qd2 Qxa8 23. Bxb5 Qa7
{ An important intermediate move preventing White from O-O. Next Black will focus on developing his kingside. Black is doing well here. }
*

[Event "?"]
