[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Benko Gambit Accepted Sideline 5.Nc3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5
{ Welcome to the world of Benko Gambit! Now White has two options. Either he can decline the Gambit or accept it and I have covered variations arising from both the ways of handling the Benko. }
4. cxb5 a6 5. Nc3
{ This is known as the Zaitsev line. White's main idea behind this line is to plant his knight on the b5-square, into enemy territory. }
5... axb5 6. e4
{ Only this way, by sacrificing his e4-pawn can White hope to establish his knight on the b5-square. White does not care much about losing the e4-pawn as if Black captures it then he can create threats down the e-file. }
6... b4 7. Nb5 d6
{ Now Black is ready to snatch the e4-pawn. If White defends it directly or indirectly then we can simply play ...g6 followed by ...Bg7 and O-O. }
8. a4
{ This has been played regularly by the Russian GM Ponkratov. White get rids of the weakness of the a2-pawn and cements his knight on b5 at the same time. }
8... g6 { Black prepares to play ...Bg7 and then ...O-O. } 9. Bd3 Bg7 10. Nf3
O-O 11. O-O Bg4
{ It is good for Black to exchange the knight on f3. Once the knight is eliminated, we get complete control over the e5 square so we don't need to worry about a future e4-e5 break. }
12. h3 Bxf3 13. Qxf3 Nbd7
{ Now one of our main ideas is to put pressure on the a4-pawn which cannot be defended immediately with b2-b3 as there are tricks on the a1-h8 diagonal. After playing ...Nb6 we would also like to advance our queenside pawns with c5-c4. White should also watch out for ...Ne5 exchanging White's light-squared bishop. }
14. Qe2 Nb6 { Threatening to capture the a4-pawn. } 15. Bc2 Nfd7
{ With the idea to play c5-c4. } 16. Bb3
{ White prevents the pawn advance ...c5-c4. } 16... Ra5
{ Black prepares ...Qa8 creating pressure on the a4-pawn. } 17. Bg5 h6 18. Bh4
g5 19. Bg3 Qa8
{ Black will win the pawn on a4 and we have sufficient defensive resources on the kingside in case White thinks of attacking with f2-f4. Also, it is important to note that once the a4-pawn falls, the knight on b5 might lose as well. }
*

