[Black "Benko Gambit Accepted  Mainline 5.e3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5
{ Welcome to the world of Benko Gambit! Now White has two options. Either he can decline the Gambit or accept it and I have covered variations arising from both the ways of handling the Benko. }
4. cxb5 a6 5. e3
{ 5.e3  is a popular line frequently seen in Grandmaster games. } 5... g6
{ Black goes for the traditional Benko set-up. Now as mentioned earlier, if you compare this to the mainline 5.bxa6, White will be a move late in getting his pawn to e4. We would like to use this precious time and hit in the centre with Bc8-b7 followed by e7-e6 at the right moment before White settles down comfortably. }
6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Nf3 O-O 8. a4
{ This is a generally useful move for white on the queenside. } 8... Bb7
{ We develop our bishop and pressurize the d5-pawn at the same time. Our next move can be ...e6 breaking in the centre. }
9. e4
{ White increases his control in the centre by supporting the d5-pawn beforehand. }
9... e6
{ We continue with the strategy of putting pressure on White's centre as quickly as possible. }
10. Be2 axb5
{ This is the correct time to exchange on b5 as White has just moved his bishop from f1. }
11. Bxb5 exd5 { Opening the e-file before White castles. } 12. exd5 Qe7+
{ Giving a check with the queen is more effective than ...Re8+. } 13. Be2 Na6
{ The knight heads towards the weak b4-square. } 14. d6
{ This is the only challenging try for an advantage. White pushes his vulnerable d5 pawn to d6 but it opens up the h1-a8 diagonal for our light-squared bishop. }
14... Qe6 15. O-O Nb4
{ All Black's pieces are actively placed and I believe Black has a definite compensation here. Black's knight is firmly placed on the weak b4 square and the bishop on b7 exerts pressure on the h1-a8 diagonal. Black's queen on e6 keeps an eye on the d6-pawn making it essential for White to keep constant attention on it. }
*

