[Black "Benko Gambit Accepted  Mainline 5.b6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5
{ Welcome to the world of Benko Gambit! Now White has two options. Either he can decline the Gambit or accept it and I have covered variations arising from both the ways of handling the Benko. }
4. cxb5 a6 5. b6
{ White gives the pawn back keeping the lines closed on the queenside aiming for a positional struggle ahead. }
5... e6
{ We immediately start grappling in the centre before White gets a chance to increase the hold with Nb1-c3 and e2-e4. The pawn on b6 is going nowhere and will be won sooner or later. }
6. Nc3 Nxd5 7. Nxd5 exd5 8. Qxd5 Nc6
{ There have been a couple of exchanges on d5 and it might seem that White has gained a nice control on this square. But, in fact, the queen is very unstable on d5 as it can be easily chased away. Black would like to play Bf8-e7 followed by O-O and then taking the pawn on b6. }
9. Nf3
{ White not only develops his knight but also threatens Nf3-e5 at the same time, exploiting the pin on the c6-knight. }
9... Rb8
{ Black gets away from the pin on the c6-knight and prepares to play ...Rxb6 at the right moment. }
10. e4 { Intending to develop the bishop actively to c4. } 10... Be7 11. Bc4
O-O 12. O-O Rxb6
{ Both sides have completed their development and the position is around equal. White has control on the important d5 square while Black has pressure on the b-file and a decent control of the d4-square. The control of the d4-square is important for Black in this structure because we would like to establish one of our pieces @@StartBracket@@mostly our knight@@EndBracket@@ on d4.  Black will soon start contesting for the control of the d5-square. Our immediate plan is to play d7-d6 followed by developing the bishop to e6.  This line can be found in Chapter 32. }
*

