[Black "Benko Gambit Accepted  Mainline 5.bxa6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5
{ Welcome to the world of Benko Gambit! Now White has two options. Either he can decline the Gambit or accept it and I have covered variations arising from both the ways of handling the Benko. }
4. cxb5 a6 5. bxa6 g6 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Nf3 O-O 8. g3
{ Fianchettoing the bishop on g2 has always been an attractive way of playing from the White Side in the Benko Gambit Accepted lines. }
8... d6 9. Bg2 Nxa6
{ This is the point of delaying the capture on a6. Now, instead of the traditional capture with the bishop we recapture on a6 with our knight so as to use our light-squared bishop on h3-c6 diagonal. }
10. O-O Bf5
{ Black has developed all his pieces and we are now ready to play ...Qa5 or ...Qc7 followed by bringing the f8-rook on the queenside to the b8-square. The bishop on f5 stops White's plan of Ra1-b1 followed by b2-b3. }
11. Nh4 { White kicks our well-placed bishop back from the f5-square. } 11...
Bd7 12. Rb1
{ White moves his rook away from the a1-h8 diagonal and prepares to play b3. }
12... Qa5
{ We place our queen actively on a5 and again prevent White from playing b3. }
13. Bd2 Rfb8
{ The rook joins the party on the queenside. Now Black's main idea is to play Na6-c7-b5. The exchange of the knights will shake up the white queenside. }
14. b3
{ White sets up his queenside pawn structure in an ideal way and intends to play a4, gaining some space on the queenside. }
14... Qa3 { Preventing a2-a4. } 15. Bc1 Qa5 16. Bb2 c4
{ a strong novelty! With a timely pawn break on the queenside Black opens up lines for pieces to create counter-play. Black has a nice pressure on the queenside and is going good here.  This 7.Nf3 line can be found in Chapter 34. }
*

