[Black "Benko Gambit Accepted  Mainline 5.bxa6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5
{ Welcome to the world of Benko Gambit! Now White has two options. Either he can decline the Gambit or accept it and I have covered variations arising from both the ways of handling the Benko. }
4. cxb5 a6 5. bxa6 g6 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. e4 O-O 8. e5
{ White pushes the knight back from f6 so that he can create a direct onslaught on Black's kingside. }
8... Ne8 9. h4
{ White starts his assault speedily on the kingside and plans to play h5 next. This line is quite complicated and I will be covering the mainline in this Quickstarter guide. However, to get a complete understanding I would urge the readers to take a good look at chapter 32. }
9... Bxe5
{ It is essential to eliminate the e5-pawn immediately so that we can arrange our pieces appropriately in order to face White's onslaught. Once we address and slow down White's kingside attack then we can focus on creating our own counterplay. }
10. Bh6
{ White puts his bishop actively on h6 and prepares to play Qd2 sometime soon. }
10... Ng7 11. Nf3 { Developing the knight as well as hitting the e5-bishop. }
11... Bf6 12. h5 d6
{ We are at a critical juncture where White should decide how to continue the attack. }
13. Qd2 { White places his queen on the ideal d2 square and prepares O-O-O. }
13... Qa5
{ The a5 square is the best for the Black queen in this position in terms of creating counterplay. From a5 it puts pressure on the c3-knight and also the a2-pawn if White moves his rook from a1. }
14. Ng5 { White brings his pieces closer to the Black king. } 14... Nxa6
{ Capturing with the knight always gives Black an option of going ...Nb4 which would be very strong if White decides to O-O-O. }
15. Rc1 Rb8
{ Our rook is well placed on the b-file, eyeing the b2-pawn, which we know well by now, is a source of counterplay for black. Black's kingside is safe for now and he has sufficient counterplay on the queenside to hold the balance.  This 7.e4 line can be found in Chapter 33. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. London System"]
[Black "London System 4.c3 Qb6 5.Qc2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
{ The London system has become very popular nowadays. At first, this system was a favourite among the players who just liked to get a 'game' and take opponents out of book. But with more and more games played regularly, especially by the World Champion Magnus Carlsen himself, the London has become quite popular and theoretically dense. It mostly comprises strategic elements and plans but there are also some lines that have a very concrete nature.  I am recommending an easy-to-follow setup against the London system but there are some lines in which you need to study the concrete variations carefully. }
2... d5 3. e3
{ This is undoubtedly the most flexible move order for White. He has to play e2-e3 at some point so it is better to play it immediately and later decide when to develop the g1-knight to f3.   3.Nf3  c5  4.e3  transposes to the mainline. }
3... c5 4. c3
{ White sets up a typical London pawn structure and delays the development of the g1-knight. }
4... Qb6 5. Qc2
{ Is a passive way of defending the b2-pawn and just an inferior version of the 6. Qb3 variation. We can continue with, }
5... Nc6 6. Nd2 { 6.Nf3  transposes } 6... Nh5
{ Exploiting the fact that the h5 square is no longer covered by the white queen.   6...g6!?  with the idea to play ...Bf5 is another decent alternative. }
7. Be5 { Can be met by } 7... cxd4 8. exd4
{ Against  8.cxd4  we play the same  8...f6!  9.Bg3  e5!  and Black gains a nice initiative in the centre. }
8... f6 9. Bg3 e5 10. dxe5 Nxg3 11. hxg3 fxe5
{ Black has seized the centre and the bishop pair as well. } *

