{ Was once tried by the World Champion in a blitz game against Kramnik.   8.Bd3  is not much different from the mainline.  8...Bxd3  9.Qxd3  e6  10.O-O  Be7  11.a4  a6!  this is a typical response to White's a2-a4 advance.  12.Ne5  Rc8  13.a5  Qd8  14.c3  O-O=  With a fine position for Black. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@34@@EndBracket@@ Kamsky, G @@StartBracket@@2665@@EndBracket@@-Korchmar, V @@StartBracket@@2451@@EndBracket@@ chess.com INT 2020.   8.c3  e6  9.a4  White intends to play a4-a5-a6 and weaken Black's queenside. So, our typical response whenever White plays a2-a4 is,  9...a6!  stopping the white pawn on a5.  10.a5  Qd8  11.Bd3  Bxd3  12.Qxd3  Be7=  Followed by O-O when Black has a fine position. 1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@30@@EndBracket@@ Demchenko,A @@StartBracket@@2642@@EndBracket@@ - Bluebaum @@StartBracket@@2644@@EndBracket@@ Moscow RUS 2019   For  8.a4  please see Kravtsiv-Bok in the Model Games section. }
8... e6 9. O-O Be7 10. a4
{ White intends to play a4-a5-a6 and weaken the light squares on Black's queenside. }
10... a6
{ Remember to play this move whenever White plays a2-a4. How White's a-pawn cannot advance further than the a5-square. }
11. a5 Qd8 12. Ne5
{ White would like to alter our pawn structure by exchanging knights on c6. }
12... Rc8
{ Prepares to recapture on c6 with the rook so that our pawn structure remains intact. }
13. c3 O-O 14. Re1 Ne4
{ And Kramnik got a comfortable position out of the opening with the black pieces. The black knight generally aims for the d6-square from where it can put pressure on White's queenside. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@41@@EndBracket@@ Carlsen,M @@StartBracket@@2872@@EndBracket@@-Kramnik,V @@StartBracket@@2753@@EndBracket@@ Moscow RUS 2019 }
