[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Trompowsky"]
[Black "Trompowsky 5.Nc3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 d5 3. Bxf6
{ White should exchange on f6 sooner or later in the spirit of the Trompowsky, creating an unbalance by giving up the bishop pair but ruining Black's pawn structure.   3.Nc3  transposes to the Veresov   3.Nf3  transposes to the Torre Attack   3.e3  c5  should transpose to the mainline after,  4.Bxf6  gxf6 }
3... gxf6 4. c4
{ White attacks the centre immediately before Black gets a chance to break with c7-c5. }
4... e5
{ This is an interesting way of challenging the centre. We open up our dark-squared bishop immediately and I believe this is the best way of making use of our bishop pair.   4...dxc4  is the main move and is a good alternative. }
5. Nc3 { This forces us to take on c4. } 5... dxc4 6. d5
{ With this advance White maintains his control in the centre and plans to recapture the c4-pawn soon. But, as it turns out White can't get both at the same time without giving anything in return. }
6... c6 7. e4 b5
{ A strong novelty! We protect our c4-pawn and force White to exchange on c6 which will open up the position. An open position is favourable for us due to our bishop pair.   7...f5  1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@31@@EndBracket@@ Glidzhain, G @@StartBracket@@2148@@EndBracket@@ -Askarov, M @@StartBracket@@2438@@EndBracket@@ Kazan 2006 }
8. dxc6 Qxd1+ 9. Rxd1 Nxc6 10. Nxb5 Bb4+ 11. Nc3 Be6
{ The c4-pawn is still standing, both our bishops are developed and we plan to play Ra8-b8 adding pressure on the b-file. }
