[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Trompowsky"]
[Black "Trompowsky 5.e3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 d5 3. Bxf6
{ White should exchange on f6 sooner or later in the spirit of the Trompowsky, creating an unbalance by giving up the bishop pair but ruining Black's pawn structure.   3.Nc3  transposes to the Veresov   3.Nf3  transposes to the Torre Attack   3.e3  c5  should transpose to the mainline after,  4.Bxf6  gxf6 }
3... gxf6 4. c4
{ White attacks the centre immediately before Black gets a chance to break with c7-c5. }
4... e5
{ This is an interesting way of challenging the centre. We open up our dark-squared bishop immediately and I believe this is the best way of making use of our bishop pair.   4...dxc4  is the main move and is a good alternative. }
5. e3 { This was recently chosen by GM Mamedyarov against GM Giri. } 5... exd4
6. exd4 Qe7+
{ We want to exchange on c4 and play against the Isolated Queen’s Pawn, but it would be even better if we could exchange the queens before doing so. An endgame against the Isolated Queen’s Pawn is better for us than the middlegame. If White blocks the check with the knight or the bishop, then after 7...dxc4 he will find it tough to recover the c4-pawn.   6...Bb4+  1-0 @@StartBracket@@43@@EndBracket@@ Mamedyarov, S @@StartBracket@@2765@@EndBracket@@-Giri, A @@StartBracket@@2779@@EndBracket@@ Paris FRA 2019 }
7. Qe2 Qxe2+ 8. Bxe2 dxc4 9. Bxc4
{ We have got a comfortable version of the IQP. Yes, we have doubled pawns on the f-file, but it is easily compensated by our bishop pair. A normal way for us to develop here would be }
9... Bf5 10. Nc3 Nc6 11. Nge2 O-O-O
{ With pressure on the d4-pawn. Black is at least equal in this position. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Trompowsky"]
[Black "Trompowsky 5.e3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 d5 3. Bxf6
{ White should exchange on f6 sooner or later in the spirit of the Trompowsky, creating an unbalance by giving up the bishop pair but ruining Black's pawn structure.   3.Nc3  transposes to the Veresov   3.Nf3  transposes to the Torre Attack   3.e3  c5  should transpose to the mainline after,  4.Bxf6  gxf6 }
3... gxf6 4. c4
{ White attacks the centre immediately before Black gets a chance to break with c7-c5. }
4... e5
{ This is an interesting way of challenging the centre. We open up our dark-squared bishop immediately and I believe this is the best way of making use of our bishop pair.   4...dxc4  is the main move and is a good alternative. }
5. e3 { This was recently chosen by GM Mamedyarov against GM Giri. } 5... exd4
6. Qxd4
{ White threatens the d4-pawn and looks like a tough move to meet, but we have a nice resource up our sleeves. }
6... Nc6
{ Developing with a tempo! We temporarily sacrifice the d5-pawn in order to gain initiative by bringing out our pieces quickly. }
7. Qxd5 Qxd5 8. cxd5 Nb4 9. Na3 a6
{ This is a better option to fight for the initiative. We cover the b5-square and would like to go b7-b5 followed by Bc8-b7, adding more pressure on the d5-pawn. Another important thing to note is that the b4-knight not only attacks the d5-pawn but also the a2-pawn. So, if White wants to defend his d5-pawn then he will have to part with the pawn on a2.   9...Nxd5  1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@50@@EndBracket@@ Harshkou, M @@StartBracket@@2261@@EndBracket@@-Ziaziulkina, N @@StartBracket@@2408@@EndBracket@@ Minsk 2015 }
10. Rd1
{ 10.O-O-O?  looks logical but is bad due to,  10...Bf5!  11.b3  O-O-O∓  we win the pawn on d5 and have also completed our development. Black stands clearly better due to the pressure of our double bishops and lead in development.   10.e4?  is a desirable way of defending d5, but it falls short to the double pawn break with,  10...f5!  It is time to hit the white centre quickly before he gets time to settle down and support the d5-pawn comfortably.  11.f3  fxe4  12.fxe4  f5!∓  This second shot at the white centre guarantees that we win the d5-pawn opening up the position at the same time, which is bad news for White. }
10... Nxa2 11. Bc4 Nb4 12. Ne2
{ Intending to bring the knight to f4 from where it will guard the d5-pawn. But the knight itself is not so stable on f4 as it is prone to exchange because of our dark-squared bishop. }
12... b5 13. Bb3 Bf5 14. Nf4 Bd6
{ Black always has the option of exchanging on f4 when White will have to find new supporters for the d5-pawn, which is hard to find. }
*

