{ 10.O-O-O?  looks logical but is bad due to,  10...Bf5!  11.b3  O-O-O∓  we win the pawn on d5 and have also completed our development. Black stands clearly better due to the pressure of our double bishops and lead in development.   10.e4?  is a desirable way of defending d5, but it falls short to the double pawn break with,  10...f5!  It is time to hit the white centre quickly before he gets time to settle down and support the d5-pawn comfortably.  11.f3  fxe4  12.fxe4  f5!∓  This second shot at the white centre guarantees that we win the d5-pawn opening up the position at the same time, which is bad news for White. }
10... Nxa2 11. Bc4 Nb4 12. Nf3 b5 13. Bb3 Bb7
