[White "2. Trompowsky"]
[Black "Trompowsky 4.e3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 d5 3. Bxf6
{ White should exchange on f6 sooner or later in the spirit of the Trompowsky, creating an unbalance by giving up the bishop pair but ruining Black's pawn structure.   3.Nc3  transposes to the Veresov   3.Nf3  transposes to the Torre Attack   3.e3  c5  should transpose to the mainline after,  4.Bxf6  gxf6 }
3... gxf6 4. e3 c5 5. Nc3
{ This has been one of the main ways for the Trompovsky players to play in this position. White delays the decision of exchanging on c5. His main idea is to play Qh5 next and then go for O-O-O. }
5... cxd4 6. exd4 Bf5
{ This is an interesting and very fresh line. In general Black plays e7-e6 when the bishop remains closed inside. So, I prefer to develop it immediately before White gets a chance to play Qh5. Our main plan is to play Nb8-c6, Qd8-d7 and then O-O-O. There are very few games from this position so I analysed some sample variations. }
7. g4 { was tried in one of the games but exposes White's kingside too much. }
7... Be6
{ It's better to maintain the bishop on the h3-c8 diagonal so that when we hit with ...h7-h5 it will carry a lot of weight.   7...Bg6  1-0 @@StartBracket@@39@@EndBracket@@ Saptarshi, R @@StartBracket@@2378@@EndBracket@@-Sahu, V @@StartBracket@@2139@@EndBracket@@ New Delhi 2012. }
8. Bg2
{ 8.f4  can be met by  8...Nc6  9.f5  Bd7  where ...h7-h5 is on the way with a great position for Black. If White tries  10.Nxd5?  then after,  10...Qa5+  11.Nc3  h5!-+  White's position collapses. }
8... h5
{ This ensures weakening of the white kingside. At the same time, we get rid of our lone h-pawn. The ...h5-break needs to be done immediately before White gets a chance to manoeuvre his knight to f4 and cover the h5-square. }
9. gxh5 Nc6
{ We plan to play ... Qd7 followed by O-O-O when our bishop pair and his own weak pawn structure will start giving White a lot of troubles. }
