1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 d5 3. Bxf6
{ White should exchange on f6 sooner or later in the spirit of the Trompowsky, creating an unbalance by giving up the bishop pair but ruining Black's pawn structure.   3.Nc3  transposes to the Veresov   3.Nf3  transposes to the Torre Attack   3.e3  c5  should transpose to the mainline after,  4.Bxf6  gxf6 }
3... gxf6 4. e3 c5 5. Nc3
{ This has been one of the main ways for the Trompovsky players to play in this position. White delays the decision of exchanging on c5. His main idea is to play Qh5 next and then go for O-O-O. }
5... cxd4 6. exd4 Bf5
{ This is an interesting and very fresh line. In general Black plays e7-e6 when the bishop remains closed inside. So, I prefer to develop it immediately before White gets a chance to play Qh5. Our main plan is to play Nb8-c6, Qd8-d7 and then O-O-O. There are very few games from this position so I analysed some sample variations. }
7. Bd3 { A logical move offering the exchange of bishops. } 7... Qd7 8. Nge2
Nc6 { We prepare for O-O-O. } 9. Nf4 O-O-O 10. O-O
{ 10.Ncxd5?  is bad due to  10...Bxd3  11.Qxd3  Qd6!-+  tying both the knights which will lead to losing one of them. }
10... h5
{ Our king is safe on the queenside and we can start action of the kingside. }
