[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. Veresov & Jobava Attack"]
[Black "Veresov 1.d4 Nf6 2.Nc3 d5 3.Bg5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 { This is the entrance to the Veresov or the Jobava Attack. }
2... d5 3. Bg5
{ The Veresov. This opening has some similarities with the Trompowsky. Though White usually plays the Veresov to try and get e2-e4 as quickly as possible. }
3... c5
{ We attack White's centre immediately. This recommendation has many similarities with the Trompowsky recommendation and we will see that many times it will transpose to the Trompowsky chapter. }
4. Bxf6
{ 4.e3  cxd4  5.exd4  Bf5  we develop our bishop outside of the pawn chain before playing e7-e6.  6.Bxf6  gxf6  and this position transposes to the Trompowsky chapter. }
4... gxf6 5. e4
{ This is the main move for White in the spirit of the Veresov.   5.e3  transposes to the Trompowsky chapter. }
5... dxe4 6. dxc5 f5
{ This is an important move to remember. We protect our e4-pawn and do not fear losing our right to castle. After the exchange of queens, our king will be quite safe in the centre. }
7. Qxd8+ Kxd8
{ Now if we assess this position, the material is equal, but Black has won a central pawn while White has won a wing pawn.  White is going to go to O-O-O next and put some pressure on our king, but it would be insufficient as White does not have the support of the rest of his pieces. He needs to complete his kingside development first to have some chances of our king's temporary weak position. }
8. O-O-O+ Bd7 9. f3
{ is slightly inferior as it does not contribute to the opening up of the position. We can comfortably reply with, }
9... Bh6+
{ A nice intermediate check. Before playing ...Bg7, which is the most desirable square for our dark-squared bishop, we would like to push the white king to b1 so that it is further away from the centre. This might seem quite insignificant at the moment but in the endgames, every move is of a high value and pushing the white king away from the centre may cost White a move further down the road.   9...Bg7  1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@38@@EndBracket@@ Heberla, B @@StartBracket@@2433@@EndBracket@@ - Gajewski, G @@StartBracket@@2354@@EndBracket@@ Bartkowa 2002 }
10. Kb1 Bg7 11. Nge2 exf3 12. gxf3 e6
{ With the idea to play Kd8-e7 next. Black has a nice initiative because of the bishop pair and a better pawn structure. }
*

