[White "3. Veresov & Jobava Attack"]
[Black "Veresov 1.d4 Nf6 2.Nc3 d5 3.Bg5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 { This is the entrance to the Veresov or the Jobava Attack. }
2... d5 3. Bg5
{ The Veresov. This opening has some similarities with the Trompowsky. Though White usually plays the Veresov to try and get e2-e4 as quickly as possible. }
3... c5
{ We attack White's centre immediately. This recommendation has many similarities with the Trompowsky recommendation and we will see that many times it will transpose to the Trompowsky chapter. }
4. Bxf6
{ 4.e3  cxd4  5.exd4  Bf5  we develop our bishop outside of the pawn chain before playing e7-e6.  6.Bxf6  gxf6  and this position transposes to the Trompowsky chapter. }
4... gxf6 5. e4
{ This is the main move for White in the spirit of the Veresov.   5.e3  transposes to the Trompowsky chapter. }
5... dxe4 6. dxc5 f5
{ This is an important move to remember. We protect our e4-pawn and do not fear losing our right to castle. After the exchange of queens, our king will be quite safe in the centre. }
7. Qxd8+ Kxd8
{ Now if we assess this position, the material is equal, but Black has won a central pawn while White has won a wing pawn.  White is going to go to O-O-O next and put some pressure on our king, but it would be insufficient as White does not have the support of the rest of his pieces. He needs to complete his kingside development first to have some chances of our king's temporary weak position. }
8. O-O-O+ Bd7 9. g4
{ White wants to undermine the e4-pawn and open up the position at the same time, before Black consolidates. }
9... Bh6+
{ A nice intermediate move before playing ...Bg7. We want to push the white king away from the centre which could prove useful for us in the endgame. }
10. Kb1 Bg7 11. Nge2
{ Making sure that the queenside pawn structure does not get ruined further. White also threatens gxf5 now. }
11... fxg4 12. Nxe4 Nc6
{ Black has a better pawn structure and the bishop pair. White needs to open up the position hoping to exploit the unstable position of the black king, otherwise, he will end up in a clearly minus position. }
13. h3
{ 13.Nf4  with the idea to meet ...Kc7 with Nd5+. We can continue with,  13...Ke8  with the idea to play ...h5 followed by ...Rd8.  14.Nh5  Be5=+  we are ready to bring out our rook next with a slightly better position because of our better pawn structure. }
13... h5
{ Maintaining a pawn on g4 which limits White's light-squared bishop. Black can now focus on improving his king's position and joining the rooks. }
14. hxg4 hxg4 15. Rxh8+ Bxh8 16. Ng5 Ne5 17. Nf4 Ke8
{ We are ready to bring our rook in the game with ...Rd8. Black is slightly better again because of the same reasons, better pawn structure and the bishop pair. 0-1 @@StartBracket@@46@@EndBracket@@ Brandberg,J @@StartBracket@@2277@@EndBracket@@-Osipov,A @@StartBracket@@2295@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2015 }
