[White "3. Veresov & Jobava Attack"]
[Black "Jobava Attack 1.d4 Nf6 2.Nc3 d5 3.Bf4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 { This is the entrance to the Veresov or the Jobava Attack. }
2... d5 3. Bf4
{ This line is named after the Georgian GM Baadur Jobava as he heavily popularised it by playing it regularly at the top level. }
3... a6
{ The idea behind this move is quite obvious. We cover the b5-square and prevent Nc3-b5 which is one of the main points behind placing the bishop on f4. Later the move a7-a6 can also be useful in expanding on the queenside with b7-b5. }
4. e3 Bf5
{ We develop our bishop outside the pawn chain before playing e7-e6. } 5. Bd3
{ Challenging our light-squared bishop without first gaining space on the kingside does not look threatening. }
5... Bg6
{ It's better to let White capture on g6 as it will open up the h-file for our rook. }
6. Nf3 e6 7. Ne5
{ The knight is active and well placed on e5, but it will soon get a challenge from our b8-knight. Remember to challenge the e5-knight by Nb8-d7 instead of Nb8-c6.   7.O-O  was recently tried by GM Artemiev against GM Nakamura in one of the online blitz games.  7...Nbd7  preventing White's Nf3-e5.  8.Re1  c5  9.Bxg6  hxg6  10.e4  White broke in the centre with hopes for initiative. But, Black has an easy simplifying continuation.  10...dxe4  11.Nxe4  Nxe4  12.Rxe4  Nf6  13.Re1  cxd4=  with the idea to play Bf8-c5 next, Black was doing well. 0-1 @@StartBracket@@76@@EndBracket@@ Artemiev,V  @@StartBracket@@2716@@EndBracket@@-Nakamura,H @@StartBracket@@2736@@EndBracket@@ chess.com INT 2020 }
7... c5 8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. O-O Nbd7
{ Black is fine.   A sample variation could be,  9...Nc6  1/ 2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@52@@EndBracket@@ Naroditsky, D @@StartBracket@@2621@@EndBracket@@ -Moranda, W @@StartBracket@@2601@@EndBracket@@ chess. com INT 2020 }
10. Qf3 Nxe5 11. Bxe5 Bd6
{ Exchanging more pieces which is favourable for Black. We are slightly better in this position because of our good control in the centre. }
*

