1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 { This is the entrance to the Veresov or the Jobava Attack. }
2... d5 3. Bf4
{ This line is named after the Georgian GM Baadur Jobava as he heavily popularised it by playing it regularly at the top level. }
3... a6
{ The idea behind this move is quite obvious. We cover the b5-square and prevent Nc3-b5 which is one of the main points behind placing the bishop on f4. Later the move a7-a6 can also be useful in expanding on the queenside with b7-b5. }
4. e3 Bf5
{ We develop our bishop outside the pawn chain before playing e7-e6. } 5. Nf3
{ has been played very rarely but it seems like a logical continuation. White wants to establish his knight on e5 and then play against our light-squared bishop with g2-g4. }
5... e6 6. Ne5 Nbd7 { We should challenge the strong e5-knight immediately. }
7. g4 { With this White manages to gain the bishop pair. } 7... Nxe5 8. gxf5
Nc6 9. fxe6 fxe6
{ White has won the bishop pair but it has come at the cost of advancing his g-pawn which has weakened White's kingside a bit. }
10. Bh3
{ 10.Bg2  was tried in one game.  10...Bd6  11.Ne2  O-O  12.O-O  Ne7  13.Bg3  Nf5=+  and Black has a nice initiative on the kingside. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@33@@EndBracket@@ Chigaev, M @@StartBracket@@2531@@EndBracket@@-Iskandarov, M @@StartBracket@@2405@@EndBracket@@ Khanty Mansiysk 2015 }
10... Qd7 11. Qd3 { White prepares O-O-O. } 11... O-O-O 12. O-O-O Qf7
{ With the idea to play ...Kb8 and ...Bd6 with a completely fine position for Black. White has the bishop pair for the moment, but the dark-squared bishops are soon going to be exchanged once we play ...Bd6. }
