[White "3. Veresov & Jobava Attack"]
[Black "Jobava Attack 5.f3 e6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 { This is the entrance to the Veresov or the Jobava Attack. }
2... d5 3. Bf4
{ This line is named after the Georgian GM Baadur Jobava as he heavily popularised it by playing it regularly at the top level. }
3... a6
{ The idea behind this move is quite obvious. We cover the b5-square and prevent Nc3-b5 which is one of the main points behind placing the bishop on f4. Later the move a7-a6 can also be useful in expanding on the queenside with b7-b5. }
4. e3 Bf5
{ We develop our bishop outside the pawn chain before playing e7-e6. } 5. f3
{ This is the standard way of playing in this position for White. He intends to play g2-g4 followed by h2-h4 next, playing against Black's light-squared bishop and gaining space on the kingside at the same time. }
5... e6 6. g4 Bg6 7. h4 h5
{ We stop White's pawn avalanche in its tracks. We are also provoking White to play g4-g5 which weakens the f5 square. We can exploit this by placing our knight on the f5-square at some point.   7...h6  is another alternative. But it allows White to gain more space with,  8.h5 }
8. g5 Nfd7 9. Bd3
{ White needs to exchange Black's strong light-squared bishop on g6 in order to create something on the kingside or in the centre. }
9... Bxd3 10. Qxd3 c5
{ White can also try playing without breaking with g5-g6 for the moment with, }
11. Nge2 Nc6 12. O-O-O
{ Now it is essential to note that we cannot block White's g-pawn immediately with g7-g6. }
12... cxd4
{ It is necessary to exchange on d4 first so that White does not get a chance to break in the centre with e3-e4.   12...g6?  is bad due to,  13.e4!+-  and White will get a crushing initiative in the centre. }
13. exd4 { is now comfortably met by, } 13... g6 14. Rhe1 Nb6
{ preventing Nc3xd5. Black can now freely play on the queenside. } *

