[White "4. Torre Attack"]
[Black "Torre Attack 4.Bh4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. Bg5
{ The Torre Attack! The fundamental idea behind the London System  3.Bf4  and the Torre Attack  3.Bg5  is the same - to develop the dark-squared bishop out of the pawn chain before playing e2-e3. The only difference is the placement of the Bishop. Based on recent trends, it is clear that the London System has overtaken the Torre Attack and proved itself the stronger choice between the two.  We reply by centralizing our Knight on e4 and then continuing with our development. }
3... Ne4 4. Bh4
{ You may face this move rarely, mostly in a blitz game. In response to 4.Bh4, I too recommend a rare but tricky move! }
4... f6
{ An odd-looking move but it has a very clear threat: we want to go g7-g5, h7-h5 threatening to trap White's dark-squared bishop with h5-h4. If White defends it with h2-h3 then we just exchange on g3 which will ruin White's kingside completely. There is only one satisfactory response to our move which is difficult to find in a blitz game. }
5. Nfd2
{ Only this move is able to prevent Black's threat. The point is to exchange the e4 knight next and after Black recaptures with the pawn then the f3 knight won't be hanging anymore. }
5... Nd6 6. f3 { has been played before. Black can respond with, } 6... Nc6 7.
c3 e5 { Seizing control of the centre. } 8. e3 Be7 9. Bd3 f5
{ A nice move with the idea to play e5-e4 next and gain space in the centre. 0-1 @@StartBracket@@28@@EndBracket@@ Barros Lizcano,R @@StartBracket@@2088@@EndBracket@@ -Campora,D @@StartBracket@@2506@@EndBracket@@ Cali 2001 }
