1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3
{ With this move we enter the Colle-Zukertort system. In this chapter, we are mainly going to analyse two of White's most prominent setups.   Set-up 1@@EndBracket@@ When White plays c2-c3, Bf1-d3 and Nb1-d2.   Set-up 2@@EndBracket@@ When he fianchetto's his dark-squared bishop with b2-b3 and Bc1-b2. }
3... c5 4. dxc5 { This variation has seen many games recently. } 4... e6 5. a3
{ White prepares b2-b4 in case Black takes the c5-pawn, playing in the style of reversed Queens Gambit accepted. But this strategy is not so effective with black knight still on b8, as we will soon see. }
5... Bxc5 6. b4 Be7 7. Bb2 O-O
{ We would like to fianchetto our bishop to b7 next. } 8. Nbd2 b6 9. Be2 Bb7
10. O-O a5
{ an important move, forcing White to push b4-b5, freeing the c5-square for our knight. This is the reason why it is good for Black that the knight is on b8 otherwise if it would have been on c6 then after b4-b5 it would be under attack. }
11. b5 Nbd7 12. c4 Rc8 13. Rc1 Nc5
{ With our knight firmly established on c5 and all our pieces developed, we have got a fine position out of the opening. 0-1 @@StartBracket@@70@@EndBracket@@ Kovalenko, I @@StartBracket@@2635@@EndBracket@@-Swapnil,S @@StartBracket@@2533@@EndBracket@@ chess.com INT 2018 }
