[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. Colle-Zukertort"]
[Black "Colle-Zukertort 4.dxc5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3
{ With this move we enter the Colle-Zukertort system. In this chapter, we are mainly going to analyse two of White's most prominent setups.   Set-up 1@@EndBracket@@ When White plays c2-c3, Bf1-d3 and Nb1-d2.   Set-up 2@@EndBracket@@ When he fianchetto's his dark-squared bishop with b2-b3 and Bc1-b2. }
3... c5 4. dxc5 { This variation has seen many games recently. } 4... e6 5. b4
{ White defends his c5-pawn not for the sake of defending it but to create two passed pawns on the a- and b-files! }
5... a5 6. c3 axb4 7. cxb4 b6
{ We continue to undermine White's queenside pawns so that we can recover our pawn. }
8. Bb5+
{ White wants to exchange the light-squared bishops before creating a passed pawn duo on a- and b-files.   White can also go for the passed pawn duo immediately with,  8.a4  bxc5  9.b5  the difference here compared to the mainline is that Black's light-squared bishop is more useful than White's. First of all the c8-bishop can play a crucial role in preventing White's pawns from advancing further. Another thing is that Black can fianchetto the bishop to b7 and at some point, if we play d5-d4 then the bishop can prove to be a very strong piece to deal with because of the pressure on the h1-a8 diagonal. }
8... Bd7 9. Bxd7+ Nbxd7 10. a4 bxc5 11. b5
{ This was White's main strategic aim. He has got the passed pawns he wanted but it is not going to be easy for him to advance those pawns further down the board as the squares in the Black camp are firmly guarded by our pieces. Black also has a nice control in the centre because of the d5 and c5 pawns. }
11... Bd6 12. Bb2 O-O 13. O-O Ra7
{ An interesting novelty. Our idea is to play Qd8-a8 followed by Nd7-b6 putting strong pressure on the a4-pawn.   13...Qc7  1-0 @@StartBracket@@35@@EndBracket@@ Firouzja, A @@StartBracket@@2749@@EndBracket@@-So, W @@StartBracket@@2770@@EndBracket@@ chess24.com INT 2020 }
14. Nbd2 Qa8
{ We threaten Nd7-b6 winning the a4-pawn. Now White has a few options and I have analysed them for you. }
15. Nc4 { is risky for White, because after } 15... Bc7 16. Nce5 Nb6
{ The a4-pawn falls and White has to rely on the compensation of some sort. } *

