[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. Colle-Zukertort"]
[Black "Colle-Zukertort 4.b3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3
{ With this move we enter the Colle-Zukertort system. In this chapter, we are mainly going to analyse two of White's most prominent setups.   Set-up 1@@EndBracket@@ When White plays c2-c3, Bf1-d3 and Nb1-d2.   Set-up 2@@EndBracket@@ When he fianchetto's his dark-squared bishop with b2-b3 and Bc1-b2. }
3... c5 4. b3
{ This is the most popular move order for White to enter the Zukertort setup. White wants to play Bc1-b2, Bf1-d3 and Nb1-d2. }
4... cxd4
{ I like this pawn exchange forcing White to recapture with the pawn. } 5. exd4
{ In this structure White would love to develop his bishop on f4 or g5, but then the move b2-b3 will be a waste of time. Also, abandoning the b2-square now will weaken White's dark squares on the queenside. }
5... g6 6. Bb2 Bg7 7. Bd3 O-O 8. O-O Nc6
{ Black always has ideas of playing ...Nb4 followed by ... Bf5. So White usually prevents it with, }
9. Re1 { with the idea to cover the e4 square, is strongly met by } 9... Bg4
{ We set up a nice trap! } 10. h3
{ seems like a very logical move, but in fact, White falls in our trap! } 10...
Bxf3 11. Qxf3 Ne4
{ A perfectly timed knight surge in the centre, exploiting the fact that the d4-pawn is not sufficiently supported. }
12. Bxe4
{ If  12.c3  then,  12...f5  followed by e7-e5 gives Black a clear advantage. }
12... Nxd4
{ This is the point of Black's previous play. By taking the d4-pawn Black opens up the long a1-h8 diagonal for his bishop. }
13. Bxd4 dxe4 14. Rxe4 Bxd4 15. c3 Bf6
{ The series of exchanges have led us to a clear better position for Black. Our bishop is strong eyeing the pawn on c3. }
