1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3
{ With this move we enter the Colle-Zukertort system. In this chapter, we are mainly going to analyse two of White's most prominent setups.   Set-up 1@@EndBracket@@ When White plays c2-c3, Bf1-d3 and Nb1-d2.   Set-up 2@@EndBracket@@ When he fianchetto's his dark-squared bishop with b2-b3 and Bc1-b2. }
3... c5 4. c3
{ White sets-up a proper Colle pawn structure. This way of playing has been tried a lot in the classical games with it's first game dating back to the year 1897. Apart from Colle himself, 4.c3 was also tried in a few games by the Cuban genius Capablanca himself in his prime. This pawn structure with f2-e3-d4-c3-b2 is exactly similar with the pawn structure that Black gets in the Semi-Slav defence. We can also say that White is playing the Semi-Slav a move up. }
4... e6
{ We support the c5-pawn and prepare to develop our dark-squared bishop.   4...Nc6  allows additional options like  5.dxc5  followed by b2-b4 }
5. Nbd2 Nc6 6. Bd3 Bd6 7. O-O O-O
{ Both sides have castled safely and now it is up to White to initiate a plan. }
8. dxc5
{ 8.Qe2  is met by,  8...Qc7  when the line will most probably transpose to the mainline after,  9.dxc5  Bxc5  10.e4 }
8... Bxc5
{ Now White has two ways to continue. Either he can play b2-b4 with the idea to fianchetto the bishop with Bc1-b2 or break in the centre with e3-e4. }
9. e4
{ This is a more popular move than b2-b4. One of the major strategic aims for White in this line is to advance the pawn even further with e4-e5, gaining space which can be later used to create attacking chances on the kingside. Our main aim should be to prevent White from pushing e4-e5 comfortably. A huge role will be played by our dark-squared bishop as it constantly eyes the f2-pawn tying the white rook to its defence. }
9... Qc7 { We start with covering the e5-square. } 10. Qe2 b6
{ We prepare to develop our c8-bishop. } 11. e5
{ White seems to have achieved his strategic aim but he is not well prepared for this advance because we can attack his e5-pawn with.   11.Re1?!  is simply met by,  11...Ng4  12.Rf1  Nce5  and Black seizes the initiative. }
11... Ng4 12. Bxh7+
{ This tactical idea was the basis of White's previous move. But water is under the bridge for us. We can simply take his bishop with, }
12... Kxh7 13. Ng5+ Kg8 14. Qxg4 Qxe5
{ We have managed to get rid of the central e5-pawn in return for the wing pawn on h7, which is a good trade for us. In case White creates threats on the kingside, our queen is sufficient to handle them on her own. Black is slightly better in this position because of the bishop pair and good central control. Many games have been played from this position and it is no wonder that Black has scored excellently. }
