7... Nc6
{ This is the right time to develop our knight. We have established control in the centre and White's plan now is to undermine our centre with pawn breaks. }
8. Nc3 Be6 9. f4 { A typical pawn break to gain control of the d4-square. }
9... exf4 10. gxf4 Qb6+ 11. e3 Rd8
{ We bring the rook in the game and protect our d5-pawn. We would like to play ...Bf5 and gain good control on the light squares. White can try to be aggressive with, }
12. f5 Bc8 13. Kh1 Bb4 { Preparing to O-O. } 14. Nxd5 Nxd5 15. Bxd5
{ White has won a pawn with aggressive moves but his king's shelter is compromised which will give him a headache. }
15... Ne7 16. e4
{ 16.c4  is just bad because of,  16...Bxf5  17.Qf3  O-O-+  the material is level but White's kingside is very weak and his queenside is still undeveloped. }
16... Nxd5 17. exd5 O-O
{ We have amazing compensation for the pawn because of White's weak kingside. Next, we would like to play  ...Rfe8  and co-ordinate our pieces, putting pressure on f5- and d5-pawns.  18.c3  Be7  19.Qf3  Rfe8  20.Be3  Qb5  21.Rad1  Bf6∓  Black threatens ...Re5, attacking both the f5- and d5-pawns. Black stands clearly better because of our active pieces and White's exposed kingside. }
