1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. g3
{ Fianchettoing the bishop in this position does not have a good reputation. White tries to play in the style of Grunfeld Defence with reversed colours, but there is a big difference as we will soon see. }
3... c5 4. Bg2 cxd4 5. O-O
{ This is where we can see the difference. White does not want to take on  d4  immediately because if he plays  5.Nxd4  we play  5...e5  gaining control in the centre and kicking the knight away from d4. In a normal Grunfeld Defence, White's knight is on c3, so whenever White plays e4 attacking the knight on d5, Black exchanges on c3. However, here our knight is absent on c6 so White does not have that leisure of exchanging when we kick his knight away with e7-e5.  6.Nb3  h6!  preventing Bg5 ideas.  7.O-O  transposes back to the mainline. }
5... h6
{ A useful waiting move covering the g5-square. Again, we don't want to play ...Nc6 yet and wait for White to capture on d4 first. }
6. Nxd4 e5 7. Nb3
{ 7.Nf3  has also been seen in a lot of online blitz games. We can simply continue with  7...Nc6  developing our knight as well as defending the e5-pawn. We have complete control over the centre thanks to our d5 and e5-pawns. White needs to do something immediately against this centre before Black is able to complete his development.  8.c4  a typical way of hitting the centre.  8...Be6  I think this is the simplest way to go ahead. We get more control on the d5-square. Note that our ...h6 move has come in handy now as it prevents White from playing Nf3-g5.  9.cxd5   9.Qa4  threatening Nxe5 can be met with  9...Bd6=+  covering the e5-pawn and preparing to O-O when Black is slightly better.  9...Nxd5=+  and Black stands slightly better because of our extra space in the centre. Our idea next is to develop our dark-squared bishop either to e7 or d6 and then O-O. }
7... Nc6
{ This is the right time to develop our knight. We have established control in the centre and White's plan now is to undermine our centre with pawn breaks. }
8. c4 { A typical Grunfeld way of undermining the centre. } 8... d4 9. f4 Be7
{ We continue with our development. At the same time, we offer a pawn to White. If White accepts our offer then it will open lines for our pieces and we will exploit it by creating initiative. }
10. fxe5 Ng4 11. Bxc6+
{ White should accept our offer. Otherwise, after the simple ...Ngxe5 we regain our pawn with a better position. }
11... bxc6 12. Qxd4 Qxd4+
{ We exchange queens so that we can pin White's knight on d4 and then capture White's e5-pawn. }
13. Nxd4 Bc5 14. e3 Nxe5
{ threatens the c4-pawn. If White defends it we can go ...Bh3 followed by ...Rd8 or O-O-O. White's queenside is still undeveloped and his pawns are targets for our pieces. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6. 3.g3 without c2-c4"]
[Black "3.g3 with 6.Nxd4 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. g3
{ Fianchettoing the bishop in this position does not have a good reputation. White tries to play in the style of Grunfeld Defence with reversed colours, but there is a big difference as we will soon see. }
3... c5 4. Bg2 cxd4 5. O-O
{ This is where we can see the difference. White does not want to take on  d4  immediately because if he plays  5.Nxd4  we play  5...e5  gaining control in the centre and kicking the knight away from d4. In a normal Grunfeld Defence, White's knight is on c3, so whenever White plays e4 attacking the knight on d5, Black exchanges on c3. However, here our knight is absent on c6 so White does not have that leisure of exchanging when we kick his knight away with e7-e5.  6.Nb3  h6!  preventing Bg5 ideas.  7.O-O  transposes back to the mainline. }
5... h6
{ A useful waiting move covering the g5-square. Again, we don't want to play ...Nc6 yet and wait for White to capture on d4 first. }
6. Nxd4 e5 7. Nb3
{ 7.Nf3  has also been seen in a lot of online blitz games. We can simply continue with  7...Nc6  developing our knight as well as defending the e5-pawn. We have complete control over the centre thanks to our d5 and e5-pawns. White needs to do something immediately against this centre before Black is able to complete his development.  8.c4  a typical way of hitting the centre.  8...Be6  I think this is the simplest way to go ahead. We get more control on the d5-square. Note that our ...h6 move has come in handy now as it prevents White from playing Nf3-g5.  9.cxd5   9.Qa4  threatening Nxe5 can be met with  9...Bd6=+  covering the e5-pawn and preparing to O-O when Black is slightly better.  9...Nxd5=+  and Black stands slightly better because of our extra space in the centre. Our idea next is to develop our dark-squared bishop either to e7 or d6 and then O-O. }
7... Nc6
{ This is the right time to develop our knight. We have established control in the centre and White's plan now is to undermine our centre with pawn breaks. }
8. c4 { A typical Grunfeld way of undermining the centre. } 8... d4 9. f4 Be7
{ We continue with our development. At the same time, we offer a pawn to White. If White accepts our offer then it will open lines for our pieces and we will exploit it by creating initiative. }
10. fxe5 Ng4 11. Bxc6+
{ White should accept our offer. Otherwise, after the simple ...Ngxe5 we regain our pawn with a better position. }
11... bxc6 12. Qxd4 Qxd4+
{ We exchange queens so that we can pin White's knight on d4 and then capture White's e5-pawn. }
13. Nxd4 Bc5 14. Rd1 O-O
{ White's e5-pawn is not going to run away and we can capture it later. By castling immediately we intend to play ...Rd8 next putting pressure on the d4-knight. }
15. b4 { The best way to release the tension. } 15... Bxb4 16. Ba3
{ 16.Nxc6?  it feels natural to grab the c6-pawn but it is a huge mistake as Black gets a crushing initiative.  16...Bc5+  17.e3   17.Kg2?  Bb7-+  loses the c6-knight for White.   17.Kf1  f6!  -+  opens up lines around White's king with a decisive effect.  17...Nxe3  18.Bxe3  Bxe3+  19.Kf1  Bg4-+  Black has a winning advantage as our bishops are active, White's king is unstable, and his queenside pieces are yet to participate in the game. }
16... Bxa3 17. Nxa3 Nxe5
{ We have recovered our sacrificed material. Our pawn structure is better and so are our pieces. }
