1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. g3
{ Fianchettoing the bishop in this position does not have a good reputation. White tries to play in the style of Grunfeld Defence with reversed colours, but there is a big difference as we will soon see. }
3... c5 4. Bg2 cxd4 5. O-O
{ This is where we can see the difference. White does not want to take on  d4  immediately because if he plays  5.Nxd4  we play  5...e5  gaining control in the centre and kicking the knight away from d4. In a normal Grunfeld Defence, White's knight is on c3, so whenever White plays e4 attacking the knight on d5, Black exchanges on c3. However, here our knight is absent on c6 so White does not have that leisure of exchanging when we kick his knight away with e7-e5.  6.Nb3  h6!  preventing Bg5 ideas.  7.O-O  transposes back to the mainline. }
5... h6
{ A useful waiting move covering the g5-square. Again, we don't want to play ...Nc6 yet and wait for White to capture on d4 first. }
6. b3
{ This is White's best response. He waits for Black to move his e-pawn first or bring his knight out to c6, before recapturing on d4 with Nd4. }
6... e6
{ 6...Nbd7?!  with the idea to play ...e5 next, seems like a decent option. But White gets comfortable play after  7.Qxd4  preventing ...e5.  7...e6  and now  8.c4  and it is clear that the knight is not ideally placed on d7 as it should be on the c6-square. }
7. Bb2 Bc5 { We develop our bishop actively and prepare for O-O. } 8. Nxd4 e5
{ Black expands in the centre on the first chance. } 9. Nf3 e4 10. Nd4
{ The position is exactly the same as after White's 8th move. The only difference being Black's e6 pawn crossed the mid-line and stands now on e4. With the help of the pawn on e4 Black limits White's g2-bishop. }
10... O-O 11. c4 Nc6 { It is time to develop our queenside now. } 12. cxd5 Qxd5
13. Nxc6 Qxc6 14. Nc3
{ White develops his knight actively, putting pressure on the e4-pawn and intending to bring his rook to c1 which will create pressure on the c-file. }
14... Bf5
{ Black has successfully managed to maintain extra space in the centre and has connected his rooks with the previous move. If given more time, Black will bring his rooks into the game and snatch initiative. White needs to act fast. }
15. Na4 Be7 16. Rc1 Qa6 17. Bxf6
{ It feels a bit odd to give away the strong bishop on b2 for the knight on f6, but this exchange gains White access to the d5-square for his queen. }
17... Qxf6 18. Qd5 { Now both the b7- and e4-pawns are under attack. } 18...
Ba3 19. Rc7 Rac8 20. Rxb7 { can be met by } 20... Rfd8 21. Qb5 Bg4
{ Threatening ...a6 with the idea to win the e2-pawn. Black also has the option of ...Rc2 next when the pressure on the 2nd rank will be too strong to handle. }
