b5 7. Ne5 { 7.b3  cxb3  8.axb3  Bb7  9.Ne5  transposes. } 7... Bb7 8. b3
{ An interesting idea opening up the c- and a-files to create pressure on the queenside. }
8... cxb3 9. axb3 Be7 { Black prepares to O-O. } 10. Nc3
{ White threatens to win back the pawn with Nxb5. } 10... a6 11. Bb2 O-O 12.
Qc2
{ This move was tried by the Catalan expert himself, GM Vladimir Kramnik against GM Giri in a crucial round in the Qatar Masters 2014. Later an antidote to this move was soon found. We should give away our extra pawn with, }
12... Nbd7
{ This is the most comfortable way for Black to continue. We give back our extra pawn @@StartBracket@@c6-pawn@@EndBracket@@ and loosen White's grip on the position by opening lines for our pieces. }
13. Nxc6
{ The other way to recover the pawn -  13.Bxc6  can also be met comfortably with  13...Qc7  14.Bxb7  Qxb7  15.Nxd7  Nxd7=+  We would like to play to bring our rook to the c-file next. Black stands slightly better here because of our queenside pawn majority. }
13... Bxc6 14. Bxc6 Rc8
{ This forces White to exchange on d7. If the bishop moves back from c6 then we are going to play ...b4 and win White's c3 knight. }
15. Bxd7 Qxd7 16. Qd3 Qb7
{ And it is Black who has the slight advantage due to our queenside majority. ½-½ @@StartBracket@@31@@EndBracket@@ Socko,B @@StartBracket@@2601@@EndBracket@@-Anton Guijarro,D @@StartBracket@@2688@@EndBracket@@ Linares ESP 2020 }
