1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. c4 e6 4. g3
{ Welcome to the Catalan!  The Catalan has established itself as a solid opening for White. It is usually associated with positions where White can press for a long time without risking anything. The majority of lines that arise from this opening are positional.  There are a lot of options for Black where he gets a solid position and these are generally considered as the mainlines. But in this repertoire, I am suggesting a line that is relatively fresh and will carry some element of surprise. Recently this line has been extensively played by the Spanish GM Anton Guijarro.  Most of the positions coming out of this line are dynamic. For example, positions where we are a pawn up but White has some compensation for it. As you will see in the mainline we are the one sacrificing material  (an exchange)  for compensation.  Some variations are also concrete so it is essential to remember them move by move. I have done my best in adding comments and explanations on important moves which will be useful for the readers to remember these concrete variations. }
4... dxc4 5. Bg2 c6
{ I recommend this slightly rare and fresh line against the Catalan. It contains a little element of surprise and in most variations, we get fighting positions. However, some critical variations may end in a draw. GM Anton Guijarro is a strong advocate of this variation as this is his main weapon against the Catalan recently. With 5...c6 we aim to defend our dear pawn on c4 with b7-b5. There are some options for White but essentially only two ways that White can respond to 5...c6. Either he can try to win the pawn on c4 as soon as possible or he can aim for long-term compensation by sacrificing the pawn. }
6. O-O { This indicates that White is aiming for long-term compensation. } 6...
b5 7. Ne5 { 7.b3  cxb3  8.axb3  Bb7  9.Ne5  transposes. } 7... Bb7 8. a4
{ White starts to create pressure on the queenside. } 8... a6
{ 8...Qc8  was my initial recommendation, but then I rejected it because of,  9.b3  cxb3  10.Nd2!  White should recapture the b3 pawn with the knight as the knight from b3 keeps a firm control on the c5 square preventing the ...c5 break.  10...Nbd7  11.Nxb3  b4  12.Nxd7  Qxd7  13.a5!  Ba6  14.Qc2  With a firm control on the c5 square and some pressure on the c6 pawn White is slightly better here. }
9. Nc3
{ White is all set to win his pawn back on the queenside, exploiting the pin on the h1-a8 diagonal.   9.axb5  axb5  10.Rxa8  Bxa8  11.Nc3  Be7  transposes. }
9... Be7
{ I believe this is the safest way for Black to continue. We should give the pawn back and simplify the position after which we will be able to complete our development quickly and effortlessly.   9...Qc8  seemed promising at first, but I did not like it after,  10.e4  Nbd7   10...Be7  11.Ng4!  eliminating the f6-knight which is a good defensive piece for Black and making way for the e4-e5 pawn advance.  11...O-O  12.Nxf6+  Bxf6  13.e5  Be7  14.Qg4  Kh8  15.Ne4  Qc7  16.Bg5!  exchanging the dark-squared bishops is clearly in White's favour.  16...Bxg5  17.Nxg5  h6  18.f4!  and White has great attacking prospects on the kingside.  11.Nxd7  Nxd7   11...Qxd7  12.e5!  Nd5  13.Ne4  and White has a very strong compensation for the pawn. He can create threats on the kingside.  12.d5!  breaking in the centre when the Black king is still there.   12.e5?!  allows Black to carry out his break with,  12...b4  13.Ne4  c5=  12...Nc5  13.d6!  This strong passed pawn cuts the Black camp in half!  13...Nb3  14.Rb1  g6  15.e5  Bg7  16.Bf4  Black has maintained his pawn lead but with such a strong pawn duo on e5-d6 White has a good initiative. }
10. axb5 axb5 11. Rxa8 Bxa8 12. Nxb5
{ White uses the pin along the h1-a8 diagonal to recover his pawn. } 12... cxb5
13. Bxa8 O-O
{ By sacrificing the pawn back we have managed to castle quickly. White has won the bishop pair and has a strong knight on e5, but Black has a queenside pawn majority which can be very valuable in the endgame. }
14. Bg2 Nd5
{ The knight comes out in the centre before White is able to play e2-e4. } 15.
Bd2 Qc7 16. e4 Nf6
{ It might seem that we have allowed White to play e2-e4 for free. But playing e2-e4 has some drawbacks. Firstly, the d4-pawn is now slightly weak as it can no longer be supported by e2-e3. Secondly, the h1-a8 diagonal is now closed so we can play ...Nc6 challenging the e5-knight as well as the d4-pawn at the same time. }
17. Bf4 Bd6 18. Qf3 Nc6
{ was the simplest way to continue.   18...Rc8  1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@27@@EndBracket@@ Almasi, I @@StartBracket@@2407@@EndBracket@@-Kantor, G @@StartBracket@@2516@@EndBracket@@ Zalakaros HUN 2019 }
19. Nxc6 Bxf4 20. d5 Bd6
{ Black is doing fine. For example,  21.b3  exd5  22.exd5  cxb3  23.Qxb3  b4=  with a completely equal endgame. }
