1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. c4 e6 4. g3
{ Welcome to the Catalan!  The Catalan has established itself as a solid opening for White. It is usually associated with positions where White can press for a long time without risking anything. The majority of lines that arise from this opening are positional.  There are a lot of options for Black where he gets a solid position and these are generally considered as the mainlines. But in this repertoire, I am suggesting a line that is relatively fresh and will carry some element of surprise. Recently this line has been extensively played by the Spanish GM Anton Guijarro.  Most of the positions coming out of this line are dynamic. For example, positions where we are a pawn up but White has some compensation for it. As you will see in the mainline we are the one sacrificing material  (an exchange)  for compensation.  Some variations are also concrete so it is essential to remember them move by move. I have done my best in adding comments and explanations on important moves which will be useful for the readers to remember these concrete variations. }
4... dxc4 5. Bg2 c6
{ I recommend this slightly rare and fresh line against the Catalan. It contains a little element of surprise and in most variations, we get fighting positions. However, some critical variations may end in a draw. GM Anton Guijarro is a strong advocate of this variation as this is his main weapon against the Catalan recently. With 5...c6 we aim to defend our dear pawn on c4 with b7-b5. There are some options for White but essentially only two ways that White can respond to 5...c6. Either he can try to win the pawn on c4 as soon as possible or he can aim for long-term compensation by sacrificing the pawn. }
6. a4
{ White prevents our idea of ...b5 from the outset and later he can decide how to win back the c4-pawn. }
6... Bb4+ 7. Nc3
{ This transposes to the variation reaching mainly from the  g3  Slav after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  c6  3.Nc3  Nf6  4.Nf3  e6  5.g3  dxc4  6.a4  Bb4  7.Bg2  White does not aim to win the c4-pawn immediately, but first wants to develop his pieces and later go for the c4-pawn. Black's main strategic idea in this variation is to give up the c4-pawn but get in the e5-break which will free lines for our pieces. }
7... Nbd7 { Black prevents any Ne5 ideas. } 8. O-O O-O 9. Qc2
{ Going for the pawn directly with,  9.Nd2?  is bad because of,  9...e5!  Black pounces on the opportunity and carries out an equally important pawn break in the centre @@StartBracket@@apart from the ...c5 break@@EndBracket@@. Any successful break in the centre frees Black's pieces. After the departure of the d4-pawn Black's knight will get access to the c5-square which will help us to exploit weaknesses on White's queenside.  10.Nxc4  exd4  11.Qxd4  Nc5  12.Qxd8  Rxd8  and Black has a clearly better endgame because of the weaknesses on White's queenside. Black's bishop is already sitting on the weak b4 square while b3 is a juicy square for the black knight. White should always take care of his a4-pawn. 0-1 @@StartBracket@@30@@EndBracket@@ Straub,P  @@StartBracket@@2168@@EndBracket@@ -Filipenko,A @@StartBracket@@2353@@EndBracket@@ Rijeka 2011 }
9... a5
{ An important prophylactic move, preventing White's future advance a5. } 10.
Rd1
{ 10.Na2  Bd6  11.Qxc4  e5!=  Black has achieved his desired break and has a comfortable position. 1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@40@@EndBracket@@ Perevertkin,V @@StartBracket@@2605@@EndBracket@@-Straka, Z @@StartBracket@@2584@@EndBracket@@ ICCF 2016 }
10... Qe7
{ Of course the ...e5-break is only possible if we move our queen away from the d-file. }
11. Na2
{ If White plays,  11.Bf4  preventing the ...e5 break then we can protect our c4-pawn with,  11...Nb6=  and White will find it hard to win the pawn back. }
11... Bd6 12. Qxc4 e5
{ We achieve our main strategic aim! We have given the c4-pawn back in order to achieve the ... e5 break which opens lines for our pieces. }
13. Qc2 exd4 14. Nxd4 Nc5
{ After the ...e5-break, the position has opened up and Black's pieces are sitting on comfortable squares. Black is doing fine in this position. ½-½ @@StartBracket@@30@@EndBracket@@ Bescós Anzano,M @@StartBracket@@2561@@EndBracket@@-Müller,G @@StartBracket@@2568@@EndBracket@@ ICCF 2018 }
