[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. c4 e6 4. g3
{ Welcome to the Catalan!  The Catalan has established itself as a solid opening for White. It is usually associated with positions where White can press for a long time without risking anything. The majority of lines that arise from this opening are positional.  There are a lot of options for Black where he gets a solid position and these are generally considered as the mainlines. But in this repertoire, I am suggesting a line that is relatively fresh and will carry some element of surprise. Recently this line has been extensively played by the Spanish GM Anton Guijarro.  Most of the positions coming out of this line are dynamic. For example, positions where we are a pawn up but White has some compensation for it. As you will see in the mainline we are the one sacrificing material  (an exchange)  for compensation.  Some variations are also concrete so it is essential to remember them move by move. I have done my best in adding comments and explanations on important moves which will be useful for the readers to remember these concrete variations. }
4... dxc4 5. Bg2 c6
{ I recommend this slightly rare and fresh line against the Catalan. It contains a little element of surprise and in most variations, we get fighting positions. However, some critical variations may end in a draw. GM Anton Guijarro is a strong advocate of this variation as this is his main weapon against the Catalan recently. With 5...c6 we aim to defend our dear pawn on c4 with b7-b5. There are some options for White but essentially only two ways that White can respond to 5...c6. Either he can try to win the pawn on c4 as soon as possible or he can aim for long-term compensation by sacrificing the pawn. }
6. Ne5
{ White goes on the quest to win the pawn quickly by attacking it immediately. }
6... Bb4+
{ An important intermediate check before we do something to defend our c4-pawn.   6...b5?!  is not good for Black due to,  7.Nxc6   7.a4  is also a very good alternative as Black is now forced to play,  7...Nd5  which we do not want to play unless White has a knight on c3 as whenever White plays e4 we can exchange the knight on c3. Otherwise, after e4 our d5-knight will be kicked back and White will gain time.  7...Qb6  8.Na5!  a nice tactical resource in order to fulfil positional aims.  8...Nd5   8...Qxa5+?  9.Bd2+-  9.Bd2  and the a5 knight teamed up with the g2 bishop is very annoying for Black as it is not so easy to complete our queenside development. }
7. Nc3 Nd5 8. O-O
{ This is an interesting sacrifice for initiative! But we don’t need to fear and should accept the challenge with, }
8... Nxc3 9. bxc3 Bxc3
{ Grabbing the pawn without fear! In general, it is not recommended to go on a pawn grabbing spree in the opening itself ignoring our development. But in this exact position we can do so as we have concrete reasons supporting our decision. }
10. Ba3 { Making sure that the black king stays in the centre. } 10... Qxd4
{ Continuing with our strategy of winning pawns one by one! Concrete variations make sure that it turns out to be fine for Black. }
11. Qxd4
{ A lot of White's pieces are under attack so White has to exchange queens. }
11... Bxd4 12. Nxc4
{ White gives up his a1-rook with hopes that Nd6+ would create some problems for Black. }
12... Bxa1 13. Rxa1
{ White is an exchange and two pawns down, but he still calmly recaptures the black bishop as the black king cannot run away from the centre yet. }
13... f6 { Creating an escaping square for our king. } 14. Nd6+ Kd7 15. Nf7
{ White can also start with,  15.Rd1  Kc7  16.Nf7  and after  16...Re8  we transpose to the position in the line after 15.Nf7. }
15... Re8 16. Rd1+ Kc7 17. Bd6+
{ It seems White is getting nearer to the black king, but now even after the simple, }
17... Kd7
{ White has nothing better than to settle for a perpetual.   17...Kb6  also leads to a draw after  18.Rb1+  Ka6  19.Rb3  Now White threatens to play Bc5 which vacates the d6-square for his knight. It would be extremely risky for us once the white knight joins the attack. So it is better to force a draw with,  19...e5  and since Black is threatening ...Be6 White should force a draw with,  20.Ra3+  Kb5  21.Rb3+  Ka6=  and the line ends in a repetition. }
18. Bf8+ Kc7 19. Bd6+ Kd7 { And the game ends in a perpetual. } *

