{ I recommend this slightly rare and fresh line against the Catalan. It contains a little element of surprise and in most variations, we get fighting positions. However, some critical variations may end in a draw. GM Anton Guijarro is a strong advocate of this variation as this is his main weapon against the Catalan recently. With 5...c6 we aim to defend our dear pawn on c4 with b7-b5. There are some options for White but essentially only two ways that White can respond to 5...c6. Either he can try to win the pawn on c4 as soon as possible or he can aim for long-term compensation by sacrificing the pawn. }
6. Ne5
{ White goes on the quest to win the pawn quickly by attacking it immediately. }
6... Bb4+
{ An important intermediate check before we do something to defend our c4-pawn.   6...b5?!  is not good for Black due to,  7.Nxc6   7.a4  is also a very good alternative as Black is now forced to play,  7...Nd5  which we do not want to play unless White has a knight on c3 as whenever White plays e4 we can exchange the knight on c3. Otherwise, after e4 our d5-knight will be kicked back and White will gain time.  7...Qb6  8.Na5!  a nice tactical resource in order to fulfil positional aims.  8...Nd5   8...Qxa5+?  9.Bd2+-  9.Bd2  and the a5 knight teamed up with the g2 bishop is very annoying for Black as it is not so easy to complete our queenside development. }
7. Bd2 Be7
{ This was the point of ...Bb4+. We have provoked White's bishop to d2 and now the d4-pawn is hanging so White has to delay his plans of recovering the c4-pawn. }
8. Bc3
{ This was White's early reaction when he faced 7...Be7 in tournament games. But it is obvious that the White bishop is misplaced on c3 as it takes away the natural developing square from the b1-knight. }
8... a5
{ An important move to remember, we gain space on the queenside with this advance.   8...b5!?  is an interesting exchange sacrifice that we will see in the mainline, which is also possible here.  9.Nxc6  Nxc6  10.Bxc6+  Bd7  11.Bxa8  Qxa8  12.f3  h5!  a typical h-pawn raid especially when our opponent has a weak kingside. Black plans to play ...h4 gaining space and inducing further weaknesses in White's kingside.  13.O-O  h4  14.g4  O-O  and Black has a nice compensation for the exchange because of space on both sides of the board and some weak squares in White's camp.   8...O-O  9.Nxc4  c5!?  is a direct way to go for the ...c5 break   9...b6  1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@21@@EndBracket@@ Vidit, S @@StartBracket@@2701@@EndBracket@@-Nguyen, N @@StartBracket@@2641@@EndBracket@@ Makati 2018.  But after,  10.O-O  cxd4  11.Qxd4  Qxd4  12.Bxd4  I believe White has a typical Catalan slight edge in this endgame. }
9. Nxc4
{ We would be glad if White captures the pawn immediately! It allows us to gain further space with, }
9... b5
{ With ...b5 we not only attack the knight on c4 but also intend to push further to b4 kicking the c3-bishop and snatching valuable space on the queenside. }
10. Ne5 b4 11. Bd2 O-O
{ Now there will be no check on c6 and we are threatening to take the d4-pawn. }
12. Be3 Bb7 13. O-O Nd5 { Getting ready for ...c5. } 14. Nd2 c5
{ Black has achieved his strategic pawn break with extra space on the queenside. }
*

