1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. c4 e6 4. g3
{ Welcome to the Catalan!  The Catalan has established itself as a solid opening for White. It is usually associated with positions where White can press for a long time without risking anything. The majority of lines that arise from this opening are positional.  There are a lot of options for Black where he gets a solid position and these are generally considered as the mainlines. But in this repertoire, I am suggesting a line that is relatively fresh and will carry some element of surprise. Recently this line has been extensively played by the Spanish GM Anton Guijarro.  Most of the positions coming out of this line are dynamic. For example, positions where we are a pawn up but White has some compensation for it. As you will see in the mainline we are the one sacrificing material  (an exchange)  for compensation.  Some variations are also concrete so it is essential to remember them move by move. I have done my best in adding comments and explanations on important moves which will be useful for the readers to remember these concrete variations. }
4... dxc4 5. Bg2 c6
{ I recommend this slightly rare and fresh line against the Catalan. It contains a little element of surprise and in most variations, we get fighting positions. However, some critical variations may end in a draw. GM Anton Guijarro is a strong advocate of this variation as this is his main weapon against the Catalan recently. With 5...c6 we aim to defend our dear pawn on c4 with b7-b5. There are some options for White but essentially only two ways that White can respond to 5...c6. Either he can try to win the pawn on c4 as soon as possible or he can aim for long-term compensation by sacrificing the pawn. }
6. Ne5
{ White goes on the quest to win the pawn quickly by attacking it immediately. }
6... Bb4+
{ An important intermediate check before we do something to defend our c4-pawn.   6...b5?!  is not good for Black due to,  7.Nxc6   7.a4  is also a very good alternative as Black is now forced to play,  7...Nd5  which we do not want to play unless White has a knight on c3 as whenever White plays e4 we can exchange the knight on c3. Otherwise, after e4 our d5-knight will be kicked back and White will gain time.  7...Qb6  8.Na5!  a nice tactical resource in order to fulfil positional aims.  8...Nd5   8...Qxa5+?  9.Bd2+-  9.Bd2  and the a5 knight teamed up with the g2 bishop is very annoying for Black as it is not so easy to complete our queenside development. }
7. Bd2 Be7
{ This was the point of ...Bb4+. We have provoked White's bishop to d2 and now the d4-pawn is hanging so White has to delay his plans of recovering the c4-pawn. }
8. e3 { White defends the d4-pawn and is now ready to capture on c4. } 8... b5
{ This leads to an interesting exchange sacrifice which the engines don't like for Black initially but as we go deeper they appreciate its strength! We support our advanced c4-pawn as it is more dear to us than the exchange. }
9. b3
{ This is a typical pawn sacrifice by White. Instead of trying to recover his pawn, White goes for the b3-break and decides to forget about his lost pawn. The idea behind it is to open up files on the queenside and then create some positional pressure through these files. }
9... cxb3 10. axb3 Bb7 11. Ba5
{ The white bishop is well placed on a5 preventing Black's queenside pawn advance with ...a5, thus keeping Black a little passive for the moment.   11.O-O  is obviously met by,  11...a5  When Black is comfortable on the queenside. ½-½ @@StartBracket@@70@@EndBracket@@ Bryakin,M @@StartBracket@@2428@@EndBracket@@ -Harsha,B @@StartBracket@@2523@@EndBracket@@ El Prat ESP 2019 }
11... Qc8
{ Now we would like to go for our main strategic break ...c5 on the next move. }
12. Qf3 { Playing against the ...c5 break. } 12... Nbd7
{ The tactics work fine for Black. } 13. Nxc6
{ This leads to a more or less forced variation. There are a lot of moves ahead but they are quite easy to learn because of their forced nature. }
13... Nd5 { First of all, we cut the c6-knight's backup. } 14. Nxe7 Qc1+ 15.
Qd1
{ White is forced to exchange the intruder.   15.Ke2  Surprisingly this second option suggested by the engines does not lose for White despite losing the queen!  15...Qb2+  16.Nd2  Nc3+  Any human would leave the variation here seeing that White's queen is about to fall on the next move. But cold-hearted engines do not flinch!  17.Bxc3  Bxf3+  18.Bxf3  Qxc3  Now there are a few moves for White to maintain the balance. One logical move is  19.Bxa8  Kxe7  20.Rhc1!  getting the c-file under control before capturing the a7-pawn.   20.Rxa7?!  Rc8=+  with the idea of ...Rc7 gives Black a slight edge.  21...Qb2  22.Rab1  Qa3  23.Ra1  and the position would end in repetition after  23...Qb2= }
15... Qxd1+ 16. Kxd1 Nxe3+
{ A discovered check gets us White's important light-squared bishop.   16...Kxe7  is of course not our idea because that will leave us in a slightly inferior endgame as White enjoys the advantage of double bishops. }
17. fxe3 Bxg2 18. Rg1 Bb7
{ Now the brave e7-knight is under trouble and play revolves around it the next few moves. }
19. Bb4
{ And it seems that Black has lost a piece. But tricks do not end here yet! }
19... a5 { It's time to kick White's bishop around. } 20. Bd6 Ra6 21. Bb4
{ This forces the exchange of rooks which frees the c6 square for the e7-knight.   21.Ba3  is strongly met by  21...Rb6!  threatening ...b4 which was not possible earlier with a rook on a6 due to Bxb4 followed by Rxa6. }
21... axb4 22. Rxa6 Bxa6 23. Nc6
{ The knight finally manages to escape and equalize the game for White. } 23...
Bb7 24. Nxb4 Ke7
{ And after a series of forced moves we have transposed to a completely equal endgame. Black can advance on the kingside with h5-h4 or try to create play via the a-file by playing ...Ra8. }
