Nxc6 10. Bxc6+ Bd7 11. Bxa8
{ 11.Qf3?!  declining the challenge does not make sense now.  11...Rc8  12.Bxd7+  Qxd7  Black will castle next and enjoy a slight edge here due to more space on the queenside. }
11... Qxa8 12. f3 e5
{ A strong move opening up our light-squared bishop. This bishop is going to play an important role in the struggle as White is missing his light-squared bishop and his light squares on the kingside are weak. }
13. dxe5 { was once tried by GM Vidit, who is a Catalan expert. } 13... Ng4 14.
O-O Nxe5 { Our knight is going to settle down on the beautiful d3-square. } 15.
Bc3 Nd3 16. b3
{ is the move that Vidit chose in the game trying to uproot the knight from d3.   16.Bxg7  White grabs a pawn and hopes to give the exchange back at some point as he will still remain a pawn up. The drawback is that it opens up the g-file which creates new opportunities for Black to attack. When you analyse this position it all looks very easy to defend with White, but in a practical game, White has an uphill defensive task.  16...Rg8  17.Bd4  Bh4!   17...h5!?  is another interesting alternative here  18.Kh1   18.Rf2  is also a defensive try for White.  18...Bxg3!  Black should dare and sacrifice the bishop breaching lines against the white king.  19.hxg3  Rxg3+  20.Rg2  Rxg2+  21.Kxg2  Qd5  Black's pieces are teaming up to mate the white king. But White can defend himself with,  22.Qe2  Qg5+  23.Kh1  Qh4+  24.Qh2  and now we have to settle for a perpetual after,  24...Qe1+  25.Qg1  Qh4+=  18...Bxg3!  blasting White's defensive shield. Black also threatens to take on  h2  next.  19.Qe2  Rg6!  The black rook threatens to join the assault ...Rh6.  20.Nd2  Bh4  Black's pieces put a lot of pressure on White and he has to be tactically aware otherwise one miss by White and the game will be over. Black threatens to play ...Bh3 distracting the rook from f1 so that we can get in ...Nf2+. The position is still quite complex. I would like to continue a sample variation further.   20...Rh6?  does not work now due to,  21.Rg1!  Rxh2  22.Qxh2+-  and now we can see that because of 20.Nd2 the f3-pawn is protected and we don't have ...Qf3+.  21.e4  White covers the f2-square with his bishop and prepares Rg1.  21...Nf4  22.Qe3  Bh3  23.Rg1  Bg2+  24.Rxg2  Nxg2  25.Qc3  Ne1!  We intend to plant our knight on d3 again where it is very annoying for White. One of our threats is also to play ...Qc8 followed by ...Qh3 creating strong attacking threats against the white king. The position is still complex and with accurate play, he can still defend this position but it is tough to do so in a tournament game. }
16... O-O
{ We first ensure that our king is safe and then the next step is to activate our pieces. }
17. bxc4 bxc4 18. Nd2
{ White attacks the c4-pawn in order to unstabilize the knight on d3. } 18...
Bh3 { It is time to win our exchange back! } 19. Nxc4 Bxf1 20. Kxf1 Rd8
{ The black knight still stands tall on d3 and Black has sufficient compensation for equality. The game was drawn after a few moves. ½-½ @@StartBracket@@27@@EndBracket@@ Vidit,S @@StartBracket@@2711@@EndBracket@@-Vitiugov,N @@StartBracket@@2726@@EndBracket@@ Prague 2019 }
