6. Ne5
{ White goes on the quest to win the pawn quickly by attacking it immediately. }
6... Bb4+
{ An important intermediate check before we do something to defend our c4-pawn.   6...b5?!  is not good for Black due to,  7.Nxc6   7.a4  is also a very good alternative as Black is now forced to play,  7...Nd5  which we do not want to play unless White has a knight on c3 as whenever White plays e4 we can exchange the knight on c3. Otherwise, after e4 our d5-knight will be kicked back and White will gain time.  7...Qb6  8.Na5!  a nice tactical resource in order to fulfil positional aims.  8...Nd5   8...Qxa5+?  9.Bd2+-  9.Bd2  and the a5 knight teamed up with the g2 bishop is very annoying for Black as it is not so easy to complete our queenside development. }
7. Bd2 Be7
{ This was the point of ...Bb4+. We have provoked White's bishop to d2 and now the d4-pawn is hanging so White has to delay his plans of recovering the c4-pawn. }
8. e3 { White defends the d4-pawn and is now ready to capture on c4. } 8... b5
{ This leads to an interesting exchange sacrifice which the engines don't like for Black initially but as we go deeper they appreciate its strength! We support our advanced c4-pawn as it is more dear to us than the exchange. }
9. Nxc6 { Accepting the challenge is the critical test of Black's idea. } 9...
Nxc6 10. Bxc6+ Bd7 11. Bxa8
{ 11.Qf3?!  declining the challenge does not make sense now.  11...Rc8  12.Bxd7+  Qxd7  Black will castle next and enjoy a slight edge here due to more space on the queenside. }
11... Qxa8 12. f3 e5
{ A strong move opening up our light-squared bishop. This bishop is going to play an important role in the struggle as White is missing his light-squared bishop and his light squares on the kingside are weak. }
13. O-O exd4 14. exd4 O-O
{ Both sides have castled but White's king is still not so comfortable on the kingside because of the weak light squares and absence of the light-squared bishop around the king. One of Black's main idea is to play ...Nd5 followed by ...Bf6 adding pressure on the d4-pawn. We can also think of expanding on the queenside with ...a5-b4 or on the kingside with ...h5-h4. }
15. Re1 Nd5 16. Nc3 Bf6 { The d4-pawn is a target for us. } 17. Nxd5 Qxd5 18.
Bc3 h5 { With the intention to create more weaknesses in White's kingside. }
19. Qe2 a5 { Switching sides! Now ...b4 is on the way. } 20. Bxa5
{ 20.a3  White temporarily stops our ...b4 advance.  20...Rb8  insisting on ...b4.  21.Qe4  exchanging the active centralized black queen is favourable for White.  21...Qxe4  22.Rxe4  b4  23.axb4  axb4  24.Bd2  Bf5  pushing the white rook to an uncomfortable square and improving the position of the light-squared bishop.  25.Rf4  Bd3  and it is Black who is slightly better. Our bishops are strong and White has to always watch our for ...c3 followed by b3 when the b-pawn can be very dangerous. }
20... Qxd4+ 21. Kg2 Qxb2 22. Qxb2 Bxb2
{ Followed by ... c3 when the endgame is going to be equal. } *

