[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8. Deviations to the Vienna"]
[Black "Deviations to Vienna 4.cxd5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. c4 e6 4. cxd5
{ White exchanges on d5 depriving Black of the option to take on c4 and play the Vienna. }
4... exd5
{ The drawback of White's previous move is that it immediately opens up the diagonal for our light-squared bishop, so we can develop it quickly now. In general, the best place for our light-squared bishop is on f5, where it is not only well placed but also prevents White's bishop from developing actively with Bf1-d3. But, when playing ...Bf5 we should always watch out for the move Qd1-b3 as it creates some annoying pressure on the b7-pawn. }
5. Nc3 c6
{ 5...Bf5?!  We should not immediately develop our bishop to  f5  because of,  6.Qb3  which exploits the absence of the bishop on  c8  by putting pressure on the b7-pawn.  6...Nc6  This is the only comfortable way for Black to meet the threat to the b7-pawn.  7.Bg5  increasing pressure on the d5-pawn.  7...Na5  Black needs to urgently kick the white queen from  b3  before it is too late.  8.Qa4+  c6  9.Bxf6  gxf6=  Even though this position is playable for Black, I prefer not to play with these doubled f-pawns straight out of the opening. }
6. Bg5 Be7
{ Now we are all set to play Bc8-f5 because Qd1-b3 can be met by Qd8-b6.   6...Bf5?!  is again not the right time because of,  7.Qb3 }
7. Qc2
{ Preventing ...Bf5.   7.e3  does not pose any problems for Black. We simply continue with,  7...Bf5  8.Bd3  Bxd3  9.Qxd3  Nbd7  10.O-O  O-O=  With a completely fine game for Black.  11.Rab1  a5  12.Qc2  Re8  13.Bxf6  Nxf6  14.a3  Bd6  15.Ne2  Qc7  16.Nc1  a4  17.Ne2  Ne4  18.Rbc1  Re6  19.Nc3  Nxc3  20.Qxc3  Rae8  21.h3  Qd7  22.Rfe1  Rf6  23.Kf1  Bc7  24.Qd3  Ba5  25.Red1  Bc7  26.b4  axb3  27.Qxb3  Bd6  28.a4  Rfe6  29.Rc3  R6e7  30.Rb1  1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@30@@EndBracket@@ Kamsky,G @@StartBracket@@2683@@EndBracket@@-Shankland,S @@StartBracket@@2661@@EndBracket@@ Saint Louis 2015 }
7... g6 8. e4
{ This break was a bit challenging two decades ago, but now Black would be happy to face this line anytime.   8.Bxf6?!  is not good because of,  8...Bxf6  9.e4  O-O  and White's central aggression may backfire as he is still behind in development.   8.e3  is again easy to meet.  8...Bf5  9.Bd3  Bxd3  10.Qxd3  Nbd7  11.O-O  O-O=  we have managed to exchange the light-squared bishops which is in our favour. Black has a comfortable game.  12.h3  Re8  13.Bf4  Bf8  14.Ne5  Bg7  15.Bh2  Nxe5  16.Bxe5  Ne4  17.Bxg7  Kxg7  18.Nxe4  Rxe4  19.b4  a6  20.a4  Qd6  21.b5  c5  22.dxc5  Qxc5  23.bxa6  Rxa6  24.Rfb1  Raxa4  25.Rxa4  Rxa4  26.Rxb7  d4  27.exd4  Qc1+  28.Kh2  Qf4+  29.Qg3  Qxg3+  30.Kxg3  Rxd4  31.Kf3  Rc4  32.Kg3  Rd4  33.Kf3  Rc4  34.Kg3  Rd4  1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@34@@EndBracket@@ Bu,X @@StartBracket@@2723@@EndBracket@@-Wei,Y @@StartBracket@@2696@@EndBracket@@ Wuxi 2016 }
8... dxe4
{ 8...Nxe4?!  9.Bxe7  Qxe7??  loses to  10.Nxd5!+-   Black is still fine after,  9...Kxe7  10.Nxe4  dxe4  11.Qxe4+  Be6=  Black plays ...Re8 followed by ...Kf8 next when his king will be comfortable on the kingside. }
9. Bxf6 Bxf6 10. Qxe4+ Qe7
{ It is best to transpose to an endgame as endgames are generally good for the side playing against the IQP.   10...Kf8  with the idea to play ...Kg7 is also completely playable for Black. }
11. Bc4 Bf5 12. Qxe7+ Kxe7
{ Now one of our ideas is to play Nb8-d7-b6 and we can also bring our rooks into the game pretty quickly. If our king ever feels uncomfortable on e7, it can always travel to the safe square on g7. }
