[White "8. Deviations to the Vienna"]
[Black "Deviations to Vienna 4.e3 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. c4 e6 4. e3
{ I have tried this move in a couple of games. In general White wants to avoid a theoretical debate and focus on a more strategic game and typical pawn structures like the Isolated Queen’s Pawn, Hanging Pawns etc. }
4... a6
{ a generally useful move. One of the ideas is to capture on c4 and when White recaptures with the bishop we can play b7-b5. }
5. b3
{ White supports the c4-pawn so that he can recapture back with the b-pawn on c4.   5.Nc3  dxc4  transposes to chapters 11, 12 and 13   5.Nbd2  should most probably transpose to our mainline after,  5...c5  6.b3   6.cxd5  can be met by,  6...Nxd5  7.Bd3  Nc6  8.O-O  cxd4  9.exd4  Be7=  Black had a comfortable version of the IQP. One thing to note here is that the knight on d2 is oddly placed and it should have been on c3. 0-1 @@StartBracket@@57@@EndBracket@@ Cori,J @@StartBracket@@2652@@EndBracket@@-Svane,R @@StartBracket@@2613@@EndBracket@@ chess.com INT 2020   6.dxc5  avoiding ...cxd4 has also been played in a few games.  6...Bxc5  7.a3  White obviously wants to play b4 and then Bb2.  7...dxc4  We use the same idea to develop our light-squared bishop with a tempo.  8.Bxc4  b5  9.Be2  Bb7  10.b4  Bd6  this retreat breaks the symmetry. Notice White's kingside bishop is on e2 whilst ours is placed actively on d6.  11.Bb2  O-O  12.O-O  Nbd7  with pawns facing each other on b4 and b5, it is usually recommended to develop our knight from d7 so that it can go to b6 later.  13.Rc1  Qe7=  We are ready to bring our rooks into the game on the d- and c-files. Black is doing well in this position. ½-½  (76)  Westerberg,J  (2489)  -Grandelius,N  (2643)  Uppsala 2016  6...cxd4  7.exd4  Nc6  8.Bb2  g6  9.Bd3  Bg7  10.O-O  O-O  transposes. }
5... c5 6. Bb2 cxd4
{ We make sure that White ends up with hanging pawns with this exchange. We will sooner or later also exchange pawns on c4. }
7. exd4 Nc6 8. Bd3
{ 8.Nbd2  g6!?  developing the bishop to g7 is the best way to play in this structure. There might soon be hanging pawns on the board once we capture with ...dxc4. When this happens, our bishop will be strongly placed on the a1-h8 diagonal.  9.Bd3  Bg7  10.O-O  O-O  leads to the mainline. }
8... g6
{ Fianchettoing the bishop to g7 is the best way to play against the hanging pawns. With the bishop on g7, we can put pressure on the d4-pawn. }
9. O-O Bg7 10. Nc3
{ Surprisingly, this is a novelty! White develops his knight to c3 with the idea to play c5 next. If Black breaks with ...b6 then White wants to capture on b6 and followed by activating his knight further with Na4-c5. }
10... O-O 11. c5 b6
{ Black should of course break on the queenside as quickly as possible. } 12.
cxb6 Nd7
{ A nice move, intending to recapture the b6-pawn with the knight. The f6-knight needed to move anyway so that the g7-bishop can come to life and exert pressure on the d4-pawn. }
13. Na4 Nxb6 14. Nc5
{ White achieved his main idea of activating his knight on the strong c5-square. But we don't let his knight stabilize there and challenge it immediately with }
14... Nd7 15. Rc1 Nxc5 16. Rxc5
{ White now has a rook on c5 instead of a knight. However, the rook is not a problem for us and we can simply continue with }
16... Qd6
{ Intending to play ...Bd7 followed by bringing our rook to c8. Black is doing fine in this position. The pressure on the d4-pawn limits White's possibilities. }
