[White "9. Vienna 5.Qa4+"]
[Black "Vienna 5.Qa4+ Nbd7 6.e4 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. Qa4+
{ Very rarely have I faced  5.Qa4+  in my entire career with the Vienna opening. This move is more of an attempt to transpose into the Slav Defence. But we will avoid going into the Slav territory. }
5... Nbd7
{ We block the check with the knight and not with our c-pawn because we want to go for the direct c7-c5 break in the future. Our ideal plan now is to play a7-a6, b7-b5, Bc8-b7 and then break with c7-c5. Of course, White will try his best to hamper our plans.   5...c6  6.Qxc4  b5  is a major alternative that transposes into the variations of the Slav Defence. }
6. e4
{ This is the only challenging continuation here for White and rightly the most popular move which can create problems in our previously mentioned plans. White establishes control in the centre and prepares to capture on c4 with the bishop. }
6... a6 7. Bxc4 Rb8 8. Qc2 b5 9. Bd3 Bb7
{ 9...c5?!  would be premature due to,  10.Bf4  Rb6  11.a4!  , creating a strong pressure on the Queenside gives White a clear advantage. }
10. Bf4
{ A nice multi-purpose move, developing the bishop as well as delaying Black's ...c5 break. White has also got the option of O-O-O in some cases. }
10... Nh5
{ This strong novelty was overlooked by many strong players! Black's idea is simple, we want to push White's bishop away from the h2-b8 diagonal so that we can carry out our break with c7-c5.   10...Rc8  is a logical reply, but White gets a nice initiative with  11.d5!  exd5  12.O-O-O!  a quick O-O-O gives White a very strong initiative as the black king is still stuck in the centre. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@21@@EndBracket@@ Rapport,R @@StartBracket@@2731@@EndBracket@@-Van Foreest,J @@StartBracket@@2612@@EndBracket@@ Wijk aan Zee 2019 }
11. Be3 c5
{ Now in order to maintain the tension, White needs to go ahead with } 12. d5
c4 13. dxe6 fxe6 14. Be2 Nhf6
{ Avoiding any tricks with an unprotected knight on h5 and putting pressure on the e4-pawn at the same time. Black now plans to play ... Bc5 next offering the exchange of the dark-squared bishops which is in Black's favour. }
15. Rd1 { Preventing ...Bc5. } 15... Bb4 16. O-O Qe7
{ Black is now all set to O-O with a fine position. Our pieces are active and we have space on the queenside as compensation for a slightly weak pawn structure. White can try to create some threats on the kingside with }
17. e5 Bxc3
{ Exchanging on c3 in order to get unrestricted access to the d5-square for our knight. }
18. bxc3 Nd5 19. Bc1 h6
{ An important prophylactic move preventing Ng5 ideas. It is now safe for Black to castle on the next move. }
20. Rd4 O-O 21. Rg4 { Threatening Bxh6. Now after the simple } 21... Kh8
{ There are no more attacking ideas for White on the kingside and Black can think of ways to create pressure around the e5-pawn. Ideas like ...Rxf3 can also be taken into consideration. Black is fine here. }
