{ This is the only challenging continuation here for White and rightly the most popular move which can create problems in our previously mentioned plans. White establishes control in the centre and prepares to capture on c4 with the bishop. }
6... a6 7. Bxc4 Rb8 8. Qc2 b5 9. Bd3 Bb7
{ 9...c5?!  would be premature due to,  10.Bf4  Rb6  11.a4!  , creating a strong pressure on the Queenside gives White a clear advantage. }
10. Bf4
{ A nice multi-purpose move, developing the bishop as well as delaying Black's ...c5 break. White has also got the option of O-O-O in some cases. }
10... Nh5
{ This strong novelty was overlooked by many strong players! Black's idea is simple, we want to push White's bishop away from the h2-b8 diagonal so that we can carry out our break with c7-c5.   10...Rc8  is a logical reply, but White gets a nice initiative with  11.d5!  exd5  12.O-O-O!  a quick O-O-O gives White a very strong initiative as the black king is still stuck in the centre. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@21@@EndBracket@@ Rapport,R @@StartBracket@@2731@@EndBracket@@-Van Foreest,J @@StartBracket@@2612@@EndBracket@@ Wijk aan Zee 2019 }
