c4 13. dxe6 fxe6 14. Be2 Nhf6 15. Nd4 { Attacks the e6-pawn directly. } 15...
Qb6
{ A surprising way to defend the e6-pawn, not worrying about the discovered attack by the bishop on e3. We would like to play ...Bc5 on the next move, attacking the d4-knight and preparing to O-O.   15...Bb4!?  temporarily sacrificing the e6-pawn in order to counter-attack the e4-pawn is also an interesting alternative. }
16. Ndxb5
{ This is the critical continuation for White. Otherwise Black get a comfortable position after ...Bc5. }
16... Bc5 17. Na3
{ it is better to retreat on a3 directly without giving Black the opportunity to activate the d7-knight. }
17... Bxe3 18. fxe3 Ne5 19. Nxc4 Nxc4 20. Bxc4 Ng4
{ This is the best move for Black, waiting for the right opportunity to capture on e3 and also forcing White to find the best move.   20...Qxe3+  also leads to an equal endgame after  21.Qe2  Qxe2+  22.Kxe2  Nxe4  simplifying the position as much as possible.  23.Nxe4  Bxe4  24.b3  Ke7  and after  25.Bxa6  Bxg2  26.Rhg1  Bd5  27.Rxg7+  Kd6=  White has managed to win a pawn and in fact, has two passed pawns on the queenside, but the position still remains balanced as it is not easy for White to advance his pawns. Black also has very good chances to create counterplay by using our rooks. }
21. Rf1 Ba8
{ Not only threatening the b2-pawn but also protecting the b6-queen so that ...Nxe3 becomes possible now.   21...Nxe3?  would be a huge mistake due to the strong  22.Qf2!+-  pinning the e3-knight and threatening Qf7+. }
22. Nd1 { Defending both pawns. } 22... Nxe3
{ It is time to simplify the position. } 23. Nxe3 Qxe3+ 24. Qe2 Qxe2+ 25. Bxe2
Rxb2
{ The material is equal and Black's rook is active on the 2nd rank. Black is at least equal in this position. }
