1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. Qa4+
{ Very rarely have I faced  5.Qa4+  in my entire career with the Vienna opening. This move is more of an attempt to transpose into the Slav Defence. But we will avoid going into the Slav territory. }
5... Nbd7
{ We block the check with the knight and not with our c-pawn because we want to go for the direct c7-c5 break in the future. Our ideal plan now is to play a7-a6, b7-b5, Bc8-b7 and then break with c7-c5. Of course, White will try his best to hamper our plans.   5...c6  6.Qxc4  b5  is a major alternative that transposes into the variations of the Slav Defence. }
6. e4
{ This is the only challenging continuation here for White and rightly the most popular move which can create problems in our previously mentioned plans. White establishes control in the centre and prepares to capture on c4 with the bishop. }
6... a6 7. Bxc4 Rb8 8. Qc2 b5 9. Bd3 Bb7
{ 9...c5?!  would be premature due to  10.Bf4  Rb6  11.d5! } 10. e5
{ With this move, White gains space in the centre and makes sure @@StartBracket@@with further moves@@EndBracket@@ that Black will not be able to break with ...c5. But White in turn hands over the d5 square outpost to us permanently which more than compensates for not being able to get in the ...c5 break. }
10... Nd5 11. Nxd5 Bxd5 12. O-O c5
{ Black should break with ...c5 as soon as possible before it is too late and White starts putting pressure on the c7-pawn.   12...Bxf3?!  13.gxf3  c5  would be a bit risky this time as White is ready to bring his rooks into play quickly this time.  14.dxc5  Bxc5  15.Be4  Black cannot O-O immediately because the h7-pawn hangs. White is ready to create pressure on the open d- and c-files by bringing his rooks into the game quickly. }
13. Be4 Bxe4 14. Qxe4 c4
{ Keeping the lines closed for now and creating a pawn majority on the queenside. Black is doing fine in this position. A sample variation could be, }
15. a4 Nb6 16. axb5 axb5 17. Bg5 Qd5
{ Because of his firm control of the d5-square, Black is enjoying a pleasant position. For example }
18. Qg4 Ra8 { Cutting any active ideas for White along the a-file. } 19. Nd2
{ A logical transfer of the knight to a better position. } 19... h6 20. Be3
{ Now there are 3 options suggested by the engine that gives a good play for Black. I would like to mention two of them. }
20... Na4
{ 20...h5  is another fine move for Black. We distract White's queen from g4. If it moves away from the g-file then we can safely develop our bishop to e7  (as the g7-pawn will no longer be attacked)  .  21.Qg5  keeping an eye on the g7-pawn.  21...Na4  22.Rfb1  c3!  creating a passed pawn on the queenside.  23.bxc3  Nxc3  24.Rxa8+  Qxa8  25.Re1  Qd8!  it is funny that after so many moves Black's queen has returned to its original square! We challenge White's queen so that we can develop our bishop from f8.  26.Qxd8+  Kxd8  27.Ra1  Na4  preventing any penetration along the a-file. This line may end in a repetition after  28.Rb1  Nc3  29.Ra1  Na4= }
21. Ne4 h5
{ Hitting the queen so that we can develop our bishop.   21...Nxb2?  loses to  22.Nc3  Qb7  23.Nxb5!  +-  White manages to open up the queenside and with our king still in the centre, it is the end for Black. }
22. Qf3 Be7 23. h4 { Fixing the pawn on h5. } 23... O-O
{ Black has castled safely and now it is up to White to figure out a way for creating something on the kingside. With accurate play, White manages to find a draw but it is very difficult to do so in a practical game. }
24. Bg5 { White ignores the b2-pawn and focuses completely on the kingside. }
24... Bxg5 25. hxg5 Nxb2 26. Rae1
{ A surprisingly cool move. White protects the e4-knight and prepares Qxh5. }
26... Nd3 27. Qxh5 Nxe1 28. Rxe1 Qxd4
{ And now White should force a draw with an elegant knight sacrifice. } 29.
Nf6+ gxf6 30. g6
{ 30.gxf6??  throws away the draw due to  30...Qf4!-+  covering all the dangerous entry squares of White's queen. }
30... fxg6 31. Qxg6+ Kh8 32. Qh6+ Kg8 { And this line too will end in a draw. }
