{ Very rarely have I faced  5.Qa4+  in my entire career with the Vienna opening. This move is more of an attempt to transpose into the Slav Defence. But we will avoid going into the Slav territory. }
5... Nbd7
{ We block the check with the knight and not with our c-pawn because we want to go for the direct c7-c5 break in the future. Our ideal plan now is to play a7-a6, b7-b5, Bc8-b7 and then break with c7-c5. Of course, White will try his best to hamper our plans.   5...c6  6.Qxc4  b5  is a major alternative that transposes into the variations of the Slav Defence. }
6. e4
{ This is the only challenging continuation here for White and rightly the most popular move which can create problems in our previously mentioned plans. White establishes control in the centre and prepares to capture on c4 with the bishop. }
6... a6 7. Bxc4 Rb8 8. Qc2 b5 9. Bd3 Bb7
{ 9...c5?!  would be premature due to  10.Bf4  Rb6  11.d5! } 10. e5
{ With this move, White gains space in the centre and makes sure @@StartBracket@@with further moves@@EndBracket@@ that Black will not be able to break with ...c5. But White in turn hands over the d5 square outpost to us permanently which more than compensates for not being able to get in the ...c5 break. }
10... Nd5 11. Be4 Nxc3
{ Trading pieces is favourable for Black as White has the space advantage.   Another decent alternative for Black to play is  11...N7b6  12.O-O  Be7  Black would like to play ...h6 followed by O-O.  13.Nxd5  Bxd5  14.Be3  h6=  followed by O-O next gives Black a fine position. White has more space in the centre but Black has a firm outpost on the d5-square maintaining the balance. This position is quite similar to the mainline where the light-squared bishops are missing from the board. }
12. Bxb7 Rxb7 13. Qxc3 Be7
{ 13...c5?!  would be premature due to  14.Ng5!  and if  14...cxd4??  then  15.Qf3+- }
14. Be3 O-O 15. Qc6 { forcing the rook to the b6 square. } 15... Rb6 16. Qc2
Rb8
{ Black frees the b6 square for the knight. White should also watch out for the ...c5 break which may be possible due to some concrete tactics. }
17. O-O Nb6
{ Black has a firm outpost on the d5 square, his bishop is slightly better than White's and he can think of expanding on the queenside with a6-a5-a4. White on the other hand has pressure on the c-file, his knight also has a good post on the e4 square. In short, the position is playable for both sides but I would prefer to play with the black pieces. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10. Vienna 5.g3"]
[Black "Vienna 5.g3 c5 6.Bg2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. g3
{ It is possible that you will never face this line in your entire career but it is better to be prepared for it than to be caught off-guard. The 5.g3 variation is rarely played against the Vienna and rightly so as it is just an inferior version of the Catalan or the g3 variation in the Slav Defence. If you compare it to the Catalan then we can see that White has already committed his knight to c3 and if you compare it with the g3 variation of the Slav Defence then Black has not played c7-c6 and can go for the ...c5 break in one move. In both cases, it is Black who benefits from these slight changes. }
5... c5 { I recommend going for action in the centre immediately. } 6. Bg2 Nc6
7. Qa4
{ Finally White decides to recover the pawn before it is too late.   7.dxc5?!  Qxd1+  8.Nxd1  Bxc5  and White will have a hard time regaining the pawn on c4. Even if White manages to recover the pawn Black will have sufficient time to complete his development and bring his rooks into action. ½-½ @@StartBracket@@20@@EndBracket@@ Ivanov,M @@StartBracket@@2445@@EndBracket@@-Farago,I @@StartBracket@@2520@@EndBracket@@ Osterskars 1995 }
7... cxd4 { This leads to a few exchanges and simple equality for Black. } 8.
Nxd4 Qxd4 9. Bxc6+ Bd7 10. Bxd7+ Qxd7 11. Qxc4 Rc8
{ Black will play ...Bc5 next followed by ...O-O with complete equality for Black. 1/2-1/ 2 @@StartBracket@@14@@EndBracket@@ Javakhishvili,L @@StartBracket@@2472@@EndBracket@@-Zhukova,N @@StartBracket@@2457@@EndBracket@@ Novi Sad 2009 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10. Vienna 5.g3"]
[Black "Vienna 5.g3 c5 6.Qa4+ #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. g3
{ It is possible that you will never face this line in your entire career but it is better to be prepared for it than to be caught off-guard. The 5.g3 variation is rarely played against the Vienna and rightly so as it is just an inferior version of the Catalan or the g3 variation in the Slav Defence. If you compare it to the Catalan then we can see that White has already committed his knight to c3 and if you compare it with the g3 variation of the Slav Defence then Black has not played c7-c6 and can go for the ...c5 break in one move. In both cases, it is Black who benefits from these slight changes. }
5... c5 { I recommend going for action in the centre immediately. } 6. Qa4+ Bd7
7. Qxc4 { Now I would like to recommend an interesting novelty for Black! }
7... b5
{ This move has never been played before. Black sacrifices the b-pawn to open up lines on the queenside and bring the pieces out with tempo. The time gained with this sacrifice can be utilized to create pressure on the queenside. }
8. Nxb5 { White has to accept the challenge. } 8... Qb6 9. a4
{ just weakens the b3 square for White and is met by, } 9... a6 10. Na3
{ 10.Nc3  Nc6  the idea of Nc6-a5-b3 is very troublesome for White and gives Black a strong initiative. }
10... cxd4 11. Bg2
{ 11.Nxd4??  is a huge mistake due to,  11...Bb4+-+  White's king will forever stay in the centre until its demise. }
11... Bb4+ 12. Bd2 Bxd2+ 13. Nxd2 Nc6
{ Black will O-O next with a completely fine position. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10. Vienna 5.g3"]
[Black "Vienna 5.g3 c5 6.Qa4+ #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. g3
{ It is possible that you will never face this line in your entire career but it is better to be prepared for it than to be caught off-guard. The 5.g3 variation is rarely played against the Vienna and rightly so as it is just an inferior version of the Catalan or the g3 variation in the Slav Defence. If you compare it to the Catalan then we can see that White has already committed his knight to c3 and if you compare it with the g3 variation of the Slav Defence then Black has not played c7-c6 and can go for the ...c5 break in one move. In both cases, it is Black who benefits from these slight changes. }
5... c5 { I recommend going for action in the centre immediately. } 6. Qa4+ Bd7
7. Qxc4 { Now I would like to recommend an interesting novelty for Black! }
7... b5
{ This move has never been played before. Black sacrifices the b-pawn to open up lines on the queenside and bring the pieces out with tempo. The time gained with this sacrifice can be utilized to create pressure on the queenside. }
8. Nxb5 { White has to accept the challenge. } 8... Qb6 9. Na3
{ The main idea behind retreating the knight to a3 rather than c3 is that after Black captures ...cxd4 White won't be forced to recapture immediately @@StartBracket@@the knight will not be under attack@@EndBracket@@.   9.e4  is strongly met by  9...a6  kicking the knight away before capturing on d4.  10.Nc3  cxd4  11.Nxd4  Bc5=+  Black is ready to O-O next with a nice initiative for the pawn. We also have ideas like ...Nc6 putting more pressure on the d4-knight. Another move to consider is ...Ng4 in case White chooses to defend with Be3.   9.e3?  is clearly a mistake due to  9...Bc6∓  followed by ...Qb7 where White will be in trouble. }
9... cxd4 10. Bg2
{ 10.Nxd4??  is a huge mistake exactly similar to what we saw in the variation of 9.a4.  10...Bb4+  -+  forcing White's king to stay in the centre forever. }
10... Nc6
{ White exploits the power of his light-squared bishop along the h1-a8 diagonal, but things are not so easy for him. }
11. Nxd4 Nxd4 12. Bxa8 Bb4+ 13. Kf1 O-O
{ It is very rare that you castle with a threat! The bishop on a8 is under attack. }
14. Be3
{ The only move! It is essential for White to eliminate the powerful d4-Knight.   14.Bg2?  loses to  14...Bxa3!  eliminating the knight in order to gain access to the b5-square.  15.bxa3  Bb5  16.Qb4  Ng4-+  Black has a winning advantage as our attack on the f2 and e2 pawns are unbearable for White. }
14... Rxa8 15. Bxd4 Qb7 16. f3 e5 { Freeing our light-squared bishop. } 17. Bc3
{ 17.Bxe5?  loses more or less by force after  17...Bh3+  18.Kf2  Rc8  Black's last piece rushes out with a tempo.  19.Qd3  Ng4+!  A nice deflecting sacrifice, clearing the path for Black's queen.  20.fxg4  Bc5+  and now White loses by force.  21.Bd4  Qg2+  22.Ke3  Bxd4+  23.Qxd4  Re8+  24.Kd2  Qxe2+  25.Kc3   25.Kc1  Rc8+  -+ wins for Black as well.  25...Re3+  26.Kb4  Re4-+  and Black wins the queen with a winning position. White's pawns are weak and his king is exposed. }
17... Bxa3 18. bxa3 Rc8 19. Qb4 Bb5 { Threatening ...Qxf3+ } 20. Kg2 Nd5
{ The knight jumps to d5 with a triple attack. } 21. Qb2 Ne3+
{ It is better to maintain the pressure rather than win material and let White's pieces escape. }
22. Kf2 Qb6
{ And it is clear that Black has more than sufficient compensation for the exchange due to our active pieces and the weak position of the white king. }
*

