[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11. Vienna 5.Bg5"]
[Black "Vienna 5.Bg5 a6 6.e4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. Bg5
{ This move is not seen frequently in tournament practice. With  5.Bg5  White develops his bishop and pins the knight on f6. He can later decide whether to play e2-e3 or e2-e4 next. }
5... a6
{ I believe this is the strongest reply against 5. Bg5. Black uses the fact that White has delayed recapturing the c4-pawn and prioritized the development of his dark-squared bishop.   With  5...a6  we prepare to support the c4-pawn with b7-b5, when it will be difficult for White to win the pawn at all.   5...c5  and  5...Bb4  are other possible options for Black. }
6. e4
{ White controls the centre and threatens to play e4-e5  (we will see later that it's actually not a threat that needs to be feared!)  but at the cost of the c4-pawn as Black is all set to protect it. }
6... b5
{ This position is very similar to the Botvinnik variation of the Slav defence which is considered to be a very complex variation. Comparing this position to the Botvinnik variation, a huge difference is that Black has supported the pawn on c4 with a6-b5, not c6-b5.  This absence of the black pawn on c6 is to our advantage as we can go for the break c7-c5 in one move and also when we fianchetto our light-squared bishop to b7 it will put pressure on the h1-a8 diagonal as the diagonal is now open with our pawn on c7. }
7. a4 { Can be met by the simple } 7... Bb7
{ The bishop comes into the game, putting pressure on White's centre at the same time. We are ready to sacrifice our b5 pawn where capturing will waste valuable time for White. }
8. axb5 axb5 9. Rxa8 Bxa8 10. e5 h6 11. Bh4 { is met by } 11... g5 12. Nxg5
hxg5 13. Bxg5 Nbd7 14. exf6
{ 14.Nxb5??  loses to,  14...Qb8!-+  when Black uses the unprotected b5-knight to get out of the pin on the f6-knight. Black will be a clear piece up. }
14... b4
{ Black will win the f6-pawn sooner or later with a clear advantage as White's king may experience a lot of problems in the centre. On top of that Black's queenside pawns can be dangerous as they are already far advanced. }
*

