7. e5
{ Going after the f6-knight. Now the continuation is forced for a few moves. }
7... h6 8. Bh4 g5 9. Nxg5
{ 9.Bg3  does not make any sense as after  9...Nd5  Black is a clear pawn up. }
9... hxg5 10. Bxg5 Nbd7 { Black develops the knight and prevents Bxf6. } 11.
Be2 Bb7 12. Bf3 { Does not work for White due to a nice tactical shot } 12...
Nxe5 { Using the fact that the black knight can land on d3 with a check! } 13.
Bxb7
{ 13.dxe5  Qxd1+  1.Rxd1  Bxf3  15.gxf3  Nd7  Black is clearly better due to his better pawn structure. }
13... Nd3+ 14. Kf1 Rb8 15. Bc6+ Ke7
{ Black's knight on d3 is too strong and White's king is about to face problems. The d4-pawn is under attack by Black's queen and we also have ideas like ...Bh6 fighting against the pin on the f6-knight. }
16. d5 { Defends the threat of ...Qxd4 but allows Black's other idea: } 16...
Bh6 { Getting rid of the pin on the f6-knight. } 17. Bxf6+ Kxf6 18. Ne4+ Ke7
{ And Black's king is completely safe in the centre. The d3-knight is too strong! }
