[White "11. Vienna 5.Bg5"]
[Black "Vienna 5.Bg5 a6 6.e3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. Bg5
{ This move is not seen frequently in tournament practice. With  5.Bg5  White develops his bishop and pins the knight on f6. He can later decide whether to play e2-e3 or e2-e4 next. }
5... a6
{ I believe this is the strongest reply against 5. Bg5. Black uses the fact that White has delayed recapturing the c4-pawn and prioritized the development of his dark-squared bishop.   With  5...a6  we prepare to support the c4-pawn with b7-b5, when it will be difficult for White to win the pawn at all.   5...c5  and  5...Bb4  are other possible options for Black. }
6. e3
{ is too passive to be challenging. In fact, it is Black who seizes the initiative with energetic play. }
6... b5 7. a4 c6
{ This move guarantees Black an initiative. We are ready to sacrifice an exchange to bring out our pieces quickly and put pressure on White. }
8. axb5
{ White can also start with  8.Bxf6  gxf6  it is essential for us to maintain the queen on d8 so that when we sacrifice our exchange and White captures our a8-rook, our knight on b8 won't be hanging.  9.axb5  cxb5  10.Nxb5  axb5  11.Rxa8  Bb4+  12.Nd2   12.Ke2  Bb7  transposes as well.  12...Bb7  transposes }
8... cxb5 9. Nxb5 axb5
{ Sacrificing the exchange gives Black the initiative as White's kingside pieces are still undeveloped. }
10. Rxa8 Bb4+ 11. Nd2
{ Allows the white king to stay on e1, but the knight on d2 gives Black opportunities to create an initiative. }
11... Bb7 12. Bxf6 gxf6 13. Ra1 e5
{ Black opens up the centre before White castles and settles down. } 14. Be2
{ White focuses on taking his king to safety. } 14... exd4 15. O-O dxe3
{ White's centre has evaporated! } 16. Nf3 exf2+ 17. Kh1
{ The dust has settled down after a series of forced moves. White has grabbed the exchange and managed to transfer his king safely to the kingside. Black, in turn, has gotten two pawns for the exchange  (since the f2-pawn is about to fall)  and also has two strong bishops. }
17... O-O 18. Rxf2 Nc6
{ The material is more or less balanced but Black's active pieces and White's weak kingside guarantees him at least a slight edge. Black has ideas like ...Bc5 and ...Ne5. Another important point to note is that Black's b5-c4 pawn chain effectively restricts White's pieces - especially his bishop. }
