10. Rxa8 Bb4+ 11. Ke2
{ with this White manages to keep his knight active on f3 but loses the right to castle and the white king is going to stay in the centre for a long time. It is instructive to see how White lost quickly from this position in a game between two top players. }
11... Bb7 12. Bxf6 gxf6 13. Ra1 O-O
{ We are ready to break in the centre with e6-e5 and open up the d-file which will help us to harass the white king. }
14. Qc2
{ This natural-looking move that appears to improve the position of the queen, is in fact an error that was exploited ruthlessly by Black in the game. }
14... f5 15. Nd2 Nc6 16. Rd1 { And now after the nice strike, } 16... Qxd4
{ White's position collapsed quickly. In White's defence I must say that this was a blitz game, but it is still instructive for us to know this game as Black. 0-1 @@StartBracket@@26@@EndBracket@@ Mamedyarov,S @@StartBracket@@2817@@EndBracket@@ -Nakamura,H @@StartBracket@@2746@@EndBracket@@ Kolkata 2018 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11. Vienna 5.Bg5"]
[Black "Vienna 5.Bg5 a6 6.a4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. Bg5
{ This move is not seen frequently in tournament practice. With  5.Bg5  White develops his bishop and pins the knight on f6. He can later decide whether to play e2-e3 or e2-e4 next. }
5... a6
{ I believe this is the strongest reply against 5. Bg5. Black uses the fact that White has delayed recapturing the c4-pawn and prioritized the development of his dark-squared bishop.   With  5...a6  we prepare to support the c4-pawn with b7-b5, when it will be difficult for White to win the pawn at all.   5...c5  and  5...Bb4  are other possible options for Black. }
6. a4
{ White prevents Black from supporting the c4-pawn with b7-b5 but it creates new weaknesses in White's queenside, for example, the b4 square is now weak. }
6... Nc6
{ Black finds a unique way of protecting his pawn on c4 and making it tough for White to recover it. Our knight is heading towards a5. }
7. e4
{ This aggressive advance will make it even more difficult for White to recover the c4-pawn as his central pawns on d4 and e4 remain a bit shaky. }
7... Na5 8. e5
{ leads to a forced sequence and is usually met in style.   8.Qc2  leads to a clearly better position for Black after,  8...Be7  9.Rd1  h6  forcing White to decide what to do with the bishop.  10.Bxf6  Bxf6  11.e5  Be7  12.d5  White decides to go all out in the centre, but Black can simply ignore White's aggression with,  12...O-O!  giving up the extra pawn to exploit White's lack of development on the kingside.  13.dxe6  Qe8  14.exf7+  Qxf7  White is still far behind in development and Black dominates on the queenside. ½-½ @@StartBracket@@49@@EndBracket@@ Mamedyarov,S @@StartBracket@@2817@@EndBracket@@-Anand,V @@StartBracket@@2773@@EndBracket@@ Kolkata 2018. }
8... h6 9. Bh4 g5 { Breaking the pin. } 10. Nxg5 hxg5 11. Bxg5 Be7 12. exf6
Bxf6 13. Bxf6 Qxf6
{ After a forced sequence of moves we have reached a position where Black is clearly better. He plans to play Bc8-d7 followed by either Bd7-c6 or O-O-O. Black has won all the 4 games that have been played from this position!: 0-1 @@StartBracket@@24@@EndBracket@@ Van Wely,L @@StartBracket@@2622@@EndBracket@@ -Van Foreest,J @@StartBracket@@2613@@EndBracket@@ Amstelveen 2018 }
