[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12. Vienna 5.e3 a6 6.a4"]
[Black "Vienna 5.e3 a6 with 8.d5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. e3 a6 6. a4
{ This is the obvious alternative to  6.Bxc4  and the second most popular alternative for White. He prevents b7-b5 and aims to recapture the c4-pawn on the next move.  With a2-a4 White manages to prevent Black's queenside expansion but at the same time weakens the  b4  square permanently, which Black is going to use for his own benefit in the middlegame as well as in the endgame. }
6... c5 { 6...b6  is another fighting alternative for Black. } 7. Bxc4 Nc6
{ Since white has played a4, the knight is perfectly placed on c6, from where it eyes the weak square on b4. }
8. d5 { is harmless. Black can play } 8... exd5 9. Nxd5 Na5
{ An important intermediate move pushing the white bishop back from its active post.   9...Be6  is also a decent possibility but White has,  10.e4!?  which might be a bit complicated. }
10. Ba2 Be6 11. Nxf6+
{ 11.e4  is not so strong now as it can easily be met by,  11...Nxe4  12.O-O  c4!  cutting the support of the white bishop and the knight.  13.Nf4  Qxd1  14.Rxd1  Bc5  Black is a clear pawn up plus our active pieces put a lot of pressure on White. }
11... Qxf6 12. Bd2 Bxa2 13. Bxa5
{ 13.Rxa2  Qe6  14.Ra3  Nc6  Black intends to play ...Be7 followed by ...O-O with a slightly favourable position because of weaknesses on White's queenside. }
13... Be6 14. O-O Be7
{ The position is more or less equal. However, I still prefer Black due to the bishop pair which has great potential. White can try to exploit his temporary initiative by chasing our queen. }
15. Bc3 Qg6 16. Ne5 Qe4 17. Qe2 O-O 18. f3 Qh4
{ The chasing game is over. Black's queen is safe on the Kingside and we are ready to push the e5-knight with f7-f6 with a completely fine game. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12. Vienna 5.e3 a6 6.a4"]
[Black "Vienna 5.e3 a6 with 9.dxc5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. e3 a6 6. a4
{ This is the obvious alternative to  6.Bxc4  and the second most popular alternative for White. He prevents b7-b5 and aims to recapture the c4-pawn on the next move.  With a2-a4 White manages to prevent Black's queenside expansion but at the same time weakens the  b4  square permanently, which Black is going to use for his own benefit in the middlegame as well as in the endgame. }
6... c5 { 6...b6  is another fighting alternative for Black. } 7. Bxc4 Nc6
{ Since white has played a4, the knight is perfectly placed on c6, from where it eyes the weak square on b4. }
8. O-O Be7
{ Black focuses on 0-0. We don't want to clarify the situation in the centre yet by playing   8...cxd4  . Even though after  9.exd4  Black gets a comfortable version of the IQP @@StartBracket@@since he has firm control on the weak b4 square@@EndBracket@@, it is better to keep the bishop on c1 limited as far as possible. }
9. dxc5
{ Since the black bishop has already moved, White now decides to capture on c5 and clarify the situation in the centre. }
9... Qxd1
{ I prefer to take the game into an endgame before White gets a chance to avoid it with Qd1-e2. The endgame is quite comfortable for Black because of the control of the weak b4 square. }
10. Rxd1 Bxc5
{ Let us understand the important points of this endgame. White is slightly ahead in development. He just needs to solve the problem of his dark-squared bishop and bring his a1 rook into the game. He has two ways to do that.   The bishop can be developed either on d2 or through a fianchetto on b2  (after b2-b3)  . Another important plan for White is to bring his knight to e4 by playing Nd2-e4 or Ng5-e4. By bringing his knight to e4, he hits the bishop on c5 and intends to penetrate on the d6 square.   Black on the other hand needs to take care of his light-squared bishop on c8 and also connect his rooks, either by playing ...Ke7 or simply O-O. If we decide to play ...Ke7 we need to make sure that the king will be safe on e7 and will not be harassed by the white pieces. Even without the queens on the board, the black king can experience some problems on e7. The safest way is usually to just O-O.   The slight lead in development gives White a very tiny edge but it can easily be liquidated with a few good moves by Black. A huge drawback for him is that the b4 square is weakened and is firmly in Black's control. With a pawn on a3 instead of a4, he would have much better chances in this endgame. But, the weak b4 square always limits his possibilities to create something in this endgame. }
11. Nd2
{ White intends to bring his knight to e4 which is one of his main plans.   11.Ng5  is just an inferior move compared to 11.Nd2, because, from g5 the knight can only go to the e4 square, while from d2 the knight can go to e4 and b3. Black can continue here with,  11...Bb4  12.Bd2  Ke7  Black will play Bc8-d7 next followed by bringing his rooks in the game. }
11... Ke7
{ In this variation Black can safely place his king on e7 which also helps in covering the d6 square. }
12. b3
{ was also tried in one game but Black is able to smoothly carry on with his development. }
12... Rd8 13. Bb2 Bb4 14. Be2 { White frees the c4-square for his knight. }
14... Na5
{ A nice prophylactic move preventing Nc4 and also putting pressure on the b3-pawn. }
15. Ba3 Bxa3 16. Rxa3 Nc6
{ Black makes sure that White does not get to play b3-b4.   16...Bd7  17.Nc4  0-1 @@StartBracket@@58@@EndBracket@@ Candela Perez,J @@StartBracket@@2406@@EndBracket@@-Perez Candelario,M @@StartBracket@@2509@@EndBracket@@ San Sebastian 2006 }
17. Raa1 Bd7 18. Bf3 Rac8 19. Nc4 Rc7
{ Black is ready to play Nc6-b4 next. Again, I like Black's position because of White's weak dark squares on the queenside. }
