{ 12...Nb4  has been Black's favourite move here played by Topalov, Nielsen and Van Wely. But, surprisingly no one from the White side played the most challenging reply,  13.Be4!  N  a slightly counter-intuitive move, allowing the strong light-squared bishop to be exchanged. But it helps White to create problems in Black's piece coordination.  13...Ra7  14.Ne5  here I believe White gets a slight initiative. }
13. Ne4 Be7
{ 13...Nxe4  looks fine too, but strong play can give White a slight edge after,  14.Bxe4  Ke7  N   14...f5  1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@17@@EndBracket@@ Agrest, E @@StartBracket@@2590@@EndBracket@@-Nielsen, P @@StartBracket@@2680@@EndBracket@@ Helsingor 2009  15.Bc3  f6  16.b4!  Bd6  17.Nd2  b5  Black covers c4 but weakens the c5 square.  18.Nb3  because of the weak c5 square and pressure on the queenside White is slightly better. }
