1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. e3 a6 6. a4
{ This is the obvious alternative to  6.Bxc4  and the second most popular alternative for White. He prevents b7-b5 and aims to recapture the c4-pawn on the next move.  With a2-a4 White manages to prevent Black's queenside expansion but at the same time weakens the  b4  square permanently, which Black is going to use for his own benefit in the middlegame as well as in the endgame. }
6... c5 { 6...b6  is another fighting alternative for Black. } 7. Bxc4 Nc6
{ Since white has played a4, the knight is perfectly placed on c6, from where it eyes the weak square on b4. }
8. O-O Be7 9. Ne5
{ was tried by a few strong Grandmasters. But I believe Black gets easy play with simple moves. }
9... cxd4 10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. exd4
{ The aim of 9.Ne5 was to get this structure. But Black has no problems here once we play our next move. }
11... a5
{ this is an important move to remember. By playing ...a5 we prevent White from playing a5 which would lock our light-squared bishop on c8. Now we always have the option of exchanging the light-squared bishops with ...Ba6. }
12. Qf3 Qb6 13. Rd1 O-O
{ and Black is doing completely fine in this position. Our next idea is to play ...Ba6.   We can take a look at a sample game that continued from this position.  14.Ne4  Nxe4  15.Qxe4  Ba6  16.b3  Bxc4  17.bxc4  Qb3  18.Qe2  Rfd8  19.Be3  Bf6=+  and it was Black who was exerting pressure in this position. ½-½  (74)  Tazbir,M  (2517)  -Svane,R  (2542)  Germany 2016 }
