13. h3
{ This is the only way for White not to end up in a lost position.   13.Bxd4?  loses to,  13...Nxd4  14.Bxf7+  trying to create a mess.   14.Rxd4  Qxd4!  wins a clear exchange for Black.  14...Kxf7  15.Qc4+  Ke8  16.Rxd4  Qc8-+  and White had no compensation whatsoever for the sacrificed piece. 0-1 @@StartBracket@@26@@EndBracket@@ Sulashvili, M @@StartBracket@@2455@@EndBracket@@ -Kulaots, K @@StartBracket@@2525@@EndBracket@@ Tallinn 2007. }
13... Bxf3 14. Qxf3 O-O
{ Black can calmly O-O as there is no way for White to regain the d4-pawn.   Black would love to play,  14...Qb6?  but White escapes with,  15.Nd5!  Nxd5  16.Qxd5  O-O  17.Bxd4= }
15. Bg5
{ 15.Bf4  Bd6  16.Ne2  Qc7  17.Rac1  Bxf4  18.Qxf4  Qxf4  19.Nxf4  Rfd8  and Black was a comfortable pawn up in 0-1 @@StartBracket@@66@@EndBracket@@ Akesson, R @@StartBracket@@2446@@EndBracket@@-Jonkman,H @@StartBracket@@2396@@EndBracket@@ Helmond 2014   Now the strongest move for Black is to play, }
15... Nd7
{ A strong move, breaking the pin on the d4-pawn and also forcing the exchange of the dark-squared bishops.   15...Rc8  1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@28@@EndBracket@@ Farago,I @@StartBracket@@2485@@EndBracket@@-Rogozenco,D @@StartBracket@@2537@@EndBracket@@ Hamburg 2001 @@EndBracket@@ }
16. Bxe7 Qxe7 17. Nd5 Qd6 { And Black is a clear pawn up. } *

