[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13. Vienna 5.e3 a6 6.Bxc4 b5 7.Bd3 & 7.Be2"]
[Black "Vienna 5.e3 a6 with 7.Be2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. e3 a6 6. Bxc4 b5 7. Be2
{ This is the simplest to meet among all the 3 bishop retreats. From the looks of it, White is not fighting for an opening advantage but rather just wants to focus on developing his pieces and get an equal game. }
7... Bb7 8. O-O Nbd7
{ Here we don't need to hurry with c7-c5 as White cannot, anyways, play e3-e4. }
9. b3
{ White develops his bishop on b2 and solves the problem of his dark-squared bishop.   9.a3  is another way to fianchetto the c1-bishop. But, expanding on the queenside with a3-b4 can lead to a serious weakening of the c4 square.  9...c5  10.dxc5  Bxc5  11.b4  Be7  Now if we observe the position carefully, it is obvious that the black knight on d7 is better placed than the white knight on c3. Because the knight on d7 can quickly reach the weak c4 square via b6 @@StartBracket@@or e5 if possible@@EndBracket@@, while the knight on c3 will find it really tough to exploit the c5 square in Black's camp. Now we will follow a game between Bachmann vs. Mamedyarov, where Black shows an ideal way to play with the black pieces.  12  Bb2  Rc8  13.Qb3  Qb6  14.Rab1  O-O  15.a4  this is a way for White to exchange all the pawns on the queenside to simplify the position towards a draw.  15...Bxf3!  a typical exchange in this position. Black eliminates the knight on f3 and makes way for his knight to the c4 square via e5.  16.Bxf3  Ne5  17.Be2  Nc4  This knight is very annoying for White if it manages to reach the c4 square. Now Mamedyarov slowly develops an attack on the kingside.  18.Rbd1  Bd6!  Transferring the bishop to a better diagonal.  19.Ba1  Bb8  20.axb5  axb5  21.g3  White blocks the black bishop's diagonal, but Black now finds fresh targets to attack.  21...Ba7  22.Rd3  Qb7  23.Nb1  e5!  limiting the bishop on  a1  .  24.Rfd1  h5!  time to launch the h-pawn.  25.Rc3  h4  26.Bf1  Qf3!  The queen will soon create threats against the white king.  27.Nd2  Nxd2  28.Rxd2  Ne4  29.Rxc8  Rxc8  30.Rc2  Rxc2  31.Qxc2  Nxf2!  32.Qe2  Nh3+!  A nice attacking game by Mamedyarov! 0-1 @@StartBracket@@33@@EndBracket@@ Bachmann, A @@StartBracket@@2593@@EndBracket@@-Mamedyarov,S @@StartBracket@@2736@@EndBracket@@ Berlin 2015 }
9... c5 10. Bb2 Be7
{ Placing the bishop actively with,  10...Bd6?!  is slightly inaccurate here due to,  11.dxc5!  now our desirable recapture with,  11...Nxc5  is strongly met by,  12.b4!  This is the drawback of having the bishop on d6. Now, the black knight cannot retreat back on d7 as the bishop will be lost.  12...Nce4  13.Nxe4  Nxe4  14.Qd4!  and with Black still yet to complete his development, White can hope to put some pressure. }
11. Rc1 O-O
{ Black has smoothly completed his development and is now ready to bring his major pieces into the game. }
12. Qc2 Rc8 13. Qb1 Qb6 14. Rfd1 Rfd8
{ Black is well developed and has slightly more space on the queenside than White, which gives us a pleasant position. 0-1 @@StartBracket@@59@@EndBracket@@ Mamedyarov,S @@StartBracket@@2817@@EndBracket@@-Carlsen,M @@StartBracket@@2835@@EndBracket@@ St Petersburg 2018 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13. Vienna 5.e3 a6 6.Bxc4 b5 7.Bd3 & 7.Be2"]
[Black "Vienna 5.e3 a6 with 7.Bd3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. e3 a6 6. Bxc4 b5 7. Bd3
{ The bishop looks well placed on d3 but it is nothing special. It will be anyways difficult for White to get the dream pawn advance with e3-e4-e5. It is also important to note that once White plays e3-e4 the bishop on d3 will be closed. This is the reason why I prefer the white bishop on b3 rather than on d3. }
7... c5
{ Black should hit the centre immediately, not giving White any chance to go for e3-e4.   7...Bb7  should transpose to our mainline after 8.0-0. But it also gives an additional option of,  8.e4  even though after,  8...c5  the position is playable for both sides.   8...b4  is met by,  9.e5  bxc3  10.exf6  cxb2  11.fxg7  Bxg7  12.Bxb2  and White is slightly better due to a better pawn structure. }
8. O-O Bb7 9. Qe2
{ White prepares to play Rd1 and also supports a future e4 advance. } 9... Nbd7
{ Black has placed both his queenside knight and bishop on ideal squares. } 10.
e4 cxd4 11. Nxd4 Bd6
{ followed by ...0-0, when Black has developed all his pieces to good squares and has a fine position. }
*

