{ The bishop looks well placed on d3 but it is nothing special. It will be anyways difficult for White to get the dream pawn advance with e3-e4-e5. It is also important to note that once White plays e3-e4 the bishop on d3 will be closed. This is the reason why I prefer the white bishop on b3 rather than on d3. }
7... c5
{ Black should hit the centre immediately, not giving White any chance to go for e3-e4.   7...Bb7  should transpose to our mainline after 8.0-0. But it also gives an additional option of,  8.e4  even though after,  8...c5  the position is playable for both sides.   8...b4  is met by,  9.e5  bxc3  10.exf6  cxb2  11.fxg7  Bxg7  12.Bxb2  and White is slightly better due to a better pawn structure. }
8. O-O Bb7 9. Qe2
{ White prepares to play Rd1 and also supports a future e4 advance. } 9... Nbd7
{ Black has placed both his queenside knight and bishop on ideal squares. } 10.
Rd1 Qb8
{ this is a very typical reaction to Rd1. Black removes his queen from the d-file and hides it on b8. The queen might look passive on b8 but it can add pressure on the h2-b8 diagonal and always keeps an eye on the e5 square which prevents White from advancing his e-pawn all the way to e5. }
11. b3
{ is a simple way of playing here for White. This was tried by a few players but it does not pose Black any serious challenge as he can smoothly complete his development. }
11... Bd6
{ developing the bishop actively. The h2-pawn is always under the radar. } 12.
h3 O-O
{ Black has successfully completed his development and now it is time to play in the centre. }
13. Bb2 cxd4 { this timely pawn exchange allows Black to gain more activity. }
14. Nxd4 Nc5 15. Bc2 b4
{ White has to choose between two bad options:   1. Retreat the knight to the passive b1 square or   2. Play Nc3-a4 but accept a bad pawn structure. }
16. Na4 Nxa4 17. bxa4 Rc8
{ and due to the better pawn structure and actively placed pieces, Black is slightly better. 0-1 @@StartBracket@@25@@EndBracket@@ Sadilek,P @@StartBracket@@2277@@EndBracket@@ -Stevic,H @@StartBracket@@2611@@EndBracket@@ Austria 2014 }
