Bb7
{ A direct  7...c5  gives White an additional option of  8.e4  which was tried by Grischuk against Kramnik in the FIDE Candidates tournament, Berlin 2018.   8.O-O  Bb7  transposes to our mainline. }
8. O-O c5 9. Qe2
{ This is the most popular move for White in this position. He develops his queen to a logical square, prepares for e3-e4 and frees the d1 square for his rook. }
9... Nbd7
{ The knight should be developed on d7 where it does not hinder the bishop on b7. }
10. Rd1 Qb8
{ It is very important to remember that the b8 square is usually the best square for the black queen in this structure. The queen is very safe on the b8 square away from White's pieces and it also controls the e5 square which discourages White from getting in his dream pawn advance of e3-e4-e5. }
11. e4
{ is simply met by the usual response that you are quite familiar by now, }
11... cxd4 12. Nxd4 Bd6
{ developing the bishop with a tempo. This another advantage of having the queen on b8. }
13. g3
{ Just to mention in passing that the rash piece sacrifice,  13.Bxe6?  falls short due to,  13...fxe6  14.Nxe6  Kf7!  we use our king to defend the g7-pawn. Another idea behind this move is to transfer the king to the kingside where it will feel much safer than in the centre.  15.Ng5+  Kg8  White lacks compensation for the piece. Now, if he tries to include his queen in the attack with,  16.Qc2  then after,  16...Bxh2+  17.Kh1  Nb6!-+  Black is ready to interpose his knight in-between on c4. }
13... O-O
{ Black is ready to bring his rook into the game next with a completely fine position. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@31@@EndBracket@@ Svidler,P @@StartBracket@@2756@@EndBracket@@-Shankland,S @@StartBracket@@2722@@EndBracket@@ Hoogeveen 2018 }
