12. Bxd4 Be7
{ 12...Nxe4?  is again not recommendable as after,  13.Nxe4  Bxe4  14.Re1+-  White gains a powerful initiative. }
13. f3 O-O 14. Be3
{ There are many ways for Black to play here as the position is already comfortable and harmless. I would like to add a game of Vienna expert Jan Gustafsson where he created chances from this equal position and converted into a win!   14.Qd2  just leads to an equal endgame after,  14...e5!  Black forces the exchange of queens which helps us activate our own dark-squared bishop.  15.Be3  Qxd2  16.Bxd2  Bc5+  17.Kh1  h6=  covering the g5 square, thus limiting White's dark-squared bishop. This endgame is equal. ½-½ @@StartBracket@@49@@EndBracket@@ Pérez López,A @@StartBracket@@2265@@EndBracket@@ -Fister,B @@StartBracket@@2226@@EndBracket@@ ICCF 2016 }
