[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "14. Vienna 5.e3 a6 6.Bxc4 b5 7.Bb3"]
[Black "Vienna 5.e3 a6 with 9.e4 and 11.Nxc6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. e3 a6 6. Bxc4 b5 7. Bb3
{ This is more challenging than the other two retreats 7.Bd3 and 7.Be2. } 7...
Bb7
{ A direct  7...c5  gives White an additional option of  8.e4  which was tried by Grischuk against Kramnik in the FIDE Candidates tournament, Berlin 2018.   8.O-O  Bb7  transposes to our mainline. }
8. O-O c5 9. e4
{ This is an interesting try that has gained some momentum recently. White offers a pawn in order to open up the lines in the centre. If Black does not accept the pawn sacrifice then White achieves his main aim that is to play e3-e4, increase control in the centre and play against the bishop on b7. }
9... cxd4
{ eliminating the d4-pawn before it decides to march forward and gain space in the centre with d4-d5.   9...Nxe4?  grabbing a pawn like this without completing development is poisonous!  10.Nxe4  Bxe4  11.Re1  White got a very strong initiative in the game, 1-0 @@StartBracket@@23@@EndBracket@@ Adhiban,B @@StartBracket@@2701@@EndBracket@@ -Albornoz Cabrera,C @@StartBracket@@2566@@EndBracket@@ Havana CUB 2019 }
10. Nxd4
{ 10.Qxd4?!  Qxd4  11.Nxd4  Nc6=  is just an inferior version on the mainline. }
10... Nc6
{ I prefer this direct approach over 10...Nbd7. Black develops his knight as well as immediately challenges the strong central knight on d4. }
11. Nxc6 Qxd1
{ It is important to immediately exchange the queens before White avoids it on the next move.   11...Bxc6  allows White to avoid the exchange of queens with  12.Qe2  White has more space in this position so keeping more pieces on the board favours him. The white rook will also join the game on d1 gaining tempo on the black queen on d8. This position is of course playable for Black, but I prefer to play this structure without the queens on the board. }
12. Rxd1 Bxc6 13. f3
{ White sets up a wall against Black's light-squared bishop, making it difficult for us to create play for this bishop. Moreover, White is ready to develop his dark-squared bishop and bring his rook into the game with Rac1 while Black will need more time to bring all his pieces in the game as his king is still in the centre. But the absence of the queens on the board makes it easy for Black to handle these problems.   13.Bg5?  was tried in a game but it just loses a pawn after  13...Nxe4  14.Nxe4  Bxe4  15.a4  Be7!  and Black was a clear pawn up in 0-1 @@StartBracket@@56@@EndBracket@@ Repka,C @@StartBracket@@2513@@EndBracket@@-Sarana,A @@StartBracket@@2577@@EndBracket@@ Moscow 2018 @@EndBracket@@ }
13... Bc5+
{ Not only activating the bishop with a check but also preventing White from playing Bc1-e3, which is an ideal square for White's dark-squared bishop. }
14. Kf1 { It makes sense to keep the king closer to the centre. } 14... Ke7
{ Black too does the same. Now our rooks are connected and ready to participate on the open files. Black would like to first bring his kingside rook to d8 or c8. }
15. Ne2
{ Not a very challenging move but it carries a threat. White threatens to play Bc1-g5 followed by either e4-e5 or Ra1-c1 winning a piece in both cases. With 15. Ne2 White has opened the c-file, so, whenever his rook comes to c1 it will attack Black's bishops on the c-file. Hence, it makes sense to put our rook on c8 as well. }
15... Rhc8
{ It is important to bring the h8 rook on the c-file so that in case Black is needed to play Ke7-e8 or f8, the rook on h8 won't be locked in.   15...Rhd8?  is a logical move but a mistake because it does not solve our problem on the c-file. White continues with his intended move,  16.Bg5!  Rxd1+   16...h6  is strongly met by,  17.Rdc1!  hxg5  18.Rxc5  and Black loses his g5-pawn.  17.Rxd1  Bd6  and now White executed a spectacular combination  18.Rxd6!!  Kxd6  19.e5+  Kxe5  20.Bf4+  Kf5  21.Bc2+  Ne4  22.fxe4++  and White's two pieces are much stronger than the rook. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@45@@EndBracket@@ Artemiev,V @@StartBracket@@2736@@EndBracket@@ -Izoria,Z  @@StartBracket@@2603@@EndBracket@@ Astana 2019 }
16. Bg5
{ 16.Nd4  Can be met by retreating the bishop with  16...Be8  it is good to retreat the bishop to e8 rather than to d7 so that the d7-square is kept free for the f6-knight in case White plays e5.  17.e5?!  This advance looks good gaining space in the centre, but it could also prove to be risky as White is ignoring his queenside development.  17...Nd7  18.f4  a5!  =+  and Black starts his action on the queenside with a slight initiative as White is still behind in development. }
16... h6 17. Rac1 Bb7
{ this is the benefit of having the rook on c8. Now the c5 bishop can be protected. }
18. Bd2 Nd7 { transferring the knight to a better position. } 19. a4 bxa4
{ is the simplest way to continue here for Black.   19...b4  1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@29@@EndBracket@@ Fremmegaard,J @@StartBracket@@2151@@EndBracket@@ -Clark,R @@StartBracket@@2125@@EndBracket@@ ICCF 2017 }
20. Bxa4 Nb6 21. Bb3 a5 { and Black is completely fine here. } *

