{ eliminating the d4-pawn before it decides to march forward and gain space in the centre with d4-d5.   9...Nxe4?  grabbing a pawn like this without completing development is poisonous!  10.Nxe4  Bxe4  11.Re1  White got a very strong initiative in the game, 1-0 @@StartBracket@@23@@EndBracket@@ Adhiban,B @@StartBracket@@2701@@EndBracket@@ -Albornoz Cabrera,C @@StartBracket@@2566@@EndBracket@@ Havana CUB 2019 }
10. Nxd4
{ 10.Qxd4?!  Qxd4  11.Nxd4  Nc6=  is just an inferior version on the mainline. }
10... Nc6
{ I prefer this direct approach over 10...Nbd7. Black develops his knight as well as immediately challenges the strong central knight on d4. }
11. Nxc6 Qxd1
{ It is important to immediately exchange the queens before White avoids it on the next move.   11...Bxc6  allows White to avoid the exchange of queens with  12.Qe2  White has more space in this position so keeping more pieces on the board favours him. The white rook will also join the game on d1 gaining tempo on the black queen on d8. This position is of course playable for Black, but I prefer to play this structure without the queens on the board. }
12. Rxd1 Bxc6 13. f3
{ White sets up a wall against Black's light-squared bishop, making it difficult for us to create play for this bishop. Moreover, White is ready to develop his dark-squared bishop and bring his rook into the game with Rac1 while Black will need more time to bring all his pieces in the game as his king is still in the centre. But the absence of the queens on the board makes it easy for Black to handle these problems.   13.Bg5?  was tried in a game but it just loses a pawn after  13...Nxe4  14.Nxe4  Bxe4  15.a4  Be7!  and Black was a clear pawn up in 0-1 @@StartBracket@@56@@EndBracket@@ Repka,C @@StartBracket@@2513@@EndBracket@@-Sarana,A @@StartBracket@@2577@@EndBracket@@ Moscow 2018 @@EndBracket@@ }
13... Bc5+
{ Not only activating the bishop with a check but also preventing White from playing Bc1-e3, which is an ideal square for White's dark-squared bishop. }
14. Kf1 { It makes sense to keep the king closer to the centre. } 14... Ke7
{ Black too does the same. Now our rooks are connected and ready to participate on the open files. Black would like to first bring his kingside rook to d8 or c8. }
15. e5
{ This is the most critical test for Black in this position. The knight on f6 is kicked away from its active position and White prepares to develop the bishop with a check by Bc1-g5+.   15.Bg5  This direct developing move does not carry any challenge.  15...h6  This is Black's usual response whenever White's bishop comes on g5. We want to kick it back as soon as possible.  16.Bh4  g5  17.Bf2  Bxf2  18.Kxf2  Rhc8  19.Rac1  Nd7=  Black is fine in this position without any problems. ½-½ @@StartBracket@@44@@EndBracket@@ Ponomariov,R @@StartBracket@@2739@@EndBracket@@-Anand,V @@StartBracket@@2788@@EndBracket@@ Moscow 2009 }
15... Nd7 16. Bg5+ Ke8
{ A counter-intuitive move, but a strong novelty! Just two moves back we connected our rooks and were ready to bring them into play. But now we are voluntarily shutting them down. This might seems worrisome for us but in fact, it is not. First of all, 16...f6 was not an option for us and secondly, by playing 15.e5 White has gained space but also exposed the e5-pawn to an attack by the black pieces. The e5-pawn is now threatened and Black is ready to push back White's active dark-squared bishop from the h4-d8 diagonal with h7-h6 and g7-g5. Once the bishop moves away we can again play our king back to e7. In the meantime, White should figure out a way and waste time defending his e5-pawn.   16...f6?  was a huge mistake. After,  17.exf6+  gxf6  18.Re1  the lines against the black king were opened, White snatched the initiative and converted it into a full point. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@28@@EndBracket@@ Korobov,A @@StartBracket@@2675@@EndBracket@@ -Lesiege,A @@StartBracket@@2512@@EndBracket@@ Baku 2016 }
17. f4 { Is a very natural way to support the e5-pawn, but it is a mistake! }
17... Be3
{ A very strong move. Black puts pressure on the f4-pawn and threatens to play h7-h6 next kicking the bishop from g5 and winning the pawn on f4. The c1 square is covered at the same time preventing Ra1-c1. }
18. Rd6
{ 18.Ke2?  is also met by,  18...h6!  19.Kxe3  hxg5-+  and we can see that all White's three pawns - h2, g2 and e5 are in trouble. }
18... Rc8 19. Re1 Bc5 20. Rdd1 b4
{ pushing the knight on c3 back and also intending Bc6-b5. } 21. Ne2 h6 22. Bh4
g5 { breaking on the kingside using the exposed pawn on e5. } 23. Bg3 Bb5
{ White's pieces are clumsily placed while Black's bishop puts pressure on their diagonals. One look gives a feeling that Black has the initiative in this position. }
