{ Black too does the same. Now our rooks are connected and ready to participate on the open files. Black would like to first bring his kingside rook to d8 or c8. }
15. e5
{ This is the most critical test for Black in this position. The knight on f6 is kicked away from its active position and White prepares to develop the bishop with a check by Bc1-g5+.   15.Bg5  This direct developing move does not carry any challenge.  15...h6  This is Black's usual response whenever White's bishop comes on g5. We want to kick it back as soon as possible.  16.Bh4  g5  17.Bf2  Bxf2  18.Kxf2  Rhc8  19.Rac1  Nd7=  Black is fine in this position without any problems. ½-½ @@StartBracket@@44@@EndBracket@@ Ponomariov,R @@StartBracket@@2739@@EndBracket@@-Anand,V @@StartBracket@@2788@@EndBracket@@ Moscow 2009 }
15... Nd7 16. Bg5+ Ke8
{ A counter-intuitive move, but a strong novelty! Just two moves back we connected our rooks and were ready to bring them into play. But now we are voluntarily shutting them down. This might seems worrisome for us but in fact, it is not. First of all, 16...f6 was not an option for us and secondly, by playing 15.e5 White has gained space but also exposed the e5-pawn to an attack by the black pieces. The e5-pawn is now threatened and Black is ready to push back White's active dark-squared bishop from the h4-d8 diagonal with h7-h6 and g7-g5. Once the bishop moves away we can again play our king back to e7. In the meantime, White should figure out a way and waste time defending his e5-pawn.   16...f6?  was a huge mistake. After,  17.exf6+  gxf6  18.Re1  the lines against the black king were opened, White snatched the initiative and converted it into a full point. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@28@@EndBracket@@ Korobov,A @@StartBracket@@2675@@EndBracket@@ -Lesiege,A @@StartBracket@@2512@@EndBracket@@ Baku 2016 }
17. Rac1 { White brings his rook into action at the cost of the e5-pawn. }
17... h6
{ We focus on our own plan of pushing the bishop back from g5.   We should not be tempted by  17...Nxe5?  grabbing this pawn loses valuable time which White can use to gain the initiative by,  18.Ne4  Be7   18...Bxe4  19.Rxc5+-  just loses as both Black pieces are attacked.  19.Nd6+  Kf8  20.Bf4  Black is far behind in development and his pieces are shaky and prone to attack by the white pieces. }
18. Bh4 g5
{ shutting the bishop off from the h4-d8 diagonal. Black would like to play Ke8-e7 next, connecting the rooks once again. }
19. Be1 { This is White's last try and final hurdle to cross for Black. } 19...
Rc8
{ It is essential to bring the rook to the c-file first, preventing any tactical ideas. Now Black is all set to play Ke8-e7.   The most logical move,  19...Ke7?  falls short due to concrete tactics on the a3-f8 diagonal.  20.Ne2!+-  opening the c-file for the rook and threatening Rxc5 followed by Be1-b4.  20...Rac8  21.Rxc5  Nxc5  22.Bb4+-  and White wins material. }
20. Ne2 { still hoping for Black to fall in the same trick. } 20... Bb7
{ Another important move. Supporting the c5 bishop before playing Ke8-e7.   20...Ke7?  is a mistake again due to the same,  21.Rxc5+- }
21. Rc2 Ke7 22. Rdc1 { and now after the simple, } 22... Rhd8
{ Black has finally managed to bring all his pieces into the game and is doing fine in this position.  23.Rxc5?  Does not work here for White due to,  23...Rxc5!  freeing the c8-square for the other rook in order to support on c5.  24.Bb4  Rdc8  with Ke7-e8 coming next, Black is the one with a clearly better position. }
