[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "14. Vienna 5.e3 a6 6.Bxc4 b5 7.Bb3"]
[Black "Vienna 5.e3 a6 with 9.e4 and 11.Nxc6 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. e3 a6 6. Bxc4 b5 7. Bb3
{ This is more challenging than the other two retreats 7.Bd3 and 7.Be2. } 7...
Bb7
{ A direct  7...c5  gives White an additional option of  8.e4  which was tried by Grischuk against Kramnik in the FIDE Candidates tournament, Berlin 2018.   8.O-O  Bb7  transposes to our mainline. }
8. O-O c5 9. e4
{ This is an interesting try that has gained some momentum recently. White offers a pawn in order to open up the lines in the centre. If Black does not accept the pawn sacrifice then White achieves his main aim that is to play e3-e4, increase control in the centre and play against the bishop on b7. }
9... cxd4
{ eliminating the d4-pawn before it decides to march forward and gain space in the centre with d4-d5.   9...Nxe4?  grabbing a pawn like this without completing development is poisonous!  10.Nxe4  Bxe4  11.Re1  White got a very strong initiative in the game, 1-0 @@StartBracket@@23@@EndBracket@@ Adhiban,B @@StartBracket@@2701@@EndBracket@@ -Albornoz Cabrera,C @@StartBracket@@2566@@EndBracket@@ Havana CUB 2019 }
10. Nxd4
{ 10.Qxd4?!  Qxd4  11.Nxd4  Nc6=  is just an inferior version on the mainline. }
10... Nc6
{ I prefer this direct approach over 10...Nbd7. Black develops his knight as well as immediately challenges the strong central knight on d4. }
11. Nxc6 Qxd1
{ It is important to immediately exchange the queens before White avoids it on the next move.   11...Bxc6  allows White to avoid the exchange of queens with  12.Qe2  White has more space in this position so keeping more pieces on the board favours him. The white rook will also join the game on d1 gaining tempo on the black queen on d8. This position is of course playable for Black, but I prefer to play this structure without the queens on the board. }
12. Rxd1 Bxc6 13. e5 { is not so good for White. Black replies with, } 13...
Ng4 14. Re1 Bc5 15. Re2
{ The active rook on d1 has become passive on e2 defending both the white pawns on e5 and f2. This indicates that 13.e5?! is not a way for White to play. }
15... Bd4 16. Bf4 g5
{ going after the pawn on e5 also opening up the g-file at the same time. } 17.
Bxg5 Rg8 18. Bh4
{ 18.Bf4??  loses to  18...Nxf2!-+  the g2-pawn is under attack and the discovered check on the next move is very deadly for White. }
18... Nxe5 19. Bg3 Nc4
{ Objectively the position is equal, but Black's pieces are active. ½-½  (35)  Hinz,H  (2178)  -Neumann,B  (2167)  GER email 2003 }
