[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "15. Vienna 5.e4 Bb4 6.Bxc4"]
[Black "Vienna 5.e4 Bb4 6.Qc2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. e4 Bb4 6. Qc2
{ This is a rare way of dealing with the threat of ...Nxe4. I have never faced this move in my entire career. But still, it is better to know how to face 6.Qc2.   6.Qa4+  This has been tried in a few games without much success.  6...Nc6  7.Bg5  White threatens to play e5 next.  7...Bd7  We break the pin and threaten ...Nxd4.  8.Qc2   8.e5??  is not possible due to  8...Nxd4  9.Qd1  Nxf3+  10.gxf3  h6-+  When Black is simply winning.  8...h6  9.Bd2  Now White is ready to recover his pawn with Bxc4. But we won't let it happen so easily.  9...b5!  An important move making it tough for White to recover his pawn.  10.Nxb5  Bxd2+  11.Nxd2   11.Qxd2  Nxe4  12.Qf4  Nd6=+  gives Black a slight advantage. ½-½ @@StartBracket@@96@@EndBracket@@ Liascovich,L @@StartBracket@@2473@@EndBracket@@-Sosa,T @@StartBracket@@2465@@EndBracket@@ Buenos Aires 2017  11...a6  pushing White's knight back so that we can capture the d4-pawn.  12.Na3  Nxd4  13.Qxc4  Bb5  Our bishop is well placed on  b5  . If White decides to exchange it then it opens up the a-file for our rook.  14.Qc5  Qd6  15.Rc1   15.Qxd6  cxd6=+  with the idea to play ...Ke7 followed by ...Rhc8 when Black is pressing.  15...O-O  16.f3  Rfd8  17.Qxd6  cxd6=+  it is clear that Black has a nice initiative in this endgame as White's pieces, especially his h1-rook, are yet to join the game. }
6... b5 { We start by supporting the c4-pawn. } 7. a4 c6 8. Be2
{ White develops his bishop and prepares to 0-0. After 8.Be2 we transpose to a position that arises from one of the sidelines in the Slav Defence. }
8... Bb7 9. O-O
{ The most popular move in this position. White now intends to capture on b5.   9.Bg5  This was the choice of GM Aronian.  9...Qb6  getting away from the pin, taking care of the b5-pawn and preparing to develop with ...Nbd7.   9...h6  1-0 @@StartBracket@@37@@EndBracket@@ Aronian,L @@StartBracket@@2805@@EndBracket@@ -Duda,J @@StartBracket@@2717@@EndBracket@@ Riadh 2017  10.Bxf6  gxf6  11.O-O  Nd7  12.Rfd1  a6=+  giving added protection to the b5-pawn. Black is ready to 0-0 next with a slightly better position. ½-½ @@StartBracket@@45@@EndBracket@@ Zubov,O @@StartBracket@@2328@@EndBracket@@-Ivanov,A @@StartBracket@@2321@@EndBracket@@ Dnipropetrovsk 2000 }
9... a6 { We simply support our b5-pawn. } 10. Bg5
{ This is the standard way of playing for White. He threatens to play e5 next. }
10... h6 11. Bh4 Be7
{ I prefer this simple but less played way of playing against White's threat of e5.   11...Nbd7  is the most popular way of playing here for Black. This position is quite similar to the Botvinnik Variation of the Slav Defence, though this is a better version for Black. }
12. e5 { White goes for the exchange of the dark-squared bishops. } 12... Nd5
13. Bxe7 Qxe7
{ White has managed to exchange the dark-squared bishops which can be considered an achievement for him as, after these exchanges, White can infiltrate the weak dark squares with this knight. But as we will see it is not a big problem for Black. }
14. Ne4 O-O 15. Nd6
{ The knight seems to dominate on the d6-square but there is nothing to fear as we can play around the d6-knight comfortably. }
15... Qc7
{ We shift our queen to c7 so that our b7-bishop will remain protected when we play ...Nd7 next.   15...Rd8?!  with the idea to sacrifice the exchange is a decent idea but here it is not a good one. White can continue with  16.Nd2  and now after  16...Rxd6  17.exd6  Qxd6  18.b3!  White can create strong pressure on the queenside. For example,  18...cxb3  19.Nxb3  Nd7  20.Na5+=  With a slightly better position for White. }
16. Qd2
{ This was the choice of White in two correspondence games that reached this position. With 16.Qd2 White covers the e3 square and prepares to play Nh4 followed by f4 without worrying about ideas like ...Ne3. }
16... Rd8
{ This is the correct moment to sacrifice the exchange on d6 as White does not have the option of Nd2 anymore. }
17. Rfd1 Rxd6 18. exd6 Qxd6
{ Followed by ...Nd7 next with a clearly better position for Black. We have two healthy pawns for the exchange. ½-½ @@StartBracket@@44@@EndBracket@@ Feco,J @@StartBracket@@2461@@EndBracket@@-Oreopoulos,K @@StartBracket@@2475@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2014 }
