1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. e4 Bb4 6. e5
{ This seems like the easiest way to prevent the threat of ...Nxe4 but it surrenders the d5-square forever. }
6... Nd5
{ We immediately hop on to the d5-square attacking the c3-knight at the same time.   6...Ne4?!  performs the same job as 6...Nd5, but the knight is unstable on e4. For example, White can simply play,  7.Qc2  defending the c3-knight as well as attacking our knight on e4.  7...Qd5  8.Be2→  followed by 0-0 White gets a nice initiative for the pawn. }
7. Bd2 Nb6
{ We retreat our knight, supporting the c4-pawn.   7...Bxc3  8.bxc3  b5  is another playable alternative for Black, but I would prefer not to give up our dark-squared bishop. }
8. Be2
{ Was recently chosen by GM Salem Saleh against GM Shakhriyar Mamedyarov. }
8... Nc6 { Developing the knight as well as hitting the d4-pawn. } 9. a3
{ 9.Bg5  should be met by  9...Ne7   9...Qd5  1-0 @@StartBracket@@69@@EndBracket@@ Ikonnikov, V @@StartBracket@@2570@@EndBracket@@-Wippermann, T @@StartBracket@@2455@@EndBracket@@ Germany 2009  10.Bxc4  White uses the opportunity to recover the c4-pawn immediately. But we are more than happy to give the extra pawn back in exchange for White's light-squared bishop.   10.O-O  h6  pushing White's bishop to h4 before continuing with our development.  11.Bh4  Bd7=+  with the idea to play ...Bc6, when our bishop will be very well placed on the c6-square. Later we can also think about ...g5 gaining space on the kingside.  10...Bxc3+  11.bxc3  Nxc4  12.Qa4+  Qd7  13.Qxc4  O-O  =+  The position looks equal at first sight but after ...b6 followed by ...Bb7 our bishop will be very strong on the h1-a8 diagonal. This gives Black a slight edge in this position. }
9... Be7 10. Be3 Bd7
{ We should focus on developing our queenside first, especially bring the bishop to the h1-a8 diagonal. We can think of castling once we complete our queenside development.   10...O-O  seems natural but it allows White to start an attack on the kingside with,  11.h4↑  0-1 @@StartBracket@@32@@EndBracket@@ Salem,A @@StartBracket@@2682@@EndBracket@@-Mamedyarov,S @@StartBracket@@2764@@EndBracket@@ ICC INT 2020 }
11. Qc2 { White still waits for us to 0-0, but we are not going to do that. }
11... Na5 12. O-O Bc6
{ Black is slightly better as White lacks a clear compensation for the pawn. Our next move is going to be ...Qd7 and then 0-0-0. Our king will be quite safe on the queenside. }
