{ This seems like the easiest way to prevent the threat of ...Nxe4 but it surrenders the d5-square forever. }
6... Nd5
{ We immediately hop on to the d5-square attacking the c3-knight at the same time.   6...Ne4?!  performs the same job as 6...Nd5, but the knight is unstable on e4. For example, White can simply play,  7.Qc2  defending the c3-knight as well as attacking our knight on e4.  7...Qd5  8.Be2→  followed by 0-0 White gets a nice initiative for the pawn. }
7. Bd2 Nb6
{ We retreat our knight, supporting the c4-pawn.   7...Bxc3  8.bxc3  b5  is another playable alternative for Black, but I would prefer not to give up our dark-squared bishop. }
8. a3
{ 8.Ne4  With hope to exchange the dark-squared bishops. But Black has a strong intermediate move.  8...Qd5!  9.Bxb4  Qxe4+  10.Be2  Nc6  N developing our knight with a tempo.   10...Nd5  1-0 @@StartBracket@@46@@EndBracket@@ Nueesch, G @@StartBracket@@2207@@EndBracket@@-Peredy, F @@StartBracket@@2374@@EndBracket@@ Basel 2000  11.Ba3  It is logical for White to maintain his bishop on the a3-f8 diagonal.  11...g5!  A strong surprising resource exploiting the unsupported g2-pawn. Black now threatens to play ...g4.  12.h3  this prevents ...g4 but weakens the kingside.   12.O-O  is safest, but it is simply met by  12...g4∓  winning the d4-pawn. Black clearly stands better.  12...Nd5!  The knight joins the kingside action with the idea to play ...Nf4.  13.g3  White covers the f4-square but again further weakens the kingside.  13...Rg8  and Black dominates the kingside. If White tries to castle short with  14.O-O  then after  14...Nf4!!  a strong knight sacrifice shattering White's kingside.  15.gxf4  g4  16.hxg4  Rxg4+  17.Kh2  Qg6-+  threatening a check on the h-file. Black has a crushing attack! }
8... Be7 9. Bxc4
{ this is usually the idea behind pushing our bishop back from b4 with 8.a3. But we are not afraid to give back the extra pawn because we get White's strong light-squared bishop in return.   9.Ne4  Centralizes the knight but loses control of the a4-square which we can exploit with  9...Bd7  10.Be2  Ba4  N  disturbing the queen from the d1-square before putting pressure on the d4-pawn with ...Nc6.   10...Bc6  0-1 @@StartBracket@@50@@EndBracket@@ Abdulla,A  @@StartBracket@@2386@@EndBracket@@-Dydyshko,V @@StartBracket@@2525@@EndBracket@@ Istanbul 2000  11.Qc1  Nc6  12.Be3  Na5∓  and Black is clearly better due to our domination on the queenside on top of the extra pawn.   9.Na4  White goes for the c4-pawn without giving up his light-squared bishop.  9...Nc6  10.Bc3?  this gives Black a very big advantage.   10.Nxb6  N was a better try for White.  10...axb6  11.Bxc4  Nxd4  We have won the pawn again but White can hope for some compensation due to his active pieces and more space on the kingside.  12.Bc3  Nf5  13.Qe2  Bd7  Developing the queenside before castling.  14.O-O-O  h5=+  stabilizing the knight on  f5  . White has some compensation but I believe it is not sufficient for equality. Black is slightly better.  10...Qd5  The queen is strongly placed on d5 covering the c4-pawn at the same time.  11.Nxb6  axb6  12.Be2  Na5  N Black can start dominating the queenside.   12...O-O  1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@18@@EndBracket@@ Grooten, H @@StartBracket@@2390@@EndBracket@@-Mikhalchishin, A @@StartBracket@@2510@@EndBracket@@ Sas van Gent 1990  13.O-O  Nb3  14.Rb1  Bd7-+  with the idea to put our bishop on c6 or a4 and then 0-0-0. Our king will be very safe on the queenside. }
9... Nxc4 10. Qa4+ Nd7
