11. Rad1 Nbd7 12. Ne5
{ White would like to get in f2-f4, establishing his knight firmly on e5. }
12... Nb6 13. Bd3 Nfd5
{ simplifications are always good for Black. The more pieces we are able to exchange, the better it is for us to defend against White's threats on the kingside. We are also a pawn up, so transposing into an endgame is beneficial for us in general. }
14. Bg3
{ 14.Bxe7  Qxe7  15.Bb1  Bd7  16.Qd3  g6  17.h4  is an attempt to open the b1-h7 diagonal by playing h5 next.   17.Rfe1  Be8  18.Ne4  Nd7  Black would like to play ...N7f6 and then ...Kg7 with a good game. White has some compensation but Black is solid on the kingside.  17...Be8  by bringing the bishop to e8 we give added protection to the g6-pawn. Now we are ready to capture the h4-pawn.   17...Qxh4??  loses to  18.Nxg6!  +-  crushing Black's kingside.   17...Nf6?  is not an ideal way to prevent h5 as well. Because after  18.h5!  Nxh5  19.Nxg6+-  gives White a winning attack.  18.h5  This seems to be White's best bet.   18.Qg3?!  can be comfortably met by,  18...Nf6  covering the h5-square.  19.Ne4  Nbd5=+  the other knight joins the defence. Our rook is also ready to enter the game with ...Rd8. Once our pieces start to co-ordinate, White has to be careful not to lose all the compensation for the pawn.   18.g3?!  is too slow and is again met by,  18...Nf6=+  followed by ...Rd8 when Black stands slightly better.  18...Nf4  It is obvious that we should go for the h5-pawn.  19.Qf3  This was White's idea. He wants to take the b7-pawn.   19.Qe3?  hoping to win the h6-pawn in case Black plays ...Nxh5. But Black can simply stabilize his knight with  19...g5!  with the idea to play ...f5 next, soaking up all the kingside pressure.  20.Ng4  White aims to create some threats on the kingside, but we can simply ignore them with  20...Bc6!  now if,  21.Nxh6+  Kh8  of course not   21...Kg7??  due to  22.Nf5++-  winning the queen.  22.f3  Nbd5!  This move supports our queen on e7 thus enabling us to play ...f5 on the next move. Now, we start playing against the h6-knight.  23.Nxd5  Nxd5-+  with the idea to play ...f5 next with a winning advantage as the knight on h6 is trapped.   19.Qe4  leads to the same thing as 19.Qf3.  19...Nxh5  20.Qxb7  Nf6  After refuting White's attacking chances by winning the h5-pawn we retreat our knight.  21.Rfe1  creating some tactical ideas like d5.  21...Qd6  we sidestep any d5 tricks. Black is doing completely fine. For example White can now try to create pressure against the c7-pawn starting with,  22.Ne4  Nxe4  23.Bxe4  a5  freeing the a8-rook.  24.Rc1  now we can further simply the position by capturing the d4-pawn.  24...Qxd4  25.Nf3  Qd8  the idea of placing the queen on d8 is that we can play ...Rc8 in case White captures the c7-pawn with his rook.   25...Qxb2??  loses to  26.Rxc7+-  with the threat of Rb1 when Black's pieces stand shaky.  26.Red1   26.Rxc7  is met by  26...Rc8  27.Rxc8   27.Rec1?  is bad due to  27...Rxc7  28.Rxc7  Qd1+  29.Kh2  Nd7∓  with the threat to play ...Qd6+ followed by ...Nc5, Black is clearly better.  27...Nxc8  28.Qb8  f6  vacating the f7-square for our bishop.  29.Bc2  Bf7=+  we have managed to support the d8-queen which means there is no more danger on the 8th rank. White still has some compensation for the pawn but I believe that Black's chances are slightly better as White has to play accurately to maintain the balance.  26...Nd5  this leads to more simplifications.  27.Bxd5  exd5  28.Rxd5  Rb8!  again forcing more exchanges.  29.Qxc7  Qxc7  30.Rxc7  Rxb2=  White will capture the a5-pawn next when the endgame will be completely equal. }
