{ It is important to exchange on c3 before settling for 0-0.   The most logical move,  9...O-O?!  would be inaccurate here as White has the strong central break,  10.d5!  This is the drawback of having the knight on c6! Now Black does not have time to exchange on c3 as White will capture the knight on c6  @@StartBracket@@now we can see the advantage of inserting  Qa4+  for White@@EndBracket@@.  10...exd5   10...Bxc3?  is met by,  11.dxc6!  and Black's dark-squared bishop lacks squares.  11...Bxb2  12.Rab1  b5  13.Bxb5+-  White has a great advantage here as Black's dark-squared bishop is out of squares while the pawn on  c6  dominates Black's light-squared bishop.  11.Nxd5  Be7  12.Nxe7+  Qxe7  13.Rfe1!  no time to relax for Black, White develops his pieces with tempo.  13...Qb4   after  13...Be6  14.Bxe6  fxe6  15.Qb3  White enjoys a nice pressure on Black's position.  14.Qc2  White enjoys a nice initiative here as Black's pieces are not coordinated right now and he will need some time to bring his rooks into play. }
10. bxc3 O-O { The direct, } 11. Ne5
{ was once tried by Mamedyarov against Duda. This move requires more concrete handling by Black than White's other 11th moves. }
11... Qd6
{ immediately getting away from the pin and putting pressure on the knight on e5. }
12. Rfe1 Nd5
{ a typical idea in this position for Black. After ... Nd5, Black’s f-pawn is ready to march forward either to f6 or f5. }
13. Bxd5
{ 13.Bd3  is also a possibility for White. Bd3 frees the c4-square for the knight in case Black plays ...f6.  13...f6  we still play  ...f6  in order to push back White's pieces.   13...Nxc3?  is bad due to  14.Qc2+-  when Black is in great danger.  14.Nc4  Qe7  15.Bd2  Qf7=∞  tucking the queen away from the e-file avoiding any tactical tricks. Next, we are ready to develop our bishop to d7 with a solid position though White maintains compensation for the pawn. }
13... Qxd5
{ is a slightly better way to recapture than  13...exd5  , which leads to clear equality;  14.Nxc6  Qxc6  15.Qxc6  bxc6  16.Bf4  Bf5=  1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@31@@EndBracket@@ Mamedyarov,S @@StartBracket@@2817@@EndBracket@@-Duda,J  @@StartBracket@@2738@@EndBracket@@ Wijk aan Zee 2019   Play may continue, }
14. Rab1 f6 15. Nxc6 bxc6
{ Black will try to break with c6-c5 next. Black is still a pawn up here though the position is still very close to equal due to the presence of opposite colour bishops. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "15. Vienna 5.e4 Bb4 6.Bxc4"]
[Black "Vienna 8.Qa4+ with 9.Bg5 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. e4 Bb4 6. Bxc4
{ This an interesting dynamic line for White. He ignores the threat of Black's previous move ...Bb4 @@StartBracket@@pinning the c3-knight and attacking the e4-pawn@@EndBracket@@ and continues developing his pieces. This line became popular when Rustam Kasimdzhanov played it at the highest level against Boris Gelfand in the World Championship Candidates Semi-Final in Elista 2007. After this game 6.Bc4 started appearing regularly in the Grandmaster encounters and it quickly became established as one of the main fighting replies against the Vienna Opening. Check out the model game Halkias vs. Perunovic, Kostic Memorial 2008, where White won a brilliant attacking game showing the dynamic potential of this line.   The main strategy for White in this line is that by sacrificing the pawn on e4 he aims for quick development. White will use his quick development by rapidly posting his pieces on aggressive squares where they will start exerting pressure on Black's position or hinder Black from developing his pieces. A major source of problem for Black is his bishop on c8. If Black’s light-squared bishop manages to see the light of the day without ruining his overall position, then Black is usually doing fine. An important role in this line is played by Black's knight on b8. It craves to go on the kingside with a typical manoeuvre Nc6-e7-g6 or f5.   To sum up the introduction of this line, White's play is easier than Black's. For the sacrifice of the e4-pawn, he gets free play for his pieces. Black should know how to tackle White's quick development and initial pressure. }
6... Nxe4
{ Black must accept the challenge. Otherwise, he would simply surrender the centre for free. }
7. O-O Nf6
{ I believe retreating the knight is one of the most comfortable ways to play against the 6.Bc4 line.   7...Nxc3  8.bxc3  Bd6!?  is another interesting way to play and less explored compared to 8...Be7. I once played this line against the strong young Indian GM S.L. Narayanan and escaped with a draw after defending against his onslaught.   8...Be7  was established as the mainline here for Black. It is still doing fine, but Black gets a very passive position which is not to my taste. }
8. Qa4+
{ White forces the black knight to c6, where it will be a target. 8. Bg5 and 8. Qe2 are the other moves, where White plays in a standard fashion for compensation. }
8... Nc6 9. Bg5 Bxc3
{ It is important to exchange on c3 before settling for 0-0.   The most logical move,  9...O-O?!  would be inaccurate here as White has the strong central break,  10.d5!  This is the drawback of having the knight on c6! Now Black does not have time to exchange on c3 as White will capture the knight on c6  @@StartBracket@@now we can see the advantage of inserting  Qa4+  for White@@EndBracket@@.  10...exd5   10...Bxc3?  is met by,  11.dxc6!  and Black's dark-squared bishop lacks squares.  11...Bxb2  12.Rab1  b5  13.Bxb5+-  White has a great advantage here as Black's dark-squared bishop is out of squares while the pawn on  c6  dominates Black's light-squared bishop.  11.Nxd5  Be7  12.Nxe7+  Qxe7  13.Rfe1!  no time to relax for Black, White develops his pieces with tempo.  13...Qb4   after  13...Be6  14.Bxe6  fxe6  15.Qb3  White enjoys a nice pressure on Black's position.  14.Qc2  White enjoys a nice initiative here as Black's pieces are not coordinated right now and he will need some time to bring his rooks into play. }
10. bxc3 O-O
{ This is a critical position of the 9.Bg5 variation.  White has decent compensation for the pawn due to the bishop pair and active pieces. His idea is to mount an attack on the kingside. Furthermore, Black's bishop on c8 will require a bit of work to get developed.  White has several ways of playing here but there exists a common route for his pieces in all of them:  - Either rook will go to e1,  - He will aim to get in Ne5,  - The light-squared bishop will go to d3,  - The Queen will go to c2  So, if we are not careful, we may quickly find ourselves under a strong kingside attack.  Our main idea is to try to bring the c6-knight to the kingside on f5 or g6, via e7. But first of all, it is important to insert the move h7-h6 and force White's dark-squared bishop to commit its position either on the kingside  (in case he plays Bh4)  or on the queenside  (in case he plays Bc1)  .  If the bishop goes to h4, we should play Ne7.  If it goes to c1, then we should play Nd5.  This line is fresh and White's best continuation is not yet established. Let's review some of white's possibilities. }
11. Rad1 { is met by our typical move, } 11... h6
{ Forcing White to commit his bishop's position. } 12. Bh4
{ 12.Bc1  as mentioned earlier, is met by,  12...Nd5!  13.Qc2  Qd6=  preventing Bc1-a3. Black will next focus on his light-squared bishop by either developing it directly to d7 or after b7-b6 to b7. }
12... Ne7
{ Now we can see that the move Ne7-f5 will come with a lot of force as White will be forced to exchange his dark-squared bishop for our knight. }
13. Bxf6
{ This is the usual reaction - White immediately exchanges his bishop, ruining Black’s pawn structure. }
13... gxf6
{ It might seem that our weak kingside pawn formation will give good opportunities for White to create an attack, but this is far from true. Black is easily able to hold on the kingside @@StartBracket@@as proved in the games from similar positions@@EndBracket@@, especially with our knight ready to go to g6 and help our king in the defence. }
14. Qc2 Rb8
{ This seems like an improvement to me over Ne7-g6 played by Itturizaga. We should focus on developing our light-squared bishop. Ra8-b8 prepares b7-b5 followed by developing the bishop to b7. A sample variation could be -   14...Ng6  is a logical move but we don't need to bring the knight immediately to g6. 0-1 @@StartBracket@@68@@EndBracket@@ Narayanan,S @@StartBracket@@2611@@EndBracket@@-Iturrizaga,E @@StartBracket@@2629@@EndBracket@@ chess24.com INT 2020 @@EndBracket@@ }
15. Rfe1 b5 16. Bb3
{ The usual  16.Bd3  is not so good without the knight on g6  16...Bb7  17.Qd2  Kg7  18.Nh4   18.Re3?!  is met by,  18...Nd5  when Black seizes the initiative.  18...Rh8  19.Re3   19.Bxb5?  does not work due to,  19...Bxg2!  19...Bd5  Black's pieces are well placed. He has solved the problem of his light-squared bishop and his king always has a safe square on f8. }
16... Kg7 17. Re3 Rb6
{ a nice move. The rook is well placed on b6 and can provide a helping hand via the 6th rank. The variation may continue, }
18. Nh4 f5 19. Rg3+ Kh7 20. Nf3 Bb7 { intending to exchange the knight on f3. }
21. Ne5 Ng6
{ Black is comfortably holding on the kingside while White still needs to prove compensation for the sacrificed pawn. }
*

