1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. e4 Bb4 6. Bxc4
{ This an interesting dynamic line for White. He ignores the threat of Black's previous move ...Bb4 @@StartBracket@@pinning the c3-knight and attacking the e4-pawn@@EndBracket@@ and continues developing his pieces. This line became popular when Rustam Kasimdzhanov played it at the highest level against Boris Gelfand in the World Championship Candidates Semi-Final in Elista 2007. After this game 6.Bc4 started appearing regularly in the Grandmaster encounters and it quickly became established as one of the main fighting replies against the Vienna Opening. Check out the model game Halkias vs. Perunovic, Kostic Memorial 2008, where White won a brilliant attacking game showing the dynamic potential of this line.   The main strategy for White in this line is that by sacrificing the pawn on e4 he aims for quick development. White will use his quick development by rapidly posting his pieces on aggressive squares where they will start exerting pressure on Black's position or hinder Black from developing his pieces. A major source of problem for Black is his bishop on c8. If Black’s light-squared bishop manages to see the light of the day without ruining his overall position, then Black is usually doing fine. An important role in this line is played by Black's knight on b8. It craves to go on the kingside with a typical manoeuvre Nc6-e7-g6 or f5.   To sum up the introduction of this line, White's play is easier than Black's. For the sacrifice of the e4-pawn, he gets free play for his pieces. Black should know how to tackle White's quick development and initial pressure. }
6... Nxe4
{ Black must accept the challenge. Otherwise, he would simply surrender the centre for free. }
7. O-O Nf6
{ I believe retreating the knight is one of the most comfortable ways to play against the 6.Bc4 line.   7...Nxc3  8.bxc3  Bd6!?  is another interesting way to play and less explored compared to 8...Be7. I once played this line against the strong young Indian GM S.L. Narayanan and escaped with a draw after defending against his onslaught.   8...Be7  was established as the mainline here for Black. It is still doing fine, but Black gets a very passive position which is not to my taste. }
8. Qa4+
{ White forces the black knight to c6, where it will be a target. 8. Bg5 and 8. Qe2 are the other moves, where White plays in a standard fashion for compensation. }
8... Nc6 9. Ne5
{ This seems more consistent with White's previous move 8.Qa4+. } 9... Bd6
{ Black retreats his bishop to d6 taking prophylactic measures against White's threat of Nc6. This move played by Caruana against Magnus is simple and easy to understand compared to 9...Rb8.   Initially, I wanted to recommend  9...Rb8  as the mainline for Black. But I realised that Carlsen's idea of 10.Rd1 is quite annoying to face.  10.Rd1!  A nice idea by Magnus. White defends the d4-pawn and prepares to capture the a7-pawn after the knight exchange on c6.  10...O-O  11.Nxc6  bxc6  12.Qxa7  this is the point! Instead of taking the c6-pawn, White takes on a7 thus creating a clear outside passed a-pawn.  12...Bd7  13.Qa4  c5  14.Qc2  Bc6!  N  is an improvement over Duda's move 14...cxd4.   14...cxd4?!  this was inaccurate and Magnus won a nearly perfect game against Duda. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@71@@EndBracket@@ Carlsen, M @@StartBracket@@2835@@EndBracket@@-Duda,J @@StartBracket@@2738@@EndBracket@@ Wijk aan Zee 2019 Mega2019 Updates @@StartSquare@@Nielsen,Peter Heine@@EndSquare@@  15.dxc5  Qe7  16.a4!  White starts advancing his passed pawn immediately.  16...Qxc5  17.Bd3  I believe White has a slight pressure here due to his passed a-pawn. His next moves are going to be Bc1-e3 and then Nc3-b5 creating pressure on the c-file as well. }
10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. Qxc6+ Bd7 12. Qf3 O-O
{ It is desirable to prevent Bc1-g5 with  12...h6  but it would allow White to break in the centre with,  13.d5!  N   13.Bf4  1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@18@@EndBracket@@ Gozzoli,Y  @@StartBracket@@2614@@EndBracket@@-Gharamian,T @@StartBracket@@2586@@EndBracket@@ Chartres FRA 2019  13...O-O  and now after  14.dxe6  Bxe6  15.Bxe6  fxe6  16.Qe2  Black's pawn structure is ruined further and White has a stable advantage. }
13. Bg5 h6 14. Bh4 Rb8
{ Attacking the b2-pawn while also preparing to go to the b6 square. } 15. b3
{ 15.Qe2  allows Black to activate his light-squared bishop with,  15...Bc6=  when all Black's pieces are well placed and Black is doing fine. }
15... Rb6
{ The rook is well placed on b6 supporting ideas like Bd7-c6, activating our light-squared bishop. Another very important idea for Black is to play Qd8-a8, challenging the active white queen on f3. White still seems to have some pressure, but his temporary initiative can be neutralized with good moves  (as Caruana managed to do against Magnus in their encounter)  . I have analysed a few sample variations which show black's main ideas. }
16. Rfd1 { Preparing for a timely d4-d5 break is simply met by, } 16... Qa8
{ A nice way to unpin the f6-knight and offering the exchange of queens at the same time. Black is now all set to meet the d5 break. }
17. d5 Nxd5 18. Nxd5 exd5 19. Bxd5 Bc6
{ A few more exchanges are likely to happen in this position, resulting in a balanced endgame. }
*

