16. Ne4 Be7 17. Nxf6+ Bxf6 18. Bxf6 Qxf6 19. Qxf6 gxf6 20. d5
{ White eliminates his weakness on d4 by pushing the pawn forward. His main aim is now to create play against Black's isolated pawns on c7 and a7. Till now we are following the game between Carlsen and Caruana. Here best for Black was to start playing on the queenside with, }
20... a5
{ Black should get in the a5-a4 break as quickly as possible. If given time, White will bring his rooks in the game quickly creating play against Black's weak queenside pawns. There is a high probability of a double rook endgame appearing on the board sooner or later. When that happens, we should remember as Black to always look for opportunities to create counterplay with our rooks. If you have a choice between defending a pawn or sacrificing it to get activity and create counterplay, always prefer counterplay over the material in this endgame.   20...e5  1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@43@@EndBracket@@ Carlsen,M @@StartBracket@@2882@@EndBracket@@-Caruana,F @@StartBracket@@2818@@EndBracket@@ Saint Louis USA 2019 }
21. Rfc1 Rd8
{ The rook on d8 waits patiently for the opening of the d-file! One of the ideas for Black now is to play the c7-c6 break. }
22. dxe6 Bxe6 23. Bxe6 Rxe6
{ Black's two rooks provide sufficient counterplay to hold the balance in this endgame. }
