1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. e4 Bb4 6. Bg5 c5 7. dxc5
{ This capture is just a try to take prepared players out of book towards new paths. 7.dxc5 has been played in a few games but it is not challenging at all, as Black can get easy equality with simple logical play. }
7... Qxd1+ 8. Rxd1 Bxc3+
{ It is better to capture on c3 immediately and ruin White's pawn structure.   8...Nbd7  is the most popular move with 29 games played till now according to my database. This is quite similar to our main move  8...Bc3+  , but it gives White an additional option. Here White has a chance to prevent ruining his pawn structure with  9.Bd2  .  White gets ready to recapture on c3 with the bishop. This way it makes sense to capture on c3 immediately on the 8th move, stripping White of the option if 9.Bd2 }
9. bxc3 Nbd7
{ Developing the knight as well as threatening to capture the pawns on c5 and e4. In this position, we should not hurry to 0-0. We can wait until the air on the queenside is clear, as our king is safe in the centre. Now White has a few options we need to take a look at.   9...Nxe4??  10.Rd8#  would of course never happen! }
10. c6
{ With this advance, White closes the c-file and makes sure that he will not have a weak c3-pawn on the c-file. But this also helps Black's light-squared bishop to come into the game quickly. }
10... bxc6 11. Nd2 Ba6
{ Black makes sure he gets to exchange the light-squared bishop. } 12. Bxf6
Nxf6 13. f3
{ White supports his pawn on e4 while preparing to capture our c4-pawn. Now in this position, it is in our interest if we manage to exchange our bishop for White's knight. In the resulting knight vs. bishop endgame, our knight will have a stable square on c5. Thus, I recommend forcing White to capture on c4 with his knight by playing, }
13... Rd8
{ 13...Ke7  1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@24@@EndBracket@@ Troff,K @@StartBracket@@2482@@EndBracket@@ -Nyzhnyk, I @@StartBracket@@2610@@EndBracket@@ Chicago 2017 }
14. Rb1 { can be met by, } 14... Ke7 15. Nxc4
{ 15.Bxc4?  is again bad due to,  15...Rxd2  16.Bxa6  Rxa2-+  when Black ends with a clear pawn up and a winning advantage. }
15... Rb8 16. Rb3 { and now, } 16... Bxc4 17. Bxc4 Nd7
{ Black's knight is ready to stabilize itself on the c5-square. Black is fine. }
