13. Qxc4 e5
{ Another simple move, supporting the very important pawn on d4. For the past few moves Black has been defending against the threats from White and has just lost his pawn on c4 but what has he gained in return? Well, now the defending part is over and it is time to go on the offensive! Black's previous move 13...e5 has firmly supported the pawn on d4 and also opened Black's light-squared bishop to come to active squares like e6 or f5. The black a8 rook is ready to come to c8 where combined with ideas like ...Nb4, it can create serious threats on the queenside. Another important fact is that the white queen is badly misplaced on the c-file. }
14. Nxe5
{ This is a very stress-relieving move for White! This is White’s best chance to give the piece back and curb Black's initiative before it becomes unstoppable. }
14... Nxe5 { 14...fxe5??  15.Nd6+!+- } 15. Qxd4
{ White has eliminated all three black pawns. Black's kingside is slightly weak but Black has good counterplay on the queenside which does not give sufficient time for White to exploit it. }
15... O-O { The aggressive, } 16. f4 { is premature due to, } 16... Rc8+ 17.
Nc3 { 17.Kb1?  Bf5-+ } 17... Bc5 18. Qd5 { 18.Qd2  Qb6!-+ } 18... Qb6
{ and Black gets a very strong attack. } 19. fxe5 Bf5 { with Be3 to follow. }
20. Bd3 Ba3 { Black crashes through on the queenside. } *

