{ Another important position of this line. White has managed to win a piece using tactics, but Black on the other hand, has gained 3 important pawns. His pawns on c4 and d4 are well advanced and limit white's pieces. Another very important concession that White made in the process of winning the piece is that he committed his king on the queenside where it is vulnerable. One of Black's main strategies from this position is to create play against the white king. Now Black has 3 moves that he has tried in practice and according to me, the simplest to understand and play is, }
12... a6
{ This silent little pawn move is quite annoying for White as it forces him to capture on c4 with the queen. If White does not take the c4-pawn then we are ready to advance on the queenside with b7-b5 when the black pawn avalanche on the white king looks dangerous just by its mere sight! }
13. Qxc4 e5
{ Another simple move, supporting the very important pawn on d4. For the past few moves Black has been defending against the threats from White and has just lost his pawn on c4 but what has he gained in return? Well, now the defending part is over and it is time to go on the offensive! Black's previous move 13...e5 has firmly supported the pawn on d4 and also opened Black's light-squared bishop to come to active squares like e6 or f5. The black a8 rook is ready to come to c8 where combined with ideas like ...Nb4, it can create serious threats on the queenside. Another important fact is that the white queen is badly misplaced on the c-file. }
14. Nxe5
{ This is a very stress-relieving move for White! This is White’s best chance to give the piece back and curb Black's initiative before it becomes unstoppable. }
14... Nxe5 { 14...fxe5??  15.Nd6+!+- } 15. Qxd4
{ White has eliminated all three black pawns. Black's kingside is slightly weak but Black has good counterplay on the queenside which does not give sufficient time for White to exploit it. }
15... O-O
{ With this Black completes his development and is all set to take action on the queenside. }
16. Be2 Qc8+
{ To a better endgame for Black leads the following forced sequence. } 17. Qc3
{ is met by, } 17... Bf5 18. Bxf6
{ this way of capturing the f6-pawn is refuted by the powerful, } 18... Bb4
{ Forcing White to exchange queens on c8. } 19. Qxc8 Raxc8+
{ The knight on e4 hangs, so White is forced to retreat it to c3. } 20. Nc3
Bxc3 21. bxc3 Rxc3+ 22. Kd2 Rc2+ 23. Ke1 Re8
{ The pressure on the e-file is too strong to handle. We are going to win material one way or another. Black has a winning advantage. }
*

