{ We would love not to play such a weakening move, but everything is still under control. }
15. Rfe1 a6 16. Nd4 Ne5 { Forcing the exchange of one of White's bishops. } 17.
Bxe5 Qxe5 18. Qe3 { Threatening to win the e4-knight with f3. } 18... Qf6
{ Now Black is a comfortable pawn up and given a few more moves we can easily consolidate our position. So, White needs to act quickly. }
19. Nxf5 { It is necessary for White to open up the position. } 19... Qxf5 20.
Qxe4 Qxf2+ 21. Kh1 Bd7
{ Finally we have managed to develop our bishop and connect our rooks while maintaining our extra pawn! }
22. Rad1 b5
{ An intermediate move of paramount importance. The white bishop is perfectly placed on c4 covering the f1-square  @@StartBracket@@which prevents any back-rank mating ideas@@EndBracket@@ and attacking the a6-pawn @@StartBracket@@which ties Black's rook to its defence@@EndBracket@@. So, it is vital to unsettle the bishop from c4.   22...Bb5  1-0 @@StartBracket@@28@@EndBracket@@ Yilmaz,M @@StartBracket@@2595@@EndBracket@@ -Salomon,J @@StartBracket@@2507@@EndBracket@@ Batumi GEO 2019 }
23. Rxd7 { Leads to an equal endgame after, } 23... bxc4 24. Qxe6+ Kh8 25. h3
{ Creating luft for the white king. } 25... Qg3
{ According to me both sides have equal chances in this major piece endgame. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18. Vienna 5.e4 Bb4 6.Bg5 c5 7.Bxc4 with 10.Nb5"]
[Black "Vienna 7.Bxc4 with 10.Nb5 Nxe4 11.Bf4 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. e4 Bb4 6. Bg5 c5 7. Bxc4
{ This is White's most popular move. He captures the c4-pawn and prepares to 0-0. }
7... cxd4
{ We should take immediate action in the centre before White is able to 0-0 and settle down. So, the next few moves are concrete in nature. }
8. Nxd4 Bxc3+
{ It is better to exchange on  c3  immediately before playing ...Qa5. Because immediate  8...Qa5  gives White an additional option of  9.Bd2  . }
9. bxc3 Qa5 { Threatening both the g5-bishop and the c3-pawn. } 10. Nb5
{ This is the third most popular move in this position. White supports the c3-pawn and at the same time has ideas to exploit the control over the d6 and c7 squares, thanks to his active knight on b5. White is ready to sacrifice his e4-pawn for the initiative. 10.Nb5 requires concrete play from Black. The correct way to play against this has already been established long back. It is just important to remember the exact response from our side. This line gained its followers when the Ex-World Champion Anatoly Karpov played it in his match against Jan Timman in 1993. }
10... Nxe4
{ 10...O-O  would be a mistake due to,  11.Bxf6  gxf6  12.Qg4+  Kh8  13.Qh4  Nd7  14.Rd1+-  the white rook on d1 is all set to transfer to the kingside via d3, creating a very strong attack. }
11. Bf4
{ This continuation is much stronger and requires more precision from Black. As compensation for the pawn, White has a strong pair of bishops. At the same time, Black is behind in development and his knight is quite vulnerable in the centre. Nevertheless, Black has enough resources to keep the balance. }
11... O-O 12. O-O
{ White needs to move his king away from e1 as soon as possible, otherwise tactics would work against him.   12.Qf3?  is bad due to,  12...Bd7!-+  and Black gets a winning advantage by counter-attacking the b5-knight.   12.Qd4?  is another losing queen sortie. Black again has the same counter-attacking move,  12...Bd7!  the b5-knight and the c3-pawn are under pressure.  13.Nc7  Nc6  14.Qxe4  Qxc3+-+  wins for Black. }
12... Nc6
{ Black is ready to advance ... e5 and cut White's f4 bishop from the queenside. }
13. Bc7 b6 14. Qf3
{ This forces Black to weaken his kingside.   14.a4  allows Black to develop freely with,  14...Bb7  Black has connected the rooks and can play ...a6 at the right moment, kicking the b5-knight. Black is slightly better here as White still needs compensation for his sacrificed pawn. }
14... f5
{ We would love not to play such a weakening move, but everything is still under control. }
15. Rfe1 a6 16. Nd4 Ne5 { Forcing the exchange of one of White's bishops. } 17.
Bxe5 Qxe5 18. Qe3 { Threatening to win the e4-knight with f3. } 18... Qf6
{ Now Black is a comfortable pawn up and given a few more moves we can easily consolidate our position. So, White needs to act quickly. }
19. Nxf5 { It is necessary for White to open up the position. } 19... Qxf5 20.
Qxe4 Qxf2+ 21. Kh1 Bd7
{ Finally we have managed to develop our bishop and connect our rooks while maintaining our extra pawn! }
22. Rad1 b5
{ An intermediate move of paramount importance. The white bishop is perfectly placed on c4 covering the f1-square  @@StartBracket@@which prevents any back-rank mating ideas@@EndBracket@@ and attacking the a6-pawn @@StartBracket@@which ties Black's rook to its defence@@EndBracket@@. So, it is vital to unsettle the bishop from c4.   22...Bb5  1-0 @@StartBracket@@28@@EndBracket@@ Yilmaz,M @@StartBracket@@2595@@EndBracket@@ -Salomon,J @@StartBracket@@2507@@EndBracket@@ Batumi GEO 2019 }
23. Bb3 Rae8
{ Now we can freely defend the e6-pawn and our a6-pawn is no longer under attack. We are a pawn ahead but White has sufficient compensation to maintain equal chances in this position. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "19. Vienna 5.e4 Bb4 6.Bg5 c5 7.Bxc4 with 10.Bf6"]
[Black "Vienna 10.Bxf6 with 13.Bb5+"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. e4 Bb4 6. Bg5 c5 7. Bxc4 cxd4 8.
Nxd4 Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 Qa5 10. Bxf6
{ This is the second most popular move for White. He exchanges on f6 first and intends to 0-0 immediately next. }
10... Qxc3+
{ Of course, we should not give him that chance. With the 10...Qxc3 intermezzo, we not only win a pawn but also deny White his castling rights. }
11. Kf1 gxf6
{ It would be wrong to capture White's light-squared bishop due to,  11...Qxc4+?  12.Kg1  and now Black cannot escape with the 'logical'  12...O-O  because of  13.Qg4  g6  14.e5+-  when Black's dark squares are chronically weakened. }
12. Rc1
{ 12.Bb5+  should be met by,  12...Ke7   not,  12...Bd7??  due to,  13.Rc1+-  13.Rc1  Qa5  transposes. }
12... Qa5 { White has a forced draw after, } 13. Bb5+ Ke7
{ Not  13...Bd7??  due to,  14.Rc8++- } 14. e5
{ Trying to open up Black’s king's shelter. } 14... fxe5 15. Qh5 Nd7
{ A cool developing move supporting the pawn on e5.   15...exd4??  loses to,  16.Qg5+!  f6  17.Qc5+!  Kf7  18.Be8++  and White wins the Queen. }
16. Qg5+ Kf8 17. Rxc8+
{ this pushes Black to find the best moves. A direct draw would be,  17.Nxe6+  fxe6  18.Qh6+  Kf7  19.Qh5+= }
17... Rxc8 18. Bxd7 Qd8
{ Now it is important to remember this exact move by Black which saves the game. }
19. Nxe6+
{ 19.Qxe5?!  Rc1+  20.Ke2  Rxh1  21.Nxe6+   21.Qxh8+?  leads to a losing endgame after,  21...Ke7  22.Qxd8+  Kxd8  23.Ba4  Rxh2-+  and Black's rook and two extra pawns will overpower White's knight and bishop.  21...fxe6  22.Qxh8+  Ke7  23.Qg7+  Kd6  and White needs to play accurately to hold the balance. }
19... fxe6 20. Qh6+ Kf7 21. Qxe6+ Kf8 22. Qh6+ Kf7
{ There are many games in the database that have followed this path towards a draw. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "19. Vienna 5.e4 Bb4 6.Bg5 c5 7.Bxc4 with 10.Bf6"]
[Black "Vienna 10.Bxf6 with 13.Nb5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. e4 Bb4 6. Bg5 c5 7. Bxc4 cxd4 8.
Nxd4 Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 Qa5 10. Bxf6
{ This is the second most popular move for White. He exchanges on f6 first and intends to 0-0 immediately next. }
10... Qxc3+
{ Of course, we should not give him that chance. With the 10...Qxc3 intermezzo, we not only win a pawn but also deny White his castling rights. }
11. Kf1 gxf6
{ It would be wrong to capture White's light-squared bishop due to,  11...Qxc4+?  12.Kg1  and now Black cannot escape with the 'logical'  12...O-O  because of  13.Qg4  g6  14.e5+-  when Black's dark squares are chronically weakened. }
12. Rc1
{ 12.Bb5+  should be met by,  12...Ke7   not,  12...Bd7??  due to,  13.Rc1+-  13.Rc1  Qa5  transposes. }
12... Qa5
{ This is the only move in the position. It is important to control the c7 square preventing the white knight from arriving there in the future.   12...Qb4  looks logical but does not work due to,  13.Nb5!  the white knight creates havoc.  13...Na6  14.a3  another strong move pushing the black queen to an inferior square.  14...Qc5   14...Qa5  15.Qh5!  Ke7  16.e5+-   14...Qe7  15.Nd6+  Kf8  16.Bxa6+-  15.Nd6+  Ke7  16.Nxf7+- }
13. Nb5
{ This knight sortie which caused Black a lot of trouble in case of 12... Qb4, now loses its power as the c7 square is now under control. Black can immediately kick the white knight with, }
13... a6
{ This is the last precise move. White doesn't have enough resources to create any problems for Black. After }
14. Nd6+ Ke7 15. h4
{ Trying to activate the rook via h3. But White does not have sufficient time for that as Black forces the exchange of pieces with, }
15... Rd8 16. Nxc8+ Rxc8
{ Followed by Nd7, Black has quite a decent position. White lacks compensation for the pawn. }
