[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "19. Vienna 5.e4 Bb4 6.Bg5 c5 7.Bxc4 with 10.Bf6"]
[Black "Vienna 10.Bxf6 with 13.Qg4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. e4 Bb4 6. Bg5 c5 7. Bxc4 cxd4 8.
Nxd4 Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 Qa5 10. Bxf6
{ This is the second most popular move for White. He exchanges on f6 first and intends to 0-0 immediately next. }
10... Qxc3+
{ Of course, we should not give him that chance. With the 10...Qxc3 intermezzo, we not only win a pawn but also deny White his castling rights. }
11. Kf1 gxf6
{ It would be wrong to capture White's light-squared bishop due to,  11...Qxc4+?  12.Kg1  and now Black cannot escape with the 'logical'  12...O-O  because of  13.Qg4  g6  14.e5+-  when Black's dark squares are chronically weakened. }
12. Rc1
{ 12.Bb5+  should be met by,  12...Ke7   not,  12...Bd7??  due to,  13.Rc1+-  13.Rc1  Qa5  transposes. }
12... Qa5
{ This is the only move in the position. It is important to control the c7 square preventing the white knight from arriving there in the future.   12...Qb4  looks logical but does not work due to,  13.Nb5!  the white knight creates havoc.  13...Na6  14.a3  another strong move pushing the black queen to an inferior square.  14...Qc5   14...Qa5  15.Qh5!  Ke7  16.e5+-   14...Qe7  15.Nd6+  Kf8  16.Bxa6+-  15.Nd6+  Ke7  16.Nxf7+- }
13. Qg4
{ the white queen intends to infiltrate on g7. Complications arise after }
13... Ke7
{ Black plans to play ...Rd8, attacking the d4-knight. If White moves the knight from d4 then Black will continue developing his queenside. Note - in such positions, usually, losing the pawn on h7 is not a big deal as Black will get sufficient counterplay by developing his queenside pieces. }
14. Qg7 Rf8
{ 14...Rd8??  unfortunately, does not work due to the tactical resource.  15.Nf5+!  exf5  16.Qxf7+  Kd6  17.Rd1+  Kc5  18.Rd5++-  and White wins the queen. }
15. e5
{ a nice idea opening up the e-file.   Maintaining the pressure with a move like,  15.h4  can be met by transferring the queen to the queenside with,  15...Qd2  16.Nb3  Qf4  17.Qxh7  Bd7  the material is equal but Black's pieces will come into play creating problems for White as White's pieces are uncoordinated. }
15... Qxe5 16. Nxe6
{ The point behind White's previous move. White intends to play the deadly Re1 next. Now the play is forced for both sides. }
16... Bxe6 17. Bxe6 Qg5
{ This nice defensive resource transposes the game into an equal ending. } 18.
Qxg5 fxg5 19. Bc8 { Winning the pawn back. } 19... Nd7 20. Re1+ Kd8 21. Bxb7
Rb8 22. Bf3 f5 { and this endgame is clearly equal. } *

