{ This is the only move in the position. It is important to control the c7 square preventing the white knight from arriving there in the future.   12...Qb4  looks logical but does not work due to,  13.Nb5!  the white knight creates havoc.  13...Na6  14.a3  another strong move pushing the black queen to an inferior square.  14...Qc5   14...Qa5  15.Qh5!  Ke7  16.e5+-   14...Qe7  15.Nd6+  Kf8  16.Bxa6+-  15.Nd6+  Ke7  16.Nxf7+- }
13. g3 { Now Black must focus on completing his queenside development with, }
13... Bd7
{ Black prepares 14...Nc6.   Intending to bring the rook to  d8  is not so strong here due to,  13...Ke7?!  14.Kg2  Rd8  15.Re1!  White's idea of Nd4-f5 is very strong to defend against.  15...Nc6  16.Nf5+!  exf5  17.exf5+  Ne5  18.Qh5  Kd6  N   18...Rf8  19.f4+-  1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@30@@EndBracket@@ Rustemov, A @@StartBracket@@2537@@EndBracket@@ -Neubauer, M @@StartBracket@@2431@@EndBracket@@ Germany 2012  19.Bxf7  White threatens Qh6 and has a very strong attack. }
14. Kg2 Nc6 15. Nb5 { should be met by, } 15... Ne5
{ Attacking both the bishop on c4 and the knight on b5. } 16. Nd6+ Ke7
{ I prefer to place our king on e7 as we can keep an eye on the d6 knight.   16...Kf8  1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@50@@EndBracket@@ Postny,E @@StartBracket@@2600@@EndBracket@@-Aleksandrov,A @@StartBracket@@2608@@EndBracket@@ lichess.org INT 2020 }
17. f4
{ 17.Nxb7  is harmless due to,  17...Qb6  18.Qb3  Qxb3  19.axb3  Bc6  and Black is slightly better as our pieces are better placed than White's. }
17... Bc6 18. Bd5 exd5 19. fxe5 fxe5 20. Nxf7
{ the best move for White that allows him to escape with a perpetual check. }
20... Kxf7 21. Qh5+ Ke6 22. Qf5+ Kd6 23. Qf6+ Kc7
{ Black tries to escape to the queenside. Now White has two ways to force a draw.   23...Kd7  would also lead to a draw after -  24.Qf7+  Kd8   it would be wrong to retreat with -  24...Kd6?  because of  25.Rhf1!+-  and White wins.  25.Qf6+  Kd7= }
24. Qxe5+ Kb6 25. Qd4+ Ka6
{ and here it is essential for White to find the only move } 26. a4
{ a multipurpose move. White covers the b5-square so that he can deliver a check from d3 and Black won't be able to interpose anything in between on b5. Another idea is that a4 restricts the black queen's mobility. So, infact White is now threatening the lethal Rc5. }
26... dxe4 27. Rc5 { is now met by } 27... e3+
{ making the d2-square available for the queen. White is forced to exchange on c6. }
28. Rxc6+ bxc6 29. Qc4+ Kb7
{ this is the correct square for the king to retreat to, keeping the b6-square free for Black's queen to interpose itself on the b-file. }
30. Rb1+ Qb6 31. Qf7+ Ka6 32. Qc4+ Kb7 { and the game ends in a perpetual. } *

