[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20. Vienna 5.e4 Bb4 6.Bg5 c5 7.Bxc4 with 10.Bb5"]
[Black "Vienna 10.Bb5+ with 12.Bxd7+ #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. e4 Bb4 6. Bg5 c5 7. Bxc4 cxd4 8.
Nxd4 Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 Qa5 10. Bb5+ Bd7
{ This is Black's second most popular move.  10...Nbd7  is the most popular move here for Black and has been played in many top-level games. It is a good alternative to 10...Bd7. After,  11.Bxf6  Qxc3+  12.Kf1  gxf6  13.h4  the play is quite complex. Black has won a pawn but is behind in development on the queenside. White tries his best to get compensation for his sacrificed pawn. Until now, Black has performed satisfactorily in this line. }
11. Bxf6
{ White needs to exchange on f6 as the bishop on g5 is always under the radar of the black queen on a5 and Black has ideas like ...Nxe4 in air. }
11... gxf6 12. Bxd7+ Nxd7 13. O-O
{ there are more than 100 games played from this position and now I would like to propose a rare line for Black! }
13... Qxc3
{ There are very few games played from this position. It caught my attention when Vishy Anand played it against Magnus in 2019. Black simply grabs the c3-pawn and challenges White to prove compensation for it. As we will see Black has sufficient resources to defend against White's threats.   13...a6  has always been the main response here for Black, covering the a6 square and preparing to retreat the queen to c7 in case of Ra1-b1.  14.Rb1  Qc7  15.Qh5  White usually got a slight initiative. }
14. Rb1 { is an interesting deceptive move, hoping for Black to 0-0. } 14...
Rd8
{ this is usually a good preparatory move before going for ...0-0. Black protects his knight on d7 avoiding any kind of discovered tricks on it.   The real deception behind White's previous move is revealed if Black goes for the logical,  14...O-O??  Now White has the strong  15.Rc1!  pushing the black queen to an inferior square before taking the e6-pawn.  15...Qa5  16.Nxe6  fxe6  17.Qxd7+-  and Black is about to lose material. }
15. Nb5
{ Again the best try for White.  15.Rxb7  is met by,  15...Nc5  16.Rc7   16.Re7+?!  looks flashy but it is of no use after  16...Kf8=  Black is completely fine.  16...Qxd4  17.Qxd4  Rxd4  18.Rc8+  Rd8  19.Rxc5  O-O  20.Rc7  Rd4=  this rook endgame is balanced. }
15... Qc6
{ we bring back our queen which will helps us face the upcoming threats. } 16.
Nd6+ Kf8
{ 16...Ke7??  would be a terrible mistake due to,  17.Nxb7  Rb8  and now the super strong -  18.Qb3!+-  and the queen check from the a3-f8 diagonal is going to be really uncomfortable for the black king. }
17. Nxb7
{ 17.Qd4  is nothing special. Black simply plays,  17...Ne5  18.Rfd1  Rg8  19.Qxa7  Kg7=  and Black is doing fine. }
17... Rb8
{ White has managed to regain the pawn, but the position is still very concrete with tactical ideas. }
18. Qc1 { takes the game to an equal ending after, } 18... Qxc1 19. Rfxc1 Kg7
20. Rc7 Nb6 21. Nc5
{ White's pieces look active and threatening but here Black has the very important move! }
21... Na4 { exploiting the back-rank weakness. } 22. Rxb8 Rxb8 23. Nb3 Rb6
{ intending to defend the a7-pawn actively with Rb6-a6 with an equal position. }
24. Rxa7 { is met by, } 24... Nc5
{ exploiting White's back-rank weakness and threatening to regain our pawn, Black equalizes. }
*

