1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. e4 Bb4 6. Bg5 c5 7. Bxc4 cxd4 8.
Nxd4 Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 Qa5 10. Bb5+ Bd7
{ This is Black's second most popular move.  10...Nbd7  is the most popular move here for Black and has been played in many top-level games. It is a good alternative to 10...Bd7. After,  11.Bxf6  Qxc3+  12.Kf1  gxf6  13.h4  the play is quite complex. Black has won a pawn but is behind in development on the queenside. White tries his best to get compensation for his sacrificed pawn. Until now, Black has performed satisfactorily in this line. }
11. Bxf6
{ White needs to exchange on f6 as the bishop on g5 is always under the radar of the black queen on a5 and Black has ideas like ...Nxe4 in air. }
11... gxf6 12. Bxd7+ Nxd7 13. O-O
{ there are more than 100 games played from this position and now I would like to propose a rare line for Black! }
13... Qxc3
{ There are very few games played from this position. It caught my attention when Vishy Anand played it against Magnus in 2019. Black simply grabs the c3-pawn and challenges White to prove compensation for it. As we will see Black has sufficient resources to defend against White's threats.   13...a6  has always been the main response here for Black, covering the a6 square and preparing to retreat the queen to c7 in case of Ra1-b1.  14.Rb1  Qc7  15.Qh5  White usually got a slight initiative. }
14. Qa4
{ This is the critical test for Black's idea with 13...Qc3. White prevents the black king from running to the kingside and connects his rooks at the same time. The white rooks are ready to join the battle with a strong effect. The position is very concrete where each move is of great value. Therefore, without wasting any further time Black should nonetheless go for... }
14... O-O { Using tactics to take the king to safety! } 15. Nxe6
{ White uses tactics in return destroying Black's pawn structure.   15.Qxd7  leads to easy equality after,  15...Rad8  16.Qxb7  Qxd4  17.Rab1  Rd7  18.Qc6  Rfd8=  Black's dominance on the d-file easily compensates for his weak pawn structure on the kingside. ½-½ @@StartBracket@@32@@EndBracket@@ Leitao,R @@StartBracket@@2620@@EndBracket@@-Morozevich,A  @@StartBracket@@2732@@EndBracket@@ Bursa 2010 }
15... Nb6
{ 15...fxe6?  is inferior due to,  16.Qxd7  Qc6  17.Qd3!  White will not exchange both his queen and rook because Black's king is weak and so is Black's pawn structure. I believe that practically it is going to be tough for Black to hold in this endgame. }
16. Qd4 { The point behind White's previous move. } 16... Rfc8
{ this is a better way to exchange queens. Black makes sure that his rook is activated in the process. }
17. Qxc3
{ 17.Rac1  leads to a straight draw after,  17...Qxc1  18.Qxf6  fxe6  19.Qxe6+  Kg7  20.Qe7+=  and the game ended in a perpetual. 1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@23@@EndBracket@@ Ipatov,A @@StartBracket@@2619@@EndBracket@@-Wojtaszek,R @@StartBracket@@2723@@EndBracket@@ Doha 2015 }
17... Rxc3 18. Nf4
{ this is the best square for the white knight. He intends to play Nf4-h5 next attacking the f6-pawn. The knight on h5 will be very uncomfortable for Black as we will always have to watch out for our f6-pawn.   18.Nd4?!  is not at all challenging as it is comfortably met by,  18...Rc4  Black is all set to win the important white pawn on e4.  19.Rfd1  Na4!  the strong threat of...Na4 forces White to move his knight from d4.  20.Nf5  Rxe4  Black has managed to win an important central pawn on  e4  . Now it is up to White to level the position with good moves.  21.Rac1  Re5  22.g4  Rc5!  A timely rook exchange before White penetrates with his rooks.  23.Rxc5  Nxc5  24.Rd6  Ne6  25.Rd7  and now the simplest way to continue is to play  25...Nc5  N   25...Rb8  1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@30@@EndBracket@@ Gajewski, G @@StartBracket@@2616@@EndBracket@@-Wojtaszek, R @@StartBracket@@2706@@EndBracket@@ Warsaw 2012  26.Rc7  b6  now Black is ready to tease the white rook with ...Ne6-c5 or ...Na6-c5. If the rook comes to e7 then Black has ...Kf8.  27.Nh6+  Kg7  28.Nxf7  Ne6  29.Rd7   29.Re7  Kf8=  Black is safe in this endgame.  29...Nc5=  and a draw by repetition is a logical result here. }
18... f5
{ A strong novelty! Black immediately gets rid of his weak pawn on f6. Again tactics come to our rescue.   18...Rc5  was played by Vishy. The idea is to play f6-f5 next. But why not do it straight away if possible?  19.g4!?  is an interesting try for White, not allowing Black to play f6-f5. White has some pressure because of Black's weak doubled pawns on the f-file. ½-½ @@StartBracket@@27@@EndBracket@@ Ponomariov,R @@StartBracket@@2758@@EndBracket@@-Morozevich,A @@StartBracket@@2737@@EndBracket@@ Saratov 2011   19.Rfd1  was Carlsen's choice which allowed Vishy to play the desirable break,  19...f5  and Vishy drew the game after some ups and downs. ½-½ @@StartBracket@@78@@EndBracket@@ Carlsen,M  @@StartBracket@@2875@@EndBracket@@-Anand,V @@StartBracket@@2767@@EndBracket@@ Zagreb CRO 2019@@EndBracket@@ }
19. exf5
{ 19.e5  is not dangerous for Black.  19...Re8  20.Rfe1  Rc5  forcing White to push the pawn,  21.e6  fxe6  22.Nxe6  Rc2=  and Black’s active rook compensates for his slightly weak kingside pawn structure. }
19... Rc5 20. Rfd1
{ 20.g4  saves the f5-pawn but loses the g4 one.  20...Rc4  21.Nh5  Rxg4+  22.Kh1  Kf8=  and Black is doing fine.   20.f6  Nd7!=  this is the main point behind playing f6-f5 immediately on the 18th move. Without White's rook on d1 Black gets a chance to play ...Nd7 and capture the f6 pawn with the knight. The black knight will be well placed on f6, keeping the f4 knight at bay. Once Black recaptures the f6 pawn he is ready to bring his a8-rook into play when the position remains equal. }
20... Rxf5 21. g3 Rc8
{ Now both the black rooks are active, which was not the case in the game between Carlsen and Vishy. Anand's f6 rook was passive which Carlsen exploited flawlessly to create problems one by one. But here with the rook actively placed on f5, Black always has a chance for counterplay. A sample variation could be, }
22. Rab1 Ra5 23. Rb2 Kf8 { improving the position of the king. } 24. Kg2 Rac5
{ intending to play ...Rc2. It is a good deal for Black to exchange a pair of rooks. }
25. Rb3 Rc2 26. a3 R2c3 { and this endgame is clearly level for both sides. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "21. Deviations to avoid the Benko 3.Nf3 cxd4 with 5.g3"]
[Black "Deviations to avoid the Benko with 6.Bd2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 { With ...c5 we invite White to enter the Benko Gambit! } 3.
Nf3 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e6
{ There are a lot of options for Black instead of 4...e6. But, I have chosen 4...e6 as the lines arising out of this variation gives Black a solid position. The idea of ...e6 is obvious- we want to play ...Bb4+ on the next move. }
5. g3 Bb4+ 6. Bd2
{ This is the most popular move in this exact position. Players with the white pieces generally avoid transposing to the Romanishin Variation with 6.Nc3. }
6... Bxd2+
{ There are various moves available at Black's disposal, but I recommend this move as is the easiest to learn and understand. 6...Qb6 is a major and reliable alternative. }
7. Nxd2
{ From the looks of it, it is pretty evident that this capture is passive compared to 8.Qd2. But it manages to avoid quick exchanges that results in the 8.Qd2 variation. In this structure the white knight should usually be on c3 exercising some control over the d5 square making it difficult for Black to achieve d7-d5 advance comfortably. But with the knight absent from the c3 square, a timely d7-d5 advance will solve all Black’s problems. }
7... Nc6 8. N2b3
{ 8.Nxc6  should be met by,  8...dxc6  9.Bg2  O-O  10.O-O  e5=  When Black is doing fine and the players agreed for a draw quickly in, ½-½ @@StartBracket@@13@@EndBracket@@ Gulko,B @@StartBracket@@2590@@EndBracket@@ -Vyzmanavin,A Moscow 1981 }
8... Qb6
{ A nice move. Black is delaying his 0-0 so that he can exploit White's uncoordinated forces. 8...Qb6 puts pressure on the d4 knight and also threatens to win the c4-pawn with Qb6-b4+. }
9. e3
{ Leko defends his c4-pawn with the bishop, but when White has to play such moves in the opening @@StartBracket@@g2-g3 and then e2-e3@@EndBracket@@, then we can safely say that Black’s opening strategy has triumphed.   9.Nc2  prevents ...Qb4 and was played in the game, when Black could have exerted more pressure on the queenside with the advance,  9...a5!  N and Black stands slightly better.   9...Ne4  1-0 @@StartBracket@@35@@EndBracket@@ Bagheri,A  @@StartBracket@@2486@@EndBracket@@-Toufighi,H @@StartBracket@@2386@@EndBracket@@ Teheran 2006@@EndBracket@@ }
9... O-O 10. Be2
{ It seems White is going to 0-0 next with a fine and playable position, but now Black missed a beautiful idea! }
10... e5
{ A very difficult idea to see especially when you have the comfortable 10...d5 move available. With 10...e5! Black wants to break with d7-d5 under more favourable circumstances.   10...d5  was fine for Black in, ½-½ @@StartBracket@@52@@EndBracket@@ Leko,P @@StartBracket@@2740@@EndBracket@@-Iturrizaga Bonelli,E @@StartBracket@@2653@@EndBracket@@ Tromsø 2014 }
11. Nb5
{ 11.Nxc6  dxc6  Black has simple yet powerful ideas like Bc8-h3 and a7-a5 followed a5-a4, when White has to suffer on both the sides. }
11... d5
{ now this break is stronger than on the previous move. The d-file is open and Black does not need to settle for an Isolated Queen’s Pawn. }
12. cxd5 Rd8 13. Nc3 Be6
{ Black’s pressure on the d5-pawn has reached its maximum limit and White cannot withstand it anymore. An important point in this line is that White cannot defend the d5-pawn anymore with, }
14. e4
{ 14.O-O  Nxd5  Black’s space advantage and better developed pieces give us a slight advantage in this position.   Black now strikes with, }
14... Nxe4 15. Nxe4 Bxd5
{ White's pieces are hanging and his last attempt to hold the position together with, }
16. Qb1 { falls short to, } 16... Qb4+
{ Black regains his piece with interest. } *

