[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "21. Deviations to avoid the Benko 3.Nf3 cxd4 with 5.g3"]
[Black "Deviations to avoid the Benko 6.Nc3 with 8.O-O #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 { With ...c5 we invite White to enter the Benko Gambit! } 3.
Nf3 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e6
{ There are a lot of options for Black instead of 4...e6. But, I have chosen 4...e6 as the lines arising out of this variation gives Black a solid position. The idea of ...e6 is obvious- we want to play ...Bb4+ on the next move. }
5. g3 Bb4+ 6. Nc3
{ With this move we enter the Romanishin variation of the Nimzo-Indian. I don't find the Romanishin variation very challenging to play against. With decent knowledge of the lines that we are going to study in this chapter, you can confidently play against this variation. }
6... O-O 7. Bg2 d5
{ This is the mainline against the Romanishin variation with over 1000 games played in it. Black immediately breaks in the centre and also hopes to put pressure on the pinned knight on c3 with subsequent moves. White now needs to address to our question that we posed to the c4-pawn. }
8. O-O
{ White sacrifices the c4-pawn in order to gain initiative based on the pressure on the h1-a8 diagonal. He hopes to regain the c4 later. }
8... dxc4 9. Qa4
{ The queen comes out attacking the bishop on b4 and frees the d1 square for the rook at the same time. }
9... Na6 { developing as well as supporting the bishop. } 10. Rd1
{ is another logical move. White brings his rook in action and threatens discovered attack with his knight on d4. }
10... Bd7 { kicking the queen back from its active square. } 11. Qc2 Qb6 12.
Bg5 Be7
{ A simple novelty that prevents our pawn structure from getting ruined on the kingside. Black just needs two moves to bring his rook out into play when we will simply be a pawn up. White needs to act quickly, so he can try,   12...Rfd8  1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@36@@EndBracket@@ Artemiev, V @@StartBracket@@2746@@EndBracket@@-So, W @@StartBracket@@2767@@EndBracket@@ chess.com INT 2019 }
13. Nf5 exf5 14. Bxf6 Bxf6 15. Rxd7 Nc5
{ Most probably White will manage to win his pawn back @@StartBracket@@the c4-pawn@@EndBracket@@, but Black’s pieces are well developed and the position remains equal. }
