5. g3 Bb4+ 6. Nc3
{ With this move we enter the Romanishin variation of the Nimzo-Indian. I don't find the Romanishin variation very challenging to play against. With decent knowledge of the lines that we are going to study in this chapter, you can confidently play against this variation. }
6... O-O 7. Bg2 d5
{ This is the mainline against the Romanishin variation with over 1000 games played in it. Black immediately breaks in the centre and also hopes to put pressure on the pinned knight on c3 with subsequent moves. White now needs to address to our question that we posed to the c4-pawn. }
