1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 { With ...c5 we invite White to enter the Benko Gambit! } 3.
Nf3 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e6
{ There are a lot of options for Black instead of 4...e6. But, I have chosen 4...e6 as the lines arising out of this variation gives Black a solid position. The idea of ...e6 is obvious- we want to play ...Bb4+ on the next move. }
5. g3 Bb4+ 6. Nc3
{ With this move we enter the Romanishin variation of the Nimzo-Indian. I don't find the Romanishin variation very challenging to play against. With decent knowledge of the lines that we are going to study in this chapter, you can confidently play against this variation. }
6... O-O 7. Bg2 d5
{ This is the mainline against the Romanishin variation with over 1000 games played in it. Black immediately breaks in the centre and also hopes to put pressure on the pinned knight on c3 with subsequent moves. White now needs to address to our question that we posed to the c4-pawn. }
8. Nc2
{ this is an interesting move tried by Yu Yangyi in his crucial 10th round of the Qatar Master 2015 against So Wesley and managed to score an important victory. The idea here is quite similar to 8.Qb3, forcing Black to exchange on c3. But, comparatively this is slightly passive. }
8... Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 Qc7
{ 9...dxc4?!  10.Ba3  Re8  11.Qxd8  Rxd8  12.Ne3  gives White an initiative. }
10. cxd5 Nxd5 11. Nb4
{ this is an interesting idea of this line. White sacrifices his c3-pawn hoping to gain some initiative in return. }
11... Qxc3+
{ this is the right capture for Black.   11...Nxc3  12.Qc2  Nd5  13.Qxc7  Nxc7  14.Bf4  offers White a strong compensation for the exchange due to his pressure on the queenside.   11...Nxb4  was Wesley's choice in his game against Yu. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@77@@EndBracket@@ Yu, Y @@StartBracket@@2736@@EndBracket@@-So, W @@StartBracket@@2775@@EndBracket@@ Doha 2015 }
12. Bd2 Qf6
{ This novelty is the correct retreat of the queen as it is well placed on f6. We have won a pawn and now the only mission is to complete our queenside development.   12...Qc5?!  was the choice of Ponomariov against Mamedyarov in Budva, 2019. After,  13.Rc1  Qb5  14.a4!  White gained some pressure on the queenside and managed to convert it into a full point. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@50@@EndBracket@@ Mamedyarov,S @@StartBracket@@2772@@EndBracket@@-Ponomariov,R @@StartBracket@@2648@@EndBracket@@ Budva MNE 2019 }
13. O-O { is met by, } 13... Nxb4 14. Bxb4 Rd8 15. Qc2 e5
{ preparing to play Nb8-c6 with a fine position for Black.   15...Nc6  is inferior due to,  16.Bxc6  bxc6  17.Ba5!  followed by capturing the c6-pawn and creating some problems. Though the position remains close to equal. }
