{ Black has developed his pieces optimally. } 15. Rb1 b6 16. Nd5 Bc5
{ Even though White has managed to stabilize his knight on d5, the knight is not doing much there. Black can play around this knight on d5. Moreover, White's pawn structure on the queenside is weak. One of Black's main ideas in this position is to play f7-f5 and e5-e4 in order to shut the bishop on g2 and gain space in the centre. }
17. e3 Qd7 18. Bc3 Rfd8 { all Black’s pieces are well placed. } 19. Qe2
{ Vacating the d1-square for White's rook. } 19... Bg4
{ A nice move, provoking f2-f3 which will weaken White's structure. } 20. Bf3
{ White settles for the exchange of the light-squared bishops, but it clear that it is Black who is going to benefit from this exchange as White's light-squared bishop is an important piece covering the light squares on the kingside. }
20... h5 21. Rbd1 Bxf3 22. Qxf3 Qg4
{ and Black was already enjoying a slight advantage in the game: 0-1 @@StartBracket@@33@@EndBracket@@ Adhiban,B @@StartBracket@@2659@@EndBracket@@ -Yu Yangyi @@StartBracket@@2709@@EndBracket@@ chess.com INT 2020 }
