[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "21. Deviations to avoid the Benko 3.Nf3 cxd4 with 5.g3"]
[Black "Deviations to avoid the Benko 6.Nc3 with 8.cxd5 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 { With ...c5 we invite White to enter the Benko Gambit! } 3.
Nf3 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e6
{ There are a lot of options for Black instead of 4...e6. But, I have chosen 4...e6 as the lines arising out of this variation gives Black a solid position. The idea of ...e6 is obvious- we want to play ...Bb4+ on the next move. }
5. g3 Bb4+ 6. Nc3
{ With this move we enter the Romanishin variation of the Nimzo-Indian. I don't find the Romanishin variation very challenging to play against. With decent knowledge of the lines that we are going to study in this chapter, you can confidently play against this variation. }
6... O-O 7. Bg2 d5
{ This is the mainline against the Romanishin variation with over 1000 games played in it. Black immediately breaks in the centre and also hopes to put pressure on the pinned knight on c3 with subsequent moves. White now needs to address to our question that we posed to the c4-pawn. }
8. cxd5 { By far the most popular move in this position. } 8... Nxd5
{ Now White has to two ways to defend the knight on c3. Bc1-d2 or Qd1-b3. Both the options are equally popular among White players. }
9. Qb3 Qb6
{ This is the 3rd most popular move, but I believe it is quite easy to learn and understand. We not only attack the knight on d4 but also threaten to win a pawn with ....Bxc3+. With both queens standing in front of each other, the exchange of queens is highly probable transposing into a queenless endgame. }
10. Nc2
{ loses a pawn for White, but he gets some compensation for it because of his strong bishop on g2. }
10... Bxc3+ { Our secondary idea winning a pawn for us. } 11. bxc3 Qxb3 12.
axb3 Nxc3 13. Nb4
{ This is the best move for White covering the d5 square and preventing ... Nd5. Next White would like to push our knight on c3 back with Bc1-b2.   13.Bb2  allows Black to block the diagonal with,  13...Nd5=  which makes it easy for Black to develop his queenside pieces. The position remains close to equal as White has some compensation for the pawn. ½-½ @@StartBracket@@59@@EndBracket@@ Korobov,A @@StartBracket@@2715@@EndBracket@@-Efimenko, Z @@StartBracket@@2651@@EndBracket@@ Kiev 2013 }
13... a5
{ this is an interesting novelty. We create some space for our pieces on the queenside, especially the a8-rook. A sample variation could be,   13...Nd7  1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@43@@EndBracket@@ Theodorou,N @@StartBracket@@2554@@EndBracket@@-Martirosyan,H @@StartBracket@@2622@@EndBracket@@ chess. com INT 2020 }
14. Bb2 Nb5 15. O-O Ra7
{ a nice way to protect our rook and threaten the b4-knight. } 16. Nd3 b6
{ Black plans Bc8-b7 next challenging White's strong g2-bishop. White still has some compensation but it is sufficient only for an equality and not more than that. Black is fine. }
