[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nf3 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e6 5. Nc3 Bb4
{ Now White has 3 major moves in this position and all are different ways to support the knight on c3. }
6. Nb5
{ The knight on d4 finds an active way of supporting its colleague on c3. From b5, the knight also eyes on the d6 and the c7 squares and can get support from the bishop on c1 coming to f4. }
6... d5
{ This is the accurate move order going for the break immediately and not allowing White to play a2-a3.   6...O-O  is possible. White goes for  7.a3  Bxc3+  8.Nxc3  and after  8...d5  , Black is doing fine. }
7. Bf4
{ A very attractive move for White, developing as well as giving a threat! But Black simply ignore it with, }
7... O-O { Cool as cucumber! } 8. Nc7
{ is refuted by two consecutive strong moves! } 8... Ne4
{ The knight on c3 is insufficiently protected. } 9. Nxa8
{ 9.Rc1  d4-+  is just crushing! There are numerous ways for Black to win after this move!   9.Qc1  loses to  g5!-+ }
9... Qf6
{ A powerful move! The arrival of the black queen in action spells death for White. Both ...Qf4 and ...Bc3+ are huge threats now.   9...Nxc3?  is not the correct way to go ahead.  10.bxc3  Bxc3+  11.Bd2  Bxa1  12.Qxa1  and the position remains unclear as it may not be so easy to trap the knight on a8. }
10. Qc2 Qxf4 11. e3 Qe5 12. Rc1 Nc6
{ the pressure on the c3 knight is still maintained, while the brave white knight is now lonely on the a8 square and will be soon trapped. }
