[White "22. Deviations to avoid the Benko 3.Nf3 cxd4 with 5.Nc3"]
[Black "Deviations to avoid Benko 5.Nc3 with 6.Qb3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nf3 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e6 5. Nc3 Bb4
{ Now White has 3 major moves in this position and all are different ways to support the knight on c3. }
6. Qb3
{ White attacks the b4-bishop and supports the knight on c3 at the same time, but the queen itself is oddly placed on b3. Moreover, it withdraws the support of the knight on d4 which Black can use to gain tempo. }
6... Bc5
{ The bishop is decently placed on c5 for now. Black now intends to develop his with ...b6, ...Bb7. The knight on b8 can be developed to either a6 or c6 according to the situation. }
7. Nf3 b6 8. Bf4 Bb7 9. e3 O-O 10. Rd1 { playing against the ...d5 break. }
10... Nc6 11. Be2 Nh5
{ a strong idea forcing White to exchange the dark-squared bishop. } 12. Bd6
Bxd6 13. Rxd6 Qe7 14. Rd1
{ White can also try to maintain his rook on d6 with   14.Qd1  White also threatens to capture the d7-pawn now.  14...Nf6  This is a good time to retreat the knight which was not doing much on edge of the board anyway.  15.O-O  Rac8  16.b3  protecting the c4-pawn before it gets attacked.   16.Qd2  with the idea to play Rd1, allows Black to win an exchange with  16...Na5  17.b3  Bd5!  =+  though White will have some compensation for the exchange, Black will be in the driver's seat.  16...Nb4  threatening to cut the communication between White's queen and his rook by playing ...Nbd5.  17.e4!?  using the fact that the d7-pawn will be hanging if Black decides to capture on e4 twice.   17.Rd2  may give Black a slight initiative after  17...d5  18.a3  Na6=+  When Black has a slight pressure on the queenside.  17...Rfd8  the simplest solution. Protecting the d7-pawn and threatening to capture the e4-pawn.   17...Nbd5  is possible too but after  18.Rxd5  exd5  19.exd5=∞  White gets some compensation for the exchange as our bishop is locked on b7.  18.e5  Ne8  19.Rd2  and now we go for our desirable break -  19...d5! =  with a completely fine position for Black. }
14... Nf6 15. O-O Na5
{ Black can follow up with ...Rfc8 or ...Rac8 and then d7-d5 with an equal position. }
