{ Now White has 3 major moves in this position and all are different ways to support the knight on c3. }
6. Bd2 Nc6 7. e3
{ This is the most popular move for White, but also very easy to meet. White supports his d4-knight and prepares to develop his bishop, but he does nothing to play against Black's main idea d7-d5. As Black we should simply go for this break.   7.Nxc6  does not make sense as after,  7...dxc6  followed by e6-e5 Black gets a comfortable position. }
7... O-O 8. Be2 { Black should straight away go for the desired, } 8... d5
{ Black is ready to exchange pieces and pawns in the centre. } 9. cxd5 Nxd4
{ A typical intermediate response. } 10. exd4 Nxd5
{ we have entered a better version of the IQP for Black and few more exchanges can be expected soon which is in our Black's favour. }
11. Nxd5 Bxd2+ 12. Qxd2 Qxd5 13. Bf3 Qb5 14. a4 Qa6
