4... cxd4 5. exd4 d5 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Be2 O-O 8. O-O Nc6
{ White has tried various moves here. I have analysed the most critical variations briefly for your reference. }
9. h3
{ White covers the g4 square. Now Black gets to show one of typical plans in this structure. }
9... dxc4 10. Bxc4 Na5 11. Bd3 Be6
{ this is a nice way of developing our light-squared bishop. We plan to play ...Rc8 followed by ...Bc4 next. }
12. Re1 Rc8 13. Bg5 Bc4
{ every exchange favours Black as we are playing against the Isolated Queen’s Pawn. Black is doing fine in this position. 1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@41@@EndBracket@@ Epishin,V @@StartBracket@@2613@@EndBracket@@-Zvjaginsev, V @@StartBracket@@2641@@EndBracket@@ St Petersburg 2009 }
