[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "23. Deviations to avoid the Benko 3.dxc5 and 3.e3"]
[Black "Deviations to avoid the Benko 3.e3 with 4.Nf3 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. e3
{ White avoids playing d4-d5 immediately and thus prevent us from playing the Benko. At the same time with 3.e3 White does not aim to fight a direct advantage. }
3... g6
{ There are many satisfactory ways for Black to deal with 3.e3, but I want to recommend a setup with our bishop on g7 as this is how we are going to play in the Benko as well. At the same time, I wanted to avoid entering the Benoni structure which is a completely different territory altogether. So, this is our strategy:- We want to fianchetto our dark-squared bishop on g7. Then we want to exchange on d4 with cxd4 and when White recaptures with exd4 we want to play ...d5. Once we get this, we will more or less end up playing the Isolated Queen’s Pawn on d4. Against the IQP a Fianchetto set-up is considered to be the best and that is what we have already done. }
4. Nf3
{ this is an inferior move-order for White as it allows us to reach a comfortable set-up with, }
4... cxd4 5. exd4 d5 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. cxd5
{ White immediately exchanges on d5 so that he could develop his bishop on c4 with tempo.   We are in time to meet  7.Qb3  with  7...dxc4  8.Bxc4  O-O=  with a good position for Black. }
7... Nxd5 8. Bb5+
{ does not create any problems for Black. We can simply play, } 8... Nc6
{ and if White tries to create pressure with, } 9. Qa4 { then we can safely, }
9... O-O 10. Bxc6 Nb6
{ next move we can recapture on c6 with a slightly better position. If White sticks to his extra pawn with, }
11. Qb5 { then after } 11... bxc6 12. Qxc6 Ba6
{ Black gets a winning advantage. } *

