{ the d6-pawn is now under firm protection and now it is time the kick back the white pieces. We intend to play ...Bd7 next kicking the b5-knight. }
15. a4 { gaining some space on the queenside and stabilizing the b5-knight. }
15... Bd7 16. Nbxd6 { falls short due to tactics. } 16... Bxd6 17. Nxd6 Nxd6
18. Bxd6 Bxa4 { wins material for Black. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "23. Deviations to avoid the Benko 3.dxc5 and 3.e3"]
[Black "Deviations to avoid the Benko 3.e3 with 4.Nc3 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. e3
{ White avoids playing d4-d5 immediately and thus prevent us from playing the Benko. At the same time with 3.e3 White does not aim to fight a direct advantage. }
3... g6
{ There are many satisfactory ways for Black to deal with 3.e3, but I want to recommend a setup with our bishop on g7 as this is how we are going to play in the Benko as well. At the same time, I wanted to avoid entering the Benoni structure which is a completely different territory altogether. So, this is our strategy:- We want to fianchetto our dark-squared bishop on g7. Then we want to exchange on d4 with cxd4 and when White recaptures with exd4 we want to play ...d5. Once we get this, we will more or less end up playing the Isolated Queen’s Pawn on d4. Against the IQP a Fianchetto set-up is considered to be the best and that is what we have already done. }
4. Nc3
{ this is the best move order for White to play against our intended set-up. White also plans to play d4-d5 when Black can no longer play ...b5 and enter the Benko because the knight on c3 already covers the b5 square. Once White plays d4-d5 we enter the Benoni Set-up which I want to avoid getting into. So, I am recommending a very fresh way of playing here with not many games played in it.   4.d5  allows us to transpose to the Benko Gambit by playing,  4...b5  and after,  5.cxb5  a6  we transpose to Chapter  15. }
4... cxd4
{ 4...Bg7  5.d5  Now Black will sooner or later break in the centre with ...e6 when we enter the Benoni Setup. }
5. exd4 Bg7
{ now we are all set to play d7-d5.   5...d5  as mentioned earlier in the notes to Black's 3rd move, is not ideal for us in this position because White has the annoying  6.Qb3!  and we don't have time to exchange on c4 and 0-0. }
6. d5
{ White gains space in the centre and prevents us from achieving our intended set-up after d7-d5. }
6... O-O 7. Nf3 e6
{ We challenge White's centre and prepare to open the e-file. } 8. Be2 exd5 9.
cxd5 d6 10. O-O
{ both sides have completed their kingside development and it is time to talk about strategy here. First of all, there are only 4 games played until now in my database so this position is quite fresh. Now if we assess this position we can see that White has more space in the centre because of his pawn on d5. The drawback of this is that the a1-h8 diagonal is open and our bishop on g7 is well placed to put pressure on it. Our main strategy is to manoeuvre our knight to c5 via d7. With a knight on c5, we always have the option of playing ...Nfe4 challenging the knight on c3 thus enhancing the pressure of the bishop on g7. Our rook on f8 goes to e8 controlling the e-file and next our idea can be to play ...Bd7 followed by ...Rc8. The only two open files in this position are the e- and c-files, so it is logical to place both our rooks on these open files.   Since there are very few games here, I have analysed this position and presented to you some sample variations for your reference. }
10... Nbd7 11. Bf4 Nc5 12. Nd2
{ White covers the e4 square and also plans to play Nd2-c4 putting pressure on the d6-pawn. }
12... Re8 13. Nc4 Nfe4 14. Nb5 Bf8
{ the d6-pawn is now under firm protection and now it is time the kick back the white pieces. We intend to play ...Bd7 next kicking the b5-knight. }
15. a4 { gaining some space on the queenside and stabilizing the b5-knight. }
15... Bd7 16. Be3 a6 17. Nbxd6
{ Now we enter a forcing variation which ultimately leads to an equal endgame. }
17... Nxd6 18. Bxc5 Nxc4 19. Bxf8 Nxb2 20. Qd4 Rxf8 21. Qxb2 b5
{ This endgame is just equal. } *

