[Round "?"]
[White "24. Benko Gambit Declined: Sideline 4.Nd2"]
[Black "Benko Gambit Declined 4.Nd2 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. Nd2 { White prepares e2-e4. } 4... bxc4 5. e4 e6
{ Our age-old strategy of breaking in the centre.   5...c3  6.bxc3  g6  is the most popular way of playing here. }
6. dxe6
{ This capture is not good for White if he has already committed his pawn to e4 as the d4 square is weak. }
6... dxe6
{ This seems to be a slightly counter-intuitive recapture compared to the normal recapture with the f-pawn. dxe6 is good in this position because White has already committed his pawn to e4 which weakens the d4-square and Black can exploit it by playing Nc6-d4. Thus, opening the d-file is good for us as it adds more control on the d4 square. }
7. Bxc4 Bb7
{ This position is very similar to one of the lines in the 4.Nf3 variation. }
8. Ngf3
{ Provoking to capture on e4.   8.Qe2  is the main move here which will soon transpose to 8.Ngf3 line.  8...Nc6  9.Ngf3  Be7  10.O-O  O-O  transposes. }
8... Nc6
{ It is better to develop our knight on c6 than d7 so that we can exploit the weak d4-square.   8...Nxe4??  is a blunder due to,  9.Qa4+!  Nd7   9...Bc6  10.Bb5+-  wins a piece for White straight away.  10.Nxe4  Bxe4  11.Bf4+-  with the idea to 0-0-0 next, when the d7 knight will come under pressure and the black king will be stuck in the centre. }
9. O-O Be7 10. Qe2 O-O 11. e5 Nd7
{ we want to create pressure on the e5-pawn. } 12. Re1 Qc7 13. Bd3
{ The bishop is well placed on the b1-h7 diagonal. White also frees the c4-square for the knight in order to give good protection to the e5-pawn. }
13... Rad8 14. Nc4 Nb6 15. b3 Nxc4 16. Bxc4 Rd7
{ With the idea to play ...Rfd8 next. White has not been able to create any threats on the kingside as the pawn on e5 has constantly been under pressure. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "24. Benko Gambit Declined: Sideline 4.Nd2"]
[Black "Benko Gambit Declined 4.Nd2 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. Nd2 { White prepares e2-e4. } 4... bxc4 5. e4 e6
{ Our age-old strategy of breaking in the centre.   5...c3  6.bxc3  g6  is the most popular way of playing here. }
6. Bxc4 exd5 7. exd5 d6 8. Ne2
{ Keeping both white knights flexible.  8.Ngf3?!  does not make sense as both white knights get in the way of each other. }
8... Be7 9. O-O O-O 10. b3
{ 10.Nc3  Nbd7  11.Re1  hoping to create some pressure down the e-file. We continue our plan,   11.b3  Nb6  12.Bb2  transposes  11...Nb6  12.b3  Re8  Black gets ready to neutralize the pressure on the e-file. Now after,  13.Bb2  Nxc4   13...Bf8  1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@21@@EndBracket@@ Loifenfeld, J @@StartBracket@@2413@@EndBracket@@ -Scheider, J @@StartBracket@@2306@@EndBracket@@ Germany 2018  14.Nxc4  Ba6  we transpose to the mainline. }
10... Nbd7
{ It is important to place our knight on b6 first from where it puts pressure on the d5-pawn and the c4-bishop. We see this same manoeuvre in the 4. Qc2 variation as well. }
11. Bb2 Nb6 12. Nf4
{ By placing the knight on f4 instead of c3 White hopes to create some pressure on the kingside. }
12... Ne8
{ This is the simplest way for Black to continue. We intend to play ...Bf6 challenging White's dark-squared bishop and neutralizing any future pressure on the a1-h8 diagonal. }
13. Nh5
{ This prevents our plan of ...Bf6 and hopes to induce some weaknesses on our kingside. But we can safely play, }
13... g6 14. Ng3 Bf6 15. Bxf6 Nxf6 16. Qf3 a5
{ Creating counterplay on the queenside. I believe the position is balanced here and Black has good play on the queenside. }
*

