[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "25. Benko Gambit Declined: Sideline 4.a4"]
[Black "Benko Gambit Declined 4.a4 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. a4 Qa5+
{ I am a big fan of this intermediate move before closing the queenside with ...b4. Once we close the queenside with ...b4 White would like to fianchetto his bishop with b2-b3 and Bc1-b2. However, by interposing ...Qa5+ we provoke him to play Bd2 which misplaces his bishop and he cannot fianchetto anymore.   4...bxc4  5.Nc3  d6  6.e4  g6  is the main way to go here. }
5. Bd2
{ 5.Nd2?  is very bad because of,  5...bxc4  the d5-pawn is hanging and White cannot even play e4 because Black will simply capture the e4-pawn as well.   5.Nc3?!  simply hands over a free move to Black after,  5...b4  6.Nb1  g6   5.Qd2?  is also bad due to,  5...Qxd2+  6.Nxd2  bxc4  7.e4  e6!  this compels White to surrender his centre, otherwise, after ...exd5 White will be saddled with a weak pawn on d5.  8.dxe6  fxe6  9.Bxc4  Bb7  10.f3  d5-+  and Black a very strong initiative as White is far behind in development! }
5... b4
{ Now we close the queenside. Our plan is very simple. We want to go ...g6, ...d6, ...Bg7 and then 0-0. Once this is done we can think whether to close the centre with ... e5 and start playing on the kingside @@StartBracket@@this is usually done when White has already castled on the kingside@@EndBracket@@ or we can play ...e6 and open up the centre. }
6. Qc2 { White prepares e2-e4. } 6... g6 7. e4 d6 { Preventing e4-e5. } 8. Bd3
Bg7 9. h3 O-O 10. Nf3 Qc7
{ A good waiting move. The queen was not doing anything on a5 so it makes sense to bring it back. We are waiting for White to 0-0 so that we can play ...e5, close the centre and then start playing on the kingside just like in the style of king's Indian Defence. }
11. O-O e5
{ The correct strategy! It might seem a counter-intuitive move closing the diagonal of our strong dark-squared bishop, but our main point is that we want to close the centre and start creating an attack on the kingside. This structure is quite similar to the King's Indian Defence, though, with one big difference - White does not have his traditional counter-play on the queenside as it closed here. So, it is just a one way attack for Black on the kingside. }
12. dxe6 { makes things even worse, as, } 12... fxe6 13. Be3
{ White vacates the d2-square for his knight. One important point to mention is that we should not be worried about moves like  13.e5  , with the aim to ruin our pawn structure because after  13...dxe5  we not only win a pawn but it also enhances our control of the d4-square and our knight is soon going to reach there via c6. Additionally, the h1-a8 diagonal opens up which can be another headache for White. }
13... e5
{ With the idea to play ... Nc6-Ne4 Black's stronghold on the d4 square gives him a clear advantage at the least. 0-1 @@StartBracket@@47@@EndBracket@@ Norlin,E @@StartBracket@@2125@@EndBracket@@-Englert,F  @@StartBracket@@2316@@EndBracket@@ Stockholm 2014 }
*

