[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "26. Benko Gambit Declined: Sideline 4.f3"]
[Black "Benko Gambit Declined 4.f3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. f3
{ I used to play this variation in my childhood against the Benko. White prepares for e2-e4 but by playing f2-f3 he takes away the most natural f3-square from his g1 knight. }
4... bxc4 5. e4 d6
{ We prevent e4-e5 and now our plan is very straightforward. We want to go ...g6-Bg7 and then 0-0. }
6. Ne2
{ White first puts his knight on c3 and then will decide whether to capture on c4 with the bishop or with the knight. }
6... g6 7. Nec3 Bg7 8. Na3 { 8.Bxc4  O-O  9.O-O  transposes to the mainline. }
8... O-O 9. Nxc4 Ba6
{ Placing the bishop on a6 always gives us the option of exchanging on c4. }
10. Be2 Nbd7 11. O-O Rb8
{ Our rook is very useful on the b-file. Right now, it ties the c1 bishop to the defence of the b2-pawn. }
12. Qc2
{ gives Black an opportunity to showcase one of his main ideas in this position. We play, }
12... Bxc4
{ This exchange paves the way for our knight to come in the centre. } 13. Bxc4
Ne5 14. Be2 c4
{ The point of previous exchange. We are ready to sacrifice a pawn by playing ...Nd3. }
15. Be3
{ Preventing ...Qb6+.   15.f4  Qb6+  16.Kh1  Nd3  17.Bxd3  cxd3  18.Qxd3  Nd7  with ...Rfc8 coming next, Black has huge pressure on the queenside. }
15... Qa5
{ With the idea to play ...Rfc8 and ... Nfd7 Black is doing good here. We should think of playing ...Nd3 at the correct moment. }
*

