6... g6 7. Nec3 Bg7 8. Na3 { 8.Bxc4  O-O  9.O-O  transposes to the mainline. }
8... O-O 9. Nxc4 Ba6
{ Placing the bishop on a6 always gives us the option of exchanging on c4. }
10. Be2 Nbd7 11. O-O Rb8
{ Our rook is very useful on the b-file. Right now, it ties the c1 bishop to the defence of the b2-pawn. }
12. Rb1 Bxc4
{ The start of a nice tactical operation...   12...Ng4  0-1 @@StartBracket@@41@@EndBracket@@ Montenegro,E @@StartBracket@@1986@@EndBracket@@-Ramirez,A @@StartBracket@@2576@@EndBracket@@ San Jose 2012 }
13. Bxc4 Ng4 { A nice tactical idea threatening ...Bxc3 and ...Bd4+. } 14. Qc2
Bd4+ 15. Kh1 Nde5 { No coming back, only forward! } 16. Bb5 Qa5 17. a4 a6
{ Another fine counter-attacking move, finally forcing White to capture on g4. }
18. fxg4 axb5 19. Nxb5 Rxb5 20. axb5 Qxb5
{ Black has an amazing compensation for the exchange! Our bishop and knight have owned the d4 and e5 squares, respectively. Our rook is going to join the action on the queenside by coming to the b8-square, putting pressure on the b2-pawn. On top of that it is easy to note that White's pawn structure is weak. }
