[White "26. Benko Gambit Declined: Sideline 4.f3"]
[Black "Benko Gambit Declined 4.f3 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. f3
{ I used to play this variation in my childhood against the Benko. White prepares for e2-e4 but by playing f2-f3 he takes away the most natural f3-square from his g1 knight. }
4... bxc4 5. e4 d6
{ We prevent e4-e5 and now our plan is very straightforward. We want to go ...g6-Bg7 and then 0-0. }
6. Bxc4 { 6.Na3  g6  7.Nxc4  Bg7  8.Ne2  O-O  9.Nc3  transposes. } 6... g6 7.
Ne2 Bg7 8. O-O O-O 9. Nec3
{ White wants to put one knight on c3, hoping to manoeuvre the other knight to c4 in the future. }
9... Nbd7 10. a4 Ne8
{ Bringing the knight to c7 is one of the typical manoeuvres for Black in this structure. }
11. Na3 Nc7 12. f4 Rb8
{ We would like to place our rook on the weak b4-square. } 13. Nab5 Nxb5
{ 13...a6  is risky due to,  14.Na7  Bb7  15.Nc6  Bxc6  dxc6  Nb6  17.Ba2  and White might get some attack on the kingside. }
14. axb5 Rb7 15. Be3 Nb6 16. Be2 f5
{ A crucial break for Black after which we are doing fine. Our pawn on a7 is weak but it can easily be defended by our major pieces. White should always keep attention on the b5-pawn by keeping it supported and after the break with ...f5 the d5-pawn also needs care. At some point, Black can also think about the ...e6 break. }
