1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. Nf3
{ White develops his knight and waits for Black to capture on c4. Once Black captures on c4 then White will play Nc3 followed by e4. }
4... Bb7
{ We in turn develop our bishop and put pressure on the d5-pawn which adds more value to the e7-e6 break. At the same time 4...Bb7 is a waiting move as well, not allowing White to develop his other knight to c3 immediately as it will be kicked with b5-b4.   4...bxc4  allows White to develop freely with,  5.Nc3  followed by e4 and then Bc4. }
5. Qc2 { Second most popular move. White prepares the e2-e4 advance. } 5...
bxc4 6. e4 e6
{ It is important to hit in the centre when White is unable to support it firmly. }
7. dxe6 dxe6
{ This seems to be a slightly counter-intuitive recapture compared to the normal recapture with the f-pawn. dxe6 is good in this position because White has already committed his pawn to e4 which weakens the d4-square and Black can exploit it by playing Nc6-d4. Thus, opening the d-file is good for us as it adds more control on the d4 square. }
8. Nc3
{ 8.e5?  Nfd7  is bad for White as the e5-pawn becomes a huge target.   8...Nd5  0-1 @@StartBracket@@31@@EndBracket@@ Thompson,B @@StartBracket@@1898@@EndBracket@@-Zhu,J Mesa 2010@@EndBracket@@ }
8... Be7 9. Bxc4 O-O 10. O-O Nc6
{ Black is already slightly better in this position because of the weakness of the d4 square. We can further move our queen to c7 or a5 and easily bring our rooks in the game. If white tries to expand with, }
11. e5 { then we can simply continue with } 11... Nd5 12. Rd1 Ncb4
{ Attacking the white queen as well as supporting its colleague on d5. } 13.
Qe2 Nxc3 14. bxc3 Nd5 { Black has managed to place another knight on d5. } 15.
Bd2 Qc7
{ Our knight is very well placed on d5 and next we can bring our rook on the d-file.½-½ @@StartBracket@@62@@EndBracket@@ Hoeksema, H @@StartBracket@@2331@@EndBracket@@-Zaragatski,I @@StartBracket@@2499@@EndBracket@@ Netherlands 2017 }
