5. a4
{ White forces Black to make a decision on the queenside so that it would be clear for him to develop the knight on c3 or on d2.   5.Nc3?!  does not make sense as we simply kick the knight with,  5...b4  6.Na4  d6  followed by ... g6-Bg7 and 0-0 when we get a better version of the mainline as here the white knight is stranded on a4.   On  5.e3  we simply continue with,  5...g6  followed by ...Bg7 and 0-0. White has to make a decision on the queenside at some point. Otherwise, it will be difficult for him to develop normally. }
5... Qa5+
{ This is a nice intermediate move before playing b5-b4. We would like to lure the white bishop to d2 first before going for b5-b4. The point behind this is that White will have to waste one more move with his dark-squared bishop in order to free the d2 square for his b1 knight. Another point is that White will not be able to fianchetto his dark-squared bishop with b2-b3 and Bc1-Bb2. Thus, our dark-squared bishop will be unopposed on the a1-h8 diagonal. }
6. Bd2 b4
{ Now we can see that the bishop is misplaced on d2 and its place belongs on the b2-square. Our main plan now is quite simple. We want to play ...d6-Nbd7-g6-Bg7-0-0 and then play e7-e5. Once we do this then we get a better version of the King's Indian as the queenside is closed here and White lacks his traditional counterplay on the queenside. }
7. Qc2 d6 8. e4 Nbd7 9. Bd3 g6 10. O-O Bg7 11. h3
{ White prevents ... Ng4-Ne5 ideas. } 11... O-O
{ 11...O-O-O  is  also an interesting alternative when the king is quite safe on the queenside and we can focus exclusively on the kingside. }
12. Bf4
{ This looks like a logical follow-up as h2-h3 has created a square for White's dark-squared bishop on h2. We can still get in our desired ...e5 advance by force with, }
12... Nh5 13. Bh2 e5
{ With this pawn advance we achieve our strategic aim and lock in White's dark-squared bishop on  h2  at the same time. It is important to note that White cannot capture the d6-pawn after  14.dxe6  fxe6  15.Bxd6?  because of the strong exchange sacrifice  15...Rxf3!  16.gxf3  Ne5-+  when we get a crushing attack on the kingside.   You can find this game in the Model games section where I analysed the remaining moves of the game. 1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@21@@EndBracket@@ Brunello,S @@StartBracket@@2573@@EndBracket@@-Swapnil,S @@StartBracket@@2418@@EndBracket@@ Chennai 2015 }
