[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "28. Benko Gambit Declined: Mainline 4.Qc2"]
[Black "Benko Gambit Declined 4.Qc2 with 6.Nc3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. Qc2
{ White develops his queen not to support the c4-pawn but to prepare the pawn advance e2-e4. }
4... bxc4 5. e4
{ 5.Qxc4?  is of course not White's idea as the queen is misplaced on c4.  5...e6  6.e4  exd5  7.exd5  Na6!  a strong move, the knight aims to go to b4 or c7 and put pressure on the d5-pawn. We can clearly see the drawback of having the queen on c4, the pawn on d5 lacks sufficient support.  8.a3   8.Nc3  Nb4  9.Qb3  Qa5!  10.Bd2  Ba6  and Black gets a strong initiative.  8...Nc7  9.Nc3  Bb7  White simply loses the d5-pawn. It makes no difference if White pins the f6-knight with  10.Bg5  as Black can still grab the pawn with  10...Ncxd5  11.Nxd5  Bxd5  12.Bxf6  the forcing moves continue.  12...Bxc4  13.Bxd8  Bxf1  14.Kxf1  Kxd8-+  and Black ends up a clear pawn ahead in the endgame. }
5... e6
{ We hit in the centre immediately as we have done in some other variations of the Benko.   5...d6  6.Bxc4  g6  is a popular way of playing in this variation. }
6. Nc3 exd5 7. e5
{ White kicks the f6-knight so that he could recapture the d5-pawn with his knight.   7.Nxd5?!  will lead to an inferior version of the mainline. The difference is that after,  7...Nxd5  8.exd5  Be7  9.Bxc4  O-O  10.Nf3  d6  11.O-O  Nd7  Black has the f6 square easily available for our bishop which we need to work for in the mainline.   7.exd5  d6  8.Bxc4  Be7  9.Nf3   9.Nge2  O-O  10.O-O  transposes to the mainline.  9...O-O  10.O-O  transposes to the mainline. }
7... Bb7
{ This simple developing move is surprisingly the best for Black. We sacrifice the f6-knight in favour of the d5-pawn!   7...Ng4  is inferior due to,  8.Nxd5  Nxe5  9.Qe4  N   9.Nf3  0-1 @@StartBracket@@27@@EndBracket@@ Wichmann,C @@StartBracket@@2361@@EndBracket@@-Pap,M @@StartBracket@@2501@@EndBracket@@ Bad Woerishofen 2012  9...d6  and now the simple developing move,  10.Nf3!  is sufficient to guarantee at least a slight edge.  10...Nbc6  11.Bxc4  White dominates the central squares and Black's king is stuck in the centre.  11...Be7  12.Nxe5  Nxe5   12...dxe5?  13.Nxe7+-  loses for Black.  13.Bb5++=  this forces Black's king to move. Even though Black will still be a pawn up, it matters little as White's d5-knight is very powerful plus Black's king will be a source of trouble. }
8. Bg5 { White rejects our 'gift' for the moment and prepares to 0-0-0. } 8...
h6
{ This is an important intermediate move. It is in Black's favour to push the Bishop to h4 and only then play ... Qe7.   The direct  8...Qe7?  is bad due to  9.O-O-O  Qxe5  10.Nf3+-  White gets a chance to develop his knight with a tempo. The problem for Black is that White's dark-squared bishop covers the f4-square, preventing ...Qf4+.  10...Qc7  11.Bxc4!!  Time is everything in this position. White sacrifices the bishop and brings another rook into the attack without wasting time.  11...dxc4  12.Rhe1++-  and White has a crushing attack!  8...Be7  1-0 @@StartBracket@@68@@EndBracket@@ Cabrera Trujillo,J @@StartBracket@@2331@@EndBracket@@-Medina Martin,A @@StartBracket@@1926@@EndBracket@@ Santa Cruz de La Palma 2018 }
9. Bh4 { can now be comfortably met by, } 9... Qe7 10. O-O-O Qxe5 11. Nf3
{ does not work here due to } 11... Qf4+ 12. Kb1 Be7
{ and Black is in time to castle on the next move with a clearly better position. }
*

