{ We hit in the centre immediately as we have done in some other variations of the Benko.   5...d6  6.Bxc4  g6  is a popular way of playing in this variation. }
6. Nc3 exd5 7. e5
{ White kicks the f6-knight so that he could recapture the d5-pawn with his knight.   7.Nxd5?!  will lead to an inferior version of the mainline. The difference is that after,  7...Nxd5  8.exd5  Be7  9.Bxc4  O-O  10.Nf3  d6  11.O-O  Nd7  Black has the f6 square easily available for our bishop which we need to work for in the mainline.   7.exd5  d6  8.Bxc4  Be7  9.Nf3   9.Nge2  O-O  10.O-O  transposes to the mainline.  9...O-O  10.O-O  transposes to the mainline. }
7... Bb7
{ This simple developing move is surprisingly the best for Black. We sacrifice the f6-knight in favour of the d5-pawn!   7...Ng4  is inferior due to,  8.Nxd5  Nxe5  9.Qe4  N   9.Nf3  0-1 @@StartBracket@@27@@EndBracket@@ Wichmann,C @@StartBracket@@2361@@EndBracket@@-Pap,M @@StartBracket@@2501@@EndBracket@@ Bad Woerishofen 2012  9...d6  and now the simple developing move,  10.Nf3!  is sufficient to guarantee at least a slight edge.  10...Nbc6  11.Bxc4  White dominates the central squares and Black's king is stuck in the centre.  11...Be7  12.Nxe5  Nxe5   12...dxe5?  13.Nxe7+-  loses for Black.  13.Bb5++=  this forces Black's king to move. Even though Black will still be a pawn up, it matters little as White's d5-knight is very powerful plus Black's king will be a source of trouble. }
8. exf6 Qxf6 9. Nf3 Be7
{ A simple developing move preparing to 0-0 next. We should wait for White to play Be2 so that we get to advance ...d4 followed by ...d3 attacking the bishop on e2 as well as White's queen.   9...Na6  0-1 @@StartBracket@@26@@EndBracket@@ Grehling, M @@StartBracket@@2190@@EndBracket@@-Gierth, K @@StartBracket@@2187@@EndBracket@@ GER email 2010   9...d4?  is a wrong timed pawn advance. White has a simple refutation -  10.Nb5+-  followed by bxc4 when White wins an important pawn. }
10. Be2 d4
{ This is the correct time to advance the pawn as the White bishop has arrived on e2. }
11. Nb5 { White creates counter-threats on the queenside. } 11... d3 12. Qxc4
dxe2 13. Nc7+ Kd8
{ From the d8-square the king covers the white knight's retreat square. } 14.
Nxa8 Qg6
{ Threatening to capture the g2-pawn. The position is quite dynamic with both the kings still in the centre and an unbalanced material correlation. I have analyzed this position further and have found that Black is doing well against all of White's replies here. I would like to suggest an interesting and funky line!  15.Bg5!?  blocking the black queen's path to g2.  15...Bxg5  16.Ne5  White goes for another corner rook!  16...Qf6  17.Nxf7+  Ke7  18.Nxh8  and now it is important to remember the important move -  18...Bd2+!  a beautiful bishop sacrifice forcing White's king out of his comfort zone.  19.Kxd2   19.Kxe2?  does not work due to,  19...Ba6-+  19...Qxb2+  this is the point behind the bishop sacrifice. Now White cannot escape the perpetual.  20.Ke3  Qe5+  21.Kd2  Qb2+  22.Ke1  Qxa1+  23.Kxe2  Qb2+  It is important not to let White's king runs to the c2-square as can be seen from the 23...Qe5+ variation.   23...Qe5+?  would be a mistake due to,  24.Kd1  Qa1+  25.Kc2!  and White manages to escape the perpetual checks.  25...Qxh1  26.Qf7+  Kd6  27.Qf4+  Kd5  28.Nf7+-  White has some strong mating threats which ensure his victory.  24.Kd1  Qb1+  25.Qc1  Qd3+  26.Qd2  Qb1+  27.Ke2  Qe4+=  and the checks continue. If White goes for the exchange of queens here, then he may run the risk of losing both of his knights. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "28. Benko Gambit Declined: Mainline 4.Qc2"]
[Black "Benko Gambit Declined 4.Qc2 with 6.Bxc4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. Qc2
{ White develops his queen not to support the c4-pawn but to prepare the pawn advance e2-e4. }
4... bxc4 5. e4
{ 5.Qxc4?  is of course not White's idea as the queen is misplaced on c4.  5...e6  6.e4  exd5  7.exd5  Na6!  a strong move, the knight aims to go to b4 or c7 and put pressure on the d5-pawn. We can clearly see the drawback of having the queen on c4, the pawn on d5 lacks sufficient support.  8.a3   8.Nc3  Nb4  9.Qb3  Qa5!  10.Bd2  Ba6  and Black gets a strong initiative.  8...Nc7  9.Nc3  Bb7  White simply loses the d5-pawn. It makes no difference if White pins the f6-knight with  10.Bg5  as Black can still grab the pawn with  10...Ncxd5  11.Nxd5  Bxd5  12.Bxf6  the forcing moves continue.  12...Bxc4  13.Bxd8  Bxf1  14.Kxf1  Kxd8-+  and Black ends up a clear pawn ahead in the endgame. }
5... e6
{ We hit in the centre immediately as we have done in some other variations of the Benko.   5...d6  6.Bxc4  g6  is a popular way of playing in this variation. }
6. Bxc4 exd5 7. exd5 d6
{ Now White has two ways of developing the g1 knight. Ne2 or Nf3. } 8. Ne2
{ White wants to take his knight to g3 from where it will have the option of going to f5 in the future. }
8... Be7 9. O-O O-O 10. Nbc3 { 10.Ng3  Nbd7  11.Nc3  will transpose. } 10...
Nbd7
{ We develop in our typical way. We intend to place our knight on b6 putting pressure on the c4 bishop and d5-pawn. }
11. Ng3 Nb6 12. b3
{ This is a critical position where Black has tried different ways to continue. I would like to propose a rare continuation. }
12... Nxc4 13. bxc4 Ng4
{ a multi-purpose move. We plan to place our knight on e5 where it will put pressure on the c4-pawn. Other ideas include playing ...f5 or ... Bf6. }
14. Rb1 f5 { a space gaining move for Black. } 15. Nce2 g6 16. Nf4
{ White has manoeuvred his knight to f4 hoping to exploit the weakness on e6. But it is not possible for White to do that. }
16... Bf6 17. Nd3
{ 17.Ne6?  Bxe6  18.dxe6  Qe7  and the e6-pawn will be in trouble. } 17... Ne5
18. Re1 Bd7
{ Black has managed to setup his pieces comfortably and has a fine position. }
