{ We hit in the centre immediately as we have done in some other variations of the Benko.   5...d6  6.Bxc4  g6  is a popular way of playing in this variation. }
6. Bxc4 exd5 7. exd5 d6
{ Now White has two ways of developing the g1 knight. Ne2 or Nf3. } 8. Nf3
{ 8.Nc3 is the main move here which will transpose to our mainline anyway. But, withholding the knight's development gives White additional options like fianchettoing the dark-squared bishop with b3 and Bb2. }
8... Be7 9. O-O O-O 10. Nc3
{ 10.h3  Nbd7  11.Nc3  transposes to the mainline. } 10... Nbd7
{ We develop the knight first and plan to place it on b6 from where it puts pressure on both the d5-pawn and the c4 bishop. }
11. h3
{ This covers the g4 square so Black does not have the option of ...Bg4-Bh5-Bg6 anymore. It also frees the h2 square for the dark-squared bishop in case White plays Bf4. One of White's major ideas in this position is to manoeuvre the knight to g3 and create some action on the kingside.   11.Re1  is not so challenging as it allows a comfortable development of our light-squared bishop after,  11...Nb6  12.b3  Nxc4  13.bxc4  Bg4  14.Nd2  Qd7=  With the black bishop comfortably sitting on the b1-h7 diagonal, there can be no problems for us. ½-½ @@StartBracket@@33@@EndBracket@@ Pastir,S @@StartBracket@@2120@@EndBracket@@ -Macko,M @@StartBracket@@2170@@EndBracket@@ Slovakia 2016 }
11... Nb6 12. b3 Rb8
{ The b-file is about to open soon once we exchange on c4, so it is useful to place our rook on the b-file. We don't need to hurry with the exchange on c4 as it can also be done on the next move. By delaying the exchange for a move, we keep the c3 knight tied down to the d5-pawn. }
13. Bb2
{ With the idea to put pressure on the a1-h8 diagonal. We can start our counterplay on the queenside with, }
13... Nxc4 14. bxc4 Rb4
{ Using the rook aggressively to create pressure against the c4-pawn. } 15. Nb5
{ With the evil intention of trapping our rook is bad due to, } 15... Nxd5
{ Exploiting the overloaded pawn on c4. } 16. Nxa7 { is strongly met by, }
16... Bb7 { Covering the c6 square and locking the knight on a7. } 17. cxd5
Bxd5
{ We are soon going to win the knight on  a7  when we will be a pawn up. It is up to White to play accurately and try to equalize.  If White insists on bringing his knight back at any cost with  18.a4  then after  18...Bxf3  19.gxf3  Qd7  20.Nb5  Rh4-+  and White is about to get mated soon or lose heavy material. }
