6... fxe6 7. e4 d5 8. Nc3 Be7 9. Bg5 d4
{ This advance releases the tension in the centre but gains space and time for Black.   9...Bb7  10.Nh3  h6  11.Bxf6  1/2-1/ 2 @@StartBracket@@11@@EndBracket@@ Kuzubov,Y @@StartBracket@@2475@@EndBracket@@-Kulicov,O @@StartBracket@@2422@@EndBracket@@ Alushta 2004 }
10. Nb1 O-O 11. Nd2 Nbd7
{ Black would like to provoke the bishop on g5 to exchange on f6 by playing h7-h6. We also have tactical ideas like ...Nd5 on cards. }
12. Nh3 h6
{ Black can also go directly for our key tactical idea from the mainline -  12...Nd5!  13.exd5   13.Bxe7  Qxe7!!  14.exd5  exd5+-+  transposes to the mainline with only one difference that our pawn stands on h6 rather than on h7. Black has a winning attack.  13...Bxg5  14.dxe6  Ne5  White's king is stuck in the centre and is going to suffer a lot.  15.Nxg5  Qxg5  16.Ne4  Qh4+!  provoking g2-g3 which weakens the f3-pawn.  17.g3  Qe7  18.f4  is now strongly met by  18...Bb7!  19.Bg2  Nc4  the knight is going to enter on e3 with a devastating effect. }
13. Bh4 Nd5 { An elegant way to exchange the dark-squared bishops. } 14. Bxe7
Qxe7
{ An amazing piece sacrifice which White is forced to accept otherwise our knight will be a monster if it lands on e3. }
15. exd5 exd5+ 16. Qe2 Qf7
{ White's pieces are completely un-coordinated, his king is in the centre and cannot hope to be safe on the queenside as well. Black's pawn phalanx of d5-c5-d4 covers critical squares from White's pieces and gives us a great opportunity for the king hunt. }
