[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "29. Benko Gambit Accepted: Sideline 5.f3"]
[Black "Benko Gambit Accepted Sideline 5.f3 with 6.Nc3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. cxb5 a6 5. f3
{ With this White intends to build a solid centre with f3-e4-d5 pawn chain. White is ready to sacrifice the pawn on b5 as he knows that after he plays e2-e4, Black will have to waste moves to defend the b5-pawn. All in all, I don't think that this is a challenging variation and Black has various ways to deal with this confidently. }
5... e6
{ This is the second most popular move and it leads to interesting complications. With 5...e6 we hit the centre immediately and do not allow White to consolidate in the centre.   I have tried,  5...axb5  6.e4  Qa5+  which gave me good results and is one of the main replies to the 5.f3 variation. This variation is already covered in some books and courses so I decided to recommend a fresh line where we explore uncharted territory.   5...g6  6.e4  d6  or  6...Bg7  is another decent option for Black. }
6. Nc3
{ is not so good for White as the knight on c3 is unstable and Black will always have the option of pushing it with a future b5-b4 advance. }
6... axb5 7. e4 c4
{ A very nice move opening the g1-a7 diagonal which can prove to be a big weakness for White. }
8. Nxb5 { is met by, } 8... Ba6
{ Black attacks the white knight and makes sure that the c4-pawn will be supported at the same time once White moves his knight away from b5. }
9. Nc3 Bc5 10. Nh3
{ 10.dxe6  fxe6  11.e5  is bad for White again due to,  11...Nh5  12.Ne4  Nc6!  13.f4  Bb4+!  14.Kf2   14.Bd2  Nxf4-+  14...Nxf4  15.Bxf4  O-O-+ }
10... O-O 11. Bg5 h6 12. Bh4 exd5 13. exd5 Qb6
{ Unpinning the f6 knight and hitting the b2-pawn.   13...d6  0-1 @@StartBracket@@37@@EndBracket@@ Aubel,J  @@StartBracket@@2290@@EndBracket@@-Alvarez Ibarra,R @@StartBracket@@2390@@EndBracket@@ Terrassa 1998 }
14. Qc2 Re8+ 15. Be2 Bb7 16. O-O-O Na6 17. Bxc4 Nb4 18. Qb3
{ It seems that White has managed to hold his own on the queenside. However, this is not the case as Black can continue with, }
18... Ba6
{ Exchanging the c4-bishop weakens the white king's defences. Black is ready to include his rooks in the attack next. }
19. a3 Bxc4 20. Qxc4 Rec8
{ The most logical way to create threats is via the c-file where both White's queen and king are situated. }
21. Kb1
{ and now just when White seems to have settled on the queenside, Black strikes with the move, }
21... Nfxd5 { Resulting in a crushing attack on the queenside. } *

