[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "29. Benko Gambit Accepted: Sideline 5.f3"]
[Black "Benko Gambit Accepted Sideline 5.f3 with 6.e4 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. cxb5 a6 5. f3
{ With this White intends to build a solid centre with f3-e4-d5 pawn chain. White is ready to sacrifice the pawn on b5 as he knows that after he plays e2-e4, Black will have to waste moves to defend the b5-pawn. All in all, I don't think that this is a challenging variation and Black has various ways to deal with this confidently. }
5... e6
{ This is the second most popular move and it leads to interesting complications. With 5...e6 we hit the centre immediately and do not allow White to consolidate in the centre.   I have tried,  5...axb5  6.e4  Qa5+  which gave me good results and is one of the main replies to the 5.f3 variation. This variation is already covered in some books and courses so I decided to recommend a fresh line where we explore uncharted territory.   5...g6  6.e4  d6  or  6...Bg7  is another decent option for Black. }
6. e4 exd5 7. e5
{ This is White's only challenging try. White pushes our active f6-knight back before developing his own pieces. }
7... Qe7 8. Qe2 Ng8 9. Nc3
{ 9.Nh3  c4  10.Nc3  Bb7  transposes to the mainline. } 9... Bb7
{ This is an important position where White has tried a few different moves. }
10. Nh3
{ This is by far White's best move. 10.Nh3 not only develops the knight but also plans to develop his dark-squared bishop with tempo by Bg5. }
10... c4
{ An important pawn advance for Black. This cuts the support of the b5-pawn and gains space for Black on the queenside. It also frees the c5 and b4 square for the black queen. }
11. Nf4 Qc5
{ Black seems to have amazing control in the centre and prepares to further enhance it with ...d4. But here White has a nice tactical trick that throws the game into wild complications. }
12. Nfxd5 Bxd5 13. Be3 Qb4 14. a3 Qa5 15. Bd2 Be6
{ Black keeps the pawn on c4 supported for a while.   15...Bb7?  would be a mistake as it reduces Black's defensive options and forces Black to exchange our light-squared bishop for the white knight as we will soon see.  16.Nd5  Qd8   16...Qa4  17.Nc7+  Kd8  18.Nxa8  Bxa8  19.Qxc4!+-  White will gain two clear passed pawns on the queenside giving him a winning advantage.   19.bxa6  1-0 @@StartBracket@@59@@EndBracket@@ L'Ami, A @@StartBracket@@2362@@EndBracket@@ -Christiansen, J @@StartBracket@@2071@@EndBracket@@ Reykjavik 2013  17.Qxc4  and now as we can see there is simply no way to protect the threat of Nc7+ apart from exchanging on d5 @@StartBracket@@which is not the case in the mainline@@EndBracket@@.  17...Bxd5  18.Qxd5+-  followed by Bc4 when White will have two passed pawns on the queenside with a winning advantage. }
16. Nd5 c3
{ It is better to give up the c-pawn on c3 so that when White captures, the c-file will be closed and White will not be able to create pressure on it.   The direct,  16...Qd8  also seems possible, but it gives White the option of creating pressure on the c-file with,  17.Qxc4  Ra7  18.Rc1  which I would prefer to avoid. }
17. Bxc3 Qd8 18. Qc4 Ra7 { Preventing Nc7+. } 19. b6
{ does not work for White due to, } 19... Bxd5 20. bxa7 Bxc4 21. a8=Q Be6
{ it is in Black's favour to preserve the light-squared bishops. } 22. Bxa6 Bc5
{ Black stands clearly better. We would like to play ...Ne7 followed by ...0-0. Our pieces will soon team up and coordinate well. On the other hand, White's king is going to experience problems as castling kingside seems impossible and castling queenside is not so safe. }
*

