{ This is White's only challenging try. White pushes our active f6-knight back before developing his own pieces. }
7... Qe7 8. Qe2 Ng8 9. Nc3
{ 9.Nh3  c4  10.Nc3  Bb7  transposes to the mainline. } 9... Bb7
{ This is an important position where White has tried a few different moves. }
10. Nh3
{ This is by far White's best move. 10.Nh3 not only develops the knight but also plans to develop his dark-squared bishop with tempo by Bg5. }
10... c4 11. Bd2
{ is a slightly passive way of preparing 0-0-0, but it is a playable alternative. }
11... Qc5
{ c5 is a good square for our queen as it also defends the d5-pawn and puts pressure on White's b5-pawn. }
12. b6
{ White sacrifices the pawn in order to keep the queenside closed.   12.a4?!  This pawn does not go well with 11.Bd2 as after playing a4, White cannot castle queenside.  12...Nh6  developing the knight without hindering the f8-bishop. Black also aims to play ...Nf5 followed by ...Nd4.  13.g4  Be7→  Black is ready to 0-0 and has a nice initiative as White's king is still stuck in the centre. ½-½  (51)  Fire 3.1  (3096)  -Critter 1.6a  (3031)  @@LinkStart@@http://tcec.chessdom.com@@LinkEnd@@ 2014   12.b4  Qb6  now both of White's b-pawns are under attack.   12...Qxb4?  would be a mistake due to  13.bxa6  Bxa6  this is forced for Black otherwise Rb1 would have won the b7-bishop for White.  14.Nxd5±  after the departure of the d5-pawn, White clearly stands better. 1-0  (35)  Komljenovic,D  (2470)  -Campos Gambuti,L  (2230)  Cordoba 1990  13.Nf4  axb5  and now White needs to find the only move to keep the balance.  14.a4!  N   14.Nfxd5?  Bxd5  15.Nxd5  Qd4∓  0-1  (62)  Boudignon,S  (2230)  -Torgersen,T  (2013)  ICCF email 2009  14...Bxb4∞  the position still remains quite complex but one thing is clear - it is White who has to play carefully to not end up being clearly worse. }
12... Nc6
{ Development takes the first priority. We develop our knight and threaten ...Nd4.   12...Qxb6?!  gives White a strong initiative after  13.Nf4  Ne7  14.O-O-O↑  and Black's king is still stuck in the centre. }
13. O-O-O d4
{ time to roll the central pawns. White's e5 pawn is also under pressure now. }
14. Ne4
{ 14.Ne4?!  Seems more logical than  14.Na4  ,  but it is inferior as it takes the e4-square away from White’s queen. }
14... d3
{ a strong intermediate move that safeguards the c4-pawn.   14...Qxe5??  loses to  15.Bf4  +-  Black's queen will be forced to move away from the e-file after which the double check will end the game for Black.   The direct  14...Qxb6?  is also bad due to  15.Nd6+  Bxd6  16.exd6  Kf8  17.Qxc4±  and Black will experience problems with his king. }
15. Qe1 Qxb6
{ Black has won the b6-pawn under favourable circumstances and clearly stands better. }
