[White "30. Benko Gambit Accepted: Sideline 5.Nc3"]
[Black "Benko Gambit Accepted Sideline 5.Nc3 axb5 6.Nxb5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. cxb5 a6 5. Nc3
{ This is an interesting line known as the Zaitsev Line. White's main idea behind this line is to plant his knight on the b5 square, into enemy territory. }
5... axb5 6. Nxb5
{ This is surely not the idea of White when he goes for the 5.Nc3 variation, but it is better to be prepared for it. }
6... e6
{ 6...Ba6  7.Nc3  g6  transposes to the mainline of the Benko with hundreds of games in it, but it contradicts our recommendation. }
7. dxe6
{ 7.Nc3?!  just gives Black easy play after,  7...Nxd5  8.Nxd5  exd5  9.Qxd5  Nc6  Black simply plans to play ...Be7 followed by 0-0. Then we can kick the white queen from d5 and get in d7-d5 controlling the centre. We will also get good play on the a- and b-files. }
7... Qa5+ { It is better to drive the knight back first. } 8. Nc3 fxe6
{ Now Black simply wants to play ...d5 and gain control in the centre. } 9. Bd2
Qb6 10. e4
{ White plays against our idea d7-d5 idea.   10.b3?!  This is not needed as Black was not threatening to take on b2 anyway.  10...Nc6  11.g3  Now Black missed a nice resource  11...c4!  N   11...Bd6  0-1 @@StartBracket@@32@@EndBracket@@ Arakeljan, A @@StartBracket@@2331@@EndBracket@@-Pogosyan, G @@StartBracket@@2375@@EndBracket@@ Dubna 2016  12.bxc4  Bc5  13.e3  Ne5  with ...Bb7 coming next Black has an amazing initiative for the pawns. }
10... Nc6
{ 10...Qxb2?  11.Rb1  Qa3  12.Nb5+-  10...Bb7  0-1 @@StartBracket@@34@@EndBracket@@ Uwira,O  @@StartBracket@@2249@@EndBracket@@-Milov, L @@StartBracket@@2540@@EndBracket@@ Frankfurt 2013 }
11. Nf3 Be7 12. Bc4
{ 12.Be2  0-1  @@StartBracket@@28@@EndBracket@@ Hernandez,C @@StartBracket@@2245@@EndBracket@@-Teran Alvarez,I @@StartBracket@@2245@@EndBracket@@ Caceres 1993 }
12... O-O 13. O-O Bb7
{ Black plans to play ...Nd4 and has good compensation for the pawn. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "30. Benko Gambit Accepted: Sideline 5.Nc3"]
[Black "Benko Gambit Accepted Sideline 5.Nc3 axb5 6.e4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. cxb5 a6 5. Nc3
{ This is an interesting line known as the Zaitsev Line. White's main idea behind this line is to plant his knight on the b5 square, into enemy territory. }
5... axb5 6. e4
{ Only this way, by sacrificing his e4-pawn can White hope to establish his knight on the b5 square. White does not care much about losing the e4-pawn as if Black captures it then he can create threats down the e-file. }
6... b4 7. Nb5 d6
{ Now Black is ready to snatch the e4-pawn. If White defends it directly or indirectly then we can simply play ...g6 followed by ...Bg7 and 0-0. In general, whenever we take the pawn on e4, White gets good long term compensation. So, I feel it is easier to just play ...g6, ... Bg7 followed by ...0-0 and then continue playing strategically.   It would be great if we could win the e4-pawn immediately with,  7...Nxe4??  but it is not possible due to,  8.Qe2!  and we surely don't want to get mated in the opening after,  8...Nf6?   8...f5  9.f3+-  9.Nd6# }
8. Bf4
{ This is the most popular move in this position preparing to break in the centre with e4-e5. But this move has gone down from fashion once Black found the correct antidote, which is, }
8... g5
{ A nice move provoking the white bishop to g5 so that we can capture the important central e4-pawn with a tempo, attacking the bishop on g5.   8...g6?!  is strongly met by,  9.e5!  Nh5  10.exd6!  exd6  and now,  11.Qe2+  is very annoying from White. }
9. Bxg5 Nxe4
{ We have not only managed to capture the e4-pawn but are also ready to develop our bishop to g7. }
10. Bf4
{ Now White threatens Qe2, so we should first address this threat by retreating our knight. }
10... Nf6 { A nice prophylactic retreat. } 11. Qe2 { is safely met by, } 11...
Ra6
{ Supporting the d6-pawn and planning to continue with ...Bg7 followed by 0-0 next. }
*

