[White "30. Benko Gambit Accepted: Sideline 5.Nc3"]
[Black "Benko Gambit Accepted Sideline 6.e4 with 8.Bc4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. cxb5 a6 5. Nc3
{ This is an interesting line known as the Zaitsev Line. White's main idea behind this line is to plant his knight on the b5 square, into enemy territory. }
5... axb5 6. e4
{ Only this way, by sacrificing his e4-pawn can White hope to establish his knight on the b5 square. White does not care much about losing the e4-pawn as if Black captures it then he can create threats down the e-file. }
6... b4 7. Nb5 d6
{ Now Black is ready to snatch the e4-pawn. If White defends it directly or indirectly then we can simply play ...g6 followed by ...Bg7 and 0-0. In general, whenever we take the pawn on e4, White gets good long term compensation. So, I feel it is easier to just play ...g6, ... Bg7 followed by ...0-0 and then continue playing strategically.   It would be great if we could win the e4-pawn immediately with,  7...Nxe4??  but it is not possible due to,  8.Qe2!  and we surely don't want to get mated in the opening after,  8...Nf6?   8...f5  9.f3+-  9.Nd6# }
8. Bc4
{ A simple developing move that carries a trap if Black captures the e4-pawn. }
8... g6
{ 8...Nxe4?  is refuted by,  9.Qe2  Nf6  10.Bf4  White threatens to capture on d6 and surprisingly it is difficult to defend against this.  10...Ra6  is still met by,  11.Nxd6+!  Rxd6  12.Bb5+  and as we can see Black cannot interpose his rook on d7 as the knight on b8 hangs.  12...Bd7  13.Bxd6  Qb6  14.Bxd7+  Nbxd7  15.Bg3  Nxd5  16.Nf3  White is clearly better as Black has insufficient compensation for the exchange }
9. e5
{ A dubious try to complicate things.   9.Nf3  Bg7  10.O-O  O-O  transposes. }
9... dxe5 { Black accepts the challenge! } 10. d6 exd6 11. Bg5
{ Threatening Qf3 which forks the f6-knight and the a8-rook. } 11... Nbd7
{ Covering the f6-knight. } 12. Qb3 { can be met by, } 12... Qb6 13. Bxf7+ Kd8
14. Qf3 Qxb5
{ Black eliminates the annoying knight on b5 and is ready to sacrifice the exchange as we already have too many pawns in the centre. }
15. Bxf6+ { is not a problem for us. } 15... Nxf6 16. Qxf6+ Kc7 17. Qxh8
{ Even though this is a mistake, it seems like a logical continuation. The reason why you play 15.Bxf6+ is because you can win the h8-rook.   The best move is  17.Ne2  but even after this, Black stands much better by playing  17...Ba6  18.O-O  Qd7!  keeping an eye on the f7-bishop. Also, ...Bxe2 is a threat.  19.Qxh8  Qxf7-+  ...Bxe2 is still a threat and White's queen is very uncomfortable on h8. Black is winning. }
17... Ba6
{ Even though White is an entire rook up, Black's threat of ...Qf1+ is lethal. The white king's position is very weak giving Black a winning attack. An important point to note is that White cannot castle queenside due to - }
18. O-O-O Bh6+ { Winning the queen for Black. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "30. Benko Gambit Accepted: Sideline 5.Nc3"]
[Black "Benko Gambit Accepted Sideline 6.e4 with 8.Bc4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. cxb5 a6 5. Nc3
{ This is an interesting line known as the Zaitsev Line. White's main idea behind this line is to plant his knight on the b5 square, into enemy territory. }
5... axb5 6. e4
{ Only this way, by sacrificing his e4-pawn can White hope to establish his knight on the b5 square. White does not care much about losing the e4-pawn as if Black captures it then he can create threats down the e-file. }
6... b4 7. Nb5 d6
{ Now Black is ready to snatch the e4-pawn. If White defends it directly or indirectly then we can simply play ...g6 followed by ...Bg7 and 0-0. In general, whenever we take the pawn on e4, White gets good long term compensation. So, I feel it is easier to just play ...g6, ... Bg7 followed by ...0-0 and then continue playing strategically.   It would be great if we could win the e4-pawn immediately with,  7...Nxe4??  but it is not possible due to,  8.Qe2!  and we surely don't want to get mated in the opening after,  8...Nf6?   8...f5  9.f3+-  9.Nd6# }
8. Bc4
{ A simple developing move that carries a trap if Black captures the e4-pawn. }
8... g6
{ 8...Nxe4?  is refuted by,  9.Qe2  Nf6  10.Bf4  White threatens to capture on d6 and surprisingly it is difficult to defend against this.  10...Ra6  is still met by,  11.Nxd6+!  Rxd6  12.Bb5+  and as we can see Black cannot interpose his rook on d7 as the knight on b8 hangs.  12...Bd7  13.Bxd6  Qb6  14.Bxd7+  Nbxd7  15.Bg3  Nxd5  16.Nf3  White is clearly better as Black has insufficient compensation for the exchange }
9. e5
{ A dubious try to complicate things.   9.Nf3  Bg7  10.O-O  O-O  transposes. }
9... dxe5 { Black accepts the challenge! } 10. d6 exd6 11. Bg5
{ Threatening Qf3 which forks the f6-knight and the a8-rook. } 11... Nbd7
{ Covering the f6-knight. } 12. Qb3 { can be met by, } 12... Qb6 13. Bxf7+ Kd8
14. Qf3 Qxb5
{ Black eliminates the annoying knight on b5 and is ready to sacrifice the exchange as we already have too many pawns in the centre. }
15. Qxa8 Bg7 16. a4
{ White can also try a move like  16.Bd5  centralizing the bishop.  16...Kc7  We unpin our f6-knight intending to exchange White's d5-bishop.  17.Qa7+  Bb7  18.Qxb7+  Qxb7  19.Bxb7  Kxb7-+  and Black gets a winning advantage in this endgame because of our beautiful pawn chain. }
16... Qb7 17. Qxb7 Bxb7 18. f3 d5
{ The beautiful phalanx of black pawns gives us a winning advantage. } *

