[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "30. Benko Gambit Accepted: Sideline 5.Nc3"]
[Black "Benko Gambit Accepted Sideline 6.e4 with 8.a4 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. cxb5 a6 5. Nc3
{ This is an interesting line known as the Zaitsev Line. White's main idea behind this line is to plant his knight on the b5 square, into enemy territory. }
5... axb5 6. e4
{ Only this way, by sacrificing his e4-pawn can White hope to establish his knight on the b5 square. White does not care much about losing the e4-pawn as if Black captures it then he can create threats down the e-file. }
6... b4 7. Nb5 d6
{ Now Black is ready to snatch the e4-pawn. If White defends it directly or indirectly then we can simply play ...g6 followed by ...Bg7 and 0-0. In general, whenever we take the pawn on e4, White gets good long term compensation. So, I feel it is easier to just play ...g6, ... Bg7 followed by ...0-0 and then continue playing strategically.   It would be great if we could win the e4-pawn immediately with,  7...Nxe4??  but it is not possible due to,  8.Qe2!  and we surely don't want to get mated in the opening after,  8...Nf6?   8...f5  9.f3+-  9.Nd6# }
8. a4
{ This is the best move for White here and has been played regularly by the Russian GM Ponkratov. White gets rid of the weakness of the a2-pawn and cements his knight on b5 at the same time.   8.Bd3  can strongly be met by,  8...e6!  with the idea to play ...Be7 and ...0-0. }
8... g6
{ we focus on our own plan of kingside castling.   8...bxa3?!  seems like a logical move for Black, but after,  9.Rxa3  Rxa3  10.bxa3  the threat of Qa4 is very annoying.   8...Nxe4 !?  is an interesting but complicated alternative.  9.Bc4  White threatens Qe2 and then Bf4 creating threats on the d6-pawn.  9...Nf6!  a good prophylactic move.   9...g6?!  10.Qe2  Nf6  11.Bf4  Ra6  12.Nxd6+!  is a similar trap that we have already witnessed previously.  12...Rxd6  13.Bb5+  Rd7  14.Bxb8  10.Qe2  Ra6  protecting d6-pawn  11.Bg5   11.Bf4?  can now be easily met by,  11...Bb7  when we attack the d5-pawn but also protect the b8-knight so that White's idea of Nxd6 will not work.  12.O-O-O  g6  13.Nf3  Bg7  14.Rhe1  Kf8  and Black is a clear pawn up.  11...h6  12.Bxf6  gxf6  By sacrificing the pawn White has managed to ruin Black's pawn structure on the kingside making it risky for Black to castle short.  13.Nf3  Bg7  14.b3   14.O-O?!  is inferior as after f5 White will find it tough to play b2-b3.  14...h5!  N  I believe this is a better option for Black than the logical 14...f5 which was played by Dubov. Black wants to gain space on the kingside first before playing ...f6-f5.   14...f5  0-1 @@StartBracket@@60@@EndBracket@@ Ponkratov, P @@StartBracket@@2610@@EndBracket@@ -Dubov, D @@StartBracket@@2661@@EndBracket@@ Kaliningrad 2015  15.O-O  h4  16.Rae1  Kf8  17.h3  Ra8  18.Qe4  f5  19.Qf4  Bf6  Black has gained space on the kingside and made sure that White does not get to exploit our lack of development. White on the other hand has locked the queenside completely and puts some pressure on our kingside. The position remains complicated where White has compensation for the pawn, but it is pretty stable as well. }
9. Bd3 Bg7 10. Nf3 O-O 11. O-O Bg4
{ It is good for Black to exchange the knight on f3. Once the knight is eliminated we get complete control over the e5 square so we don't need to worry about a future e4-e5 break. Another important benefit is that the white knight usually gravitates towards the c4-square where it is well placed. So, we exchange the knight before it gets a chance to go there.   11...Na6  with the idea to play ...Nc7 followed by ...Ba6 putting pressure on the b5 knight is also a good alternative. }
12. h3 Bxf3 13. Qxf3 Nbd7
{ Now one of our main ideas is to put pressure on the a4-pawn which cannot be defended immediately with b2-b3 as there are tricks on the a1-h8 diagonal. After playing ...Nb6 we would also like to advance our queenside pawns beginning with c5-c4. White should also watch out for ...Ne5 exchanging White's light-squared bishop. }
14. Qe2 Nb6 { Immediately putting pressure on the a4-pawn. } 15. Bc2 Nfd7
{ with the idea to play c5-c4. } 16. Bb3
{ White prevents the advance of ...c4 but now he cannot protect the a4-pawn with b2-b3, so we start putting pressure on it with, }
16... Ra5
{ We fix the pawn on a4 and prepare to attack it with moves like ...Qa8 at the correct moment. }
17. Bg5 h6 18. Bh4 g5 19. Bg3 Qa8
{ Black will win the pawn on a4 with sufficient defensive resources on the kingside if White thinks of attacking with f2-f4. Also, it is important to note that once the a4-pawn falls, the knight on b5 might be lost as well. }
