[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "31. Benko Gambit Accepted: Mainline 5.e3"]
[Black "Benko Gambit Accepted Mainline 5.e3 with 7.a4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. cxb5 a6 5. e3
{ This is another way to maintain the pawn lead. White prefers to keep the pawn on b5 and waits for Black to capture on b5 so that he could develop his bishop in one move straight to b5. White does not want to help Black in developing his queenside pieces by capturing on a6 with 5.bxa6, which is the mainline. The drawback is White will be one move late in setting up his ideal pawn structure in the centre @@StartBracket@@e4-d5@@EndBracket@@ with Nb1-c3 followed by e3-e4 which he manages to do quickly in the mainline 5.ba6. White's main follow-up is to play Nb1-c3, Ng1-f3, a2-a4, Ra1-a3. With this White would like to degrade Black's counterplay on the queenside. Therefore, instead of focusing on the queenside, we will focus on the centre. }
5... g6
{ Black goes for the traditional Benko set-up. Now as mentioned earlier, if you compare this to the mainline 5.bxa6, White will be a move late in getting his pawn to e4. We would like to use this precious time and hit in the centre with Bc8-b7 followed by e7-e6 at the right moment before White settles down comfortably. }
6. Nc3 Bg7
{ Now White has various options here, but in most of the cases he plays Ng1-f3 sooner or later, which will transpose into the mainline. We will analyse those options where White will be developing his knight anywhere but the f3 square. }
7. a4 O-O 8. Bc4
{ This is the second most popular move in this position. White develops his bishop before his knight so that he could develop his knight on e2 next without hindering the bishop.  This might seem like a flexible move but it has a drawback. The bishop on c4 itself becomes a target for Black's knight. So we change our general plan of breaking with ...e6 to bringing our knight to the b6-square. This will put pressure on the c4-bishop. }
8... d6
{ with a clear idea of transferring our knight to b6.   8...e6!?  is also an interesting alternative.   8...axb5  9.Bxb5  Bb7  10.Nge2  this is scoring well for white.   10.Nf3  transposes. }
9. Nge2
{ 9.e4  Keep White's options flexible. We anyway continue with our intended plan -  9...Nbd7  N   9...axb5  0-1  (42)  Babula,V  (2536)  -Plachetka,J  (2348)  Hustopece 2010  10.Nf3  Nb6  11.Be2  Now White wants to play a5 followed by b6 so we should exchange on b5.  11...axb5  12.Bxb5  Bd7!  exchanging the light-squared bishop opens the files on the queenside for Black's rooks.  13.Bxd7  Qxd7  14.O-O  Ra6=∞  with the idea to play ...Rfa8 gives Black a nice compensation because of the typical pressure on the queenside in the Benko Gambit. }
9... Nbd7 10. O-O Nb6 { Now White needs to waste a move to defend his bishop. }
11. Qb3
{ This looks like the most logical move, keeping things stable on the queenside. However, Black has a nice reply which weakens White's queenside fortress.   11.b3  is White's best move, but it simply loses the pawn after -  11...axb5  12.Bxb5  Nbxd5=+  Black uses the power of his strong bishop on g7 to recover the pawn. Black is slightly better as he will continue to exert pressure on the queenside. }
11... Nfd7
{ the other knight comes in action, threatening ...Ne5 which will trap White's bishop. }
12. Nf4 { creating space for the c4-bishop. } 12... Nxc4
{ it is in Black's favour to eliminate the bishop before it escapes. } 13. Qxc4
Nb6 14. Qb3 axb5 15. Nxb5 Ba6
{ Black is clearly better. We would like to play ...Qd7 next which gives a strong threat of ...Nxa4. Also, Black can even simply continue bringing his pieces in action with ...Rfb8 when the queenside pressure is too much to handle for White. ½-½  (48)  Sachdev,T  (2411)  -Adhiban,B  (2561)  Wijk aan Zee 2012 }
