6. Nc3 Bg7
{ Now White has various options here, but in most of the cases he plays Ng1-f3 sooner or later, which will transpose into the mainline. We will analyse those options where White will be developing his knight anywhere but the f3 square. }
7. a4 O-O 8. Ra3
{ This is a typical square for the white rook in this structure. The idea of putting the rook on a3 is that now the a4-pawn is not pinned anymore and the rook also moves to a safer square away from the a1-h8 diagonal which is always a cause of concern for White in the Benko. We will see White playing Ra3 in the mainline as well, the only difference here is that White has not committed Ng1-f3 and has the option of developing the knight to h3.   8.Nf3  Bb7  transposes   8.e4  transposes to the mainline }
8... Bb7 9. Nh3
{ This is a rare idea. White prefers to bring the knight to f4, adding more control on d5, which will help him deal with the e7-e6 break.   9.Nf3  transposes. }
9... axb5
{ Seeing that White has developed his knight to h3, away from the centre, we can switch our play to the queenside.   9...e6  is not so effective now because of,  10.Nf4  When it will be difficult to create counterplay in the centre due to White's stronghold on the  d5  square. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@39@@EndBracket@@ Pelletier, Y @@StartBracket@@2350@@EndBracket@@-Cramling, P @@StartBracket@@2525@@EndBracket@@ Biel 1994 CBM 043 @@StartSquare@@Stohl, I@@EndSquare@@ }
10. axb5 { is bad due to, } 10... Rxa3 11. bxa3 Qa5 12. Qd2 d6
{ Black's simple plan is ...Nd7-b6 and bring the rook to a8. The pressure on the queenside, especially on the c3 knight is not easy to handle for White. Black can also consider inserting ...c5-c4, freeing more squares for his pieces. }
