{ This is another rare and independent try by White. Instead of setting up an ideal formation on the queenside, White decides to focus on completing his development. }
8... axb5
{ Usually, whenever White moves his bishop from f1 we should take on b5 forcing the white bishop to recapture on b5 wasting its move. }
9. Bxb5 Ne4
{ nice tactics exploiting the low support on the b5 bishop, as White's pawn on a4 is missing.   9...e6!?  is a possible alternative. }
10. Nxe4 Qa5+ 11. Nc3
{ 11.Bd2?!  is bad because of,  11...Qxb5  12.Bc3  Bxc3+  13.bxc3  d6  The white king has to stay in the centre. }
11... Bxc3+ 12. bxc3 Qxb5 13. Nd2 { plans c4 to block the f1-a6 diagonal. }
13... Qa4
{ this is the simplest solution, transposing the game to a completely fine endgame for Black.   13...Qd3  0-1 @@StartBracket@@70@@EndBracket@@ Foisor,S  @@StartBracket@@2358@@EndBracket@@ -Sambuev,B @@StartBracket@@2522@@EndBracket@@ Calgary 2017 }
14. c4 d6 15. Bb2 Qxd1+ 16. Kxd1 Ra4
{ an important move putting pressure on the c4-pawn and preventing White's a2-a4 advance at the same time. }
17. Kc2 Nd7
{ This position is completely fine for Black. We would like to play ...Ba6 and then ...Rfa8 adding pressure on the c4- and a2-pawns. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "31. Benko Gambit Accepted: Mainline 5.e3"]
[Black "Benko Gambit Accepted Mainline 7.Nf3 with 8.Be2 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. cxb5 a6 5. e3
{ This is another way to maintain the pawn lead. White prefers to keep the pawn on b5 and waits for Black to capture on b5 so that he could develop his bishop in one move straight to b5. White does not want to help Black in developing his queenside pieces by capturing on a6 with 5.bxa6, which is the mainline. The drawback is White will be one move late in setting up his ideal pawn structure in the centre @@StartBracket@@e4-d5@@EndBracket@@ with Nb1-c3 followed by e3-e4 which he manages to do quickly in the mainline 5.ba6. White's main follow-up is to play Nb1-c3, Ng1-f3, a2-a4, Ra1-a3. With this White would like to degrade Black's counterplay on the queenside. Therefore, instead of focusing on the queenside, we will focus on the centre. }
5... g6
{ Black goes for the traditional Benko set-up. Now as mentioned earlier, if you compare this to the mainline 5.bxa6, White will be a move late in getting his pawn to e4. We would like to use this precious time and hit in the centre with Bc8-b7 followed by e7-e6 at the right moment before White settles down comfortably. }
6. Nc3 Bg7
{ Now White has various options here, but in most of the cases he plays Ng1-f3 sooner or later, which will transpose into the mainline. We will analyse those options where White will be developing his knight anywhere but the f3 square. }
7. Nf3 { 7.e4  O-O  8.a4  Bb7  9.Nf3  Transposes to the mainline after 7.Nf3 }
7... O-O 8. Be2
{ This is another rare and independent try by White. Instead of setting up an ideal formation on the queenside, White decides to focus on completing his development. }
8... axb5
{ Usually, whenever White moves his bishop from f1 we should take on b5 forcing the white bishop to recapture on b5 wasting its move. }
9. Bxb5 Ne4
{ nice tactics exploiting the low support on the b5 bishop, as White's pawn on a4 is missing.   9...e6!?  is a possible alternative. }
10. Bd2 Nxd2 11. Nxd2 Na6
{ With the white bishop on b5 it makes more sense to bring our knight to c7 hitting the b5-bishop.   11...Bb7  1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@26@@EndBracket@@ Salonen,J @@StartBracket@@1899@@EndBracket@@ -Eshuis,H @@StartBracket@@2062@@EndBracket@@ Lechenicher SchachServer 2013 }
12. O-O Rb8 13. Rb1 Nc7 14. Bc4 d6 { preparing the ...e6 break. } 15. Qc2
{ Now there are two ways to play in this position. Either we can simply play in the typical Benko style by slowly increasing pressure on the queenside or we can start counter-play in the centre. }
15... e6
{ 15...Na8!?  is a possible alternative, with the idea to play ...Qa5 and then ...Nb6. }
16. e4 f5
{ It is beneficial for Black to open up the position as White will surely miss his dark-squared bishop. The position is quite complex and Black has very good counter-chances. A sample variation would be, }
17. dxe6
{ 17.a3  is met by,  17...fxe4  18.Ndxe4  Bb7  19.Rbd1  Bd4!  centralizing the bishop and cutting the support of the d5-pawn.  20.dxe6  d5  21.Ba2  Nxe6  the position is very concrete and complex but I believe that Black has good chances here. }
17... Nxe6 18. exf5 Rxf5 { ...d5 is coming up next. } 19. Qd3 Kh8
{ Black is still a pawn down but has very good compensation for it in the form of bishop pair and active pieces. One of the ideas now would be to play ...Nf4 followed by ...d5. }
