{ a good developing move. One of Black’s ideas now is to take his knight to b4 where it will be very well placed.   13...Ne4  0-1  @@StartBracket@@31@@EndBracket@@ Cox,W-Tate,E @@StartBracket@@2325@@EndBracket@@ Illinois 1993 }
14. d6
{ This is the only challenging try for an advantage. White pushes his vulnerable d5-pawn to d6 but it opens up the h1-a8 diagonal for our light-squared bishop. }
14... Qe6 15. O-O Nb4
{ All of Black's pieces are actively placed and I believe that Black has a definite compensation here. The engines show this position to be slightly better for White, but as we analyse the position deeper it peters out to equality. Black's knight is firmly placed on the weak b4 square and the bishop on b7 exerts pressure on the h1-a8 diagonal. Black's queen on e6 keeps an eye on the d6-pawn making it essential for White to pay close attention to it. I have analysed a few possibilities here. }
16. a5 Nfd5 { revealing the lack of support to the d6-pawn. } 17. Ra3 Qxd6 18.
Bc4
{ It might seem that the pin on the knight on d5 is lethal but Black has a nice way of escaping from that. }
18... Qe6
{ Black moves away from the pin on the d-file and threatens to capture ...Nxc3. }
19. a6 { can be met by } 19... Bc6 20. Ng5 Qe5 21. Re1 Qd4
{ and Black is completely safe. } *

