[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. cxb5 a6 5. e3
{ This is another way to maintain the pawn lead. White prefers to keep the pawn on b5 and waits for Black to capture on b5 so that he could develop his bishop in one move straight to b5. White does not want to help Black in developing his queenside pieces by capturing on a6 with 5.bxa6, which is the mainline. The drawback is White will be one move late in setting up his ideal pawn structure in the centre @@StartBracket@@e4-d5@@EndBracket@@ with Nb1-c3 followed by e3-e4 which he manages to do quickly in the mainline 5.ba6. White's main follow-up is to play Nb1-c3, Ng1-f3, a2-a4, Ra1-a3. With this White would like to degrade Black's counterplay on the queenside. Therefore, instead of focusing on the queenside, we will focus on the centre. }
5... g6
{ Black goes for the traditional Benko set-up. Now as mentioned earlier, if you compare this to the mainline 5.bxa6, White will be a move late in getting his pawn to e4. We would like to use this precious time and hit in the centre with Bc8-b7 followed by e7-e6 at the right moment before White settles down comfortably. }
6. Nc3 Bg7
{ Now White has various options here, but in most of the cases he plays Ng1-f3 sooner or later, which will transpose into the mainline. We will analyse those options where White will be developing his knight anywhere but the f3 square. }
7. Nf3 { 7.e4  O-O  8.a4  Bb7  9.Nf3  Transposes to the mainline after 7.Nf3 }
7... O-O 8. a4 { This is generally a useful move for white on the queenside. }
8... Bb7 9. e4
{ White stabilizes in the centre by supporting the d5-pawn beforehand. } 9...
e6
{ we continue with the strategy of putting pressure on White's centre as quickly as possible. }
10. Be2
{ 10.Bc4  leads to the same thing after  10...axb5  11.Bxb5  exd5  transposes. }
10... axb5
{ This is the correct time to exchange on b5 as White has just moved his bishop from f1. }
11. Bxb5 exd5 12. exd5
{ this is one of the critical positions suggested in the Principled Queen's Gambit - part 2 }
12... Qe7+
{ it might seem counter-intuitive to give a check with the queen instead of the rook. However, our queen is more effective if White blocks the check with Be3.   12...Re8+?!  seems like the most natural move to make here, but after,  13.Be3  Ng4  14.O-O!  White sacrifices a pawn for the initiative.  14...Nxe3  15.fxe3  Rxe3  16.Qd2  Followed by Rae1, when White has more pieces on the kingside while our pieces are stuck on the queenside. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@43@@EndBracket@@ Fier,A @@StartBracket@@2628@@EndBracket@@-Rambaldi,F @@StartBracket@@2513@@EndBracket@@ Biel 2015 }
13. Be2
{ 13.Qe2?!  is of course not a good option for White, because  13...Qxe2+=  and Black wins the d5-pawn next. }
13... Na6
{ a good developing move. One of Black’s ideas now is to take his knight to b4 where it will be very well placed.   13...Ne4  0-1  @@StartBracket@@31@@EndBracket@@ Cox,W-Tate,E @@StartBracket@@2325@@EndBracket@@ Illinois 1993 }
14. d6
{ This is the only challenging try for an advantage. White pushes his vulnerable d5-pawn to d6 but it opens up the h1-a8 diagonal for our light-squared bishop. }
14... Qe6 15. O-O Nb4
{ All of Black's pieces are actively placed and I believe that Black has a definite compensation here. The engines show this position to be slightly better for White, but as we analyse the position deeper it peters out to equality. Black's knight is firmly placed on the weak b4 square and the bishop on b7 exerts pressure on the h1-a8 diagonal. Black's queen on e6 keeps an eye on the d6-pawn making it essential for White to pay close attention to it. I have analysed a few possibilities here. }
16. a5 Nfd5 { revealing the lack of support to the d6-pawn. } 17. Ra3 Qxd6 18.
Bc4
{ It might seem that the pin on the knight on d5 is lethal but Black has a nice way of escaping from that. }
18... Qe6
{ Black moves away from the pin on the d-file and threatens to capture ...Nxc3. }
19. Qb3 Qf5 { and we are out safely from the pin on the d5-knight. } 20. a6 Bc6
{ Black has neutralised White's temporary initiative and he is free to create his own plans now. }
