{ is strongly met by, } 14... d4 15. Bd2
{ 15.Nxd4?  is a huge mistake due to,  15...cxd4  16.Bxb4   16.Bxd4  Qxd4!-+  16...Bxb4+  17.axb4  Qxb4+  18.Qd2  Qxd2+  19.Kxd2  Rxb2+-+  and Black is simply a pawn up in this endgame. }
15... Nc6 { and Black has a nice initiative on the queenside. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "32. Benko Gambit Accepted: Mainline 5.b6"]
[Black "Benko Gambit Accepted Mainline 5.b5 e6 with 9.Nf3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. cxb5 a6 5. b6
{ White gives the pawn back immediately and aims for a positional struggle ahead. }
5... e6
{ I believe this is a very straightforward way to achieve complete equality. We immediately start grappling in the centre before White gets a chance to increase the hold with Nb1-c3 and e2-e4. The pawn on b6 is going nowhere and will be won sooner or later. 5...d6 followed by ...Nbd7 and then recapturing the b6-pawn with our knight is another formidable alternative for Black. 5...e6 is more concrete and direct in nature. }
6. Nc3 Nxd5 { 6...exd5 leads to the same thing as 6...Nd5. } 7. Nxd5 exd5 8.
Qxd5 Nc6
{ There have been a couple of exchanges on d5 and it might seem that White has gained a nice control on this square. But in fact, the queen is a very unstable piece on d5 as it can be easily chased away. So White still needs a few moves to complete his development and establish proper control on d5. Black would like to play Bf8-e7 followed by 0-0 and then taking the pawn on b6. }
9. Nf3
{ White not only develops his knight but also threatens Nf3-e5 at the same time, exploiting the Pin on the c6 knight. }
9... Rb8
{ side-stepping White's idea of Nf3-e5. Black anyways wanted to play Ra8-b8 and grab the pawn on b6 with his rook. With the rook active on the b-file we create pressure on the b-file.   Our intended,  9...Be7?!  is, of course, inferior here due to,  10.Ne5!  The benefit of playing 9.Nf3 immediately.  10...O-O  11.Nxc6  dxc6  12.Qxd8  Bxd8   12...Rxd8?  13.Bf4+-  1-0 @@StartBracket@@39@@EndBracket@@ Karpov, A @@StartBracket@@2725@@EndBracket@@ -Christiansen, L @@StartBracket@@2620@@EndBracket@@ Wijk aan Zee 1993  13.e4  and because of Black's weak queenside pawns White has better chances. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@48@@EndBracket@@Grabarczyk,M @@StartBracket@@2480@@EndBracket@@ -Ehrenfeucht,W @@StartBracket@@2290@@EndBracket@@ Warsaw 1997 }
10. Bg5 f6
{ this is the correct way to block the attack on our queen, forcing the bishop to retreat. }
11. Bd2 Qxb6 12. Bc3 Nb4 13. Qd1
{ 13.Qd2  N is also met by the same,  13...d5  Black gains control in the centre and prepares ...Be6. A sample variation can be,  14.a3  d4  15.Nxd4  cxd4  16.Bxb4  Bxb4  17.axb4  Qxb4  18.Qxb4  Rxb4  with a slight initiative for Black in this endgame. White needs to play accurately to equalise from this position. }
13... d5 { taking control in the centre and threatening ...Bf5. } 14. e4
{ Now instead of complicating the game with 14...de4, Black went for the safe solution, }
14... d4 15. Bxb4 Qxb4+ 16. Nd2 Bd6
{ This creates the option of ...Bf4 pressurizing the d2-knight. } 17. b3
{ 17.Bc4  Prepares to 0-0 but of course he won't be allowed to do that.  17...Bf4!  We catch the poor d2-knight and threaten to win White's c4-bishop after ...Bxd2+.  18.b3  f5!  White's king is still stuck in the centre so it makes sense to open up the centre.  19.e5  White keeps the lines closed   19.exf5?  is strongly met by  19...Kd8!  -+  with the idea to play ...Re8+ with a crushing attack against White's king.  19...Bb7  20.a3  Qb6  21.Nf3  g5!  ∓  with two strong bishops, Black has all the rights to be aggressive. Black stands clearly better here due to the space advantage and two powerful bishops. }
17... Bf4 { the pin on the d2-knight is very annoying for White. } 18. g3 Bg4
{ a nice tactical idea forcing the exchange of the light-squared bishops. } 19.
Be2 Bxe2 20. Qxe2 d3
{ another strong move that puts White under pressure. In fact, White blundered in this position and lost quickly. }
21. Qxd3
{ 21.Qh5+!  was the only move here for White to survive. White provokes ...g6 before going back to d1.  21...g6  22.Qd1  Bxd2+  23.Qxd2  Qxe4+=+  Black is a pawn up and in the upcoming rook endgame after Qe3, he will have much better chances. }
21... Rd8
{ Black is about to win material and he won the game soon after. 0-1  (33)  Ivanisevic,I  (2537)  -Degraeve,J  (2575)  Bled 2002 }
*

