{ It feels bad to put the pawns on the same colour as our bishop, but in return, we get complete control of the central d4 square. With 17...e5 we also restrict White's dark-squared bishop.   17...Bf6  is logical, but I don't want to weaken my pawn structure after,  18.e5!  1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@32@@EndBracket@@ Bagirov,R @@StartBracket@@2471@@EndBracket@@-Vuckovic,B @@StartBracket@@2444@@EndBracket@@ Istanbul 2000 }
18. Qxc8 Rxc8 19. Nd2 Nd4 20. Nc4 Rb5
{ Now Black's plan is to simply prepare for the ...a4 break on the queenside with a6-a5, Rc8-a8 and then a5-a4. Our pawn on d6 is weak and White has complete control on the d5 square, but our knight on d4 is amazing and we have very good chances to seize the initiative on the queenside. ½-½ @@StartBracket@@43@@EndBracket@@ Shabalov,A @@StartBracket@@2606@@EndBracket@@-Bartholomew,J  @@StartBracket@@2419@@EndBracket@@ Philadelphia 2007 }
