{ We continue in a normal fashion bringing the queen out to a5 immediately and creating threats. }
9. Bd2 Bxa6 10. e5
{ this is the point of 8.Be2. Now Black cannot play ...Ng4 and has to retreat the knight back to e8. White centre control with e5-d5 is temporary and soon we will start putting pressure on White's central pawns. }
10... Ne8 11. Nf3 d6 { the pressure strategy starts! } 12. e6
{ This aggressive move is the only challenging move to try and push Black on the ropes. }
12... Bxe2
{ 12...f5?  is a very desirable move to make for Black. We prevent any opening up of the kingside after exf7 and prepare to bring the e8 knight in the game via f6 or c7. But this falls short for concrete reasons.  13.h4!  White immediately starts an offensive on the kingside!  13...Nf6  14.h5!  Nxh5  and now the strongest is,  15.Rxh5!  N   15.Ng5  1-0 @@StartBracket@@32@@EndBracket@@ Tanriverdi, E @@StartBracket@@2276@@EndBracket@@ -Natsidis, C @@StartBracket@@2346@@EndBracket@@ Lvov 2018  15...gxh5  16.Nb5+  preventing the exchange of the light-squared bishops and preparing Nf3-g5 next followed by capturing the h5-pawn, White gets a crushing attack! }
13. exf7+ { White opens up a few lines on the kingside at the first chance. }
