O-O Nd7 17. a4 Bxb2 18. Bxh6 { is a possible exchange sacrifice. } 18... Bxa1
19. Rxa1
{ now White is threatening Ng5 followed by Qe6+ with a devastating attack on the kingside. So it is necessary to play }
19... Ne5
{ the knight comes to the rescue and blocks the e-file, thus making sure that White's queen does not find its way to e6. }
20. Nxe5
{ 20.Ng5?  loses its venom and can simply be met by,  20...Rf4-+  threatening to grab the a4-pawn when Black is in control and winning. }
20... dxe5
{ With this knight exchange, White has weakened Black's pawn structure even further, but the good news is that our queen can now participate in the defence from the 6th rank. White has compensation for the exchange because of Black's weak pawn structure and the passed a-pawn. However, Black is sufficiently solid. Our kingside is safe and the position remains dynamically balanced. }
