11. Bxa6 { this uses the fact that now Black cannot recapture with the queen. }
11... Nxa6 12. Qe2 d6
{ an important move preventing e4-e5 advance. Black now threatens to grab the b2-pawn.   12...Qxb2?!  regains the pawn but gives White a slight initiative after,  13.Rb1  Qa3  14.e5!  kicking the knight back  14....Ne8  15.Rb3  Qa5  16.O-O  due to the space advantage in the centre White stands slightly better. @@StartBracket@@76@@EndBracket@@ Khairullin,I @@StartBracket@@2647@@EndBracket@@ -Yuffa,D @@StartBracket@@2504@@EndBracket@@ Doha 2015 }
13. Rb1 Rfb8
{ Black has arranged his rooks in a typical Benko fashion on the a- and b-files. }
14. O-O Nd7 15. Rfc1 Nc7
{ Black would like to play ... Nb5, offering the exchange of the important c3-knight, which holds White's queenside together. }
16. h4 { should have been met by, } 16... Nb5
{ Black plans to land his knight on d4.   16...Qb7  1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@44@@EndBracket@@ Coklin,M @@StartBracket@@2429@@EndBracket@@ -Kosic,B @@StartBracket@@2417@@EndBracket@@ ICCF 2017 }
17. a3 Qb3 18. Nxb5 Qxb5 19. Qxb5 Rxb5
{ with a few important exchanges, it is now difficult for White to hold his queenside together. }
20. Bc3
{ 20.b4  h6=  and Black will soon regain his lost pawn on the queenside with complete equality. }
