10. Be2
{ 10.Bxa6?!  Qxa6  11.Qe2  White is essentially a move behind compared to position arising in the 10.Be2 variation.  11...e6!  and Black is doing well here with an extra move! }
10... Qb4
{ this is the third most popular move in this position but a strong one according to me. Black starts creating threats on the queenside with his queen before White completes his development and consolidates.   10...Bxe2  has been trending recently.  11.Qxe2  Qa6  Now, after  12.a4!  Securing the b5 square for the knight, White definitely has slightly better chances and Black has scored quite poorly from this position. Dogan,N @@StartBracket@@2272@@EndBracket@@-Nalbant,T @@StartBracket@@2340@@EndBracket@@ Konya 2018   10...d6  is the most popular move and the old way of playing in this position.  11.O-O  Bxe2  12.Qxe2  Qa6  13.Qd1!  avoiding the exchange of queens and planning to play Qd1-c2 and then later on slowly consolidating on the queenside. I believe White is slightly better here, though Black always has a typical Benko compensation. }
11. e5 Ng4 12. Nb5
{ This is the best way for White to fight for an advantage which most White players may not be even aware of. Now the play takes a forced path for a few moves. }
12... Qe4 13. O-O Bxb5
{ Black eliminates White's active b5-knight before capturing the e5-pawn. } 14.
Bxb5 Nxe5 15. Nxe5 Qxe5 16. Bc3 Qd6
{ With previous aggressive moves Black has managed to regain his pawn but he has fallen slightly behind in development as his b8-knight has not come in the game yet. White will try to utilize this time to consolidate his hold on the queenside and create some pressure. Black's plan here is simple. We would like to play Nb8-a6, when the knight can further go to b4 @@StartBracket@@or c7 in some cases@@EndBracket@@ and put pressure on the d5-pawn. Next, we would like to play . ..Rfd8 and break in the centre with e7-e6 at an appropriate moment. If White's play Qd1-d2 and it is unsupported then we can exploit the pin on the d5-pawn by pushing our e-pawn to e5 directly or transferring our knight to d4 or a5 via c6 with Nb4-c6-d4 or a5. }
17. Bxg7 Kxg7 18. a4 Na6 19. Re1
{ White brings his rook to the open file and hopes to put some pressure on the e7-pawn. Black's response is anyways going to be quite similar, bring the knight to b4 and prepare to break with e7-e6 at the right moment. }
19... Nb4
{ our knight is very stable on the b4 square.   19...Rfb8  1-0 @@StartBracket@@54@@EndBracket@@ Prieto Aranguren,A @@StartBracket@@2261@@EndBracket@@-Habans Aguerrea,J @@StartBracket@@1930@@EndBracket@@ San Sebastian 2018 }
20. Bc4 Rfd8
{ The rook belongs to the d-file where it will help us break with ...e6. } 21.
Qd2
{ As mentioned in earlier comments, with the white queen unprotected on d2 we should look out for ideas to exploit the pin on the d5-pawn. Here we can go for, }
21... e5
{ Black wants to play ... Qf6 followed by ...d6, setting up pawns on the dark squares. }
22. Re2 Qf6 23. d6 { preventing Black's plan. } 23... Nc6
{ The knight is transferred to a much powerful central square  d4  . Black is doing completely fine in this position as the knight on  d4  will dominate the centre and easily compensate for White's passed a-pawn. A sample variation could be,  24.Qd5  Preventing ...Nd4 for now.  24...Re8  defending the e5-pawn and preparing ...Nd4 again.  25.Qxc5  Nd4  26.Re4  Rab8  27.Rb1  Rec8  it is time to team up the rooks and create counterplay  28.Qd5  Rb4!  29.Bf1  Rxa4  30.Qxe5  Qxe5  31.Rxe5  White has managed to win a pawn, but after  31...Rb4=  with the idea to play ... Rcb8 attacking the pawn on b2. White's d6-pawn is also a bit weak and prone to fall. All these factors coupled with a nicely positioned knight on d4 gives Black at least an equal position }
