[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "33. Benko Gambit Accepted: Mainline 5.bxa6 Part 1"]
[Black "Mainline 5.bxa6 with 8.a7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. cxb5 a6 5. bxa6 g6 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. e4 O-O
{ This is a critical point where White has three main lines. } 8. a7
{ White sacrifices the pawn one square forward in order to lure the black rook to the a7 square where it can prove to be vulnerable. }
8... Rxa7 9. Nf3 e6
{ This is the correct way of playing here. We would like to capture ... exd5 after White recaptures with the pawn we may use the open e-file for creating counterplay. The placement of the rook on a7 supports this idea as we can double on the e-file with ...Re7 and ...Re8. With the rook on a7, we can also think of doubling and putting pressure down the a-file.   With the rook on  a7  , our main idea of,  9...Qa5  does not work due to,  10.Bd2  and now if,  10...Ba6??  then White has  11.Nb5!+-  attacking the queen on a5 as well as the rook on a7. This is White's main point of giving up his a-pawn on a7 so that Black's rook on a7 can be used for such tactics. }
10. dxe6
{ in inferior as it opens up lines for the black pieces. Since White is behind in development he should avoid opening such lines. }
10... dxe6
{ A surprising recapture! 10...dxe6 has been played in only 1 game till now, but it is better than the typical recapture 10...fxe6 which has been played in 9 games till now. }
11. Qxd8 Rxd8
{ Now we would like to develop our bishop on b7 hitting the e4-pawn. If White defends the e4-pawn with Nf3-d2 then we can play Nb8-c6 followed by establishing our knight on the d4 square. }
12. Be3
{ This move is the best according to Stockfish. It has a very subtle idea of provoking the Black to b7 so that it creates problems in the development of Black's light-squared bishop.   12.Bb5  this move was played by GM Babula in the only game that was played with the move 10...de6.  12...Bb7  13.Nd2  Now as mentioned earlier, with the white knight absent from f3 we should play,  13...Nc6  N  intending to plant our knight on the powerful central d4 square.   13...Na6  1-0 @@StartBracket@@29@@EndBracket@@ Babula, V @@StartBracket@@2559@@EndBracket@@ -Balog, I @@StartBracket@@2566@@EndBracket@@ Slovakia SVK 2019  14.Bxc6?!   14.O-O  Nd4  Gives Black a very strong compensation due to the strong d4 knight and under-developed white queenside.  14...Bxc6  15.O-O  Nd7  Black stands slightly better here due to active pieces and low development for White on the queenside. }
12... Rb7 13. Bg5
{ it is essential for White to eliminate the f6 knight before playing e4-e5. Otherwise, the e5-pawn would come under a quick attack. }
13... h6 14. Bxf6 Bxf6 15. e5 Bg7 16. Bb5
{ developing the bishop as well as protecting the b2-pawn. } 16... g5
{ threatening to play ...g4. } 17. h3 Rc7
{ Black now intends to develop fianchetto the bishop with ...Bb7. } 18. Rd1 Rf8
{ we should avoid exchanging rooks as we can use them later on the open a- and b-files. }
19. O-O Bb7 20. Rfe1 Bxf3
{ immediately ruining White's pawn structure before the knight escapes from f3. }
21. gxf3 Nc6 22. Bxc6 Rxc6
{ Black is still a pawn down but White's e5-pawn is very weak which needs constant attention from White's pieces. Black can play Rf8-b8 and if White replies with b2-b3 then c5-c4 opening up lines on the queenside even more. We can also plan to activate our king with Kg8-h7-g6-f5. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "33. Benko Gambit Accepted: Mainline 5.bxa6 Part 1"]
[Black "Mainline 5.bxa6 with 8.a7 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. cxb5 a6 5. bxa6 g6 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. e4 O-O
{ This is a critical point where White has three main lines. } 8. a7
{ White sacrifices the pawn one square forward in order to lure the black rook to the a7 square where it can prove to be vulnerable. }
8... Rxa7 9. Nf3 e6
{ This is the correct way of playing here. We would like to capture ... exd5 after White recaptures with the pawn we may use the open e-file for creating counterplay. The placement of the rook on a7 supports this idea as we can double on the e-file with ...Re7 and ...Re8. With the rook on a7, we can also think of doubling and putting pressure down the a-file.   With the rook on  a7  , our main idea of,  9...Qa5  does not work due to,  10.Bd2  and now if,  10...Ba6??  then White has  11.Nb5!+-  attacking the queen on a5 as well as the rook on a7. This is White's main point of giving up his a-pawn on a7 so that Black's rook on a7 can be used for such tactics. }
10. Be2 exd5 11. exd5 d6 12. O-O
{ White has completed his kingside development and is a pawn up. But Black will exert pressure on the queenside in a typical Benko style on the a- and b-files supported by a strong bishop on g7 which exerts pressure on the long diagonal a1-h8. Another important point to note here is that in the absence of e-pawns from the board, the white pawn on d5 can also become a target for the black pieces. Usually, a white pawn stands on e4 giving protection to the d5-pawn, but here Black has ideas like ...Bb7, ...Qa8, ... Nb4 in order to pressurize the d5-pawn. }
12... Na6
{ We start with developing our knight. This knight can further go to c7 or b4 according to the situation. }
13. Nb5 Rd7
{ protecting the d6-pawn in advance which can be threatened by moves like Bc1-f4. }
14. Bc4
{ White in turn protects his d5-pawn in advance, before Black starts piling up pressure on it. }
14... Bb7 15. Bg5 h6
{ 15...Qa8  1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@90@@EndBracket@@ Wang,A @@StartBracket@@2384@@EndBracket@@ -Sliwicka,A @@StartBracket@@2317@@EndBracket@@ chess.com INT 2020 }
16. Bh4 g5 { pushing the bishop back to g3. } 17. Bg3 Nb4
{ the d5-pawn is about the fall. If White defends it with Nc3 then we have ...Qa8 when the pawn could not be defended anymore. }
18. Qb3 Bxd5 19. Bxd5 Nbxd5 20. Rfd1
{ White tries to put pressure on the d5-knight and the d6-pawn behind it. }
20... Qb6 21. a4 Qb7
{ it is better to protect the d5-knight from b7 as it also keeps the white knight on b5 pinned to the queen.   21...Qc6  0-1 @@StartBracket@@35@@EndBracket@@ Godart,F @@StartBracket@@2439@@EndBracket@@-Maenhout,T @@StartBracket@@2377@@EndBracket@@ Bruges BEL 2020 }
22. Nd2 Rfd8 23. Nxd6 { loses to, } 23... Qxb3 24. Nxb3 Nf4
{ cutting the support of the d6-knight which is about to fall soon. } *

