[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "33. Benko Gambit Accepted: Mainline 5.bxa6 Part 1"]
[Black "Mainline 5.bxa6 with 8.Bc4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. cxb5 a6 5. bxa6 g6 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. e4 O-O
{ This is a critical point where White has three main lines. } 8. Bc4
{ This is an interesting move recommended by GM Sam Shankland in his Chessable course : Lifetime Repertoires: Sam Shankland's 1. d4 - Part 1: Sidelines. Without looking at this course I would have never covered this move at all! He did a great job of finding a rare move which gives White good chances to fight for an advantage. With that being said, with good logical moves, Black achieves a comfortable position without any troubles. }
8... Qa5 { As usual we bring our queen to the offense early on! } 9. a7
{ a nice intermediate move that throws a spanner in the works. } 9... Qxa7
{ 9...Nxe4??  does not work here due to,  10.axb8Q  Rxb8  11.Nge2+-  and White escapes with firm support on the  c3  knight. This is one of the advantages for White of not developing the knight early to  f3  . }
10. Nf3 Ba6
{ we continue with our main idea, challenging White's light-squared bishop. }
11. Nd2 d6 12. O-O Nbd7 13. a4
{ A typical pawn advance for White, gaining a little space on the queenside and covering the b5 square which can be used by the c3-knight. }
13... Ne5
{ This is a better square to attack the c4-bishop compared to the b6-square. From e5 we also aim to infiltrate on d3.   13...Nb6  was GM Shankland's recommendation in his repertoire. }
14. Bxa6 Qxa6 15. Nb5 Rfc8 16. b3
{ White covers the c4 square and intends to develop the bishop on b2. Now, before White is able to settle down and consolidate, it is high time to break on the queenside with, }
16... c4
{ A typical break on the queenside in this pawn structure. After the exchange of Black's c-pawn and White's b-pawn, the white pawn on a4 will feel very lonely. }
17. Bb2 cxb3 18. Qxb3
{ It seems White has consolidated his extra pawn and is all set to advance his a-pawn. But with our next move, we curb all White's hopes to play for an advantage. }
18... Nfd7
{ a nice manoeuvre of the knight to the c5-square. From c5 the black knight strongly threatens the a4-pawn and also increases its control on the d3 square. }
19. Rfb1 Qa5 20. Bc3 Nf3+ { This tactic helps Black equalize the game. } 21.
Nxf3 Bxc3 22. Ra2 Bf6
{ our bishop is well placed on the long-diagonal and we are ready to play ...Nc5. }
23. g3 Nc5 24. Qc2 Nxa4
{ A risky looking move, voluntarily walking into the pin on the a-file. But due to concrete reasons, Black has nothing to worry about as we will see from the sample variations. }
25. Qd1 Rc4
{ 25...Rcb8  is another fine alternative for Black.  26.Nfd4  Bxd4  27.Nxd4  Rxb1  28.Qxb1  Qb6!  29.Qa1  Qb4=  and there is no way for White to win our a4-knight. }
26. Qb3 Rcc8 { now we are threatening to pin White's b5 knight with ...Rfc8. }
27. Nfd4 Bxd4 28. Nxd4 Qc3
{ with this nice tactical idea Black escapes from the deadly pin on the a4-knight. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "33. Benko Gambit Accepted: Mainline 5.bxa6 Part 1"]
[Black "Mainline 5.bxa6 with 8.e5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. cxb5 a6 5. bxa6 g6 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. e4 O-O
{ This is a critical point where White has three main lines. } 8. e5
{ I believe this is the most challenging move and a nightmare for most of the Benko players, including me. White straight away starts an onslaught against the black king. This variation requires very concrete handling, so I would urge the readers to remember the variations as well as understand them well. }
8... Ne8 9. Nf3
{ Protects the e5-pawn but the more White holds h2-h4 the weaker the attack on the kingside gets. }
9... d6
{ Now White has many options available and I have focused on the most critical one and analysed the not so challenging lines briefly. }
10. e6 { is an interesting pawn sacrifice. } 10... fxe6 11. h4
{ 11.dxe6  can easily be met by  11...Nxa6  intending to play ...Bb7 and then ...d5.  12.h4  this signals that White won't be going for 0-0 anytime soon. So, we can open up the centre immediately with,  12...d5!  13.Nxd5  Bxe6  14.Nf4  Qxd1+  15.Kxd1  Bg4  and Black has a clear advantage in this endgame because of White's weak king position. }
11... Nf6
{ this knight is a very useful defensive piece for Black, covering the h5 square. }
12. dxe6
{ 12.h5  gxh5  13.Ng5   13.dxe6?  d5  gives Black initiative in the centre.  13...Nxa6!  the knight is ready to go to b4 creating pressure on the d5-pawn and the queenside.   13...exd5?  is bad due to,  14.Nxd5  e6  15.Nxf6+  Qxf6  16.Qc2  Qe5+  17.Be2  Rf5  18.f4  with a strong attack for White on the kingside.  14.dxe6   14.Rxh5?  seems very attractive, but it does not work due to,  14...Nb4  15.dxe6  Qe8!  the queen not only threatens the h5-rook but also intends to go to g6 from where it eyes the c2-square.  16.Rh3  Qg6  17.Bd3  Nxd3+  18.Qxd3  Qxd3  19.Rxd3  h6  and White loses his precious e6-pawn which opens up Black's light-squared bishop and give us a clear advantage.  14...Nb4  15.a3  d5!  gaining space in the centre.  16.Rb1  Nc6  Black is clearly better in this position because of our nice central control, White's e6-pawn is a target and Black has held threats on the kingside successfully. }
12... d5
{ gaining space in the centre is important for Black to create counterplay. }
13. h5 gxh5 14. Ng5 d4 { seizing more space in the centre. } 15. Nce4 Nxe4 16.
Nxe4 Qd5
{ the black queen is beautifully centralized on d5, giving threats at the same time. }
17. Bd3 { is bad for White due to, } 17... c4
{ and White is unable to handle the threats to his pieces. } 18. Rxh5 Qxe6
{ with a winning advantage for Black due to White's vulnerable king in the centre. }
*

