13... Nf6
{ Of course we don't want to push the pawns on the kingside and create weaknesses for ourselves.   13...h6?  1-0 @@StartBracket@@48@@EndBracket@@ Salomon, J @@StartBracket@@2499@@EndBracket@@-Semjonovs, I @@StartBracket@@2370@@EndBracket@@ Riga LAT 2019   Black also has an interesting counter-attacking solution in,  13...c4!?  N hitting the f2-pawn.  14.Qc2  Nxa6  15.Be3  Nb4  16.Qd2  and just when White seems to have rebuffed Black's counter, now we have a surprising resource -  16...Bd4!  Eliminating White's strong defender - the bishop on e3.  17.Nxh7  Bxe3  18.fxe3  Rf7  19.Ng5  and now it is time for another surprising move!  19...Nc2+!  20.Qxc2  Qxe3+  21.Be2  Qxg5  22.Ne4  Qe5∞  even after so much mess, the material is still level! It is very difficult to assess such situations. Black's minor pieces are still undeveloped while the c4-pawn is weak. On the other hand, White's king is still in the centre and also cannot 0-0-0 immediately. Overall, the position is very dynamic and both sides have their chances. Having said that I would still pick Black because of a safer king. }
