{ This is the main point behind White's previous move. He has kicked our knight from f6 so that he can use the absence of the knight by immediately creating pressure on the kingside with h2-h4-h5. }
9... Bxe5
{ I believe this is Black's best try to fight in this position. It is essential to eliminate the e5-pawn immediately so that we can arrange our pieces appropriately in order to face White's onslaught. Once we address and slow down White's kingside attack then we can focus on creating our own counterplay.   9...d6  seems like a reasonable alternative and I spent many hours analysing this line. But in the end I decided to drop it as I was not able to find a satisfactory reply to,  10.e6!  Nf6  It's necessary to bring the knight back in order to slow down White's attack.   10...fxe6?  is bad due to  11.h5!  and White gets a crushing attack on the kingside. So, W @@StartBracket@@2780@@EndBracket@@-Vidit, S @@StartBracket@@2718@@EndBracket@@ chess.com INT 2018  11.h5!  Nevertheless going for it.  11...Nxh5  12.g4  Nf6  13.g5  Nh5  14.Be2!  Now is the correct time to attack the black knight as the f6 square is no longer available for it.   14.Rxh5?  is very tempting but not that great due to,  14...gxh5  15.Bd3  Qe8!  Black prepares a sneaky trick!  16.Qxh5  f5!  with this trick Black manages to escape.  17.Qxe8  Rxe8  18.Bxf5  Nxa6  White still has slightly better chances due to the material advantage, but the position remains pretty dynamic and unclear according to me.  14...Qa5  15.Bxh5!   15.Bd2  is possible but it just distracts White from his main idea of taking on h5. Black can now play,  15...Qb4  16.Bxh5??  is not possible now due to,  16...Bxc3!  17.Bxc3  Qe4+-+  and Black wins the  h1  rook.  15...Bxc3+   15...gxh5?  16.Bd2+-  followed by taking on  h5  wins for White.  16.bxc3  Qxc3+  17.Bd2  Qe5+  18.Be2  fxe6  19.dxe6  Bxa6  20.f4  Even after taking the e6-pawn White is ahead in material. Although Black has some compensation for it because of White's exposed king, but I am afraid it is not sufficient for equality.   9...h5?  is a typical way to stop the h4-h5 advance and can be seen in many openings. But here it simply collapses because White does not waste time and breaks immediately with,  10.g4!  N  With a crushing attack on the kingside for White. }
10. Bh6
{ This is the accurate way to put pressure. White's best setup is to put the bishop on h6 and the queen on d2. If White delays going for this, then Black will prevent it from happening immediately and to make it happen later on will be time-consuming for White. Timing and tactics are the two most crucial factors in this variation! }
10... Ng7
{ The best way to block the bishop on h6. The knight can also serve some defensive purposes from g7.   10...Bg7?!  is objectively bad but can be given a practical try as White too needs to find the best moves to come on top.  11.Qd2  Qb6!?  threatening to take on h6 and then on b2.   11...Bxa6  is also the move I investigated. White may continue with,  12.h5  Qb6  13.hxg6  fxg6  N  this is usually the best way of re-capturing on g6.   13...Qxg6  1-0 @@StartBracket@@45@@EndBracket@@ Thomas, A @@StartBracket@@2178@@EndBracket@@ -Belluire, B @@StartBracket@@1913@@EndBracket@@ Vandoeuvre les Nancy FRA 2019  14.Nf3  Qf6  Black seems to be holding on, but now White comes up with an elegant manoeuvre  15.Rh4!  Nd6  16.Bxg7  Qxg7  17.Ra4!  suddenly White switches all his attention from the kingside to the queenside.  17...Bxf1  18.Kxf1  Rxa4  19.Nxa4  Na6  20  Re1±  threatening Qd2-e2 White stands clearly better because of Black's weak pawn structure and uncoordinated pieces.  12.h5!  not afraid of Black's threats!  12...Bxh6  13.Qxh6  Qxb2  14.Rc1  Nf6  Black hangs on. But White now brings another piece into the action.  15.hxg6  fxg6  16.Bd3!  Bxa6  17.Bxg6  and just when it seems all over for Black, he finds a life-saving resource!  17...Qxf2+!!  a beautiful queen sacrifice.  18.Kxf2  Ng4+  19.Kg3  Nxh6  20.Rxh6  hxg6  This is a very curious position. With a series of tactical moves, Black has managed to hold against White's fierce attack and even managed to win an extra pawn. But the cost of all this was lack of development and White's active pieces. So even though Black has safely transposed to an endgame White keeps the initiative due to his active pieces.  21.Nf3  White does not take on g6 yet because activity is more important than pawns for him!  21...Kg7  22.Rch1  Bd3  23.Ne5  Bf5  24.Rh7+  Kf6  25.Ng4+!  Kg5  Black seems to be miraculously fending off White's threats, but now after  26.a4!  ±  With a king on g5 Black's position still remains uncomfortable. Kudos to your opponent if he manages to find these good moves from the white side! Or you might also consider calling the arbiter and checking him :@@EndBracket@@ }
11. Nf3 Bf6 12. h5 d6
{ We have reached a critical juncture where White has to decide how to continue with the attack. I have analysed two possibilities for White.   Black can also start with,  12...Qa5  But it gives White an additional option of  13.Bd2  though, after   13.Qd2  d6  14.Ng5  transposes to the mainline  13...Bxa6  14.hxg6  fxg6  15.Ne4  Qb6  16.Bc3  Bxf1  17.Kxf1  Bxc3  18.bxc3  Qb2!  ∞  Thanks to his active queen and counterplay on the queenside, Black manages to hold the balance and avoids any immediate knock-out blow on the kingside. }
13. Ng5
{ with this active knight sortie White starts putting pressure on the kingside straight away. }
13... Qa5
{ a5 is usually the best place for the queen in this variation and in Benko Gambit in general. From a5, the black queen puts pressure on the c3 knight and also plan to capture on a6 with the c8 bishop. If White recaptures on a6 then we can, in turn, recapture with our queen on a6. }
14. Rc1 Bxa6 { White can also try the forcing, } 15. Bxa6 Qxa6 16. Bxg7 Bxg7
17. hxg6 fxg6 18. Nxh7 Rf5
{ the rook is actively placed on f5, also covering the return square of the h7 knight. }
19. Qg4 Qd3 { Black finds a nice way of defending the g6-pawn. } 20. Ne2 Qxd5
{ Black has managed to gobble up the central d5-pawn. The position still remains complex but Black is already completely OK in this position. }
*

