{ The best way to block the bishop on h6. The knight can also serve some defensive purposes from g7.   10...Bg7?!  is objectively bad but can be given a practical try as White too needs to find the best moves to come on top.  11.Qd2  Qb6!?  threatening to take on h6 and then on b2.   11...Bxa6  is also the move I investigated. White may continue with,  12.h5  Qb6  13.hxg6  fxg6  N  this is usually the best way of re-capturing on g6.   13...Qxg6  1-0 @@StartBracket@@45@@EndBracket@@ Thomas, A @@StartBracket@@2178@@EndBracket@@ -Belluire, B @@StartBracket@@1913@@EndBracket@@ Vandoeuvre les Nancy FRA 2019  14.Nf3  Qf6  Black seems to be holding on, but now White comes up with an elegant manoeuvre  15.Rh4!  Nd6  16.Bxg7  Qxg7  17.Ra4!  suddenly White switches all his attention from the kingside to the queenside.  17...Bxf1  18.Kxf1  Rxa4  19.Nxa4  Na6  20  Re1±  threatening Qd2-e2 White stands clearly better because of Black's weak pawn structure and uncoordinated pieces.  12.h5!  not afraid of Black's threats!  12...Bxh6  13.Qxh6  Qxb2  14.Rc1  Nf6  Black hangs on. But White now brings another piece into the action.  15.hxg6  fxg6  16.Bd3!  Bxa6  17.Bxg6  and just when it seems all over for Black, he finds a life-saving resource!  17...Qxf2+!!  a beautiful queen sacrifice.  18.Kxf2  Ng4+  19.Kg3  Nxh6  20.Rxh6  hxg6  This is a very curious position. With a series of tactical moves, Black has managed to hold against White's fierce attack and even managed to win an extra pawn. But the cost of all this was lack of development and White's active pieces. So even though Black has safely transposed to an endgame White keeps the initiative due to his active pieces.  21.Nf3  White does not take on g6 yet because activity is more important than pawns for him!  21...Kg7  22.Rch1  Bd3  23.Ne5  Bf5  24.Rh7+  Kf6  25.Ng4+!  Kg5  Black seems to be miraculously fending off White's threats, but now after  26.a4!  ±  With a king on g5 Black's position still remains uncomfortable. Kudos to your opponent if he manages to find these good moves from the white side! Or you might also consider calling the arbiter and checking him :@@EndBracket@@ }
11. Nf3 Bf6 12. h5 d6
{ We have reached a critical juncture where White has to decide how to continue with the attack. I have analysed two possibilities for White.   Black can also start with,  12...Qa5  But it gives White an additional option of  13.Bd2  though, after   13.Qd2  d6  14.Ng5  transposes to the mainline  13...Bxa6  14.hxg6  fxg6  15.Ne4  Qb6  16.Bc3  Bxf1  17.Kxf1  Bxc3  18.bxc3  Qb2!  ∞  Thanks to his active queen and counterplay on the queenside, Black manages to hold the balance and avoids any immediate knock-out blow on the kingside. }
13. Ng5
{ with this active knight sortie White starts putting pressure on the kingside straight away. }
13... Qa5
{ a5 is usually the best place for the queen in this variation and in Benko Gambit in general. From a5, the black queen puts pressure on the c3 knight and also plan to capture on a6 with the c8 bishop. If White recaptures on a6 then we can, in turn, recapture with our queen on a6. }
14. Rc1 Bxa6
{ this is Black's alternate idea as mentioned earlier in the comments. } 15.
Bxg7
{ 15.Qf3  an interesting alternative for White intending to transfer the queen on the h-file.  15...Qb4!  Black, as usual, seeks counterplay on the weak b2-pawn.  16.Bxa6  Nxa6  17.hxg6  fxg6  18.Qh3  Qxb2  and Black's counterplay triumphs, for example,  19.Bxg7  Qxc1+  20.Nd1  h5!  -+  Black has fended off the attack and will win material. }
15... Bxg7 16. Nxh7 Kxh7 17. hxg6+ Kg8 18. Qh5 fxg6 19. Qh7+ Kf7 20. Rh6
{ In this position, the white duo of queen and rook can get a draw at maximum from this position. There are a few ways for Black to continue safely in this position and one of them is to play, }
20... Nd7 21. Qxg6+ Kg8
{ and it is wise for White to force a draw immediately before Black manages to bring his pieces into the defence. }
22. Qh7+ Kf7 *

