{ this is a very important and critical move to remember in this position. This exchange on c3 is essential because we want our f8-rook to support our f5-bishop. We will see the point soon,   16...Kxh7?  loses by force to,  17.hxg6+  fxg6  18.Bxf5  gxf5  19.Bxg7+  Kxg7  20.Qh6+  Kf7  21.Qh5+!  leads to a mate on the next move! }
17. bxc3 Kxh7 18. hxg6+ fxg6
{ now we can see that our f8-rook is protecting the bishop on f5. } 19. Bxf5
Rxf5
{ and the black rook makes sure that we don’t get mated on the kingside. Black is fine here. }
