[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "34. Benko Gambit Accepted: Mainline 5.bxa6 Part 2"]
[Black "Mainline 5.bxa6 with 7.Nf3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. cxb5 a6 5. bxa6 g6 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Nf3 O-O 8. g3
{ The Fianchetto Variation against this type of Benko is not so effective for White here. Black has delayed the capture of the a6-pawn with the bishop and can use this fact for his own benefit by placing his pieces appropriately to maximize his counter-chances on the queenside.   8.e4  Qa5  transposes   8.a7  Rxa7  9.e4  transposes }
8... d6 9. Bg2 Nxa6
{ This is the point of delaying the capture on a6. Now, instead of the traditional capture with the bishop, we recapture on a6 with our knight so as to use our light-squared bishop on h3-c6 diagonal. White cannot achieve his optimal setup on the queenside by playing Ra1-b1 and then b2-b3 because Ra1-b1 will always be met by ...Bf5 hitting the b1 rook. Without playing Rb1 White cannot play b2-b3 because of problems on the a1-h8 diagonal.   9...Nbd7  10.O-O  Nb6  is another playable alternative for Black. }
10. O-O Bf5 11. Ne1
{ This was the choice of GM Fabiano Caruana against GM Grischuk. One of the ideas of 11.Ne1 is to play Nc2 followed by Ne3 and then settle on the c4-square. But this manuouvre is too slow and gives Black sufficient time to quickly bring the pieces to the queenside. }
11... Qb6
{ There are other possible alternatives for Black, but this was the choice of GM Grischuk and we will stick to it. Next we would like to bring our rook in action with ...Rfb8 creating pressure on the b-file. }
12. Nc2 Bxc2
{ Eliminating the knight before it reaches the strong c4-square.   13...Rfb8  1/2-1/2  (81)  (Caruana,F)  (2791)  (-Grischuk,A)  (2792)  (Dubai 2014) }
13. Qxc2 Rfb8
{ We create pressure on the b2-pawn preventing the development of White's dark-squared bishop. }
14. b3 { This advance strengthens the b-pawn but weakens the a1-h8 diagonal. }
14... Ne8
{ 14...Nb4  is another possibility for Black.  15.Qd2  and now use the vulnerability of the a1-h8 diagonal to grab the d5-Pawn with  15...Nfxd5  16.Nxd5  Nxd5  17.Bb2  Bxb2  18.Qxb2  now our d5-knight is under pressure so we support it with  18...e6  19.Rfd1  White increases the pressure on d5 and we have no way to support it further. So, we start counterplay on the queenside with the pawn break  19...c4!  20.Rxd5!  White sacrifices the exchange in order to gobble up two Black's pawns for it.  20...exd5  21.Bxd5  Ra5  22.Bxc4  Qc5=  Even though White has managed to win two pawns for the exchange, the position remains more or less balanced. Right now we are threatening to capture the bishop with ...Qxc4. Also, it is not easy for White to advance his queenside pawns as our major pieces are active and we have good control on the dark squares on the queenside. }
15. Bd2 { Protecting the c3-knight which frees White's queen. } 15... Nb4 16.
Qb2
{ It looks odd to come on the vulnerable a1-h8 diagonal, but it safer for White to avoid losing his a2-pawn.   16.Qe4?!  loses the a2-pawn for White after,  16...Bxc3!  17.Bxc3  Nxa2  18.Bd2  Ra7=  defending the e7-pawn and preparing to double on the a-file at the same time.  19.Rfb1  Nf6  20.Qc4  Rba8=+  even though material is equal and White has the bishop pair, I think it is Black who is slightly better due to the pressure on the a-file and White's weak b3-pawn. One of our ideas is to retreat the knight to b4 and then slowly exploit the weakness of the b3-pawn. }
16... Nc7 { Preparing to capture the d5-pawn. } 17. a4
{ White gives back his extra pawn in order to get rid of the pressure on the a2-pawn. }
17... Ncxd5 18. Nxd5 Nxd5 19. Qc2 Nb4
{ Forcing the opposite coloured bishops on the board. } 20. Bxb4 Qxb4 21. Bxa8
Bxa1 22. Bd5 Be5
{ Material is equal and due to the presence of the opposite coloured bishops on the board, the position is completely equal. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "34. Benko Gambit Accepted: Mainline 5.bxa6 Part 2"]
[Black "Mainline 5.bxa6 with 7.Nf3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. cxb5 a6 5. bxa6 g6 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Nf3 O-O 8. g3
{ The Fianchetto Variation against this type of Benko is not so effective for White here. Black has delayed the capture of the a6-pawn with the bishop and can use this fact for his own benefit by placing his pieces appropriately to maximize his counter-chances on the queenside.   8.e4  Qa5  transposes   8.a7  Rxa7  9.e4  transposes }
8... d6 9. Bg2 Nxa6
{ This is the point of delaying the capture on a6. Now, instead of the traditional capture with the bishop, we recapture on a6 with our knight so as to use our light-squared bishop on h3-c6 diagonal. White cannot achieve his optimal setup on the queenside by playing Ra1-b1 and then b2-b3 because Ra1-b1 will always be met by ...Bf5 hitting the b1 rook. Without playing Rb1 White cannot play b2-b3 because of problems on the a1-h8 diagonal.   9...Nbd7  10.O-O  Nb6  is another playable alternative for Black. }
10. O-O Bf5
{ Black has developed all his pieces and we are now ready to play ...Qa5 or ... Qc7 followed by bringing the f8-rook on the queenside to the b8 square. The bishop on f5 stops White's plan of Ra1-b1 followed by b2-b3. The obvious drawback is that White's knight has moved on the edge of the board further away from the centre. }
11. Nh4
{ The bishop on f5, exerting pressure on the b1-h5 diagonal, is quite annoying for White. He kicks the bishop back on the first chance and then will find his optimal setup on the queenside against Black's counterplay. }
11... Bd7
{ Now White has tried various moves in this position but Black's plan in general is quite clear. We would like to develop or queen on a5, bring our f8-rook on b8 and then manoeuvre our a6 knight to b5 via c7. Exchanging the c3 knight is favourable for us as it holds White's queenside together. Now we will examine different White ideas and see how to react against each of them. }
12. Rb1
{ This seems to be the most logical follow-up. White uses the fact that the bishop has been kicked from f5 and prepares for b2-b3. }
12... Qa5
{ This is the traditional square for the black queen in the Benko Gambit. From a5, the queen keeps an eye on the a2-pawn and the c3-knight. Black prepares to play ...Rfb8 next. }
13. Bd2 Rfb8
{ Now Black's main idea is to play Na6-c7-b5. Exchange of the knights will shake up the white queenside. }
14. Re1 { should be met with the simple, } 14... Nc7
{ preparing to offer the exchange of knights with ...Nb5.   14...Ng4  1-0 @@StartBracket@@58@@EndBracket@@ Wojtaszek,R @@StartBracket@@2637@@EndBracket@@ -Gritsak,O @@StartBracket@@2521@@EndBracket@@ Warsaw 2009 }
15. e4 Nb5 16. Nxb5 Qxb5 17. a3
{ 17.Bc3  Rxa2  18.e5  Ne8=  Black has regained his pawn and has pressure on the b2-pawn as well. The position is equal. }
17... Ng4
{ This is a typical manoeuvre of the knight to e5, especially when White's d3 square is weak. }
18. Nf3 Qb3
{ The more the pieces get exchanged, the better it is for Black. The b2-pawn is under pressure and Black has a good compensation sufficient at least for equality. }
*

