[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Maghsoodloo, Parham vs. Sarana, A., Chess.com Speed U20 Blitz 2019"]
[Result "*"]

{ In this game we will see how we can exploit White's passive play in the London System. }
1. Nf3 d5 2. d4 Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. c3
{ Not the correct move order for White. The mainline is  5.Nbd2  which is analyzed in Chapter 1. }
5... Qb6 6. Qb3 c4 { kicking the queen back. } 7. Qc2 Bf5
{ a famous tactical trick to remember! The white queen is tied down to the b2 pawn. }
8. Qc1 e6 9. Nbd2 Be7 10. Be2 O-O 11. O-O h6
{ freeing the h7 square for our light-squared bishop. } 12. b3 cxb3 13. axb3
Rfc8 { This rook is useful on the c-file. } 14. Qb2 a5
{ an important move preventing b4. } 15. Rfc1 a4
{ provoking b4 when our a-pawn will be passed. } 16. h3
{ it is hard to believe that White loses a pawn by force in this position.   16.b4  Nb8= }
16... axb3 17. Qxb3 Rxa1
{ 17...Qxb3!  was even quicker.  18.Nxb3  Ba3-+  once the rook moves from c1, we can play ...Ne4 and the c3-pawn will fall. }
18. Rxa1 Qxb3 19. Nxb3 Nd8
{ and surprisingly there is no way for White to defend his c3-pawn. Black was a clear pawn up and went on to win the game. }
20. Nc5 Bxc5 21. dxc5 Ne4 22. Nd4 Nxc3 23. Bf3 Be4 24. Ra3 Nb1 25. Ra2 Bxf3 26.
gxf3 f6 27. Bd6 Nc3 28. Rc2 Na4 29. Ra2 Nc3 30. Ra3 Nb1 31. Rd3 Ra8 32. Bc7 e5
33. Nb5 Ne6 34. Rxd5 Ra2 35. Bb6 Rb2 36. Nd6 Nc3 37. Rd3 Na4 38. Nc8 Naxc5 39.
Bxc5 Nxc5 40. Rd5 Rc2 41. Ne7+ Kf7 42. Nf5 b5 43. Rd6 b4 44. Rb6 b3 45. Kg2 b2
46. Nd6+ Ke7 47. Ne4 Nxe4 48. fxe4 h5 49. Kg3 g5 50. h4 g4 51. f3 gxf3 52. Kxf3
Kd7 53. Rb3 Kc6 54. Rb8 Kc7 55. Rb4 Kd6 56. Rb8 Kc5 57. Rc8+ Kb4 58. Rxc2 b1=Q
59. Rf2 Qg1 60. Ke2 Qg4+ 61. Kd3 Qxh4 62. Rb2+ Kc5 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Kravtsiv, Martyn vs. Bok, Benjamin, European Championship 2018, Georgia"]
[Result "*"]

{ A nice strategic victory by GM Bok Benjamin in the mainline of Chapter 1. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 d5 3. Nf3 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 cxd4 6. exd4 Qb6 7. Nb3 Bf5 8.
a4 a6
{ An important move to prevent a5-a6 pawn march.   8...e6?!  allows,  9.a5  Qd8  10.a6±  when our queenside light squares become weak. }
9. a5 Qd8 10. Bd3 Bxd3 11. Qxd3 e6 12. O-O Be7 13. Ne5 O-O
{ Black should not have allowed alternation in the pawn structure.   13...Rc8  is a typical response to Ne5 so that we are ready to meet Nxc6 with Rxc6. Next we can go ahead with 0-0. }
14. Nxc6 bxc6 15. Rfc1 Qd7 16. c4 Qb7 17. Nc5 Bxc5 18. dxc5
{ right now White's dark-squared bishop on f4 is slightly annoying as it covers important squares like b8. Bok finds a nice plan to restrict White's bishop. }
18... Rfd8 19. Be5 Ne8 { intending to advance the pawns with ...f6 and ...e5. }
20. f4 { covering the e5 square and preventing Black's advance with ...e5. }
20... f6 21. Bc3 dxc4 22. Qxc4 Rd5
{ Black starts playing on the light squares. } 23. Rd1 Rad8 24. Rxd5 Rxd5 25.
Re1 Nc7 26. Re3 Qb5 27. Qxb5 cxb5 28. b4 Rd1+ 29. Kf2 Kf7 30. Ke2
{ 30.Re1  was better when the endgame remains balanced. } 30... Nd5
{ a nice trick missed by White. } 31. c6
{ 31.Rf3  Rg1  32.Kf2  Rb1∓  when white is still under strong pressure. } 31...
Rc1 32. Kd2 Rxc3 33. Rxc3 Nxc3 34. Kxc3
{ 34.c7  does not work due to,  34...Ne4+  35.Kd3  Nd6-+  and the knight catches the White pawn. }
34... Ke7 35. Kd4 Kd6 36. c7 Kxc7 37. Kc5 h5 38. g3 g6 39. h3 g5 40. fxg5 fxg5
41. g4 h4 42. Kd4 Kd6 43. Ke4 e5 44. Kf5 Kd5 45. Kxg5 e4 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Artemiev, Vladislav vs. Dubov, Daniil, Russian Blitz Championship 2019, Sochi"]
[Result "*"]

{ In this game we will see how Black skillfully exploits White's queenside weaknesses while managing to avoid any threats on the kingside at the same time. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 d5 3. Bxf6 gxf6 4. e3 c5 5. dxc5 e6 6. c4 dxc4 7. Nd2 c3 8.
bxc3 Bxc5
{ is general it's preferable to have our dark-squared bishop on the kingside.   8...Nd7!?  is the main move of our repertoire. }
9. Ngf3 Qc7 { Black is not committing his king to the kingside yet. } 10. Bd3
Nd7
{ The knight should be developed on d7 in this structure so that it also helps in the defence. }
11. O-O b6 12. Nd4 Bb7 13. Nb5 Qb8 14. Be4 a6 15. Nd4 f5 16. Bxb7 Qxb7 17. Qh5
{ a typical square for the White queen in this structure, but with the Black still in the centre it loses its value. }
17... Nf6 18. Qh4 Be7 19. Qh3 Rc8
{ the first step towards pressurizing White's queenside. } 20. c4 O-O 21. Rab1
Kh8 { tucking the king in the corner. } 22. Qf3 Qc7 23. g3 Nd7
{ A nice regrouping of the pieces by Dubov! Improving the position of the knight and then the bishop. }
24. Qe2 Nc5 25. N2f3 Bf6 { the bishop reaches its favourite a1-h8 diagonal. }
26. Qb2 Rb8 27. Rfd1 Rfd8 28. Qc2 Ne4 29. Ne2
{ the decisive mistake losing a pawn. } 29... b5 30. Rxd8+ Rxd8 31. Rc1 Rc8 32.
Nd2 Nxd2 33. Qxd2 bxc4
{ Black is a clear pawn up and he converted it into a full point. } 34. Nd4 c3
35. Qe2 Bxd4 36. exd4 c2 37. Qxa6 Qc3 38. Qe2 Qb2 39. Qe5+ Kg8 40. Qe3 Qxa2 41.
Qg5+ Kf8 42. Qh6+ Ke8 43. Qxh7 Qb2 44. Qg8+ Kd7 45. Qg5 Qxd4 46. h4 Rb8 47. Qh5
Qd2 48. Qxf7+ Kd6 49. Rxc2 Qxc2 50. Qa7 Rb1+ *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Mensch, Etienne vs. Banikas, Hristos,  French Team Championship Gp-B 2003, France"]
[Result "*"]

{ In this game we will see how Black can dominate with his double bishops in the Trompowsky. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 d5 3. Bxf6 gxf6 4. e3 c5 5. Nc3 cxd4 6. exd4 h5
{ an interesting strategy. Whenever we have an isolated pawn on the 'a' or 'h' files, it is usually better to push it down the board and gain space before it becomes a weakness.   6...Bf5!?  is the recommended move in our repertoire. }
7. Nf3
{ 7.Qf3!  forcing Black to play,  7...e6  8.O-O-O  is the correct way for White to play in this position. }
7... Nc6 8. Bb5 h4
{ Black intends to play ...h3 weakening White's light squares. } 9. h3 Qd6 10.
Qe2 Bd7 11. O-O-O e6 12. Kb1 O-O-O
{ Black is already slightly better. He has nice space on the kingside and he can slowly start creating play on the queenside as well. }
13. Bxc6 Qxc6 14. Ka1 Kb8 15. g4 hxg3 16. fxg3 Rc8 17. Nd2 Bb4 18. Ndb1 Bd6 19.
g4 b5 { with very move Black is creating one threat or the other. } 20. Rc1 Bf4
{ 20...b4!  21.Nd1  f5  22.gxf5  exf5-+  was crushing. White is too passive to hold this game. }
21. Rcf1 Bg5 22. h4 { now White gets good counterplay. } 22... Bxh4 23. Rh3 b4
24. Qh2+ Qc7 25. Qh1 bxc3 26. Nxc3 Qb6 27. Rd1 Rc4 28. Rxh4 Rhc8 29. Qh2+ Ka8
30. Rh8 Be8 31. Qf2 { 31.Qd2= } 31... Rb8
{ 31...Rxc3-+  was winning on the spot!  32.bxc3  Rb8-+  leads to a mate on the b-file. }
32. Rb1 Qxd4 33. Qg3 Qe5 34. Qd3 f5 35. Rh5 Rxg4 36. Qa6 Rgb4 37. Rh3 d4 38.
Nd1 Ra4 39. Qf1 Qd5 40. a3 Bb5 41. Qf2 Bc6 42. Qh2 e5 43. Rh8 Bd7 44. Rxb8+
Kxb8 45. Qh8+ Kc7 46. Qf8 Ra5 47. Qe7 Qe6 48. Qf8 f6 49. Nf2 Qd6 50. Qf7 Qe6
51. Qf8 Rb5 52. Rg1 Qd6 53. Qf7 e4 54. Rg7 Rc5 55. Qb3 d3 56. Qa4 a5 57. cxd3
e3 58. Rxd7+ Qxd7 59. Qf4+ Re5 *

