{ In this game we will see how White's pawn advance on the kingside in the Jobava Attack can lead to weaknesses. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Bf4 a6 4. e3 Bf5 5. Nf3 e6 6. Ne5 Nfd7
{ 6...Nbd7  is the suggested move in our repertoire. } 7. g4 Bg6 8. h4 Nxe5 9.
Bxe5 h5 { a typical move to halt White's pawn advance. } 10. Bd3 Bxd3 11. cxd3
hxg4
{ with the move 9...h5, Black has managed to shatter White's kingside pawn chain. }
12. Qxg4 Nd7 13. h5 Nxe5 14. dxe5 c5 15. O-O-O Qd7 16. d4 cxd4 17. Rxd4 O-O-O
18. Kb1 Kb8 19. Rc1 f6
{ it is time to start rolling the pawns. With ...f6 the g7-pawn is also protected now and Black's f8 bishop is free to move. }
20. exf6 gxf6 21. e4 Bc5 22. Rd3 d4 23. Ne2 Bb6
{ the passed pawn on d4 always ties one of White's pieces. } 24. Qf4+ Ka7 25.
Qxf6 Qb5 26. Rb3
{ White crumbles under pressure.   26.Rcd1  was better, when there is still a lot to play for White. }
26... Qxe2 27. Qxe6 Ba5 28. Qe7 Rb8 29. Qc5+ b6 30. Qxd4 Rhd8
{ Black has managed to co-ordinate his pieces and White does not have sufficient compensation for the exchange. }
31. Qg7+ Rb7 32. Re3 Qxf2 33. Qg3 Qd2 34. a3 b5 35. e5 Bb6 36. Rec3 Qh6 37. Qg4
Re8 38. Rc6 Qh7+ 39. Ka1 Rxe5 40. h6 Rbe7 41. a4 bxa4 42. Qb4 Rb5 43. Qa3 Rb7
