{ In this game we will see how with good knight manoeuvres Black gains the bishop pair and exploits it with good play in the endgame. }
1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. Nbd2 e6 5. Bd3 Nc6 6. O-O Bd6 7. c3 O-O 8. dxc5
Bxc5 9. b4 Bb6 { 9...Bd6  is recommended in our repertoire. } 10. Ba3 Re8 11.
e4 { Now white plans to play b5 followed by e5. } 11... Ng4
{ a nice knight manoeuvre to seize the e5-square. This is especially effective after White has played e4 as after we play ...Ng4 there is some pressure on the f2-pawn as well. }
12. b5
{ 12.h3  Nge5  13.Bc2  was a better way to continue for White. Although after,  13...a6=+  Black stands slightly better because her bishop is stranded on a3. }
12... Nce5 13. Nxe5 Nxe5 14. Nf3
{ White should have retained her bishop pair with,   14.Be2  even though after,  14...Bd7=+  with pressure on the b5 pawn and intending ...Rc8 Black is slightly better and White's peices look un-cordinated. }
14... Nxd3 15. Qxd3 dxe4 16. Qxe4 Qd5 17. Qe2 Qh5
{ Black now threatens to advance in the centre with ...e5. } 18. Qe5 Qxe5 19.
Nxe5
{ we have transposed into an endgame where Black has a bishop pair vs. bishop & knight. Black skilfully exploits the advantage of her bishop pair. }
19... Bc7 20. Rfe1 a6 { opening lines on the queenside. } 21. bxa6 Rxa6 22. Bb4
Rd8 23. a3 f6 24. Nc4 b5 25. Ne3 Bb7
{ the light-squared bishop has come to life! } 26. Rad1 Raa8 27. Rxd8+ Rxd8 28.
c4 bxc4 29. Nxc4 Kf7 30. h3 h5 31. Rc1 Bb8 32. Nd6+
{ a blunder that loses material. Any other decent move by White would kept good chacnes for a draw. Although Black's position is very pleasant. }
32... Rxd6 33. Bxd6 Bxd6 34. a4 Ke7 35. Rb1 Be4 36. Rb5 Bc6 37. Rxh5 Bxa4
{ and Black's two bishops outweighed White's rook. } 38. Ra5 Bd7 39. g4 e5 40.
Ra7 g5 41. Rb7 Ke6 42. Ra7 Bc6 43. Ra6 Bf3 44. Ra5 f5 45. gxf5+ Kxf5 46. Ra7 e4
