[Result "*"]

{ In this game Black plays energetic chess in the Isolated Queen's Pawn structure arising out of the Colle Opening. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. e3 d5 4. Bd3 c5 5. c3 Nc6 6. O-O Bd6 7. Nbd2 O-O 8. dxc5
Bxc5 9. e4 h6 { 9...Qc7  10.Qe2  b6  was the suggestion in our repertoire. }
10. Qe2 Qc7 11. Bc2
{ with the idea to play e5 followed by Qd3 at some point, creating a battery along the b1-h7 diagonal. }
11... a5
{ a nice move gaining space on the queenside and preventing b4. Black's next idea could be develop the light-squared bishop to a6 by playing ...b6 and then ...Ba6. }
12. a4
{ 12.e5?!  is bad due to,  12...Ng4  13.Qd3  this looks threatening, but Black has a simple anti-dote.  13...f5!  14.exf6  Nxf6∓  Black has covered the h7-square and next he can plan ...b6 followed by ...Ba6 or just playing in the centre with ...e5. }
12... b6 13. exd5
{ White transposes into an IQP structure, but opening of the e-file is bad news for him. }
13... exd5 14. Nb3 Re8 15. Qd1 Bg4 16. Qd3 Re4 17. Bd1
{ Can you find the best move for Black now? } 17... Bc8
{ Black's bishop switches diagonal and this time it is strong enough to win material.   17...Rae8-+  is a good alternative. }
18. Qd2 Ba6 19. Re1 Rae8 20. Nxc5 bxc5
{ White's position is very passive and his queenside pieces are still undeveloped. }
21. Bc2 Rxe1+ 22. Nxe1 Re2 23. Qd1 Ng4 24. Nf3 Nce5
{ Black is all set to eliminate the only defender on White's kingside - the f3-knight. White resigned. }
*

