{ In this game we will see how the Indian GM Sasikiran creates an attack using his centre control in the early g3 variation. }
1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. g3 c5 4. Bg2 cxd4 5. O-O Bd7
{ this is another useful waiting move.   5...h6  is the move in our repertoire. }
6. Bf4 Nc6 7. Nxd4 Qb6 8. Nb3 e6
{ 8...e5  9.Bg5  puts some pressure on the d5-pawn. } 9. N1d2 e5
{ since the d-file is closed now because of the d2-knight, Black goes for the desired central advance. }
10. Bg5 Be6 11. Bxf6 gxf6
{ the doubled pawns on the f-file does not bother Black as his bishop pair and central control more than compensates for the crooked pawns. }
12. e4 d4 13. Qh5 O-O-O
{ There was no hurry to O-O-O. Black could have pressurized White's queenside with,   13...a5∓  followed by ...a4. }
14. Bh3 Qc7 15. f4
{ this is a big strategical mistake. White should focus playing on the queenside rather than the kingside. Opening up the side where your king stays can backfire badly.   15.c3  opening lines of the queenside was required. }
15... Bxh3 16. Qxh3+ Kb8 17. fxe5 Nxe5 18. Rac1 h5
{ the h-pawn starts it's offensive. } 19. Rxf6 h4 20. Rf5 Be7 21. Qg2 hxg3 22.
hxg3 Rdg8 23. Nf1 Ng4 24. Rf3 Qb6 25. Rd3 Bg5
{ The bishop joins the party as well. } 26. Re1 Be3+ 27. Nxe3 Nxe3 28. Qf3 Qc7
{ and White's kingside collapses. The triumph of a smooth attack by Black. }
29. Rexe3 dxe3 30. Rxe3 Rh3 31. Kg2 Rhxg3+ 32. Qxg3 Rxg3+ 33. Rxg3 Qxc2+ 34.
Kf3 Qxb2 35. Rg2 Qc3+ 36. Kf4 a5 37. Nd2 Qc2 38. e5 Qxa2 39. Rg8+ Ka7 40. Ne4
Qc4 *

