[Result "*"]

{ In this game we will see how Black coordinates his forces to create a strong attack against the white king. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. e4 Bb4 6. Bg5 c5 7. e5 cxd4 8. Nxd4
Bxc3+
{ 8...Qa5  followed by ...Bxc3+ is the given move order in the course.  But  8...Qa5  or  8...Bxc3+  is the same thing as it transposes soon. }
9. bxc3 Qa5 10. exf6 Qxg5 11. fxg7 Qxg7 12. Qd2
{ a useful waiting move. White waits for Black to 0-0 before capturing on c4. }
12... O-O 13. Bxc4
{ Now White does not need to worry about the g2-pawn as the g-file would open up creating problems for Black. }
13... Rd8 14. Qe3 Bd7 15. O-O Nc6
{ it is favourable for Black to exchange the pieces and transpose to an endgame. }
16. Nf3 { White naturally delays exchanging as much as possible. } 16... Ne7
17. Ne5 Ng6 18. f4 Rac8 { bringing the last piece into play. } 19. Be2 Bc6
{ activating the bishop. } 20. Nxc6
{ this does not ruin White's position objectively, but it is a dubious decision for sure. The knight on e5 was not just placed but it was also effectively cutting the Black queen from play. Now the Black queen directly puts pressure on the c3-pawn. }
20... Rxc6 21. Qxa7 Qxc3
{ the exchanges in the last couple of moves have resulted in the activation of Black's pieces. Now it is White who needs to be careful as even his king is slightly exposed. }
22. Qxb7 Nxf4
{ The Black knight jumps into the game pouncing on a tactical opportunity. }
23. Bf3
{ A big slip resulting into material losses.  White could have escaped with,   23.Kh1!  a tough defensive idea to see.  23...Nxe2  24.Qxf7+  Kh8  25.Rae1!  this is the point! The brave black knight has no safe square to go as Black should always watch out for Qf6+. The safest option for Black now is to play,  25...Qg7  26.Qxg7+  Kxg7  27.Rxe2  Ra8=  followed by ...Rca6 when the endgame is very close to a draw because of less number of remaining pawns on the board. }
23... Qd4+ 24. Kh1 Nd3 25. h3
{ now it all goes downhill quickly from here.  Surprisingly,   25.Be2  would have still provided White with some saving chances.  25...Nf2+  26.Rxf2  Qxa1+  27.Bf1∞  and White wins the f7-pawn @@StartBracket@@as the c6-rook hangs as well@@EndBracket@@, which will give him good compensation for the exchange due to Black's weakened king's position. }
25... Nf2+ 26. Kh2 Rc2
{ The Black rook exerts strong pressure on the 2nd rank. } 27. Qe7 Qe5+ 28. Kg1
Nxh3+ { the crushing blow! } 29. Kh1 { 29.gxh3  Qh2  mates } 29... Nf2+ 30. Kg1
Rd3 { White's pieces are no match against the aggressive Black pieces. } 31.
Qh4 Rxf3 32. Rae1 Nh3+ { a nice finish to an amazing attack! } *

