{ In this game we will witness a rare kingside attacking plan by GM Sasikiran. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 { this is of course not our move order. We go with  2...c5 }
3. g3 c5 4. Nf3 cxd4 5. Nxd4 { Finally we have transposed to our lines. } 5...
Bb4+ 6. Bd2 Bc5
{ this deviates from our recommendation. Black wants to kick the white knight from the centre before returning back to e7.   6...Bxd2+  is the recommended move in Chapter 21. }
7. Nb3 Be7 8. Bg2 Nc6 9. O-O b6
{ Black aims to develop the light-squared bishop actively on a6. } 10. Bf4 Ba6
11. N3d2
{ White defends the c4-pawn with this knight so that the b1-knight can go to c3. }
11... O-O 12. Nc3 Nh5
{ this is a start of an interesting venture on the kingside. } 13. Be3 f5
{ Black gains space on the kingside and intends to push the f-pawn further to f4. }
14. Qa4 Bb7 15. f4
{ White prevents ...f4 but this weakens the kingside slightly and provides a hook for Black which he uses immediately. }
15... g5 16. fxg5
{ this leads to further weakening.   Something simple like,  16.Kh1  would be better, even though after,  16...gxf4  17.gxf4  Kh8↑  Black has good attacking chances on the kingside. }
16... Bxg5 17. Bxg5 Qxg5 18. Rad1 Rad8
{ bringing the last piece into the game. } 19. Nf3
{ 19.Qa3=+  was the best but a tough move to play. The white queen can contribute a lot in the defence via the 3rd rank. }
19... Qe3+ 20. Kh1 Qh6 { threatening ...Nxg3+. } 21. Kg1 Nf6
{ re-routing the knight to a deadlier post on g4. } 22. Rd3 Ng4 23. Nh4 Ne3
{ There were many ways to gain a winning advantage. But Black chooses the simplest among them, exchanging White's best defensive piece - the g2-bishop. }
24. Rf4 Nxg2 25. Nxg2 Ne5
{ it is time for the other knight to join the party! } 26. Rh4 Qg5 27. Rd6 Ng6
28. Rhd4 f4 { This killer break spells the end for White. } 29. Qxa7 fxg3 30.
h4 Qf6 *

