{ In this game, in a typical Benko Gambit structure, Black turns a complex tactical scuffle in his favour. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. Nd2 bxc4 5. e4 c3
{ Black chooses the most popular move in this position. In chapter 24, I recommend the move  5...e6 }
6. bxc3 g6 7. c4 d6 { preventing e5 before playing ...Bg7. } 8. Ngf3 Bg7 9. Rb1
O-O 10. Bd3 Nbd7 11. O-O Nb6 12. Nb3 e6
{ Black needs to challenge White's authority in the centre at some point. } 13.
h3
{ this allows a forced variation that turns out to be in Black's favour.  protecting the c4-pawn in advance was a better option.   13.Qc2= }
13... exd5 14. exd5 Ba6 15. Na5
{ 15.Qc2?!  is now strongly met by,  15...Nfxd5!  16.cxd5  c4=+  Black wins his piece back on the next move, in the meantime, he has managed to open up lines on the queenside which can be useful in order to create an initiative on the queenside. }
15... Nbxd5 { the start of a forced sequence of moves. } 16. Nc6 Nc3 17. Qe1
{ This move guarantees that White won't lose material at least. } 17... Qd7 18.
Ne7+ { this is the reason why it was essential to put the White queen on e1. }
18... Kh8 19. Nxg6+ fxg6 20. Qxc3
{ The air has cleared and we have ended up with equal material after a forced tactical sequence of moves. But the lines have opened up and Black uses them energetically to his advantage. }
20... Bb7 21. Ne1
{ this is too passive.   21.Ng5  it was essential to keep the knight active.  21...Rae8=+  covering the e6-square and exerting pressure on the e-file, Black maintains the slight edge.   21...h6?  is a huge mistake as it allows,  22.Rxb7!  Qxb7  23.Ne6→  and White snacthes the initiative. }
21... Rae8
{ Black brings his last piece in the game before creating pressure on the kingside. }
22. Qb3 Bc6 23. Be3 Nh5 24. Be2 Nf4 25. Bg4 Qf7
{ All Black's pieces are wonderfully placed. } 26. Bxf4 Qxf4 27. Bf3 Bd7
{ of course, we are not going to exchange our bishop pair. } 28. Bd5 Bf5 29.
Rd1 Re2 { the rook exerts mighty pressure along the 2nd rank. } 30. a4 Be5 31.
g3 Qh6 32. Nd3 Bd4 33. Nf4 Bc2
{ wins material for Black and finishes up the game! } 34. Qf3 Bxd1 *

