{ In this game we will learn how Black plays on both sides of the board. First he gains space on the queenside, then focuses his attention on the kingside, and in the end breaks through on the queenside. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. Nf3 Bb7 5. a4 Qa5+
{ an important intermediate move before playing ...b4. Black wants to disturb the coordination between White's pieces. }
6. Bd2 b4 7. Bg5 d6 8. Nbd2 Nbd7 9. g3
{ this is not a great way of developing White's light-squared bishop as White will need to play e4 at some point anyway.   9.e4  is the line given in Chapter 27 }
9... g6 10. Bh3 Bg7 11. e4
{ White finally goes for the central advance, but now we can see that developing the bishop from h3 was not such a great idea. White could have directly played e4 followed by Be2 or Bd3. }
11... Qc7 12. O-O a5
{ Black blocks the queenside in order to focus completely on the kingside. }
13. Ne1 O-O 14. f4 h6 15. Bxf6
{ Instead of getting kicked around White gives up his bishop pair.   15.Bh4  Rae8=+  with the idea to break in the centre with ...e6 gives Black a slight edge. }
15... Bxf6 16. Nd3 Bd4+ 17. Kh1 Rae8 18. f5
{ this prevents the ...e6 break but now White's dark squares are terribly weakened. }
18... g5 19. Nf3 Bg7 20. Qd2 Nf6 21. Nf2 e6
{ this break could not have come at a better time. } 22. Rae1 exd5 23. exd5 b3
{ a very powerful move that shifts the focus entirely on the queenside. Black prevents b3 and now both the a4 and the c4 pawns are targets for Black. }
24. Ng4 Ba6 25. Qd3 Rxe1 26. Rxe1 Rb8 27. Ne3 Qd7 28. Ra1 Rb4 29. Nd2 Rxa4 30.
Rxa4 Qxa4 31. Qxb3 Qxb3 32. Nxb3 a4 33. Nd2 Nd7 { and Black wins material. }
34. f6
{ 34.Nd1  Nb6  35.Bf1  g4  36.h3  h5-+  threatening ...Bh6 with a winning endgame for Black. }
34... Nxf6 35. Bf5 Nh7 36. Bc2 Bxb2 37. Bxa4 Bc1 *

