{ In this game we will witness interesting sacrifices and the usual creative energy of GM Dubov! }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. cxb5 a6 5. Nc3 axb5 6. e4 b4 7. Nb5 d6 8. a4
Nxe4
{ This is the main move for Black but White gets a nice compensation for the pawn as can be seen in this game.   8...g6  is our mainline recommendation in chapter 30. }
9. Bc4 Nf6 10. Qe2
{ white intends to play Bf4 creating threats against the d6-pawn. } 10... Ra6
{ Black protects the d6-pawn in advance. } 11. Bg5 h6 12. Bxf6 gxf6
{ The position is dynamically balanced. White has sacrificed a pawn and managed to ruin Black's kingside structure making sure that 0-0 won't be safe for Black. On the other hand Black is a pawn up and has the bishop pair which will help him to face White's initiative. }
13. Nf3 Bg7 14. b3 f5
{ Black immediately activates his dark square bishop.   14...h5  N  is a good novelty mentioned in Chapter 30. }
15. Rd1 Bf6
{ the bishop is well placed on f6, always covering the h4-square and protecting the e7-pawn. }
16. O-O Kf8 17. Rfe1 Ra8 18. Bd3
{ White vacates the c4-square for his knight. } 18... Na6 19. Qc2 Qd7 20. Nd2
Rg8 21. f4
{ this weakens White's kingside for no reason.  White should have to continued with the planned   21.Nc4±  when he maintains a clear advantage as Black's pieces are doing so well. }
21... Nc7
{ it is very important to exchange the strong knight on b5, even at the cost of the extra pawn. }
22. Nxc7 Qxc7 23. Bxf5 Bb7 24. Be4 Bc3 25. Kh1
{ This allows Black a very strong break on the queenside.   25.Re2=  when the position is more or less equal. }
25... c4 26. bxc4
{ Now the white knight has lost its outpost on c4. We have also managed to get a passed pawn on the b-file. }
26... Bc8 27. Bf3 Bd7 28. Qh7 Rh8 29. Qd3 Rxa4 30. Re2 Qa7
{ Black's pieces have coordinated well and have started putting a lot of pressure on White's position. }
31. Rde1 Bf6 32. Qb3 Qa5 33. c5 Ra3 34. Nc4 Rxb3 35. Nxa5 Rxf3
{ a typical Dubov sacrifice. He does not miss a chance to show his creative flair!   35...Ra3  36.Nc4  Rc3  37.c6  Rxc4  38.cxd7  Kg7∓  maintains a clear advantage for Black, though it might be difficult to win due to the presence of opposite-coloured bishops on the board. }
36. gxf3 dxc5
{ as a compensation for the exchange, Black has the bishop pair and two passed pawns on the queenside. }
37. Nc6 b3 38. Rb1 { 38.Na5=  was essential to prevent ...c4. } 38... c4 39.
Ne5 Bf5 40. Rc1 Bxe5 41. fxe5 Bd3
{ the team of the black bishop and two pawns is tough for White to handle and Black converted this position into a win comfortably. }
42. Rd2 Kg7 43. Rg2+ Kh7 44. d6 exd6 45. exd6 Rd8 46. Rd2 Kg6 47. d7 Kf5 48.
Rc3 Rxd7 49. Rxc4 Bxc4 50. Rxd7 Ke5 51. f4+ Ke4 52. Kg2 Bd5 53. Rd6 b2 54. Rb6
Kd3+ 55. Kg3 Kc3 56. Rxb2 Kxb2 57. Kg4 Kc3 58. Kh5 Kd4 59. Kxh6 Ke4 60. Kg5 f5
*

