{ In this game we will see how it is tough even for top players, like GM Tomashevsky, to fight when Black secures an initiative in Benko }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. cxb5 a6 5. e3 g6 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. e4 O-O 8. a4 e6
{ Black strikes at White's centre immediately.   8...Bb7  is the recommendation in our repertoire in Chapter 31. }
9. dxe6 { I not a big fan of surrendering the centre in this way. } 9... fxe6
{ Black intends to seize the centre with ...d5. } 10. Qd6
{ White prevents ...d5, but this queen sortie wastes a valuable move and risks falling far behind in development. }
10... Bb7 11. f3 Ne8
{ another pawn sacrifice! Black rightly does not care about the second pawn as opening up the position takes priority here. }
12. Qxc5 d5
{ White is up two pawns but from now on he should take every step with caution. }
13. exd5
{ This opens up more lines in the centre which bad news for White.   13.Be3=∞  was better, intending Rd1. }
13... exd5 14. Nh3 Nd7 15. Qf2 d4 16. Bc4+ Kh8 17. O-O
{ White decides to sacrifice a piece and hide his king to the kingside. But the three pawns that White will have for the piece are of no value. }
17... dxc3 18. bxc3 Nd6 19. Bg5 Qc7 20. Bd3 Nc5 21. Rad1 axb5 22. axb5 Nde4
{ With this rescourse Black manages to exchange White's bishop pair. } 23. Bxe4
Nxe4 24. Qh4 Nxc3 25. Rde1 Ra4 { and Black has a clear winning advantage. } 26.
Qf2 Ne4 27. Qh4 Nc3 28. Qf2 Ra2 29. Qh4 Qc5+ 30. Be3 Qxb5 31. Ng5 h5 32. Ne6
Ne2+ 33. Kh1 Bf6 34. Qf2 Re8 35. Rb1 Qc6 36. Nc5 Nc3 37. Qg3 Nxb1 38. Qxg6 Rxe3
39. Qh6+ Kg8 40. Qxe3 Nd2 41. Rd1 Bc8 42. Qh6 Bf5 43. h4 Rc2 44. Nb7 Rc1 *

