{ in this game we will see how Black punishes White's negligence in development early in the opening. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. cxb5 a6 5. b6 e6 6. Nc3 Nxd5 7. Nxd5 exd5 8.
Qxd5 Nc6 9. Nf3 Rb8 10. Bg5
{ White provokes ...f6 hoping to exploit the weakness created by this in the future. But White is in no position to exploit these weaknesses as his piece are not developed yet. }
10... f6 11. Bd2 Qxb6 { now Black takes over the initiative! } 12. Bc3 Nb4
{ pushing the white queen away from the centre. } 13. Qd1 d5
{ Black has gained complete control over the centre. } 14. e4 d4
{ this is the simplest. Black forces White to give up his bishop pair.   14...dxe4  is also a good alternative. }
15. Bxb4 Qxb4+ 16. Nd2 Bd6
{ Black's bishop pair and space in the centre gives him a slight edge. } 17. b3
Bf4 18. g3 Bg4 { Using the initiative in an energetic fashion. } 19. Be2 Bxe2
20. Qxe2 d3 21. Qxd3
{ White surrenders.   21.Qh5+  gives White a good fighting chance.  21...g6  22.Qd1  Bxd2+  23.Qxd2  Qxe4+=+  Black is a pawn up and surely to be preferred in the upcoming ending. }
21... Rd8 22. Qxd8+ Kxd8 23. gxf4 Ke7
{ With the white king so exposed in the centre, he cannot hope to save half point in this endgame. }
24. Rg1 Rd8 25. Rd1 Kf8 26. Rg3 f5 27. exf5 Qxf4 28. Ke2 Qe5+ 29. Re3 Qb2 30.
a4 Qc2 31. Re5 Qd3+ 32. Ke1 Qd6 33. f4 Qd4 *

