{ In this game we will see how GM Shankland outplays White with elegant strategic manoeuvres and piece placement. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. cxb5 a6 5. bxa6 g6 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Nf3 O-O 8. g3
d6 9. Bg2 Nxa6
{ this is the advantage of delaying the capture of the a6-pawn. We can capture it with our knight and keep our bishop on the h3-c8 diagonal. }
10. O-O Bf5 11. Nh4
{ White pushes the black bishop back from f5 but his own knight comes away from the centre. }
11... Bd7 12. b3
{ White would ideally want to place his queenside pawns on b3 and a4. } 12...
Qb6 13. Bd2 Rfb8
{ Black has placed his major pieces optimally on the queenside, waiting for an opportunity to create counterplay. }
14. Re1 Nc7 { freeing the a-file for the a8-rook. } 15. Qc2 Ra3 16. Qc1 Qa7 17.
e4
{ this weakens critical squares in White's camp and allows a nice strategic knight manoeuvre.   17.Na4?  does not trap the black rook, as it can be easily supported with,  17...Nb5∓   17.h3  covering the g4 square followed by e4 was the best try for white. Though after,  17...Nb5=+  Black maintains a slight edge due to his pressure on the queenside. }
17... Ng4
{ The knight heads for the newly weakened d3-square. ...Bd4 putting pressure on f2 is also on the cards. }
18. h3 Ne5 19. Bf1 Bb5
{ exchanging pieces is usually in Black's favour as with fewer pieces on the board it becomes difficult for white to cover the entry points in the position. }
20. Qc2 Bxf1 21. Rxf1 Qa6 { again playing on the weak d3 square. } 22. Bc1
Raxb3 { Black wins the pawn back with interest. } 23. axb3 Qxa1
{ now the b3-pawn is weak. Black converted his advantage with good technique. }
24. Bg5 Qa3 25. Bxe7 Rxb3 26. Ne2 Rb2 27. Qd1 Nb5 28. Bg5 Nf3+ 29. Nxf3 Qxf3
30. Nc1 Nd4 31. Qa4 h6 32. Qe8+ Kh7 33. Bf4 f5 34. Bxd6 fxe4 35. Bxc5 Nf5 36.
Qf7 Rc2 37. Bf8 e3 38. Bd6 Rxf2 *

