{ Before the game I checked the games of GM Sokolov and knew that he mainly plays the Nimzo-Indian. He also wrote a book on it. So I decided to play Benko and get a fighting position on the board. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. Qc2
{ White develops his queen not to support the c4-pawn but to prepare the pawn advance e2-e4. }
4... bxc4 5. e4 e6
{ Hitting in the centre immediately as seen in our repertoire. } 6. Bxc4 exd5
7. exd5 Be7 8. Nf3 O-O 9. O-O d6 10. h3 Nbd7 11. Nc3 Nb6 12. b3 Rb8 13. Bf4
Nxc4 14. bxc4 Rb4
{ The attack on the c4-pawn does not bring Black any benefit as White can easily defend it.   14...Nh5!  with the idea to play ...f5 next, is the recommended move }
15. Nd2 Ba6
{ I continued with my strategy, but it is simply a waste of time and the black bishop will be misplaced on a6. }
16. a3 Rb6 17. Rfe1 Re8 18. Qa4 Bf8 19. Nde4
{ Slowly, little by little, White has started outplaying me. } 19... Nxe4 20.
Nxe4 Re7 { the only way to avoid losing immediately. } 21. Re3 Qd7 22. Qc2
{ White correctly avoids exchanging pieces as Black's pieces are cramped and un-coordinated. }
22... Qf5 23. Bg3 Bc8
{ Finally I brought my bishop back in the game, but it seems to be too late. }
24. Rae1 Reb7 25. Qc3 Bd7 26. Bh4
{ 26.Rf3  Qg6  27.Rf6+-  was a nice way to win material. } 26... h6 27. Rf3 Qh5
28. Bf6
{ first step in the wrong direction.   28.Rg3!  was the best way to go ahead.  28...Qxh4  29.Nf6+  Kh8  30.Nxd7  Rxd7  31.Re8  Qf6  32.Rxf8+  Kh7  33.Qxf6  gxf6  34.Rgg8+-  and White will soon win the h6-pawn with a winning endgame. }
28... Rb1 29. Rg3
{ This is what my opponent had in mind but it falls short due to a nice combination.   29.Rxb1  Rxb1+  30.Kh2+-  is winning for white due to a very strong attack on the kingside. }
29... Qe2 { this move was surely missed by my opponent. } 30. Rxb1 Rxb1+ 31.
Kh2 Qd1 32. Rxg7+ Bxg7 33. Bxg7 Qh1+ 34. Kg3 Bxh3 35. Bxh6 Qxg2+ 36. Kf4 f5 37.
Nf6+ Kf7 38. Qe3 Qh2+ 39. Kf3 Qg2+ 40. Ke2 Rb2+ *

