[Result "*"]

{ My opponent was an expert in the e3-Nge2 variation of the Nimzo-Indian, and hardly ever lost any games in that opening. So which opening do you choose in such a situation! The Benko, of course! Another motivation to choose Benko for this game was that a win would secure my final GM norm. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. cxb5 a6 5. bxa6 g6 6. Nc3 Bxa6 7. e4 Bxf1 8.
Kxf1 d6 9. g3 Bg7 10. Kg2 O-O 11. Nf3 Nbd7 12. h3 Qa5 13. Re1 Rfb8
{ I have placed my pieces in typical fashion on the queenside. } 14. e5
{ A timely central break. If Black gets a chance to play ...Ne8 then e5 break would be a distant dream for White. }
14... dxe5 15. Nxe5 Nxe5 16. Rxe5
{ Now with an open e-file White can hope to create some pressure on the e7-pawn. }
16... Rb7 17. Qe2 Raa7 18. Qf3 Ne8 19. Re2 Nd6
{ White is a pawn up but Black has still some pressure on the queenside. It is not so easy to untangle White's queenside pieces, though my opponent manages to do so masterfully. }
20. g4 Nc4 21. Qd3 Qb4
{ 21...Ne5  22.Qg3  Nc4=  would have maintained the balance. } 22. Qg3 Rd7 23.
Re4 Bd4 24. Bh6
{ this bishop is going to give Black a lot of troubles. Now we both were severely low on time and were blitzing out our moves from this point onwards. }
24... Qb7 25. Rd1 Nd6 { 25...f6  26.Rexd4  cxd4 } 26. Re2 Ne8
{ 26...f6=  it was essential to cover the a1-h8 diagonal discouraging any sacrifice on d4. }
27. Kg1 Nf6 28. a4 Nxd5 { falling straight into my opponent's trap! } 29. Rxd4
{ This came as a shocker for me. With the chances for my final GM norm fading away, I luckily managed to find a trick of my own! }
29... Nxc3
{ 29...cxd4  30.Qe5  Nf6   30...f6  31.Qe6+  Kh8  32.Qf7+-  leads to a mate.  31.Qxf6+-  mates Black. }
30. Rxd7
{ and White returns the favour quickly!   30.bxc3+-  or   30.Rxe7+-  would have finished the game on the spot! }
30... Nxe2+ 31. Kh2 Qh1+ { This elegant queen sacrifice saved my day! } 32.
Kxh1 Nxg3+ 33. fxg3 Rxd7 { and now its an easy win for Black. } 34. Be3 c4 35.
a5 Rd3 36. Bb6 Rd1+ 37. Kg2 Rd2+ 38. Kf3 Rxb2 39. Ke4 c3 40. Kd3 c2 41. Kd2 Ra2
42. Kc1 e5 43. g5 e4 44. h4 Kf8 45. Be3 Ke7 46. a6 Ke6 47. a7 Kd5 48. g4 Kc4
49. Kd2 Kb3 50. Bd4 Ra4 51. Kc1 *

