[Black "Lalith, Babu M.R. vs. Dhopade, Swapnil, 50th National Premier 2013, Kolkata"]
[Result "*"]

{ This win gave me a boost in my confidence of playing the Benko in crucial encounters, which I did in my future games. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. Qc2 bxc4 5. e4 g6
{ 5...e6  is recommended in our repertoire. } 6. Bxc4 d6
{ this is the most popular way of playing in this variation for Black. } 7. Nf3
Bg7 8. O-O O-O 9. h3
{ A useful prophylactic move covering the g4-square and preventing ...Bg4 or ...Ng4-Ne5 manuouvers. }
9... Nbd7
{ I wanted to to take my knight to b6 fighting for the control of the c4 square which is of great importance in this structure. }
10. Nc3 Nb6 11. Be2 a5
{ a normal space gaining pawn advance on the queenside. Now I also have the option of ...Ba6, offering the exchange of the light-squared bishops. }
12. Rd1 Nfd7 { Keeping the e5-square under firm control. } 13. a4 Ne5 14. Nxe5
Bxe5 15. Bh6 Re8 16. Nb5
{ White has played quite well upto this point. By placing his pieces correctly he has managed to keep Black's queenside activity in check. }
16... Bd7 17. f4
{ this was not required as it leads to the weakening of the g1-a7 diagonal.   17.Rac1+=  was better with the idea to play b3 and cover all the critical squares on the queenside. }
17... Bh8 18. Rac1 { This logical move falls short to a tactical shot! } 18...
Nxa4
{ Black should be always vigilant of such tactical opportunities in the Benko! By eliminating the a4-pawn Black manages to rattle the base of the b5-knight completely. }
19. b3
{ 19.Qxa4  Rb8!  Black starts pressuring the b5-knight.  20.e5  Qb6  21.e6  c4+!  exploiting the weak g1-a7 diagonal weakened by the move 17.f4  22.Kh1  Qxb5-+  and Black is a clear pawn up in the endgame. }
19... Nb2 { The brave knight jumps inside the enemy camp. } 20. Rd2 Qb6 21. Nc3
c4+ 22. Kh1 Nd3
{ 22...cxb3!  23.Qxb2  a4-+  was another stunning way to play here for Black. The two queenside pawns supports by Black's two strong bishops will bring home a full point. }
23. Bxd3 cxd3 24. Rxd3
{ Even the material is equal White stands poorly because the lines on the queenside are open for the Black's pieces to exploit @@StartBracket@@a dream of every Benko Player@@EndBracket@@. The b3-pawn is weak and there is going to be pressure down the c-file. }
24... Rec8 25. Bg5 Rc7 26. Qd1 Qb4 27. e5 Rac8 28. Ne2 Rxc1 29. Nxc1 dxe5 30.
fxe5 Bxe5
{ I managed to convert my queenside pressure into an extra pawn. The rest is easy. }
31. Re3 Bd6 32. Nd3 Qd4 33. Qf3 Bf5 34. Bf4 Rc3 35. Ne1 Rxe3 36. Bxe3 Qe5 *

