{ This game demonstrates another beautiful sacrifice stemming out of a Benko game! }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. cxb5 a6 5. bxa6 g6 6. Nc3 Bxa6 7. Nf3 d6 8. e4
Bxf1 9. Kxf1 Bg7 10. g3 O-O 11. Kg2 Nbd7 12. h3
{ White covers the g4-square preventing ...Ng4 followed by ...Ne5 manuouver. }
12... Qa5 13. Re1 Rfb8
{ I have arranged my pieces on the queenside in a typical fashion. } 14. e5
{ We saw the same central break in my game against Aleksandrov. } 14... dxe5
15. Nxe5 Nxe5 16. Rxe5 Rb7 17. Qe2 Raa7 18. Qf3 Ne8 19. Re2 Nd6 20. Bf4
{ an error as it allows my knight to mobilize towards the central d4 square.   20.g4  was the choice of Aleksandrov. }
20... Nf5 21. Qd3
{ 21.Rd2  was the best move here for White. The point lies in the variation,  21...Nd4  22.Qe4  Nb3  23.axb3  Qxa1  and now  24.d6∞  leads to crazy complications for both sides. }
21... Nd4 22. Ree1
{ giving away to b2 pawn leads to a disaster.   22.Rd2  White should have sacrificed the exchange. After,  22...Nb3  23.axb3  Qxa1  24.d6=+  Still gives White decent play for the sacrificed exchange. }
22... Rxb2 23. Reb1 Rab7 24. Nd1 c4
{ distracting the white queen from the support of the b1-rook. } 25. Qxc4 Rxb1
26. Rxb1 Rxb1 27. Qc8+ Bf8 28. Nc3 Rg1+
{ a nice rook sacrifice to end the game.   28...Rd1  is another winning suggestion by our crazy silicon friend!  29.Bh6  Ne6-+  and astoundingly Black manages to bring his rook in the defence on d8. }
